UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Consulting Services Agreement (the "Agreement") is made and entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date") between:

(A) {{party_a_company}}, a company incorporated in England and Wales (registered number {{party_a_registered_number}}) whose registered office is at {{party_a_address}} ("Client"); and

(B) {{party_b_company}}, a company incorporated in England and Wales (registered number {{party_b_registered_number}}) whose principal place of business is at {{party_b_address}} ("Consultant").

Client and Consultant are each a "Party" and together the "Parties".

This Agreement sets out the terms on which Consultant will provide professional consulting services to Client. The Parties agree that this Agreement (including any statement of work, purchase order, or other document expressly incorporated by reference) constitutes a legally binding contract supported by adequate consideration. The Parties intend that signatures (including electronic signatures) will be binding in accordance with the Electronic Communications Act 2000 and the common law of England and Wales.',
  recitals = 'A. Client wishes to engage Consultant to provide certain professional consulting services and/or deliverables.

B. Consultant represents that it has the skills, experience, personnel and resources necessary to perform the Services (as defined below) in accordance with this Agreement.

C. The Parties wish to set out the terms relating to scope, fees, intellectual property, confidentiality, data protection (including UK GDPR and the Data Protection Act 2018), compliance (including the Bribery Act 2010 and (where applicable) the Modern Slavery Act 2015), and the Parties’ respective rights and obligations.

D. The Parties acknowledge that this Agreement is intended to create a relationship of independent contracting and not employment, and the Parties will co-operate in good faith to comply with the UK off-payroll working rules (commonly referred to as "IR35") where applicable.

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises and other good and valuable consideration (the receipt and adequacy of which are acknowledged), the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS; INTERPRETATION; ORDER OF PRECEDENCE","content":"1.1 Definitions. In this Agreement, unless the context otherwise requires:\n\n(a) \"Acceptance\" means Client’s acceptance of a Deliverable in accordance with clause 3 (Deliverables; Milestones; Acceptance).\n\n(b) \"Acceptance Criteria\" means the objective criteria (including functional requirements, specifications, formats, performance requirements and/or test cases) for a Deliverable set out in {{deliverables_schedule}} or otherwise agreed in writing.\n\n(c) \"Affiliate\" means, in relation to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly Controls, is Controlled by, or is under common Control with that Party. \"Control\" means the ability to direct the affairs of an entity, whether through ownership of voting securities, contract, or otherwise.\n\n(d) \"Applicable Law\" means all applicable laws, statutes, regulations, secondary legislation, and legally binding guidance or codes of practice, in each case as amended and in force from time to time.\n\n(e) \"Background IPR\" means Intellectual Property Rights owned by or licensed to a Party prior to the Effective Date, or developed independently of this Agreement, including any improvements or derivatives of such rights not created specifically as part of the Services.\n\n(f) \"Business Day\" means a day other than a Saturday, Sunday or public holiday in England when banks in London are open for business.\n\n(g) \"Change Request\" means a written request to change the Services, Deliverables, Milestones, assumptions, timetable, Acceptance Criteria, Charges, or any other aspect of the engagement.\n\n(h) \"Charges\" means the fees and other charges payable by Client to Consultant under clause 4 (Fees, Invoicing, Expenses and Taxes).\n\n(i) \"Client Materials\" means all documents, data, content, software, materials, equipment, systems access, and information (including any Personal Data) provided or made available by or on behalf of Client to Consultant in connection with the Services.\n\n(j) \"Confidential Information\" has the meaning given in clause 9.1.\n\n(k) \"Consultant Personnel\" means Consultant’s employees, officers, workers, agents, consultants and permitted subcontractors who are engaged in the performance of the Services.\n\n(l) \"Deliverables\" means all outputs to be provided by Consultant to Client as part of the Services, including those specified in {{services_description}} and/or {{deliverables_schedule}}, and including any Work Product.\n\n(m) \"Dispute\" means any dispute, controversy, claim or difference arising out of or in connection with this Agreement (including its formation, interpretation, performance, breach, termination or invalidity).\n\n(n) \"Force Majeure Event\" means an event or circumstance beyond a Party’s reasonable control which could not reasonably have been avoided by that Party, including (without limitation) acts of God, flood, drought, earthquake or other natural disaster, epidemic or pandemic, terrorist attack, civil war, civil commotion or riots, war, threat of or preparation for war, armed conflict, imposition of sanctions, embargo, or breaking off of diplomatic relations, nuclear, chemical or biological contamination, any law or action taken by a government or public authority, collapse of buildings, fire, explosion or accident, interruption or failure of utility service, and (to the extent not caused by the affected Party) failure of suppliers or subcontractors.\n\n(o) \"Intellectual Property Rights\" or \"IPR\" means patents, utility models, rights to inventions, copyright and neighbouring and related rights, moral rights, trade marks and service marks, business names and domain names, rights in get-up, goodwill and the right to sue for passing off or unfair competition, rights in designs, rights in computer software, database rights, rights in confidential information (including trade secrets), and any other intellectual property rights, in each case whether registered or unregistered and including all applications for and renewals or extensions of such rights.\n\n(p) \"Milestones\" means any project milestones, interim deliverables, dates, or stage gates set out in {{milestones}} or otherwise agreed in writing.\n\n(q) \"Personal Data\", \"Processing\", \"Controller\", \"Processor\", \"Data Subject\", \"Personal Data Breach\" and \"Special Category Data\" have the meanings given in the UK GDPR.\n\n(r) \"Data Protection Laws\" means all Applicable Law relating to the Processing of Personal Data and privacy, including the UK GDPR, the Data Protection Act 2018, the Privacy and Electronic Communications (EC Directive) Regulations 2003, and any guidance or codes of practice issued by the ICO or other competent authority.\n\n(s) \"Services\" means the professional consulting services described in {{services_description}}, together with any additional services agreed under the Change Control procedure.\n\n(t) \"Statement of Work\" or \"SOW\" means any statement of work, schedule, proposal, or similar document describing the Services, Deliverables, Milestones or Charges, which is expressly stated to be governed by and incorporated into this Agreement. The Parties may use the description in {{services_description}} and {{deliverables_schedule}} as the initial SOW.\n\n(u) \"Trade Secrets Regulations\" means the Trade Secrets (Enforcement, etc.) Regulations 2018.\n\n(v) \"VAT\" means value added tax as charged in accordance with the Value Added Tax Act 1994.\n\n(w) \"Work Product\" means all Deliverables, materials, works, inventions, discoveries, developments, documentation, reports, analyses, specifications, designs, drawings, notes, content and other outputs created, developed, written or prepared by or on behalf of Consultant in the course of performing the Services.\n\n1.2 Interpretation. In this Agreement:\n\n(a) headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation;\n\n(b) words in the singular include the plural and vice versa;\n\n(c) references to \"including\" or \"in particular\" do not limit the generality of any words preceding them;\n\n(d) references to a person include an individual, company, partnership, LLP, unincorporated association, government body or other legal entity;\n\n(e) references to \"writing\" include email and electronic signature platforms, except where a provision expressly requires a \"signed\" writing;\n\n(f) a reference to a statute includes any subordinate legislation made under it and any amendments, re-enactments or replacements.\n\n1.3 Order of precedence. If there is any conflict or inconsistency between the documents forming this Agreement, the following order of precedence applies (highest first):\n\n(a) any variation or amendment expressly stated to amend this Agreement;\n\n(b) these clauses;\n\n(c) the SOW and/or {{services_description}} and {{deliverables_schedule}}; and\n\n(d) any purchase order or similar document.\n\nFor the avoidance of doubt, any standard terms and conditions on a purchase order or invoice are excluded and do not apply, even if referenced or purported to be incorporated.\n\n1.4 Appointment of managers (optional). The Parties may appoint day-to-day contract managers: Client manager: {{contract_manager_client}}; Consultant manager: {{contract_manager_consultant}}. Either Party may change its manager by notice in writing."},{"id":"engagement","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. ENGAGEMENT AND SERVICES","content":"2.1 Engagement. Client hereby engages Consultant to perform the Services, and Consultant accepts such engagement, in each case subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement.\n\n2.2 Scope of Services. Consultant shall perform the Services described in {{services_description}}. The Parties acknowledge that the Services may be performed on-site at {{services_location}}, remotely, or on a hybrid basis as agreed in writing.\n\n2.3 Standard of performance.\n\n(a) Consultant shall perform the Services with due skill, care and diligence, in a professional and workmanlike manner, consistent with good industry practice and using appropriately qualified Consultant Personnel.\n\n(b) Consultant shall comply with all Applicable Law in the performance of the Services, including (where applicable) health and safety requirements and Client’s reasonable site rules and policies notified to Consultant in advance.\n\n2.4 No authority to bind. Consultant has no authority to make any representation, give any warranty, incur any liability, or enter into any commitment on Client’s behalf unless Client expressly authorises Consultant in advance in a written document signed by an authorised representative of Client.\n\n2.5 Resources and key personnel.\n\n(a) Consultant shall allocate sufficient resources to perform the Services and deliver the Deliverables in accordance with any agreed timetable.\n\n(b) Where key individuals are identified in {{key_personnel}}, Consultant shall not replace those individuals without Client’s prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed). Any replacement shall have substantially equivalent skills and experience.\n\n2.6 Client responsibilities.\n\n(a) Client shall provide, in a timely manner, such access to Client personnel, information, systems, and Client Materials as Consultant reasonably requires to perform the Services.\n\n(b) Consultant shall not be responsible for any delay, failure, additional cost or inability to perform the Services to the extent caused by Client’s failure to comply with clause 2.6(a) or by inaccuracies or deficiencies in Client Materials.\n\n2.7 Working arrangements.\n\n(a) Unless otherwise agreed, Consultant may determine the order and manner in which it performs the Services, subject always to any Milestones and Acceptance Criteria.\n\n(b) If Client requires attendance at specific meetings, sites, or time windows, such requirements shall be set out in the SOW or agreed in writing.\n\n(c) The Parties acknowledge any indicative working hours (if any) stated in {{working_hours}} are for planning purposes only and do not create an employment relationship.\n\n2.8 Change Control. Any change to the Services, Deliverables, Milestones, assumptions, Acceptance Criteria, or Charges shall be subject to clause 3.7 (Change Control), unless the Parties agree in writing to a different change procedure.\n\n2.9 Dependencies and third parties. Where performance of the Services depends on third-party systems, licences, hosting providers, or other suppliers chosen by Client, Consultant shall not be liable for non-performance caused by those third parties, provided Consultant has used reasonable endeavours to mitigate the impact and to inform Client of foreseeable issues.\n\n2.10 Client policies (optional). Consultant shall comply with any Client policies notified to Consultant and reasonably applicable to contractors (including information security and acceptable use), as identified at {{client_policies_url}} or otherwise provided to Consultant, provided such policies do not conflict with this Agreement. If there is a conflict, this Agreement prevails unless expressly stated otherwise."},{"id":"deliverables_acceptance","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. DELIVERABLES; MILESTONES; ACCEPTANCE; CHANGE CONTROL","content":"3.1 Deliverables and timetable. Consultant shall deliver the Deliverables in accordance with the timetable, delivery method and format set out in {{deliverables_schedule}} and/or {{services_description}}. If no timetable is stated, Consultant shall deliver within a reasonable time having regard to the nature and complexity of the Services.\n\n3.2 Delivery method. Unless otherwise agreed in writing:\n\n(a) Deliverables shall be delivered electronically to Client via a secure method; and\n\n(b) any physical Deliverables (if required) shall be delivered to the address notified by Client.\n\n3.3 Milestones and progress updates.\n\n(a) Where Milestones apply, Consultant shall use reasonable endeavours to meet the Milestones.\n\n(b) Consultant shall provide periodic progress updates as reasonably requested by Client.\n\n3.4 Review and Acceptance procedure.\n\n(a) Upon delivery of a Deliverable, Client shall have {{acceptance_period_days}} Business Days (or, if blank, 10 Business Days) to review and either: (i) accept the Deliverable in writing; or (ii) reject the Deliverable by providing a written notice describing in reasonable detail the specific non-conformities with the Acceptance Criteria.\n\n(b) If Client does not provide an acceptance or rejection notice within the review period, the Deliverable shall be deemed accepted on the next Business Day, provided Consultant has not received a written notice of material non-conformity.\n\n(c) Client may not reject a Deliverable for minor deviations that do not materially affect use of the Deliverable for its intended purpose; such minor deviations shall be recorded and remedied within a reasonable time as part of ongoing performance.\n\n3.5 Remedy period.\n\n(a) If Client validly rejects a Deliverable under clause 3.4(a)(ii), Consultant shall, at its own cost and within {{correction_period_days}} Business Days (or, if blank, 10 Business Days), use reasonable endeavours to correct the non-conformities and re-submit the Deliverable for review.\n\n(b) The Parties shall repeat the review process until Acceptance, or until it becomes clear that Consultant cannot remedy the non-conformities within a reasonable number of cycles.\n\n3.6 Consequences of repeated failure. If a Deliverable is rejected following two (2) re-submissions for substantially the same material non-conformities, Client may (without prejudice to other rights):\n\n(a) require Consultant to provide an agreed workaround or remediation plan; and/or\n\n(b) reduce the Charges for that Deliverable to reflect diminished value; and/or\n\n(c) terminate the affected SOW (or this Agreement, if the failure is material to the overall engagement) for material breach under clause 7.4.\n\n3.7 Change Control.\n\n(a) Either Party may submit a Change Request. Change Requests should, where practicable, use the format set out in {{change_request_form}}.\n\n(b) Within a reasonable time after receiving a Change Request, Consultant shall provide a written impact assessment setting out: (i) the proposed changes; (ii) the effect on Deliverables and Milestones; (iii) any impact on Charges (including additional fees or expenses); (iv) any impact on resources and dependencies; and (v) any impact on risk and assumptions.\n\n(c) No Change Request shall be binding unless agreed in writing and signed by both Parties. Consultant shall not be obliged to start work on a Change Request until the Parties have agreed the applicable changes to scope, timetable and Charges.\n\n3.8 Client-provided acceptance criteria and dependencies. If Acceptance Criteria or requirements are provided by Client, Client warrants they are sufficiently clear for Consultant to perform. If requirements are ambiguous or incomplete, Consultant shall promptly notify Client and the Parties shall agree clarifications in writing.\n\n3.9 Partial Acceptance (optional). Client may accept a Deliverable in part where separable components meet the Acceptance Criteria. In such case, Charges may be apportioned by agreement or, failing agreement, on a reasonable basis reflecting value delivered.\n\n3.10 Records. Consultant shall maintain reasonable records of work performed, Deliverables delivered, and acceptance communications to support invoicing and delivery status."},{"id":"fees_payment","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. FEES, INVOICING, EXPENSES AND TAXES","content":"4.1 Charges. In consideration for the proper performance of the Services, Client shall pay Consultant the Charges as set out in {{services_description}} and/or {{deliverables_schedule}}, which may include one or more of the following (as applicable):\n\n(a) Fixed fee: {{payment_amount}} (exclusive of VAT);\n\n(b) Time and materials: {{hourly_rate}} per {{rate_unit}} (exclusive of VAT), calculated by reference to time spent by Consultant Personnel reasonably and properly performing the Services; and/or\n\n(c) Milestone or deliverable-based fees as set out in {{milestones}} and/or {{deliverables_schedule}}.\n\n4.2 Currency. Unless otherwise stated, all Charges and references to money amounts in this Agreement are in {{currency}}.\n\n4.3 Invoicing.\n\n(a) Consultant shall submit invoices in accordance with the SOW or, if not specified, monthly in arrears.\n\n(b) Each invoice shall include, where applicable: (i) a description of the Services performed and Deliverables delivered; (ii) relevant dates or period; (iii) any applicable Milestones achieved; (iv) time records (if time and materials); (v) VAT (if applicable) shown separately; (vi) the applicable purchase order number {{purchase_order_number}} (if required by Client and communicated in advance); and (vii) Consultant’s bank details {{bank_details}}.\n\n(c) Invoices shall be sent to {{client_invoice_email}} (and, if required by Client, copied to any other address notified in writing).\n\n4.4 Payment terms.\n\n(a) Subject to clause 4.4(b), Client shall pay undisputed invoices within {{payment_terms_days}} days of receipt.\n\n(b) If Client disputes an invoice in good faith, Client shall notify Consultant in writing within 10 Business Days of receipt, setting out the reasons for dispute and the amount disputed. Client shall pay the undisputed portion in accordance with clause 4.4(a). The Parties shall use good faith efforts to resolve disputed amounts promptly.\n\n(c) Interest on late payments. Without prejudice to Consultant’s statutory rights, overdue undisputed sums shall accrue interest and compensation in accordance with the Late Payment of Commercial Debts (Interest) Act 1998.\n\n4.5 Expenses.\n\n(a) Unless otherwise expressly agreed in writing, Consultant shall bear its own costs and expenses.\n\n(b) Where Client has agreed to reimburse expenses, only expenses that are: (i) reasonable; (ii) necessarily incurred for the performance of the Services; (iii) pre-approved in writing (or expressly permitted by an agreed expenses policy); and (iv) supported by valid receipts, shall be reimbursable.\n\n(c) Any expense cap is {{maximum_expenses}} in aggregate unless otherwise agreed. Any expenses policy or permitted categories are described at {{expenses_policy_url}} and/or {{pre_approved_expenses_description}}.\n\n(d) Mileage, travel time and subsistence (optional). If agreed in the SOW, mileage may be charged at HMRC approved rates and travel time may be charged at a reduced rate as specified in the SOW.\n\n4.6 VAT. All Charges are exclusive of VAT unless expressly stated otherwise. Where VAT is chargeable, Consultant shall provide a valid VAT invoice and Client shall pay VAT in addition to the Charges at the prevailing rate.\n\n4.7 Taxes and off-payroll working rules (IR35).\n\n(a) General. Each Party shall be responsible for its own taxes arising from this Agreement, subject to clauses 4.7(b) to 4.7(h).\n\n(b) Consultant responsibility where off-payroll rules do not apply to Client. If Client is not required to apply the off-payroll working rules (for example, because Client is a \"small\" company for the purposes of the relevant legislation), Consultant shall be solely responsible for determining and accounting for any income tax and National Insurance contributions (including employer’s NICs where applicable) and any other taxes or deductions arising from payments made under this Agreement.\n\n(c) Client responsibility where off-payroll rules apply to Client. If Client is required by law to assess the engagement and/or operate PAYE (for example, where Client is a medium or large organisation and Consultant provides services through an intermediary), Client shall issue a status determination statement where required and, if Client is the fee-payer, may make deductions for income tax and employee National Insurance contributions and account for employer’s National Insurance contributions and apprenticeship levy as required by Applicable Law.\n\n(d) Co-operation. Consultant shall promptly provide information reasonably requested by Client to enable Client to comply with its obligations under the off-payroll working rules, including information about any intermediary and the working practices.\n\n(e) Status disagreement process (where applicable). Where Client provides a status determination statement, Consultant may raise a written disagreement within 45 days. Client shall consider the representations and respond in accordance with Applicable Law.\n\n(f) No gross-up. Except as required by Applicable Law, Client is not obliged to gross-up any payments for taxes or deductions.\n\n(g) HMRC enquiries. The Parties shall co-operate in good faith with any enquiry by HMRC or other competent authority relating to the status of the engagement and/or deductions.\n\n(h) Consultant indemnity for misrepresentation. Consultant shall indemnify Client for any liabilities, costs, penalties and interest suffered by Client to the extent they arise from Consultant’s fraud, wilful default, or material misrepresentation regarding the structure of the engagement or the identity of any intermediary.\n\n4.8 Set-off. Client may set off against any sums due to Consultant any undisputed sums due from Consultant to Client under this Agreement, provided Client gives notice and reasonable supporting detail.\n\n4.9 Suspension for non-payment. If Client fails to pay any undisputed invoice by the due date, Consultant may (after giving at least 5 Business Days’ notice and an opportunity to remedy) suspend performance of the Services until payment is made, provided that suspension is proportionate and Consultant uses reasonable endeavours to minimise impact.\n\n4.10 No partnership funds. Consultant is responsible for paying its own Consultant Personnel and subcontractors. Client shall have no liability to any Consultant Personnel or subcontractor except as required by law."},{"id":"consultant_status","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. CONSULTANT STATUS; INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR; OFF-PAYROLL (IR35) WORKING PRACTICES","content":"5.1 Independent contractor. Consultant is engaged as an independent contractor. Nothing in this Agreement shall render Consultant, or any Consultant Personnel, an employee, worker, agent or partner of Client, and Consultant shall not hold itself out as such.\n\n5.2 No mutuality of obligation. Nothing in this Agreement obliges Client to offer work beyond the Services agreed, nor obliges Consultant to accept work beyond the agreed Services.\n\n5.3 No employment benefits. Consultant acknowledges that it and Consultant Personnel are not entitled to any benefits, pension, holiday pay, sick pay, redundancy pay, or other rights that would arise from an employment relationship with Client.\n\n5.4 Control and autonomy.\n\n(a) Subject to meeting Milestones and Acceptance Criteria, Consultant shall be responsible for determining how the Services are performed.\n\n(b) Client may specify outcomes, deliverable requirements, project constraints, and reasonable policies (such as security), but shall not exercise day-to-day supervision equivalent to that exercised over employees.\n\n5.5 Right of substitution (if applicable).\n\n(a) Where consistent with the SOW and security requirements, Consultant may provide a suitably skilled substitute to perform the Services, provided Consultant remains responsible for performance.\n\n(b) Client may reasonably refuse a proposed substitute on grounds of insufficient skills, security, compliance or conflicts of interest.\n\n5.6 Provision of equipment. Unless otherwise agreed, Consultant shall provide its own equipment and tools necessary to perform the Services. Where Client provides access to systems or equipment, Consultant shall comply with Client’s reasonable usage policies.\n\n5.7 Non-exclusivity. Subject to clause 9 (Confidentiality) and any conflict management agreed in writing, Consultant may provide services to other clients during the Term, provided that this does not materially interfere with Consultant’s ability to perform the Services and does not create a conflict of interest.\n\n5.8 No agency. Consultant shall not (and shall procure that Consultant Personnel shall not) represent that it has authority to bind Client. Consultant shall not incur any expense on behalf of Client without Client’s prior written approval.\n\n5.9 Responsibility for Consultant Personnel.\n\n(a) Consultant is solely responsible for all acts and omissions of Consultant Personnel as if they were Consultant’s own.\n\n(b) Consultant shall ensure all Consultant Personnel engaged in performing the Services are subject to written obligations consistent with this Agreement, including confidentiality, IP assignment (where applicable), data protection, and compliance obligations.\n\n5.10 Employment claims. Consultant shall be responsible for and shall indemnify Client against any claim by Consultant Personnel or any subcontractor that they are entitled to employment-related rights from Client (including claims for unfair dismissal, redundancy, holiday pay, discrimination, tax, or National Insurance), except to the extent caused by Client’s breach of this Agreement or unlawful act.\n\n5.11 IR35 alignment with working practices. The Parties agree to operate the engagement consistently with independent contractor status, including (where applicable) by ensuring that working practices reflect the parties’ intentions as set out in this clause 5. The Parties shall promptly notify the other if actual working practices materially deviate from those intended so that appropriate adjustments can be considered."},{"id":"insurance_audit","type":"standard","order":6,"title":"6. INSURANCE; RECORDS; AUDIT RIGHTS","content":"6.1 Insurance requirements. During the Term and for a period of at least six (6) years thereafter (or such longer period as may be required by Applicable Law), Consultant shall maintain with reputable insurers:\n\n(a) professional indemnity insurance with a limit of indemnity of not less than {{pi_insurance_amount}} per claim;\n\n(b) public liability insurance with a limit of indemnity of not less than {{pl_insurance_amount}} per claim; and\n\n(c) where Consultant has employees and Applicable Law requires it, employer’s liability insurance with a limit of indemnity of not less than {{employers_liability_amount}}.\n\n6.2 Evidence of insurance. On request, Consultant shall provide certificates of insurance and reasonable evidence of premium payment. Failure to maintain required insurance shall be a material breach.\n\n6.3 Records. Consultant shall maintain accurate and complete records relating to performance of the Services, time spent (if applicable), expenses (if applicable), and compliance with this Agreement for at least six (6) years following the later of (i) completion of the Services or (ii) termination of this Agreement.\n\n6.4 Audit (limited). Upon reasonable prior notice and no more than once in any 12-month period (unless required by a regulator or in connection with a suspected material breach), Client may audit Consultant’s records solely to verify: (a) invoiced time and expenses (where applicable); and/or (b) compliance with confidentiality and data protection obligations, provided that any audit:\n\n(a) is conducted during normal business hours;\n\n(b) is subject to Consultant’s reasonable security and confidentiality requirements;\n\n(c) does not unreasonably disrupt Consultant’s business; and\n\n(d) does not require disclosure of information relating to other clients.\n\n6.5 Costs of audit. Client shall bear its own audit costs. If an audit reveals material overcharging or material non-compliance, Consultant shall reimburse Client’s reasonable external audit costs and promptly remedy the non-compliance."},{"id":"term_termination","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. TERM; SUSPENSION; TERMINATION; EXIT","content":"7.1 Term. This Agreement commences on the Effective Date and continues until {{expiration_date}} (if specified), or if no expiration date is specified, until completion of the Services, unless terminated earlier in accordance with this clause 7 (the \"Term\").\n\n7.2 Termination for convenience. Either Party may terminate this Agreement (and/or any SOW) for convenience by giving not less than {{notice_period}} days’ written notice to the other Party.\n\n7.3 Suspension.\n\n(a) Client may require Consultant to temporarily suspend performance of the Services (in whole or part) for operational, security, compliance, or business continuity reasons, by giving written notice and (where practicable) specifying the expected duration.\n\n(b) During a suspension not caused by Consultant’s breach, the Parties shall agree in good faith the equitable consequences for Milestones and Charges (including demobilisation/remobilisation costs, if any).\n\n7.4 Termination for cause. Either Party may terminate this Agreement immediately by written notice if the other Party:\n\n(a) commits a material breach of this Agreement which (if capable of remedy) is not remedied within fourteen (14) days of receipt of a written notice requiring remedy; or\n\n(b) commits a series of breaches which, taken together, amount to a material breach; or\n\n(c) ceases, or threatens to cease, to carry on business; or\n\n(d) becomes insolvent, is unable to pay its debts as they fall due, enters into administration or liquidation, has a receiver appointed, or enters into any arrangement with creditors; or\n\n(e) engages in fraud, dishonesty, or wilful misconduct in connection with this Agreement.\n\n7.5 Termination for compliance risk (optional). Client may terminate immediately by written notice if Client reasonably believes that continuing the engagement would expose Client to a material risk of breaching Applicable Law (including the Bribery Act 2010, sanctions laws, or Data Protection Laws), provided Client has first (where reasonable) given Consultant an opportunity to propose and implement mitigation.\n\n7.6 Effect of termination or expiry.\n\n(a) Consultant shall promptly cease performing the terminated Services (except for any agreed transitional assistance under clause 7.7).\n\n(b) Client shall pay Consultant: (i) Charges for Services properly performed up to the effective date of termination; and (ii) any properly incurred and approved reimbursable expenses up to the effective date of termination.\n\n(c) If termination is due to Consultant’s material breach, Client may withhold payment for any Deliverables not Accepted and may recover any reasonable costs incurred in procuring substitute performance, to the extent permitted by law.\n\n(d) Each Party shall promptly return or (at the disclosing Party’s option) destroy the other Party’s Confidential Information in its possession or control, subject to clause 9.9 and clause 10.9 (retention where required).\n\n7.7 Exit and transitional assistance (optional). For up to {{termination_assistance_days}} days after termination (or such other period as agreed), Consultant shall provide reasonable assistance to transition the Services or knowledge to Client or a replacement supplier. Such assistance shall be charged at the rates in clause 4 unless termination was due to Consultant’s material breach, in which case it shall be provided at no additional cost to the extent reasonably necessary to mitigate Client’s loss.\n\n7.8 Survival. Clauses which by their nature are intended to survive termination or expiry shall survive, including (without limitation) clauses 4 (Fees—amounts due), 6 (Insurance; Records; Audit), 8 (Intellectual Property), 9 (Confidentiality), 10 (Data Protection), 11 (Warranties; Liability), 12 (Indemnities), and 14 (General Provisions)."},{"id":"intellectual_property","type":"negotiable","order":8,"title":"8. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; WORK PRODUCT; LICENCES","content":"8.1 Allocation of ownership.\n\n(a) As between the Parties, Client retains all right, title and interest in and to Client Materials and Client’s Background IPR.\n\n(b) As between the Parties, Consultant retains all right, title and interest in and to Consultant’s Background IPR.\n\n(c) Subject to clause 8.2, all Foreground IPR (as defined below) shall vest in Client upon creation.\n\n8.2 Assignment of Work Product and Foreground IPR.\n\n(a) In consideration of the Charges, Consultant hereby assigns to Client, by way of present assignment of future rights (to the fullest extent permitted by law), all right, title and interest in and to the Work Product and all Intellectual Property Rights in the Work Product created in the course of performing the Services (\"Foreground IPR\"), including all rights to sue for past and future infringement.\n\n(b) To the extent that any Foreground IPR does not vest in Client by operation of law or cannot be assigned at the time of creation, Consultant shall hold such rights on trust for Client and shall assign them to Client immediately upon creation or upon Client’s request.\n\n(c) Consultant shall ensure that each member of Consultant Personnel who creates any Work Product irrevocably assigns (or procures assignment of) the Foreground IPR to Consultant (or directly to Client, if requested), so that Consultant can give effect to clause 8.2(a).\n\n8.3 Moral rights. To the fullest extent permitted by the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988, Consultant hereby irrevocably waives, and shall procure the waiver of, all moral rights (and any similar rights in any jurisdiction) in the Work Product, including the right to be identified as author and the right to object to derogatory treatment.\n\n8.4 Further assurance. Consultant shall, at Client’s cost (if not due to Consultant’s breach), execute all documents and do all acts reasonably requested by Client to perfect, register, vest or enforce Client’s rights under this clause 8, including executing confirmatory assignments.\n\n8.5 Licence of Background IPR.\n\n(a) If, and only to the extent that, any Consultant Background IPR is incorporated into the Deliverables or is necessary for Client to receive and use the Deliverables, Consultant grants to Client (and Client’s Affiliates) a perpetual, worldwide, royalty-free, fully paid-up, irrevocable (except for Client’s material breach), non-exclusive licence (with the right to sub-licence to Client’s group companies, contractors and end users) to use, copy, modify, adapt, maintain, support and otherwise exploit such Consultant Background IPR solely to the extent necessary to use and benefit from the Deliverables.\n\n(b) Consultant warrants that it has the right to grant the licence in clause 8.5(a).\n\n8.6 Third-party materials.\n\n(a) Consultant shall not incorporate any third-party materials, code, datasets, images, fonts, or other content into the Deliverables unless: (i) Client has approved in writing; and (ii) Consultant has obtained appropriate licences that permit Client’s intended use.\n\n(b) Consultant shall identify in writing any third-party materials incorporated into Deliverables, including licence terms and attribution requirements, and shall provide copies of such licence terms upon request.\n\n8.7 Open source software (optional but recommended).\n\n(a) Consultant shall not include any open source software in the Deliverables in a manner that would: (i) require disclosure of Client’s proprietary source code; (ii) impose copyleft licensing obligations on Client; or (iii) otherwise restrict Client’s ability to use, commercialise, or license the Deliverables, unless Client has approved in writing.\n\n(b) Where open source software is approved, Consultant shall provide a list of open source components and applicable licences.\n\n8.8 Client feedback (optional). If Client provides feedback, suggestions, or ideas, Client grants Consultant a non-exclusive licence to use such feedback for Consultant’s business purposes, provided Consultant does not disclose Client Confidential Information.\n\n8.9 No implied licences. Except as expressly set out in this Agreement, no licence or transfer of IPR is granted or implied.\n\n8.10 Portfolio rights (optional). Consultant may not use Client’s name, trade marks, or the existence of the relationship in marketing materials or case studies without Client’s prior written consent."},{"id":"confidentiality","type":"standard","order":9,"title":"9. CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS; NON-DISCLOSURE","content":"9.1 Definition of Confidential Information. \"Confidential Information\" means all information (whether oral, written, visual, electronic or in any other form) disclosed by or on behalf of a Party (the \"Disclosing Party\") to the other Party (the \"Receiving Party\") in connection with this Agreement which is:\n\n(a) marked or stated to be confidential; or\n\n(b) by its nature or the circumstances of disclosure, ought reasonably to be regarded as confidential,\n\nincluding (without limitation) business plans, trade secrets, know-how, inventions, product plans, designs, processes, methods, financial information, pricing, customer and supplier information, security information, source code, technical information, personal data, and the terms of this Agreement.\n\n9.2 Confidentiality obligations. The Receiving Party shall:\n\n(a) keep the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information confidential and not disclose it to any third party except as permitted by this Agreement;\n\n(b) use the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information solely to perform its obligations and exercise its rights under this Agreement;\n\n(c) protect the Confidential Information using at least the same degree of care it uses to protect its own confidential information of similar importance, and in any event no less than reasonable care;\n\n(d) limit access to Confidential Information to those of its personnel, professional advisers, and permitted subcontractors who have a strict need to know for the purposes of this Agreement, and ensure such persons are bound by confidentiality obligations no less protective than those in this clause 9; and\n\n(e) promptly notify the Disclosing Party if it becomes aware of any unauthorised use or disclosure of Confidential Information.\n\n9.3 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by written evidence:\n\n(a) is or becomes public other than through a breach of this Agreement;\n\n(b) was lawfully known to the Receiving Party before disclosure by the Disclosing Party;\n\n(c) is lawfully received from a third party without restriction and without breach of any duty of confidentiality; or\n\n(d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.\n\n9.4 Permitted disclosures.\n\n(a) The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information to the extent required by Applicable Law, by any court of competent jurisdiction, or by any regulatory or supervisory authority (including a stock exchange).\n\n(b) Where reasonably practicable (and legally permitted), the Receiving Party shall: (i) give the Disclosing Party prompt written notice of the required disclosure; (ii) co-operate with the Disclosing Party to limit the disclosure; and (iii) disclose only the minimum information required.\n\n9.5 Trade secrets. The Parties acknowledge that certain Confidential Information may constitute trade secrets for the purposes of the Trade Secrets Regulations. Nothing in this Agreement limits or excludes any remedies available under the Trade Secrets Regulations or at common law, including injunctive relief.\n\n9.6 Duration. The obligations in this clause 9 shall continue during the Term and for {{confidentiality_term_years}} years after termination or expiry. In respect of trade secrets, confidentiality obligations shall continue for so long as the information remains a trade secret.\n\n9.7 Return or destruction.\n\n(a) On termination or expiry (or earlier on request), the Receiving Party shall promptly return or destroy the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information in its possession or control, and certify in writing (if requested) that it has done so.\n\n(b) Clause 9.7(a) does not require deletion of Confidential Information stored in routine back-ups, archives, or email retention systems, provided that: (i) such information remains protected in accordance with this Agreement; (ii) it is not readily accessible for ordinary business purposes; and (iii) it is deleted in accordance with the Receiving Party’s retention cycles.\n\n9.8 No press releases. Neither Party shall make any public announcement regarding this Agreement or the relationship without the other Party’s prior written consent, except as required by Applicable Law.\n\n9.9 Equitable relief. Each Party acknowledges that damages may be an inadequate remedy for breach of this clause 9 and that the Disclosing Party may seek injunctive or other equitable relief without prejudice to any other rights or remedies.\n\n9.10 Security of communications (optional). The Parties shall use reasonable endeavours to use secure methods for sharing Confidential Information and shall not send unencrypted Special Category Data by email unless expressly agreed and appropriate safeguards are in place."},{"id":"data_protection","type":"standard","order":10,"title":"10. DATA PROTECTION; UK GDPR; INFORMATION SECURITY","content":"10.1 Data protection roles. The Parties acknowledge that, in connection with the Services, Consultant may Process Personal Data. The roles are as follows (unless otherwise agreed in writing):\n\n(a) Client is the Controller of Personal Data contained in Client Materials and Personal Data processed for Client’s business purposes; and\n\n(b) Consultant acts as a Processor to the extent it Processes Personal Data on documented instructions from Client.\n\nIf the Parties are independent Controllers for any Processing activity, they shall each be responsible for their own compliance with Data Protection Laws in respect of that Processing.\n\n10.2 Compliance with Data Protection Laws. Each Party shall comply with its obligations under Data Protection Laws.\n\n10.3 Processor obligations (UK GDPR Article 28 terms). To the extent Consultant acts as a Processor, Consultant shall:\n\n(a) Process Personal Data only on documented instructions from Client (including with regard to transfers of Personal Data to a third country or international organisation), unless required to do so by Applicable Law; where required by law, Consultant shall (to the extent permitted) inform Client before Processing;\n\n(b) ensure that persons authorised to Process Personal Data have committed themselves to confidentiality or are under an appropriate statutory obligation of confidentiality;\n\n(c) implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure a level of security appropriate to the risk, including as appropriate measures described in {{security_measures}} and taking account of the state of the art, costs of implementation, and the nature, scope, context and purposes of Processing;\n\n(d) not engage another Processor (a \"Sub-processor\") without Client’s prior specific or general written authorisation. If general authorisation is provided, Consultant shall give Client reasonable prior notice of any intended changes concerning the addition or replacement of Sub-processors, giving Client the opportunity to object on reasonable grounds. Approved Sub-processors are listed at {{permitted_subprocessors}};\n\n(e) remain fully liable to Client for the performance of any Sub-processor’s obligations;\n\n(f) assist Client by appropriate technical and organisational measures, insofar as possible, to respond to requests for exercising Data Subject rights under Data Protection Laws;\n\n(g) assist Client in ensuring compliance with Client’s obligations pursuant to Articles 32 to 36 UK GDPR (security, breach notification, impact assessments, and prior consultation), taking into account the nature of Processing and information available to Consultant;\n\n(h) notify Client without undue delay (and in any event within 48 hours) after becoming aware of a Personal Data Breach affecting Personal Data processed on Client’s behalf, and provide information reasonably requested by Client to support Client’s compliance with breach notification obligations;\n\n(i) at Client’s choice, delete or return all Personal Data to Client after the end of the provision of Services relating to Processing, and delete existing copies unless Applicable Law requires storage;\n\n(j) make available to Client all information reasonably necessary to demonstrate compliance with this clause 10.3 and allow for and contribute to audits and inspections conducted by Client or an auditor mandated by Client, subject to reasonable confidentiality and security requirements and clause 6.4.\n\n10.4 Processing details. The subject matter, duration, nature and purpose of Processing, the types of Personal Data and categories of Data Subjects are described in {{data_processing_details}}.\n\n10.5 International transfers.\n\n(a) Consultant shall not transfer Personal Data processed on behalf of Client outside the UK (or to an international organisation) unless: (i) Client has given prior written instructions/authorisation; and (ii) appropriate safeguards are in place in accordance with Data Protection Laws.\n\n(b) The intended transfer mechanism (if any) is {{international_transfer_mechanism}}.\n\n10.6 Information security.\n\n(a) Consultant shall maintain and enforce appropriate information security policies and procedures designed to protect Confidential Information and Personal Data against accidental or unlawful destruction, loss, alteration, unauthorised disclosure, or access.\n\n(b) Consultant shall ensure Consultant Personnel follow secure access practices including least privilege access, strong authentication, and secure storage.\n\n(c) Consultant shall use reasonable endeavours to ensure Deliverables are free from viruses, malware, and known malicious code at the time of delivery.\n\n10.7 Prohibited data (optional). Unless expressly agreed in writing, Client shall not provide Consultant with Special Category Data or criminal offence data for Processing.\n\n10.8 Data minimisation. Consultant shall only access and Process the minimum amount of Personal Data reasonably necessary to provide the Services.\n\n10.9 Retention. Consultant shall not retain Personal Data processed on Client’s behalf for longer than necessary to perform the Services, except where retention is required by Applicable Law or reasonable back-up/archiving practices, subject always to confidentiality and security obligations.\n\n10.10 ICO and regulatory cooperation. If either Party receives a complaint, inquiry, notice, or investigation from the ICO or any competent authority relating to Processing under this Agreement, it shall (to the extent legally permitted) promptly inform the other Party and co-operate in good faith.\n\n10.11 Priority. If there is any conflict between this clause 10 and any other part of this Agreement regarding Personal Data Processing, this clause 10 shall prevail to the extent of the conflict."},{"id":"warranties_liability","type":"negotiable","order":11,"title":"11. REPRESENTATIONS; WARRANTIES; COMPLIANCE; LIMITATION OF LIABILITY","content":"11.1 Mutual authority. Each Party represents and warrants that:\n\n(a) it is duly organised and validly existing (where applicable) and has full power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement; and\n\n(b) the person signing this Agreement on its behalf is duly authorised to bind it.\n\n11.2 Consultant warranties. Consultant represents and warrants that:\n\n(a) it shall perform the Services with due skill, care and diligence and in accordance with clause 2.3;\n\n(b) it shall use appropriately skilled and qualified Consultant Personnel;\n\n(c) to the best of its knowledge and belief, the Deliverables and Work Product (excluding Client Materials) will not infringe the Intellectual Property Rights of any third party;\n\n(d) it will not knowingly introduce malware, backdoors, time bombs, or other malicious code into Client systems or Deliverables;\n\n(e) it has obtained and shall maintain all licences, permissions and consents necessary to perform the Services; and\n\n(f) it will comply with Applicable Law in performing the Services.\n\n11.3 Client warranties. Client represents and warrants that it has the right to provide Client Materials to Consultant for use in connection with the Services.\n\n11.4 Compliance with anti-bribery and corruption.\n\n(a) Each Party shall comply with the Bribery Act 2010.\n\n(b) Consultant shall not (and shall procure that Consultant Personnel shall not) offer, promise, give, request, agree to receive, or accept any financial or other advantage that would constitute an offence under the Bribery Act 2010.\n\n(c) Consultant shall maintain adequate procedures designed to prevent persons associated with Consultant from undertaking conduct that would constitute an offence under the Bribery Act 2010.\n\n11.5 Modern slavery and human trafficking (where applicable).\n\n(a) Consultant shall comply with the Modern Slavery Act 2015 and shall not engage in any activity, practice or conduct that would constitute an offence under sections 1, 2 or 4 of that Act.\n\n(b) Where Consultant is required to publish a slavery and human trafficking statement, Consultant shall, on request, provide Client with a copy of its most recent statement and/or a link to where it is published.\n\n(c) Consultant shall include in its contracts with subcontractors (where appropriate and proportionate) anti-slavery and human trafficking provisions consistent with this clause.\n\n11.6 Conflicts of interest. Consultant warrants that, as at the Effective Date, it has disclosed to Client any actual conflict of interest known to Consultant that would materially affect performance of the Services. Consultant shall promptly notify Client if a conflict arises during the Term.\n\n11.7 Disclaimer. Except as expressly set out in this Agreement, all warranties, conditions and other terms implied by statute or common law are excluded to the fullest extent permitted by law, including implied warranties of satisfactory quality and fitness for a particular purpose.\n\n11.8 Limitation of liability.\n\n(a) Subject to clause 11.9, neither Party shall be liable to the other for any loss of profits, loss of business, loss of anticipated savings, loss of goodwill, or indirect or consequential loss arising out of or in connection with this Agreement.\n\n(b) Subject to clause 11.9, each Party’s total aggregate liability to the other arising out of or in connection with this Agreement (whether in contract, tort (including negligence), breach of statutory duty, misrepresentation, restitution or otherwise) shall not exceed {{liability_cap}}.\n\n(c) If {{liability_cap}} is not specified, the cap in clause 11.8(b) shall be the total Charges paid or payable by Client to Consultant in the twelve (12) months immediately preceding the event giving rise to the claim.\n\n11.9 Unlimited and non-excludable liability. Nothing in this Agreement excludes or limits either Party’s liability for:\n\n(a) death or personal injury caused by its negligence;\n\n(b) fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation;\n\n(c) any other liability which cannot be excluded or limited under Applicable Law;\n\n(d) (optional) breach of clause 9 (Confidentiality) to the extent such limitation is prohibited by Applicable Law.\n\n11.10 Mitigation. Each Party shall use reasonable endeavours to mitigate any loss it suffers arising out of or in connection with this Agreement.\n\n11.11 Allocation of risk. The Parties acknowledge that the limitations and exclusions in this clause 11 are reasonable in light of the Charges, the nature of the Services, and the Parties’ respective commercial positions, and that the Charges reflect this allocation of risk."},{"id":"indemnification","type":"negotiable","order":12,"title":"12. INDEMNITIES","content":"12.1 Consultant indemnity—IPR infringement. Consultant shall indemnify and keep indemnified Client (and its Affiliates, directors, officers and employees) against all losses, damages, liabilities, costs and expenses (including reasonable legal fees) suffered or incurred arising from any third-party claim alleging that the Deliverables or Work Product (excluding Client Materials) infringe any third party’s Intellectual Property Rights, provided that Client complies with clause 12.4.\n\n12.2 Consultant indemnity—negligence and misconduct. Consultant shall indemnify and keep indemnified Client against all losses, damages, liabilities, costs and expenses arising from:\n\n(a) Consultant’s negligence or wilful misconduct in connection with performance of the Services; or\n\n(b) bodily injury (including death) or damage to tangible property caused by Consultant or Consultant Personnel, to the extent attributable to Consultant.\n\n12.3 Client indemnity—Client Materials. Client shall indemnify and keep indemnified Consultant against all losses, damages, liabilities, costs and expenses arising from any third-party claim alleging that Client Materials infringe any third party’s Intellectual Property Rights, provided Consultant complies with clause 12.4.\n\n12.4 Indemnity procedure.\n\n(a) The indemnified Party shall: (i) notify the indemnifying Party in writing as soon as reasonably practicable upon becoming aware of the claim; (ii) provide reasonable information and co-operation; and (iii) not admit liability or settle the claim without the indemnifying Party’s prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed).\n\n(b) The indemnifying Party shall have the right to control the defence and settlement of the claim, provided that it uses competent counsel and does not settle in a manner that imposes any admission of fault or ongoing obligations on the indemnified Party without the indemnified Party’s consent.\n\n(c) The indemnified Party may participate in the defence at its own cost with counsel of its choosing.\n\n12.5 IPR infringement remedies. Without prejudice to Client’s other remedies, if a Deliverable is or is likely to become subject to an infringement claim, Consultant shall, at its option and expense:\n\n(a) procure for Client the right to continue using the Deliverable;\n\n(b) modify or replace the Deliverable so that it is non-infringing while materially preserving functionality; or\n\n(c) if neither (a) nor (b) is reasonably practicable, refund to Client the portion of Charges paid for the affected Deliverable (on a straight-line depreciation basis over 36 months unless otherwise agreed) and, where applicable, terminate the affected SOW.\n\n12.6 Indemnity exclusions. Consultant shall have no liability under clause 12.1 to the extent the claim arises from:\n\n(a) Client Materials or specifications provided by Client;\n\n(b) modifications to the Deliverable not made by or on behalf of Consultant;\n\n(c) combination of the Deliverable with third-party products or systems not contemplated by the SOW, where the claim would not have arisen but for such combination; or\n\n(d) use of the Deliverable other than in accordance with this Agreement or reasonable instructions provided by Consultant.\n\n12.7 Relationship to limitation of liability. The indemnities in this clause 12 are subject to the limitations and exclusions in clause 11, except where and to the extent such limitations are prohibited by Applicable Law."},{"id":"optional_non_solicitation","type":"optional","order":13,"title":"13. OPTIONAL — NON-SOLICITATION; RESTRICTIVE COVENANTS","content":"13.1 Purpose and reasonableness. The Parties acknowledge that the restrictions in this clause 13 are intended to protect legitimate business interests including Client’s confidential information, workforce stability, and customer connections, and are intended to be reasonable in scope and duration.\n\n13.2 Non-solicitation of personnel (mutual or one-way).\n\n(a) During the Term and for {{non_solicitation_term_months}} months thereafter, Consultant shall not directly solicit for employment or engagement any employee, worker, or contractor of Client with whom Consultant (or Consultant Personnel) had material dealings in connection with the Services.\n\n(b) This clause 13.2 does not prohibit general recruitment advertising not targeted at such individuals.\n\n(c) (Optional mutuality) If agreed in writing, Client shall be subject to an equivalent restriction in respect of Consultant’s employees materially involved in the Services.\n\n13.3 Non-solicitation of clients/customers (optional). During the Term and for {{non_solicitation_term_months}} months thereafter, Consultant shall not knowingly solicit or entice away any customer or prospective customer of Client with whom Consultant had material contact through performing the Services, where such solicitation relates to services competing with the Services.\n\n13.4 Non-compete (highly negotiable; use with caution). During the Term and for a period of {{non_solicitation_term_months}} months thereafter, Consultant shall not provide services that are materially similar to the Services to a named competitor list agreed in writing, within {{restrictive_covenant_territory}}.\n\n13.5 Severance. If any restriction in this clause 13 is found unenforceable, it shall apply with such modifications as are necessary to make it enforceable to the maximum extent permitted by law.\n\n13.6 Injunctive relief. The Parties acknowledge that breach of this clause 13 may cause irreparable harm for which damages may be inadequate, and that the non-breaching Party may seek injunctive relief without prejudice to other remedies."},{"id":"general","type":"standard","order":14,"title":"14. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"14.1 Notices.\n\n(a) Any notice given under or in connection with this Agreement shall be in writing and shall be:\n\n(i) delivered by hand or courier to the address of the relevant Party set out in the preamble (or as otherwise notified);\n\n(ii) sent by pre-paid recorded delivery or special delivery post to such address; or\n\n(iii) sent by email to: Client: {{party_a_email}}; Consultant: {{party_b_email}}.\n\n(b) Notices shall be deemed received:\n\n(i) if delivered by hand or courier, on signature of a delivery receipt;\n\n(ii) if sent by recorded/special delivery post, at 9.00 am on the second Business Day after posting; and\n\n(iii) if sent by email, at the time of transmission provided no delivery failure notice is received, but if sent outside business hours it shall be deemed received at 9.00 am on the next Business Day.\n\n14.2 Assignment and subcontracting.\n\n(a) Neither Party may assign, transfer, charge, mortgage or deal in any other manner with any of its rights or obligations under this Agreement without the prior written consent of the other Party, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed.\n\n(b) Notwithstanding clause 14.2(a), Client may assign this Agreement to an Affiliate or successor in connection with a merger, reorganisation, or sale of all or substantially all of its assets, provided it gives written notice to Consultant.\n\n(c) Consultant may not subcontract performance of the Services without Client’s prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed). Consultant remains fully responsible for any subcontracted obligations.\n\n14.3 Entire agreement. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties and supersedes all prior discussions, correspondence, negotiations and understandings relating to its subject matter. Each Party acknowledges that it does not rely on any statement, representation, assurance or warranty not set out in this Agreement, except that nothing in this clause limits liability for fraud.\n\n14.4 Variation. No variation of this Agreement shall be effective unless it is in writing and signed by authorised representatives of both Parties.\n\n14.5 Severability. If any provision (or part-provision) of this Agreement is found by any court or competent authority to be invalid, illegal or unenforceable, it shall be deemed modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it valid, legal and enforceable. If such modification is not possible, the relevant provision (or part-provision) shall be deemed deleted. Any modification or deletion shall not affect the validity and enforceability of the rest of this Agreement.\n\n14.6 Waiver. A waiver of any right or remedy under this Agreement is only effective if given in writing and shall not be deemed a waiver of any subsequent breach or default.\n\n14.7 Force majeure. Neither Party shall be in breach of this Agreement nor liable for delay in performing, or failure to perform, any of its obligations (except payment obligations) if such delay or failure results from a Force Majeure Event. The affected Party shall: (a) promptly notify the other Party; (b) use reasonable endeavours to mitigate; and (c) resume performance as soon as reasonably practicable. If the Force Majeure Event continues for more than 30 days, either Party may terminate the affected SOW or this Agreement on written notice.\n\n14.8 No partnership or joint venture. Nothing in this Agreement is intended to, or shall be deemed to, establish any partnership or joint venture between the Parties, constitute either Party as the agent of the other, or authorise either Party to make or enter into any commitments for or on behalf of the other.\n\n14.9 Third party rights.\n\n(a) Except as provided in clause 14.9(b), a person who is not a Party to this Agreement shall not have any rights to enforce any term of this Agreement under the Contracts (Rights of Third Parties) Act 1999.\n\n(b) Client’s Affiliates and any persons indemnified under clause 12 may enforce clauses 9 (Confidentiality), 10 (Data Protection), 11 (Liability) and 12 (Indemnities) as if they were Parties, subject to the Parties’ right to vary or terminate this Agreement without the consent of such third parties.\n\n14.10 Counterparts; electronic signatures. This Agreement may be executed in any number of counterparts, each of which is an original and all of which together form one instrument. Execution and delivery by electronic signature (including via an e-signature platform) shall be valid and binding in accordance with the Electronic Communications Act 2000.\n\n14.11 Costs. Each Party shall bear its own costs and expenses in connection with the negotiation, preparation and execution of this Agreement.\n\n14.12 Dispute resolution (optional escalation).\n\n(a) The Parties shall attempt in good faith to resolve any Dispute promptly by negotiation between senior representatives.\n\n(b) If the Dispute is not resolved within 14 days of written notice of the Dispute, the Parties may attempt to settle it by mediation in accordance with the mediation procedure of {{dispute_mediation_body}} (or, if blank, CEDR Model Mediation Procedure), unless either Party reasonably considers that urgent injunctive relief is required.\n\n(c) Nothing in this clause prevents either Party from seeking interim or injunctive relief from the courts.\n\n14.13 Governing law and jurisdiction. This Agreement and any Dispute or claim (including non-contractual disputes or claims) arising out of or in connection with it are governed by the law of England and Wales. The Parties irrevocably submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of the courts of England and Wales.\n\n14.14 Rights cumulative. The rights and remedies provided under this Agreement are cumulative and are not exclusive of any rights or remedies provided by law.\n\n14.15 Further assurance. Each Party shall, at its own cost, do and execute (or procure the doing and execution of) all such acts, documents and things as the other Party may reasonably require from time to time for the purpose of giving full effect to this Agreement."}]'::jsonb,
  signature_block = 'IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Agreement as of {{signature_date}}.

