-- Update: Freelance Services Agreement (England and Wales)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Freelance Services Agreement (the "Agreement") is made on {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date") between:

(A) {{party_a_company}} (company number (if applicable): {{party_a_company_number}}) whose registered office or principal place of business is at {{party_a_address}} ("Client"); and

(B) {{party_b_name}} of {{party_b_address}} trading as {{party_b_company}} (and/or company number (if applicable): {{party_b_company_number}}) ("Freelancer").

Client and Freelancer are each a "Party" and together the "Parties".

This Agreement sets out the terms on which Client engages Freelancer to provide the Services (as defined below).',
  recitals = 'A. Client wishes to obtain certain freelance services in connection with {{project_name}} and Freelancer represents that they have the skills, experience, and resources to provide those services.

B. The Parties intend that Freelancer will act as an independent contractor and not as an employee, worker, agent (save as expressly agreed), partner, or joint venturer of Client.

C. The Parties wish to record their agreement in writing, including in relation to scope, deliverables, acceptance, fees, intellectual property, confidentiality (including protection of trade secrets), data protection, and compliance with applicable laws.

Accordingly, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATION","content":"1.1 Definitions. In this Agreement, unless the context otherwise requires:\n\n1.1.1 \"Acceptance Criteria\" means any objective criteria for acceptance of Deliverables set out in the Statement of Work, in {{services_description}}, or otherwise agreed in writing by the Parties.\n\n1.1.2 \"Acceptance Period\" means the period of {{acceptance_period_days}} Business Days following delivery of a Deliverable during which Client may review and either accept or reject that Deliverable in accordance with Section 3.\n\n1.1.3 \"Affiliate\" means, in relation to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with, that Party from time to time.\n\n1.1.4 \"Agreement\" means this Freelance Services Agreement, including any schedules, annexes, and any Change Orders.\n\n1.1.5 \"Background IPR\" means all Intellectual Property Rights owned or controlled by Freelancer (or its licensors) that (a) exist prior to the Effective Date, or (b) are developed outside the scope of the Services without use of Client Confidential Information, including Freelancer tools, templates, libraries, methodologies, know-how, and generic skills.\n\n1.1.6 \"Bribery Laws\" means the Bribery Act 2010 and any guidance issued under it.\n\n1.1.7 \"Business Day\" means a day other than a Saturday, Sunday, or public holiday in England when banks in London are open for business.\n\n1.1.8 \"Change Order\" means a written change order (including by email confirmation) agreed in accordance with Section 5 which changes the Services, Deliverables, Milestones, Fees, or any other aspect of performance.\n\n1.1.9 \"Client Materials\" means all materials, content, data, documentation, designs, specifications, systems access, software, trademarks, brand guidelines, and other information provided by or on behalf of Client to Freelancer for the purposes of performing the Services.\n\n1.1.10 \"Client Policies\" means Client’s written policies notified to Freelancer from time to time which apply to contractors while on Client premises or accessing Client systems (including information security, acceptable use, and health and safety policies), provided that such policies do not unreasonably prevent Freelancer from performing the Services or change the agreed scope without a Change Order.\n\n1.1.11 \"Confidential Information\" has the meaning given in Section 11.1.\n\n1.1.12 \"Controller\", \"Processor\", \"Personal Data\", \"Processing\" (and \"Process\"), \"Special Category Data\", and \"Personal Data Breach\" have the meanings given in the UK GDPR.\n\n1.1.13 \"Data Protection Laws\" means all applicable laws and regulatory requirements relating to the Processing of Personal Data, including the UK GDPR, the Data Protection Act 2018, and (where applicable) the Privacy and Electronic Communications (EC Directive) Regulations 2003.\n\n1.1.14 \"Deliverables\" means the deliverables, work products, outputs, and other items to be produced by Freelancer for Client as part of the Services, as described in the Statement of Work and/or {{services_description}}, and any additional deliverables agreed in a Change Order.\n\n1.1.15 \"Disputed Amount\" means any portion of an invoice that Client disputes in good faith in accordance with Section 6.11.\n\n1.1.16 \"Effective Date\" has the meaning given in the preamble.\n\n1.1.17 \"Expenses\" means reasonable out-of-pocket expenses necessarily incurred by Freelancer in performing the Services and expressly approved in advance in writing by Client in accordance with Section 8.\n\n1.1.18 \"Fees\" means the fees payable for the Services as set out in Section 6 and/or the Statement of Work.\n\n1.1.19 \"Force Majeure Event\" means an event or circumstance beyond a Party’s reasonable control, which by the exercise of reasonable diligence the affected Party could not prevent or overcome, including (as examples) natural disasters, epidemic or pandemic, war, terrorism, civil unrest, strikes (excluding strikes by the affected Party’s personnel), failure of utilities, and lawful acts of government.\n\n1.1.20 \"Intellectual Property Rights\" or \"IPR\" means all intellectual property rights anywhere in the world, whether registered or unregistered, including copyright and related rights, database rights, trade marks, service marks, trade names, domain names, goodwill, design rights, patents, utility models, rights in inventions, rights in confidential information and trade secrets, and all applications, renewals, and extensions of any of them.\n\n1.1.21 \"IR35\" means the off-payroll working rules and associated legislation and guidance, including Chapter 10 of Part 2 of ITEPA 2003 and associated regulations, and (where relevant) the intermediaries legislation in Chapter 8 of Part 2 of ITEPA 2003.\n\n1.1.22 \"Milestones\" means the milestones and dates set out in the Statement of Work, {{services_description}}, or otherwise agreed in writing.\n\n1.1.23 \"Modern Slavery Laws\" means the Modern Slavery Act 2015 and any related guidance.\n\n1.1.24 \"Open Source Software\" means any software subject to open source or similar licensing terms that may impose obligations such as disclosure of source code, licensing of derivative works, or attribution requirements.\n\n1.1.25 \"Permitted Purpose\" means performance of this Agreement and, where applicable, the receipt and internal use by Client of the Deliverables and Work Product.\n\n1.1.26 \"Services\" means the professional and/or technical services described in Section 2 and in {{services_description}}, together with any additional services agreed in a Change Order.\n\n1.1.27 \"Statement of Work\" or \"SOW\" means any statement of work, proposal, brief, specification, or schedule identified as such and agreed by the Parties, including {{statement_of_work_reference}} (if any). If there is no separate SOW, then {{services_description}} forms the SOW for the purposes of this Agreement.\n\n1.1.28 \"Sub-processor\" means any Processor engaged by Freelancer to Process Personal Data on behalf of Client.\n\n1.1.29 \"Term\" has the meaning given in Section 14.1.\n\n1.1.30 \"Trade Secrets\" means information that meets the definition of a trade secret under the Trade Secrets (Enforcement, etc.) Regulations 2018.\n\n1.1.31 \"VAT\" means value added tax chargeable in the UK or any similar sales tax in any other jurisdiction.\n\n1.1.32 \"Work Product\" means all Deliverables and all other works, materials, inventions, designs, documentation, reports, code, content, and other outputs created, developed, written, or prepared by Freelancer (alone or jointly) in the course of performing the Services, excluding Freelancer Background IPR and excluding third-party materials not assigned to Freelancer.\n\n1.1.33 \"Working Practices\" means how the Services are actually carried out in practice (including control, supervision, substitution, and integration) for IR35 purposes.\n\n1.2 Interpretation.\n\n1.2.1 References to Sections are to sections of this Agreement.\n\n1.2.2 A reference to \"including\" shall be construed as \"including without limitation\".\n\n1.2.3 Words in the singular include the plural and vice versa.\n\n1.2.4 Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation.\n\n1.2.5 If there is a conflict between documents forming part of this Agreement, the following order of precedence applies unless expressly stated otherwise in a Change Order: (a) any Change Order; (b) this Agreement; (c) the SOW; (d) any other document referenced.\n\n1.2.6 Any obligation on a Party not to do something includes an obligation not to permit or assist another person to do that thing."},{"id":"services","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. SERVICES; SCOPE; CLIENT RESPONSIBILITIES","content":"2.1 Engagement. Client engages Freelancer to perform the Services for the Term, and Freelancer accepts such engagement, in accordance with this Agreement.\n\n2.2 Scope and SOW.\n\n2.2.1 The Services, Deliverables, Milestones, and any Acceptance Criteria are set out in the SOW and/or {{services_description}}.\n\n2.2.2 Any work outside the scope described in the SOW constitutes out-of-scope work and will only be performed pursuant to a Change Order.\n\n2.3 Standard of performance. Freelancer shall perform the Services with reasonable skill and care, in a professional manner, and in accordance with (a) good industry practice; (b) any applicable Acceptance Criteria; and (c) all applicable laws and regulations.\n\n2.4 Method of working.\n\n2.4.1 Subject to compliance with this Agreement and meeting agreed deadlines, Freelancer has discretion as to the manner, method, and means of performing the Services.\n\n2.4.2 Where Client requires attendance at Client premises, such requirement must be set out in the SOW (or agreed in writing). While on Client premises, Freelancer shall comply with Client Policies provided in advance.\n\n2.5 Client cooperation and dependencies. Client shall, in a timely manner:\n\n2.5.1 provide accurate Client Materials and information reasonably required to perform the Services;\n\n2.5.2 provide access to relevant systems, accounts, stakeholders, and decision-makers where required;\n\n2.5.3 review and provide feedback/approvals within the timeframes stated in this Agreement or the SOW; and\n\n2.5.4 nominate a primary point of contact: {{client_project_contact_name}} (email: {{client_project_contact_email}}).\n\n2.6 Assumptions. Unless the SOW states otherwise, the Fees and timeline are based on the assumptions that Client will comply with Section 2.5 and that Client Materials are complete and accurate. Any delays or additional work caused by Client’s failure to meet these assumptions may result in adjustments via a Change Order.\n\n2.7 Reporting and communications. Freelancer shall provide reasonable status updates at the cadence described in the SOW (or, if none, upon reasonable request). Client shall provide consolidated feedback where practicable.\n\n2.8 Subcontracting.\n\n2.8.1 Freelancer may not subcontract or assign performance of the Services (other than as permitted in Section 9.6 regarding substitution for IR35 purposes) without Client’s prior written consent.\n\n2.8.2 Where consent is given, Freelancer remains responsible for the acts and omissions of any subcontractor as if they were Freelancer’s own.\n\n2.9 Client systems and security. If Freelancer is granted access to Client systems, Freelancer shall use such access solely for the Permitted Purpose and comply with any reasonable security requirements notified by Client, including MFA and least-privilege access where available.\n\n2.10 No legal or regulated advice. Unless expressly stated in the SOW, Freelancer is not providing legal, tax, regulated financial, or other regulated professional advice, and Client remains responsible for obtaining such advice where required."},{"id":"deliverables_acceptance","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. DELIVERABLES; REVIEW; ACCEPTANCE","content":"3.1 Delivery. Freelancer shall deliver Deliverables in the format(s) and via the delivery method(s) specified in the SOW, or if not specified, via a reasonable method agreed between the Parties (for example, secure file transfer, a shared repository, or email for smaller files).\n\n3.2 Review and acceptance process.\n\n3.2.1 Following delivery, Client shall have the Acceptance Period to review the Deliverable against the Acceptance Criteria.\n\n3.2.2 Client shall notify Freelancer in writing within the Acceptance Period either that the Deliverable is accepted or that it is rejected.\n\n3.2.3 Any rejection notice must describe in reasonable detail the specific respects in which the Deliverable fails to meet the Acceptance Criteria (or, if no Acceptance Criteria exist, the material respects in which it fails to conform to the SOW).\n\n3.3 Deemed acceptance. If Client does not provide an acceptance or rejection notice within the Acceptance Period, the Deliverable shall be deemed accepted on the next Business Day.\n\n3.4 Remedy for non-conforming Deliverables.\n\n3.4.1 If Client rejects a Deliverable in accordance with Section 3.2, Freelancer shall, as Client’s sole and exclusive remedy for that non-conformity, use reasonable efforts to remedy the non-conformity and re-deliver the Deliverable within a reasonable period (taking into account the nature of the issue and any dependencies on Client).\n\n3.4.2 Client shall then have a further Acceptance Period to review the re-delivered Deliverable.\n\n3.5 Limitations.\n\n3.5.1 Acceptance testing is limited to verifying conformity with the SOW and Acceptance Criteria. It does not include extensive performance, security, penetration, or compliance testing unless expressly included in the SOW.\n\n3.5.2 Client is responsible for final decisions regarding deployment, publication, or use of Deliverables.\n\n3.6 Partial acceptance. Where a Deliverable consists of separable components, Client may accept conforming components and reject only the non-conforming component(s), provided Client identifies those components with reasonable clarity.\n\n3.7 Client delay. If Client delays review, feedback, approvals, or acceptance, any affected Milestones shall be equitably adjusted.\n\n3.8 No waiver. Acceptance of a Deliverable does not waive Client’s rights in respect of any latent defects that could not reasonably have been discovered during the Acceptance Period, nor does it waive any rights relating to infringement claims under Section 17 (Indemnification), subject always to the limitations in Section 16 (Liability)."},{"id":"timeline_milestones","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TIMELINE; MILESTONES; SUSPENSION","content":"4.1 Timeline. The anticipated schedule and Milestones are set out in {{milestone_schedule}} and/or the SOW.\n\n4.2 Time is not of the essence. Unless expressly stated in the SOW, time shall not be of the essence in respect of the performance of the Services or delivery of Deliverables.\n\n4.3 Dependencies and assumptions. Client acknowledges that delivery dates may depend on timely input, approvals, and access from Client in accordance with Section 2.5.\n\n4.4 Delays.\n\n4.4.1 If Freelancer becomes aware of any matter likely to materially affect delivery, Freelancer shall notify Client as soon as reasonably practicable with an explanation and a proposed mitigation plan.\n\n4.4.2 Where delay is caused by Client (including late feedback, late provision of materials, scope changes, or access issues), the timeline and Milestones shall be adjusted accordingly and any additional work shall be addressed via a Change Order.\n\n4.5 Suspension for non-payment. Without prejudice to any other rights, if Client fails to pay any undisputed invoice by the due date, Freelancer may suspend performance upon giving at least 5 Business Days’ written notice, until payment is received. Any suspension may result in an equitable adjustment to Milestones.\n\n4.6 Suspension for legal/compliance concerns. Freelancer may suspend performance to the extent required to comply with applicable law, a regulator request, or to address a material information security risk relating to Client systems, provided Freelancer promptly notifies Client and resumes performance as soon as practicable.\n\n4.7 Force Majeure.\n\n4.7.1 Neither Party shall be liable for delay or failure to perform caused by a Force Majeure Event.\n\n4.7.2 The affected Party shall (a) promptly notify the other Party; (b) use reasonable endeavours to mitigate the effects; and (c) resume performance as soon as reasonably practicable.\n\n4.7.3 If a Force Majeure Event continues for more than 30 days and materially prevents performance, either Party may terminate the Agreement on written notice. In such case Client shall pay Fees properly due for Services performed up to termination and any non-cancellable committed costs pre-approved by Client."},{"id":"changes","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. CHANGES; CHANGE ORDERS","content":"5.1 No informal scope creep. Client acknowledges that changes to scope, Deliverables, priorities, assumptions, or timelines can impact Fees and Milestones. Any change must be managed through the Change Order process in this Section 5.\n\n5.2 Change request. Either Party may propose a change by providing written notice describing the requested change in reasonable detail.\n\n5.3 Change assessment. Within a reasonable time after receiving a change request, Freelancer shall (where appropriate) provide a written assessment including:\n\n5.3.1 the impact on Fees (including any additional Fees at the rates in Section 6);\n\n5.3.2 the impact on Milestones and delivery dates;\n\n5.3.3 any additional Client responsibilities or dependencies; and\n\n5.3.4 any impact on technical approach, quality, or risk.\n\n5.4 Agreement and authorisation.\n\n5.4.1 A change shall only be binding when the Parties agree it in writing as a Change Order.\n\n5.4.2 Emails are sufficient to constitute a Change Order if they clearly identify the change and are sent/confirmed by the authorised representatives set out in Section 21.\n\n5.5 Commencement. Freelancer is not required to begin work on any changed scope until a Change Order is agreed.\n\n5.6 Rate card. Unless the Change Order states otherwise, additional work will be charged at {{hourly_rate}} per day (or pro-rated for part-days) and/or at the applicable rate stated in the SOW.\n\n5.7 Emergency changes. Where urgent changes are required to avoid material harm to Client (for example, a critical production issue) and Client requests immediate assistance, the Parties may agree an interim instruction by email, with a Change Order to follow as soon as practicable. Freelancer’s work in response will be chargeable unless the Parties expressly agree otherwise."},{"id":"payment","type":"standard","order":6,"title":"6. FEES; INVOICING; PAYMENT TERMS; TAX","content":"6.1 Fees structure. The Fees shall be as set out in the SOW and/or {{services_description}}, and may include one or more of the following (as applicable):\n\n6.1.1 a fixed project fee of {{payment_amount}};\n\n6.1.2 time and materials at {{hourly_rate}} per day (or pro-rated); and/or\n\n6.1.3 a retainer of {{retainer_amount}} per month.\n\n6.2 Currency. Unless otherwise stated, all amounts are in {{payment_currency}}.\n\n6.3 VAT. Fees and Expenses are exclusive of VAT. Where VAT is chargeable, Freelancer shall add VAT at the applicable rate to its invoices and Client shall pay such VAT in addition, subject to receipt of a valid VAT invoice.\n\n6.4 Deposit (optional). If stated in the SOW, Client shall pay a deposit of {{deposit_amount}} within 7 days of the Effective Date. Unless otherwise stated, the deposit is creditable against future invoices and is non-refundable except where this Agreement is terminated by Client for Freelancer’s material breach.\n\n6.5 Invoicing.\n\n6.5.1 Freelancer shall invoice Client in accordance with the SOW and/or {{invoice_frequency}} (or, if not specified, monthly in arrears for time and materials, and upon completion of Milestones for fixed-fee work).\n\n6.5.2 Each invoice shall include sufficient detail to enable Client to understand the Services performed, including dates, relevant Milestones, and Expenses (if any).\n\n6.6 Payment due date. Client shall pay all undisputed invoices in full and in cleared funds within {{invoice_due_days}} days of receipt, to the bank account specified by Freelancer: {{freelancer_bank_details}}.\n\n6.7 No set-off. Client shall not withhold, set-off, or deduct any amounts from invoices except as required by law or as expressly agreed in writing.\n\n6.8 Late payment.\n\n6.8.1 If Client fails to pay an undisputed invoice by the due date, Freelancer may charge statutory interest and compensation under the Late Payment of Commercial Debts (Interest) Act 1998.\n\n6.8.2 Without prejudice to Section 4.5, Freelancer may also recover reasonable costs of collection where permitted by law.\n\n6.9 Expenses.\n\n6.9.1 Expenses are only payable if (a) expressly permitted in the SOW, and (b) pre-approved in writing by Client in accordance with Section 8.\n\n6.9.2 Unless otherwise agreed, the maximum reimbursable Expenses shall not exceed {{expense_cap_amount}} in total.\n\n6.10 Timesheets and verification (time and materials).\n\n6.10.1 If Fees are time-based, Freelancer shall, if requested, provide reasonable records of time spent.\n\n6.10.2 Client shall raise any query regarding time records within 10 Business Days of receipt; otherwise, time records shall be deemed accepted for invoicing purposes.\n\n6.11 Disputed invoices.\n\n6.11.1 If Client disputes an invoice, Client shall notify Freelancer in writing within 10 Business Days of receipt, specifying the basis of the dispute and the amount in dispute.\n\n6.11.2 Client shall pay the undisputed portion by the due date. The Parties shall use good faith efforts to resolve the dispute promptly.\n\n6.12 Suspension for non-payment. Freelancer’s rights to suspend under Section 4.5 apply only in relation to undisputed amounts.\n\n6.13 Taxes and National Insurance.\n\n6.13.1 Unless Section 9 (IR35) requires otherwise, Freelancer is responsible for all taxes, National Insurance contributions, and other statutory payments arising from sums paid under this Agreement.\n\n6.13.2 Client shall not be responsible for any employer’s National Insurance contributions, apprenticeship levy, pension contributions, holiday pay, sick pay, or other employment-related liabilities in relation to Freelancer.\n\n6.14 Withholding where required by law. If any withholding is required by law, Client shall (a) notify Freelancer; (b) provide evidence of payment to the relevant authority; and (c) co-operate to reduce or reclaim withholding where lawfully possible.\n\n6.15 Audit (limited). On reasonable notice, and no more than once in any 12-month period, Client may audit records reasonably necessary to verify invoices for time and materials work, provided (a) the audit is during normal business hours; (b) it does not unreasonably disrupt Freelancer; and (c) Client bears its own costs. Client shall keep any information obtained confidential."},{"id":"revisions","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. REVISIONS; CLIENT FEEDBACK","content":"7.1 Included revisions (if applicable). If the SOW specifies that revisions are included, the Fees include up to {{revision_rounds_included}} rounds of revisions for the relevant Deliverable(s). A \"round\" means one consolidated set of feedback from Client on a delivered item.\n\n7.2 Consolidated feedback. Client shall provide feedback in a consolidated manner through a single designated representative where practicable, to reduce rework and contradictory instructions.\n\n7.3 Feedback window. Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, Client shall provide feedback within {{revision_response_days}} Business Days of receipt of a Deliverable or draft.\n\n7.4 Out-of-scope revisions. The following are not included in revision rounds unless the SOW expressly states otherwise:\n\n7.4.1 changes resulting from changes in Client’s brief, brand, strategy, product requirements, or third-party requirements after commencement;\n\n7.4.2 significant changes requested after Client has approved a draft or accepted a Deliverable;\n\n7.4.3 work required due to Client’s provision of incorrect or incomplete Client Materials; and\n\n7.4.4 additional versions, formats, localisations, or platform variants not described in the SOW.\n\n7.5 Charging for additional revisions. Additional revisions or out-of-scope work will be handled via a Change Order and charged at the rates in Section 6.1.\n\n7.6 Effect on schedule. Client acknowledges that revision cycles may affect Milestones. Where Client feedback is delayed or extensive beyond what was assumed, the schedule may be adjusted through a Change Order or equitable adjustment under Section 4.\n\n7.7 No obligation to implement unlawful or infringing changes. Freelancer is not required to implement any requested change that would (a) breach law; (b) infringe third-party rights; or (c) materially compromise security or professional standards, provided Freelancer explains the concern and proposes reasonable alternatives."},{"id":"expenses","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. EXPENSES; CLIENT-PROVIDED ACCOUNTS; TOOLS","content":"8.1 General. Unless expressly stated in the SOW, Freelancer is responsible for its own costs and expenses incurred in performing the Services.\n\n8.2 Pre-approval required. Client shall only reimburse Expenses that are (a) reasonable and necessary; (b) specifically pre-approved in writing by Client; and (c) supported by receipts or other reasonable evidence.\n\n8.3 Travel and subsistence (if applicable). If travel is required, the SOW should specify permitted classes of travel and any daily limits. In the absence of such specification, Freelancer shall use reasonable endeavours to keep costs proportionate.\n\n8.4 Client-provided accounts and licences.\n\n8.4.1 Where the Services require access to Client-controlled platforms (e.g., hosting, analytics, advertising, design, or source control tools), Client shall provide appropriate accounts, licences, and permissions.\n\n8.4.2 Client remains responsible for payment of Client’s third-party platform fees unless the Parties agree otherwise in writing.\n\n8.5 Freelancer tools. Freelancer may use its own tools, templates, and methodologies in performing the Services. Any such use does not affect ownership of Background IPR under Section 10.\n\n8.6 Third-party purchases on Client’s behalf. Freelancer shall not purchase goods, media, or third-party services on Client’s behalf unless expressly authorised in writing (including a budget cap and approval workflow).\n\n8.7 No mark-up. Unless the SOW expressly permits a handling fee, Freelancer shall not mark up reimbursable Expenses."},{"id":"freelancer_status","type":"negotiable","order":9,"title":"9. INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR STATUS; OFF-PAYROLL WORKING (IR35)","content":"9.1 Independent contractor.\n\n9.1.1 The Parties intend that Freelancer is engaged as an independent contractor in business on its own account.\n\n9.1.2 Nothing in this Agreement creates, or shall be deemed to create, a relationship of employer/employee, worker, agency (save where expressly agreed), partnership, or joint venture.\n\n9.2 No employment rights. Freelancer is not entitled to and irrevocably waives any claim to (and Client shall have no liability for) holiday pay, sick pay, maternity/paternity pay, redundancy pay, notice pay, pension contributions, unfair dismissal protection, or any other employment-related rights or benefits.\n\n9.3 No mutuality of obligation. Client is not obliged to offer any minimum amount of work and Freelancer is not obliged to accept additional work outside the agreed scope. This Agreement relates only to the Services agreed and any additional Services agreed by Change Order.\n\n9.4 Control and autonomy. Subject to meeting the agreed Deliverables, Acceptance Criteria, and Milestones, Freelancer has autonomy over how the Services are performed, including selection of working location and hours, save where Client site access is required for operational or security reasons.\n\n9.5 Financial risk and business organisation. Freelancer is responsible for its own equipment, insurance, training, and business overheads, and bears the risk of profit or loss in the manner typical of an independent business.\n\n9.6 Substitution (IR35).\n\n9.6.1 Where consistent with the SOW and Client’s reasonable security requirements, Freelancer may provide a suitably qualified substitute to perform the Services.\n\n9.6.2 Freelancer shall remain responsible for the quality of the Services and Deliverables and for payment to any substitute.\n\n9.6.3 Client may refuse a proposed substitute on reasonable grounds (including lack of required skills, failure to meet security requirements, or conflicts of interest).\n\n9.7 Status determination and off-payroll rules.\n\n9.7.1 The Parties acknowledge that the application of IR35 depends on the facts and Working Practices.\n\n9.7.2 The intended status for this engagement is: {{ir35_status}}.\n\n9.7.3 Where Client is the \"end client\" and is responsible for making a status determination under Chapter 10 ITEPA 2003, Client shall use reasonable care in making that determination and, where legally required, provide Freelancer (and any relevant agency) with a status determination statement (\"SDS\"). Freelancer shall promptly notify Client of any circumstances indicating that the SDS may be inaccurate.\n\n9.7.4 Where the off-payroll rules apply and Client (or another fee-payer) is required by law to operate PAYE and account for tax and National Insurance contributions, then:\n\n(a) Fees shall be treated as inclusive of amounts subject to PAYE unless otherwise agreed in the SOW;\n\n(b) the fee-payer may make deductions required by law; and\n\n(c) Freelancer shall co-operate in providing information reasonably required to comply with the rules.\n\n9.7.5 Where Client is a \"small\" client for off-payroll purposes and the responsibility for IR35 compliance rests with Freelancer (or its intermediary), Freelancer shall be responsible for compliance with IR35 and for any tax, National Insurance, interest, and penalties arising from its failure to comply.\n\n9.8 Evidence and co-operation. Freelancer shall, upon reasonable request, provide evidence of (a) business insurance; (b) its business status (including VAT registration where applicable); and (c) its right to work in the UK, where this is required for lawful performance.\n\n9.9 No authority to bind. Freelancer has no authority to bind Client or to incur obligations on Client’s behalf unless Client expressly authorises this in writing.\n\n9.10 Agency supplies. If the Services are supplied via an agency, the Parties shall co-operate in good faith to ensure consistent documentation and Working Practices. This Agreement does not create any obligation for Client to contract with any agency.\n\n9.11 Employment-related claims. Freelancer shall indemnify Client against losses arising from any claim by Freelancer (or any substitute or subcontractor) that they are an employee or worker of Client, except to the extent such claim arises from Client’s breach of this Agreement or unlawful conduct. This indemnity is subject to Section 16 (Liability) to the extent permitted by law."},{"id":"intellectual_property","type":"negotiable","order":10,"title":"10. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; OWNERSHIP; LICENCES; MORAL RIGHTS","content":"10.1 Ownership framework. This Section 10 allocates ownership and licence rights between the Parties.\n\n10.2 Client Materials. Client (or its licensors) owns all IPR in Client Materials. Freelancer shall not acquire any rights in Client Materials except as strictly necessary to perform the Services.\n\n10.3 Ownership of Work Product.\n\n10.3.1 Subject to Section 10.6 (Freelancer Background IPR) and Section 10.7 (Third-party materials), and subject to full payment of all Fees and reimbursable Expenses due, Freelancer hereby assigns to Client, by way of present assignment of existing and future rights, all right, title, and interest in and to the Work Product and all IPR in it.\n\n10.3.2 The assignment in Section 10.3.1 includes all rights of copyright and related rights under the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988 and all other IPR, for the full term of such rights (including any extensions, renewals, and reversions), and applies worldwide.\n\n10.3.3 To the extent that any Work Product does not vest automatically or cannot be assigned by present assignment, Freelancer agrees to assign such rights to Client immediately upon creation and shall hold such rights on trust for Client until assignment is completed.\n\n10.4 Further assurance. Freelancer shall, at Client’s reasonable request and cost, execute documents and do such acts as are reasonably necessary to give effect to Section 10.3, including assisting with registering rights, provided such requests are made within 24 months after completion of the Services.\n\n10.5 Licence back (optional). Unless the SOW expressly grants a licence back, Client does not grant Freelancer any licence to use the Work Product except to the extent necessary to perform the Services and to maintain a portfolio right under Section 10.12.\n\n10.6 Freelancer Background IPR.\n\n10.6.1 Freelancer retains all right, title, and interest in and to Freelancer Background IPR.\n\n10.6.2 To the extent any Freelancer Background IPR is incorporated into the Work Product or is necessary for Client’s use of the Work Product, Freelancer grants to Client a perpetual, irrevocable, worldwide, non-exclusive, royalty-free licence (with the right to sub-licence to Client’s Affiliates, service providers, and end users as applicable) to use, reproduce, modify, adapt, and otherwise exploit such Background IPR as part of, or in connection with, the Work Product for the Permitted Purpose.\n\n10.7 Third-party materials and Open Source Software.\n\n10.7.1 Freelancer shall not include any third-party materials in the Deliverables that would materially restrict Client’s use of the Work Product (including Open Source Software with \"copyleft\" obligations) unless (a) disclosed to Client in advance in writing; and (b) approved by Client in writing.\n\n10.7.2 Where approved third-party materials are included, Client’s rights are subject to the applicable third-party licence terms, and Freelancer shall provide Client with details of those terms.\n\n10.7.3 Freelancer warrants that it will comply with the licence terms applicable to any Open Source Software it uses in delivering the Services and will not knowingly place Client in breach of such terms.\n\n10.8 Pre-existing client assets. If Client Materials are modified or adapted as part of the Services, Client owns the modified/derivative versions to the extent they constitute Work Product, subject to any continuing third-party rights in underlying materials.\n\n10.9 Moral rights.\n\n10.9.1 To the maximum extent permitted by law, Freelancer irrevocably waives any moral rights (including the right to be identified as author and the right to object to derogatory treatment) in the Work Product.\n\n10.9.2 Where moral rights cannot be waived, Freelancer irrevocably consents to Client and its licensees doing any act or omission that would otherwise infringe those moral rights.\n\n10.10 Client name and trade marks. Except as expressly permitted in Section 10.12 or otherwise agreed in writing, Freelancer shall not use Client’s name, trade marks, logos, or branding.\n\n10.11 Payment condition. The assignment in Section 10.3 is conditional upon Client’s payment in full of all Fees and reimbursable Expenses due. Until such payment, Freelancer grants Client a temporary, non-exclusive, non-transferable licence to use the Work Product solely for internal evaluation.\n\n10.12 Portfolio and self-promotion (optional).\n\n10.12.1 Unless Client opts out in writing, Freelancer may display non-confidential excerpts of the Work Product in its portfolio and marketing materials after public launch or publication by Client.\n\n10.12.2 Freelancer shall not disclose Client Confidential Information, Personal Data, or any materials that Client designates in writing as not permitted for publication.\n\n10.13 No implied licences. Other than as set out in this Agreement, no rights are granted by either Party to the other, whether by implication, estoppel, or otherwise."},{"id":"confidentiality","type":"standard","order":11,"title":"11. CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS","content":"11.1 Definition. \"Confidential Information\" means all information (in whatever form) disclosed by or on behalf of one Party (\"Discloser\") to the other Party (\"Recipient\") that is either (a) marked or identified as confidential; or (b) by its nature or the circumstances of disclosure, ought reasonably to be treated as confidential, including:\n\n11.1.1 business, financial, marketing, and product plans;\n\n11.1.2 customers, suppliers, pricing, and contracts;\n\n11.1.3 technical information, source code, designs, specifications, algorithms, models, and architecture;\n\n11.1.4 security information, access credentials, and vulnerability data;\n\n11.1.5 Personal Data (subject also to Section 12); and\n\n11.1.6 Trade Secrets.\n\n11.2 Confidentiality obligations. Recipient shall:\n\n11.2.1 use Confidential Information solely for the Permitted Purpose;\n\n11.2.2 keep Confidential Information secret and protect it using at least the same degree of care as it uses for its own confidential information of a similar nature, and in any event no less than reasonable care;\n\n11.2.3 not disclose Confidential Information to any third party except as permitted by Section 11.3; and\n\n11.2.4 take reasonable steps to prevent unauthorised access, copying, or use.\n\n11.3 Permitted disclosures. Recipient may disclose Confidential Information:\n\n11.3.1 to its employees, officers, professional advisers, insurers, and (where permitted) subcontractors who have a need to know for the Permitted Purpose and are bound by confidentiality obligations no less protective than this Section 11;\n\n11.3.2 where required by law, regulation, court order, or competent regulatory authority, provided Recipient (to the extent legally permitted) gives Discloser prompt notice and co-operates (at Discloser’s cost) to seek confidential treatment or limit disclosure; and\n\n11.3.3 with Discloser’s prior written consent.\n\n11.4 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that Recipient can demonstrate:\n\n11.4.1 is or becomes publicly available other than through breach of this Agreement;\n\n11.4.2 was lawfully known to Recipient before disclosure by Discloser;\n\n11.4.3 is lawfully received from a third party without restriction on disclosure; or\n\n11.4.4 is independently developed by Recipient without use of Discloser’s Confidential Information.\n\n11.5 Trade Secrets protection. The Parties acknowledge that unauthorised use or disclosure of Trade Secrets may cause significant harm. This Section 11 is intended to protect Trade Secrets within the meaning of the Trade Secrets (Enforcement, etc.) Regulations 2018.\n\n11.6 Return or destruction.\n\n11.6.1 Upon request and in any event upon termination of this Agreement, Recipient shall promptly return or securely destroy all Confidential Information in its possession or control, including copies, except that Recipient may retain one archival copy solely for legal, compliance, or insurance purposes.\n\n11.6.2 Any retained archival copy remains subject to this Agreement for so long as it is retained.\n\n11.7 No licence. Nothing in this Agreement grants Recipient any right or licence in Discloser’s Confidential Information except as necessary for the Permitted Purpose.\n\n11.8 Equitable relief. Each Party acknowledges that damages alone may be an inadequate remedy for breach of this Section 11. The non-breaching Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive or equitable relief in any competent court, in addition to any other remedies.\n\n11.9 Duration. The obligations in this Section 11 commence on the Effective Date and continue for {{confidentiality_period}} years after termination, provided that obligations relating to Trade Secrets shall continue for so long as the relevant information remains a trade secret under applicable law."},{"id":"data_protection","type":"standard","order":12,"title":"12. DATA PROTECTION; UK GDPR","content":"12.1 Roles.\n\n12.1.1 The Parties acknowledge that, for the purposes of Data Protection Laws, the Parties may act as (a) independent Controllers; or (b) Controller and Processor, depending on the nature of the Processing.\n\n12.1.2 Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, where Freelancer Processes Personal Data on behalf of Client solely to perform the Services, Client is the Controller and Freelancer is the Processor.\n\n12.2 Processing details. The subject matter, duration, nature and purpose of Processing, the types of Personal Data, and categories of data subjects are described in {{personal_data_description}} and/or the SOW (and if not specified, as reasonably necessary to perform the Services).\n\n12.3 Processor obligations (Article 28 UK GDPR). Where Freelancer acts as Processor, Freelancer shall:\n\n12.3.1 Process Personal Data only on documented instructions from Client (including those in this Agreement and the SOW) unless required by law, in which case Freelancer shall (to the extent permitted) inform Client of that legal requirement;\n\n12.3.2 ensure that persons authorised to Process Personal Data are subject to a duty of confidentiality;\n\n12.3.3 implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure a level of security appropriate to the risk, including as described in {{security_measures}} (or if not specified, measures reasonably appropriate to the nature of the Processing, including access controls, encryption where appropriate, and secure development practices);\n\n12.3.4 not engage any Sub-processor without Client’s prior written authorisation (general or specific). If general authorisation is granted in the SOW, Freelancer shall provide Client with reasonable advance notice of any intended changes and Client may object on reasonable grounds;\n\n12.3.5 remain fully liable for the performance of any Sub-processor’s obligations;\n\n12.3.6 assist Client, taking into account the nature of the Processing, by appropriate technical and organisational measures, insofar as possible, to respond to requests from data subjects to exercise their rights under Data Protection Laws;\n\n12.3.7 assist Client in ensuring compliance with Client’s obligations relating to security, Personal Data Breach notifications, data protection impact assessments, and prior consultation, taking into account the information available to Freelancer;\n\n12.3.8 notify Client without undue delay (and in any event within {{breach_notification_hours}} hours) after becoming aware of a Personal Data Breach affecting Personal Data Processed under this Agreement, and provide reasonable information about the breach as it becomes available;\n\n12.3.9 at Client’s choice, delete or return all Personal Data to Client after the end of the provision of Services, and delete existing copies unless UK law requires storage; and\n\n12.3.10 make available to Client all information reasonably necessary to demonstrate compliance with this Section 12 and allow for and contribute to audits, including inspections, conducted by Client or an auditor mandated by Client, subject to Section 12.8.\n\n12.4 International transfers.\n\n12.4.1 Freelancer shall not transfer Personal Data outside the UK (and, where applicable, outside the EEA) unless such transfer is compliant with Data Protection Laws.\n\n12.4.2 Where required, the Parties shall put in place appropriate safeguards (for example, the UK International Data Transfer Agreement or the UK Addendum to the EU SCCs, as applicable).\n\n12.5 Independent Controller obligations. Where each Party acts as an independent Controller in respect of Personal Data it Processes under this Agreement, each Party shall be separately responsible for complying with its obligations under Data Protection Laws, including providing appropriate privacy information to data subjects.\n\n12.6 Client instructions and prohibited data. Client shall not instruct Freelancer to Process Special Category Data or criminal offence data unless the SOW expressly states this and the Parties agree appropriate safeguards and, where required, an appropriate lawful basis and conditions under Data Protection Laws.\n\n12.7 Security and access. Freelancer shall restrict access to Personal Data to those personnel who need access for performance of the Services and shall promptly revoke access when no longer required.\n\n12.8 Audits.\n\n12.8.1 Any audit under Section 12.3.10 shall be (a) on reasonable prior notice; (b) during normal business hours; (c) limited to systems and records relevant to the Processing; and (d) not more than once per year unless required due to a Personal Data Breach or material non-compliance.\n\n12.8.2 Client shall bear its own audit costs and reimburse Freelancer’s reasonable time costs at Freelancer’s then-current rates where the audit requires material effort, unless the audit identifies material non-compliance by Freelancer.\n\n12.9 Data retention. Unless otherwise instructed by Client, Freelancer shall not retain Personal Data longer than necessary to perform the Services or to comply with legal obligations.\n\n12.10 Conflict. If there is a conflict between this Section 12 and any separate data processing addendum signed by the Parties, the signed addendum shall prevail to the extent of the conflict.\n\n12.11 Liability. Each Party’s liability under this Section 12 is subject to Section 16, except to the extent such limitation is prohibited by law."},{"id":"compliance_ethics","type":"optional","order":13,"title":"13. COMPLIANCE; ETHICS; MODERN SLAVERY; BRIBERY","content":"13.1 General compliance. Each Party shall comply with all laws and regulations applicable to it in connection with this Agreement.\n\n13.2 Bribery and corruption.\n\n13.2.1 Freelancer shall (and shall ensure that any person engaged to perform the Services) comply with Bribery Laws.\n\n13.2.2 Freelancer shall not offer, promise, give, request, or accept any financial or other advantage to induce or reward improper performance in connection with this Agreement.\n\n13.2.3 Freelancer shall maintain adequate procedures designed to prevent bribery, proportionate to its size and the nature of the Services.\n\n13.3 Modern slavery.\n\n13.3.1 Freelancer shall not engage in any activity, practice, or conduct that would constitute an offence under Modern Slavery Laws.\n\n13.3.2 Where Freelancer is required to publish a modern slavery statement, Freelancer shall do so in accordance with applicable law.\n\n13.3.3 Freelancer shall notify Client as soon as reasonably practicable if it becomes aware of any actual or suspected modern slavery in its supply chain relating to the Services.\n\n13.4 Sanctions and export controls (optional). Each Party shall comply with applicable economic sanctions and export control laws to the extent relevant to performance.\n\n13.5 Policies and training (optional). If Client provides relevant Client Policies in advance (for example, information security or anti-bribery policies), Freelancer shall comply with such policies while performing the Services, provided they are reasonable and consistent with this Agreement.\n\n13.6 Conflicts of interest. Freelancer shall promptly disclose any actual or potential conflict of interest that could materially affect performance of the Services. The Parties shall discuss in good faith measures to address the conflict.\n\n13.7 Health and safety (where on-site). While on Client premises, Freelancer shall comply with Client’s reasonable health and safety requirements notified in advance.\n\n13.8 Records. Freelancer shall maintain accurate records relating to compliance with this Section 13 where reasonably necessary to demonstrate compliance.\n\n13.9 Remedy. A material breach of this Section 13 shall be deemed a material breach for the purposes of Section 14.4 (Termination for cause)."},{"id":"term","type":"standard","order":14,"title":"14. TERM; TERMINATION; EXIT","content":"14.1 Term. This Agreement begins on the Effective Date and continues until {{expiration_date}} or completion of the Services (whichever is earlier), unless terminated earlier in accordance with this Section 14 (the \"Term\").\n\n14.2 Termination for convenience. Either Party may terminate this Agreement for convenience by giving not less than {{notice_period}} days’ written notice.\n\n14.3 Termination for cause. Either Party may terminate this Agreement immediately by written notice if the other Party:\n\n14.3.1 commits a material breach of this Agreement which (if capable of remedy) is not remedied within {{cure_period_days}} days of written notice specifying the breach and requiring remedy;\n\n14.3.2 repeatedly breaches this Agreement in a manner that reasonably justifies the opinion that its conduct is inconsistent with an intention to comply;\n\n14.3.3 becomes insolvent or unable to pay its debts as they fall due, enters administration or liquidation, has a receiver appointed, or makes any arrangement with creditors; or\n\n14.3.4 commits fraud or serious misconduct in connection with this Agreement.\n\n14.4 Suspension/termination for non-payment. Freelancer may terminate this Agreement on written notice if Client fails to pay any undisputed invoice within 14 days after receiving a reminder notice.\n\n14.5 Effect of termination.\n\n14.5.1 On termination, Freelancer shall stop performing the Services (except for reasonable wind-down and handover) and shall deliver to Client all Work Product completed up to the termination date (whether complete or in progress) in the form reasonably requested by Client.\n\n14.5.2 Client shall pay Freelancer for (a) all Services properly performed up to the termination effective date; (b) all approved Expenses incurred up to the termination effective date; and (c) any non-cancellable third-party costs pre-approved by Client.\n\n14.5.3 If Client terminates for convenience, and the SOW includes a committed minimum or booking, Client shall also pay any agreed cancellation fee specified in {{cancellation_fee_terms}} (if any), provided such fee represents a genuine pre-estimate of loss.\n\n14.6 Transition assistance (optional). If requested by Client, Freelancer shall provide reasonable transition assistance for up to 10 Business Days following termination at the rates in Section 6.1, unless termination was due to Freelancer’s material breach.\n\n14.7 Return of materials. Each Party shall return or destroy the other Party’s Confidential Information in accordance with Section 11.6.\n\n14.8 Survival. Any provisions that by their nature should survive termination shall survive, including Sections 6 (Payment for amounts due), 10 (IP), 11 (Confidentiality), 12 (Data Protection), 16 (Liability), 17 (Indemnification), 20 (Notices), and 21 (General Provisions)."},{"id":"warranties","type":"standard","order":15,"title":"15. WARRANTIES; DISCLAIMERS","content":"15.1 Mutual authority. Each Party warrants that it has full power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement.\n\n15.2 Freelancer warranties. Freelancer warrants that:\n\n15.2.1 it will perform the Services with reasonable skill and care and in accordance with Section 2.3;\n\n15.2.2 to the best of its knowledge, the Work Product (excluding Client Materials and third-party materials approved by Client) will not infringe any third party’s Intellectual Property Rights;\n\n15.2.3 it has the right to grant the rights and assignments set out in Section 10;\n\n15.2.4 it will not knowingly introduce malware into Client systems; and\n\n15.2.5 it will comply with applicable laws in performing the Services.\n\n15.3 Client warranties. Client warrants that:\n\n15.3.1 it has the right to provide Client Materials to Freelancer and to permit their use for the Services;\n\n15.3.2 Client Materials (as provided) do not, to the best of Client’s knowledge, infringe third-party rights; and\n\n15.3.3 Client will comply with applicable laws in connection with its use of the Deliverables.\n\n15.4 Disclaimer.\n\n15.4.1 Except as expressly stated in this Agreement, all warranties, conditions, and other terms implied by statute, common law, or otherwise are excluded to the maximum extent permitted by law, including any implied warranties of satisfactory quality, fitness for a particular purpose, and non-infringement.\n\n15.4.2 Freelancer does not warrant that the Deliverables will be error-free or that all defects can be corrected, particularly where defects arise from third-party platforms, Client Materials, or requirements not specified in the SOW.\n\n15.5 Client responsibility for decisions. Client acknowledges that it is responsible for (a) reviewing and approving Deliverables; and (b) decisions regarding publication, deployment, compliance, and use.\n\n15.6 Third-party services. Where Deliverables rely on third-party services, APIs, or platforms, Freelancer is not responsible for outages, changes, or discontinuation by such third parties, though Freelancer will use reasonable efforts to mitigate impacts where within scope.\n\n15.7 Exclusive remedies. Client’s remedies for breach of warranties are limited to those expressly stated in this Agreement and, where applicable, damages subject to Section 16."},{"id":"liability","type":"negotiable","order":16,"title":"16. LIMITATION OF LIABILITY","content":"16.1 Nothing in this Agreement limits or excludes liability for:\n\n16.1.1 death or personal injury caused by negligence;\n\n16.1.2 fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation;\n\n16.1.3 any other liability which cannot be limited or excluded by applicable law; or\n\n16.1.4 (optional) Client’s obligation to pay undisputed Fees and approved Expenses.\n\n16.2 Exclusion of indirect losses. Subject to Section 16.1, neither Party shall be liable to the other for any indirect or consequential loss, or for loss of profit, loss of revenue, loss of business, loss of goodwill, or loss of anticipated savings, whether arising in contract, tort (including negligence), misrepresentation, restitution, or otherwise.\n\n16.3 Liability cap. Subject to Sections 16.1 and 16.4, each Party’s total aggregate liability arising out of or in connection with this Agreement shall not exceed the total Fees paid and payable under this Agreement in the 12 months preceding the event giving rise to the claim (or, if lower/higher as specified in the SOW, {{liability_cap_amount}}).\n\n16.4 Super-cap (optional). The cap in Section 16.3 shall not apply to:\n\n16.4.1 liability under Section 11 (Confidentiality) for wilful breach; and/or\n\n16.4.2 liability under Section 17 (Indemnification) (subject to any separate cap stated there).\n\n16.5 Time limit for claims. Except for claims that cannot lawfully be time-limited, neither Party may bring any claim arising out of this Agreement more than 12 months after the Party became aware (or should reasonably have become aware) of the facts giving rise to the claim.\n\n16.6 Mitigation. Each Party shall take reasonable steps to mitigate any losses it suffers.\n\n16.7 Basis of bargain. The Parties acknowledge that the limitations and exclusions in this Section 16 are reasonable and reflect the allocation of risk and the level of Fees.\n\n16.8 Multiple claims. For the purposes of this Section 16, all claims arising from the same event or a series of connected events shall be treated as one claim."},{"id":"indemnification","type":"negotiable","order":17,"title":"17. INDEMNIFICATION","content":"17.1 Definitions. In this Section 17:\n\n17.1.1 \"Client Indemnified Parties\" means Client, its Affiliates, and their respective directors, officers, and employees.\n\n17.1.2 \"Freelancer Indemnified Parties\" means Freelancer and (if applicable) its officers and employees.\n\n17.2 Freelancer IP indemnity. Freelancer shall indemnify and keep indemnified the Client Indemnified Parties against all losses, damages, costs, and expenses (including reasonable legal fees) awarded against or incurred by a Client Indemnified Party arising from any third-party claim alleging that the Work Product (excluding Client Materials and approved third-party materials) infringes the Intellectual Property Rights of that third party.\n\n17.3 IP indemnity exclusions. Freelancer has no obligation under Section 17.2 to the extent the claim arises from:\n\n17.3.1 Client Materials or specifications provided by Client;\n\n17.3.2 modifications made by or on behalf of Client not authorised by Freelancer;\n\n17.3.3 combination of the Work Product with items not supplied by Freelancer where the infringement would not have occurred but for such combination; or\n\n17.3.4 use of the Work Product outside the scope of rights granted under this Agreement.\n\n17.4 Client indemnity. Client shall indemnify and keep indemnified the Freelancer Indemnified Parties against all losses, damages, costs, and expenses (including reasonable legal fees) arising from any third-party claim that Client Materials or Client’s instructions infringe third-party rights, or that Client’s use of Deliverables (outside scope) violates law.\n\n17.5 Conduct of claims.\n\n17.5.1 The indemnified Party shall promptly notify the indemnifying Party of any claim and provide reasonable co-operation.\n\n17.5.2 The indemnifying Party shall have control of the defence and settlement of the claim, provided it shall not settle any claim in a manner that imposes any admission of liability or obligation on the indemnified Party without the indemnified Party’s prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld).\n\n17.5.3 The indemnified Party may participate in the defence with its own counsel at its own cost.\n\n17.6 Mitigation for IP claims. If a Deliverable is (or in Freelancer’s reasonable opinion is likely to be) the subject of an infringement claim, Freelancer may, at its option:\n\n17.6.1 procure for Client the right to continue using it;\n\n17.6.2 modify or replace it so that it becomes non-infringing without material loss of functionality; or\n\n17.6.3 if neither option is commercially reasonable, terminate the affected part of the Services and refund any Fees paid for the infringing portion not yet delivered, as Client’s sole and exclusive remedy for such claim.\n\n17.7 Sole remedy. This Section 17 states each Party’s entire liability and the other Party’s sole remedies for third-party infringement claims, subject to Section 16.1.\n\n17.8 Scope and caps. Indemnities in this Section 17 are subject to Section 16 (Liability), unless the Parties expressly agree otherwise in the SOW.\n\n17.9 Third party rights. The Client Indemnified Parties and Freelancer Indemnified Parties may enforce this Section 17 under the Contracts (Rights of Third Parties) Act 1999, and this is the only Section intended to be enforceable by a third party."},{"id":"non_solicitation","type":"optional","order":18,"title":"18. NON-SOLICITATION (OPTIONAL)","content":"18.1 Non-solicitation of personnel (Client). During the Term and for {{non_solicitation_period_months}} months thereafter, Client shall not, without Freelancer’s prior written consent, directly solicit for employment or engagement any individual who is an employee or contractor of Freelancer and who was materially involved in providing the Services, except via general advertisements not targeted at such individuals.\n\n18.2 Non-solicitation of personnel (Freelancer). During the Term and for {{non_solicitation_period_months}} months thereafter, Freelancer shall not, without Client’s prior written consent, directly solicit for employment or engagement any employee of Client with whom Freelancer had material dealings in connection with the Services, except via general advertisements not targeted at such individuals.\n\n18.3 Reasonableness. The Parties agree that the restrictions in this Section 18 are reasonable and necessary to protect legitimate business interests.\n\n18.4 Remedies. Breach of this Section 18 may cause loss not readily quantifiable. Without prejudice to other rights, the non-breaching Party may seek injunctive relief.\n\n18.5 Optional fee. If the Parties wish, they may agree a fixed recruitment fee payable upon breach: {{non_solicitation_fee_amount}}. Any such fee shall be a genuine pre-estimate of loss and not a penalty."},{"id":"dispute_resolution","type":"optional","order":19,"title":"19. DISPUTE RESOLUTION (OPTIONAL)","content":"19.1 Good faith escalation. If a dispute arises out of or in connection with this Agreement, the Parties shall first attempt in good faith to resolve it promptly through escalation to their respective senior representatives.\n\n19.2 Mediation. If the dispute is not resolved within 14 days of escalation, either Party may propose mediation. Unless otherwise agreed, mediation shall be conducted in London in accordance with the Centre for Effective Dispute Resolution (CEDR) Model Mediation Procedure (or equivalent).\n\n19.3 Urgent relief. Nothing in this Section 19 prevents either Party from seeking urgent injunctive or other equitable relief from the courts, including in relation to Confidential Information, Trade Secrets, or infringement of Intellectual Property Rights.\n\n19.4 Continuity. Unless the dispute relates to non-payment of undisputed Fees or a material breach, the Parties shall continue performing their obligations during the dispute to the extent reasonably practicable."},{"id":"notices","type":"standard","order":20,"title":"20. NOTICES","content":"20.1 Form. Any notice or other communication under this Agreement shall be in writing and shall be:\n\n20.1.1 delivered by hand;\n\n20.1.2 sent by pre-paid first-class post or recorded delivery; or\n\n20.1.3 sent by email.\n\n20.2 Addresses.\n\n20.2.1 Notices to Client shall be sent to the address in the preamble (or such other address notified in accordance with this Section 20) and marked for the attention of {{party_a_name}}, and/or by email to {{party_a_email}} with a copy to {{client_project_contact_email}}.\n\n20.2.2 Notices to Freelancer shall be sent to the address in the preamble (or such other address notified) and/or by email to {{party_b_email}}.\n\n20.3 Deemed receipt.\n\n20.3.1 If delivered by hand, on signature of a delivery receipt.\n\n20.3.2 If sent by post, at 9.00 am on the second Business Day after posting.\n\n20.3.3 If sent by email, at the time of transmission provided no delivery failure notification is received, except that emails sent after 5.00 pm on a Business Day or on a non-Business Day are deemed received at 9.00 am on the next Business Day.\n\n20.4 Exclusions. This Section 20 does not apply to service of proceedings or other documents in any legal action, which shall be served in accordance with applicable rules of court."},{"id":"general","type":"standard","order":21,"title":"21. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"21.1 Governing law and jurisdiction. This Agreement and any dispute or claim arising out of or in connection with it (including non-contractual disputes or claims) shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of England and Wales, and the Parties submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of the courts of England and Wales, subject to Section 19 (if included) and Section 11.8 (equitable relief).\n\n21.2 Entire agreement.\n\n21.2.1 This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties and supersedes all prior discussions, correspondence, proposals, and understandings relating to its subject matter.\n\n21.2.2 Each Party acknowledges that it has not relied on any statement, representation, assurance, or warranty not expressly set out in this Agreement.\n\n21.3 Variation. No variation of this Agreement shall be effective unless in writing and signed by (or confirmed by email by) authorised representatives of both Parties.\n\n21.4 Assignment.\n\n21.4.1 Client may assign or transfer this Agreement to an Affiliate or in connection with a merger, reorganisation, or sale of all or substantially all of its assets, provided it gives written notice to Freelancer.\n\n21.4.2 Freelancer may not assign, transfer, charge, or otherwise deal with this Agreement or any right under it without Client’s prior written consent.\n\n21.5 Subcontracting. Except as permitted by Section 2.8 and Section 9.6, Freelancer shall not subcontract performance without Client’s prior written consent.\n\n21.6 Severance. If any provision of this Agreement is found invalid, illegal, or unenforceable, it shall be deemed modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it valid and enforceable, and the remainder shall continue in full force.\n\n21.7 Waiver. No failure or delay by a Party to exercise any right or remedy shall operate as a waiver. A waiver must be in writing and shall apply only in the circumstances for which it is given.\n\n21.8 No partnership or agency. Nothing in this Agreement is intended to, or shall be deemed to, establish any partnership or joint venture between the Parties, nor authorise either Party to make or enter into commitments for or on behalf of the other.\n\n21.9 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in any number of counterparts, each of which is an original, and together they form one instrument.\n\n21.10 Electronic signatures. The Parties agree that this Agreement may be executed electronically and that electronic signatures (including typed names, e-signature platforms, or PDF signatures) are intended to be legally binding, including under the Electronic Communications Act 2000 and the Electronic Identification and Trust Services for Electronic Transactions Regulations 2016.\n\n21.11 Third party rights.\n\n21.11.1 Except as expressly provided in Section 17.9 (Third party rights for indemnities), a person who is not a Party has no right under the Contracts (Rights of Third Parties) Act 1999 to enforce any term of this Agreement.\n\n21.11.2 The Parties may amend or terminate this Agreement without the consent of any third party, including any third party beneficiary under Section 17.9.\n\n21.12 Further assurance. Each Party shall execute such documents and do such acts as the other Party may reasonably require to give effect to this Agreement.\n\n21.13 Publicity. Neither Party shall issue any public announcement or press release relating to this Agreement without the other Party’s prior written consent, except as required by law or a stock exchange.\n\n21.14 Notices of change of details. Each Party shall promptly notify the other of any change to its address, email, or primary contact details.\n\n21.15 Insurance (optional).\n\n21.15.1 Freelancer shall maintain, with a reputable insurer, appropriate insurance coverage for the Services, which may include professional indemnity insurance of not less than {{pi_insurance_amount}} and public liability insurance of not less than {{public_liability_insurance_amount}}.\n\n21.15.2 On request, Freelancer shall provide evidence of such insurance.\n\n21.16 Rights cumulative. The rights and remedies provided under this Agreement are cumulative and not exclusive of any rights or remedies provided by law.\n\n21.17 Costs. Each Party shall bear its own costs in relation to negotiation and entry into this Agreement.\n\n21.18 Execution and authority. The individuals signing below warrant that they are duly authorised to bind the respective Party."}]'::jsonb,
