-- Update: Consultancy Agreement (England and Wales)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Consultancy Agreement (the "Agreement") is made and entered into on {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date") between:

(A) {{party_a_company}}, a company incorporated and registered in England and Wales (company number {{party_a_company_number}}) whose registered office is at {{party_a_address}} ("Client"); and

(B) {{party_b_company}}, of {{party_b_address}} (and, if applicable, incorporated and registered in {{party_b_jurisdiction}} with registration number {{party_b_company_number}}) ("Consultant").

Client and Consultant are each a "Party" and together the "Parties".

This Agreement may be executed in any number of counterparts and by electronic signature. Where it is executed using an electronic signature platform or by application of electronic signatures, the Parties agree such execution is intended to be legally binding and effective in accordance with the Electronic Communications Act 2000 and the common law of England and Wales.',
  recitals = 'A. Client wishes to appoint Consultant to provide consultancy and/or professional services to Client on the terms of this Agreement.

B. Consultant represents that it has the skill, experience, capacity and resources to perform the Services (as defined below) and that it operates an independent business undertaking.

C. The Parties intend that Consultant shall provide the Services as an independent contractor and not as an employee, worker, agent or partner of Client.

D. The Parties wish to set out the terms on which the Services will be provided, including provisions relating to intellectual property, confidentiality, data protection, and compliance.

The Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS; INTERPRETATION; ORDER OF PRECEDENCE","content":"1.1 Definitions. In this Agreement, unless the context otherwise requires:\n\n(a) \"Acceptance\" means Client’s written acceptance of a Deliverable in accordance with clause 2.7 (Acceptance Procedure), or deemed acceptance in accordance with clause 2.7(g).\n\n(b) \"Affiliate\" means, in relation to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly Controls, is Controlled by, or is under common Control with that Party from time to time.\n\n(c) \"Applicable Law\" means all laws, statutes, regulations, regulatory requirements, codes of practice, and guidance having the force of law that apply to a Party or to the provision/receipt of the Services (including, where applicable, the Bribery Act 2010, the Modern Slavery Act 2015, the Equality Act 2010, the Health and Safety at Work etc. Act 1974, the UK GDPR, the Data Protection Act 2018, the Trade Secrets (Enforcement, etc.) Regulations 2018, and all tax legislation and HMRC rules relevant to the engagement).\n\n(d) \"Background IPR\" means all Intellectual Property Rights owned by or licensed to a Party and created or acquired independently of, and not specifically for, this Agreement (including any updates or improvements to such rights that are not created specifically as part of the Services).\n\n(e) \"Business Day\" means a day other than a Saturday, Sunday or public holiday in England when banks in London are open for business.\n\n(f) \"Client Materials\" means any materials, information, content, software, documentation, data (including Personal Data), equipment, premises, systems, or other items provided or made available by or on behalf of Client to Consultant in connection with the Services.\n\n(g) \"Confidential Information\" has the meaning given in clause 7.1.\n\n(h) \"Control\" has the meaning given in section 1124 of the Corporation Tax Act 2010.\n\n(i) \"Deliverables\" means the outputs, work product and deliverables (including reports, specifications, documentation, designs, code, data sets, analyses, recommendations and other materials) described in {{services_description}} or otherwise agreed in writing pursuant to clause 2.5.\n\n(j) \"Dispute\" means any dispute, claim or controversy arising out of or in connection with this Agreement (including its formation, existence, validity, performance, interpretation, termination or the consequences of termination).\n\n(k) \"Fees\" means the fees payable to Consultant as set out in clause 3 and {{services_description}}.\n\n(l) \"Force Majeure Event\" means an event or circumstance beyond a Party’s reasonable control which by the exercise of reasonable diligence such Party cannot prevent, avoid, overcome or mitigate.\n\n(m) \"Intellectual Property Rights\" or \"IPR\" means all intellectual property rights of any kind anywhere in the world, whether registered or unregistered, including copyright and related rights, database rights, rights in confidential information (including trade secrets), know-how, patents, utility models, rights in inventions, trade marks, service marks, trade names, domain names, design rights, rights in get-up and goodwill, and all rights to apply for and be granted such rights and all renewals and extensions.\n\n(n) \"IR35\" means the intermediaries legislation and off-payroll working rules under Chapter 8 and Chapter 10 Part 2 of the Income Tax (Earnings and Pensions) Act 2003, associated NIC legislation, and related HMRC guidance and practice.\n\n(o) \"Personal Data\", \"Processing\", \"Controller\", \"Processor\", \"Data Subject\", \"Personal Data Breach\" and \"Special Category Data\" have the meanings given in the UK GDPR.\n\n(p) \"Services\" means the services described in {{services_description}} and any additional or varied services agreed in accordance with clause 2.5.\n\n(q) \"Statement of Work\" or \"SoW\" means any document, attachment or schedule agreed in writing by the Parties describing the Services, Deliverables, milestones, timetable, Acceptance criteria, Fees, and any service-specific terms. The Parties may treat {{services_description}} as the initial SoW.\n\n(r) \"Term\" has the meaning given in clause 5.1.\n\n(s) \"Third Party Rights Act\" means the Contracts (Rights of Third Parties) Act 1999.\n\n(t) \"Trade Secrets\" means information meeting the definition of a trade secret under the Trade Secrets (Enforcement, etc.) Regulations 2018 (including information that is secret, has commercial value because it is secret, and has been subject to reasonable steps to keep it secret).\n\n(u) \"Work Product\" has the meaning given in clause 6.1.\n\n1.2 Interpretation.\n\n(a) Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation.\n\n(b) A reference to \"including\" shall be construed as \"including without limitation\".\n\n(c) References to \"writing\" include email and e-signature, unless expressly stated otherwise.\n\n(d) A reference to a statute includes any modification, extension or re-enactment and any subordinate legislation made under it.\n\n(e) References to a \"person\" include an individual, company, partnership, LLP, association, government entity or other legal entity.\n\n1.3 Order of precedence. If there is any inconsistency between the terms of this Agreement and any SoW or other attachment, the following order of precedence applies (unless the relevant document expressly states it prevails): (a) clauses of this Agreement; (b) any SoW; (c) any other attachment or exhibit.\n\n1.4 No implied terms. To the fullest extent permitted by law, any terms implied by statute or common law are excluded, including (where applicable) any implied terms under the Supply of Goods and Services Act 1982, except to the extent such terms cannot lawfully be excluded."},{"id":"services","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. SERVICES; DELIVERABLES; ACCEPTANCE; CHANGE CONTROL","content":"2.1 Provision of Services. Consultant shall provide the Services to Client during the Term:\n\n(a) with all reasonable skill and care;\n\n(b) in a professional and workmanlike manner consistent with generally accepted industry standards;\n\n(c) in accordance with the SoW and any reasonable written instructions of Client consistent with the SoW;\n\n(d) in compliance with Applicable Law; and\n\n(e) using appropriately qualified personnel.\n\n2.2 Scope and Deliverables. Consultant shall provide the Deliverables and meet any milestones, service levels, and deadlines set out in {{services_description}}. Consultant acknowledges that time may be of the essence where expressly stated in the SoW.\n\n2.3 Co-operation and dependencies.\n\n(a) Client shall provide to Consultant such co-operation, access, information and decisions as are reasonably necessary for Consultant to perform the Services.\n\n(b) Consultant shall promptly notify Client if any Client dependency, assumption or requirement is likely to delay performance.\n\n(c) Consultant shall not be liable for delay to the extent caused by Client’s material breach of clause 2.3(a), provided Consultant has used reasonable endeavours to mitigate.\n\n2.4 Place and manner of performance.\n\n(a) Subject to any onsite requirements in the SoW, Consultant will determine the method, details and means of performing the Services.\n\n(b) If Consultant accesses Client premises, Consultant shall comply with Client’s reasonable security, health and safety and visitor policies notified to Consultant in writing.\n\n(c) If Consultant accesses Client systems remotely, Consultant shall comply with Client’s reasonable information security requirements notified to Consultant (including MFA, password policies and acceptable use).\n\n2.5 Change control.\n\n(a) Either Party may propose changes to the Services or Deliverables (including scope, timetable or Acceptance criteria).\n\n(b) A change will only take effect if agreed in writing by authorised representatives of both Parties (a \"Change Order\").\n\n(c) A Change Order should, where applicable, describe: (i) the change; (ii) impact on Fees and expenses; (iii) impact on timetable; (iv) assumptions and dependencies; and (v) any impact on data protection or security requirements.\n\n(d) Until a Change Order is agreed, Consultant shall continue to perform the Services in accordance with the then-current SoW.\n\n2.6 Deliverables format and handover. Unless otherwise agreed in the SoW, Deliverables shall be provided in commonly used electronic formats reasonably specified by Client, together with such instructions and documentation as are reasonably necessary to use the Deliverables.\n\n2.7 Acceptance procedure (optional where Deliverables are specified).\n\n(a) Within {{acceptance_period_days}} Business Days of receipt of a Deliverable, Client shall either: (i) provide written notice of Acceptance; or (ii) provide written notice of non-acceptance specifying in reasonable detail any material non-conformities with the Acceptance criteria.\n\n(b) If Client provides notice of non-acceptance under clause 2.7(a)(ii), Consultant shall use reasonable endeavours to remedy the identified non-conformities and re-submit the Deliverable within a reasonable time (or such time as set out in the SoW).\n\n(c) Client shall then repeat the review process in clause 2.7(a).\n\n(d) If a non-conformity is caused by Client Materials or Client instructions, the Parties shall treat the remediation as a change under clause 2.5.\n\n(e) Client’s use of a Deliverable for production or live business purposes (other than for evaluation/testing) will constitute Acceptance.\n\n(f) Acceptance does not waive Client’s rights in respect of latent defects, fraud, or non-conformity not reasonably discoverable during Acceptance testing.\n\n(g) If Client does not provide notice under clause 2.7(a) within the review period, the Deliverable shall be deemed Accepted.\n\n2.8 Progress updates and meetings. Consultant shall provide reasonable progress updates as set out in the SoW (or, if not stated, upon Client’s reasonable request). Meetings may be held remotely unless otherwise agreed.\n\n2.9 Key personnel. Where the SoW identifies key personnel, Consultant shall not replace such personnel without Client’s prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed), provided that Consultant may replace personnel urgently where necessary due to illness, resignation or unavailability, subject to promptly notifying Client.\n\n2.10 No authority. Consultant shall not (and shall procure that its personnel do not) hold itself out as having authority to bind Client, incur liabilities on Client’s behalf, or make representations as agent of Client unless expressly authorised in writing by Client."},{"id":"compensation","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. FEES; INVOICING; PAYMENT; EXPENSES; VAT","content":"3.1 Fees. In consideration of the Services, Client shall pay Consultant the Fees as set out in {{services_description}}, which may include:\n\n(a) a fixed fee of {{payment_amount}}; and/or\n\n(b) a time-based rate of {{hourly_rate}} (or such other rate as stated in the SoW), together with any agreed caps or minimum commitments.\n\n3.2 No additional charges. Except as expressly set out in this Agreement or an agreed Change Order, the Fees are inclusive of all costs and charges incurred by Consultant in performing the Services (including personnel costs, overheads, equipment, software tools and ordinary business expenses).\n\n3.3 Invoicing.\n\n(a) Consultant shall invoice in accordance with {{invoicing_frequency}} and the SoW.\n\n(b) Each invoice shall be a valid VAT invoice (where VAT is applicable) and shall include: (i) Client purchase order number (if provided); (ii) a description of the Services performed and period covered; (iii) any time records (where time-based); (iv) any pre-approved expenses with receipts; (v) VAT amount and rate (if applicable); and (vi) Consultant’s VAT registration number (if applicable).\n\n(c) Consultant shall submit invoices to {{invoice_submission_email}} (or such other address notified by Client).\n\n3.4 Payment terms.\n\n(a) Subject to clause 3.5 (Disputed amounts), Client shall pay undisputed amounts within {{payment_terms_days}} days of receipt of a valid invoice.\n\n(b) Payment shall be made in pounds sterling by bank transfer to the account details notified by Consultant.\n\n(c) Client may set off against any sums due to Consultant any undisputed sums due from Consultant to Client under this Agreement.\n\n3.5 Disputed amounts.\n\n(a) If Client disputes any part of an invoice, Client shall notify Consultant in writing within 14 days of receipt, stating the reasons for the dispute and, where possible, the amount not in dispute.\n\n(b) Client shall pay the undisputed portion in accordance with clause 3.4.\n\n(c) The Parties shall use reasonable endeavours to resolve the dispute promptly and in good faith. Any agreed adjustments shall be reflected in a subsequent invoice or credit note.\n\n3.6 Late payment.\n\n(a) If Client fails to pay any undisputed amount by the due date, Consultant may (without prejudice to other rights) charge interest on the overdue amount at the statutory rate under the Late Payment of Commercial Debts (Interest) Act 1998 (or, if the Act does not apply, at 4% per annum above the Bank of England base rate), accruing daily from the due date until payment.\n\n(b) Consultant shall not suspend performance solely due to late payment unless: (i) the payment is more than 14 days overdue; (ii) Consultant has provided at least 7 days’ written notice of intention to suspend; and (iii) suspension is permitted under the SoW.\n\n3.7 Expenses.\n\n(a) Consultant may only charge expenses if expressly stated in the SoW or pre-approved in writing by Client in advance.\n\n(b) Any reimbursable expenses must be reasonable, properly incurred, and supported by receipts.\n\n(c) Travel time is not chargeable unless expressly stated in the SoW.\n\n3.8 VAT and taxes.\n\n(a) Fees are exclusive of VAT. Where VAT is chargeable, Consultant shall add VAT at the applicable rate and Client shall pay such VAT upon receipt of a valid VAT invoice.\n\n(b) Except to the extent required by Applicable Law (including the off-payroll rules), Consultant shall be responsible for all taxes, National Insurance contributions, levies and similar charges arising from payments made under this Agreement.\n\n3.9 Records. Where Fees are time-based, Consultant shall maintain accurate time records and make them available to Client upon reasonable request for the purposes of verifying invoices.\n\n3.10 Most favoured treatment (optional). If stated in the SoW, Consultant shall apply any agreed rate card, discounts, or fee caps. Nothing in this clause obliges Consultant to offer terms more favourable than those agreed.\n\n3.11 No employee benefits. Consultant acknowledges that Consultant (and Consultant’s personnel) are not entitled to any employee or worker benefits from Client, including holiday pay, sick pay, pension contributions, redundancy pay, family leave rights, or other statutory or contractual benefits, except as required by Applicable Law."},{"id":"consultant_status","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. CONSULTANT STATUS; IR35/OFF-PAYROLL; NO AGENCY","content":"4.1 Independent contractor relationship. The Parties intend that Consultant provides the Services as an independent contractor in business on its own account. Nothing in this Agreement shall render Consultant (or any of Consultant’s personnel) an employee, worker, agent or partner of Client, and Consultant shall not be treated as such.\n\n4.2 No mutuality of obligation. Client is not obliged to offer work beyond the Services described in the SoW, and Consultant is not obliged to accept any work beyond the agreed Services.\n\n4.3 Control. Subject to clause 2.4 and the SoW, Consultant has autonomy over how the Services are performed, including selection and supervision of personnel, use of tools, scheduling and methodology.\n\n4.4 Right of substitution.\n\n(a) Consultant may provide a suitably qualified substitute to perform the Services, subject to Client’s prior written approval (not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed) and subject to the substitute meeting any security, confidentiality, vetting, and competency requirements reasonably notified by Client.\n\n(b) Consultant shall remain responsible for the acts and omissions of any substitute as if they were Consultant’s own.\n\n(c) Consultant shall bear any additional costs associated with substitution unless otherwise agreed in a Change Order.\n\n4.5 No exclusivity. Unless otherwise agreed in the SoW, Consultant may provide services to other clients, provided that such activities do not materially interfere with the performance of the Services, create a conflict of interest, or breach this Agreement.\n\n4.6 Financial risk and provision of equipment. Consultant is responsible for its own business costs, equipment, software and tools necessary to perform the Services, except where the SoW states Client will provide specific items.\n\n4.7 No authority to bind. Consultant shall not enter into contracts, make commitments, or incur liabilities on behalf of Client.\n\n4.8 Personnel matters.\n\n(a) Consultant is solely responsible for recruitment, engagement, payment, management, control and termination of its personnel.\n\n(b) Consultant shall ensure that its personnel have appropriate skills, training and (where relevant) right to work, and comply with Applicable Law.\n\n(c) Consultant shall ensure that its personnel are bound by written obligations no less protective of Client than those in this Agreement, including confidentiality, data protection and IP assignment provisions.\n\n4.9 IR35/off-payroll working rules.\n\n(a) The Parties acknowledge that the engagement may be subject to IR35/off-payroll rules.\n\n(b) Where Client is required by Applicable Law to assess employment status for tax purposes and issue a status determination statement (\"SDS\"), Consultant shall promptly provide reasonable information requested by Client to enable Client to make an SDS and to comply with its legal obligations.\n\n(c) Consultant warrants that it has not and will not take any action or omit to take any action that would cause the SDS (or any assumptions underlying it) to be inaccurate.\n\n(d) Where Applicable Law requires Client (or another entity in the supply chain) to operate PAYE and employee NICs in respect of payments under this Agreement, Client may make such deductions and account to HMRC. The Parties agree that such deductions do not create an employment or worker relationship.\n\n(e) Tax indemnity (optional, subject to reasonableness and Applicable Law). To the extent permitted by law and subject to clause 8.4 (Liability carve-outs), Consultant shall indemnify Client against any employer NICs, apprenticeship levy, income tax, penalties, interest, costs and expenses incurred by Client arising out of or in connection with: (i) any inaccuracy or misrepresentation by Consultant; or (ii) Consultant’s breach of this clause 4.9.\n\n(f) Status challenge. If Consultant challenges an SDS, the Parties shall follow a reasonable dispute process consistent with Applicable Law. Pending resolution, Client may pay in accordance with the SDS.\n\n4.10 Non-circumvention of status. Consultant shall not present itself to third parties (including Client personnel) as an employee or worker of Client and shall not accept benefits available only to employees or workers.\n\n4.11 No agency. Nothing in this Agreement creates a relationship of principal and agent, partnership or joint venture between the Parties."},{"id":"term_termination","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. TERM; TERMINATION; SUSPENSION; EXIT","content":"5.1 Term. This Agreement commences on the Effective Date and continues until {{expiration_date}} (if specified) or, if no expiry date is specified, until completion of the Services, unless terminated earlier in accordance with this clause 5 (the \"Term\").\n\n5.2 Termination for convenience. Either Party may terminate this Agreement (and/or any SoW) for convenience on not less than {{notice_period}} days’ written notice.\n\n5.3 Termination for cause. Either Party may terminate this Agreement immediately by written notice if the other Party:\n\n(a) commits a material breach of this Agreement (including any SoW) which is not capable of remedy, or (if capable of remedy) is not remedied within 14 days of written notice requiring remedy;\n\n(b) repeatedly breaches this Agreement in such a manner as to reasonably justify the opinion that its conduct is inconsistent with it having the intention or ability to give effect to the terms of this Agreement;\n\n(c) becomes insolvent, unable to pay its debts as they fall due, enters administration, has a receiver appointed, enters into liquidation (whether voluntary or compulsory), makes an arrangement with creditors, or ceases or threatens to cease carrying on business;\n\n(d) engages in fraud, dishonesty, gross negligence, or wilful misconduct in connection with this Agreement;\n\n(e) is in material breach of clause 7 (Confidentiality), clause 9 (Data Protection), or clause 12 (Compliance and Ethics) (where included).\n\n5.4 Suspension.\n\n(a) Client may suspend performance of the Services immediately on written notice to Consultant where Client reasonably believes that: (i) continued performance would create a material security risk; (ii) Consultant has materially breached Client’s security or confidentiality requirements; (iii) there is suspected fraud, corruption or unlawful conduct; or (iv) continued access to Client systems could reasonably result in harm.\n\n(b) During suspension, Consultant shall co-operate with Client to investigate and mitigate the issue. Client shall lift the suspension when the reason for suspension has been remedied or no longer applies.\n\n(c) Suspension under this clause 5.4 shall not relieve Consultant of its obligations, and Consultant shall not be entitled to additional Fees for the period of suspension to the extent the issue was caused by Consultant.\n\n5.5 Effect of termination or expiry.\n\n(a) Consultant shall immediately cease to represent itself as associated with Client and shall stop performing the Services (except for reasonable wind-down agreed by Client).\n\n(b) Consultant shall promptly deliver to Client all Deliverables (whether complete or in progress) and all Client Materials in Consultant’s possession or control.\n\n(c) Consultant shall promptly return or (at Client’s option) securely destroy Confidential Information and Personal Data in accordance with clause 7.7 and clause 9.12.\n\n(d) Client shall pay Consultant for Services properly performed up to the effective date of termination and Accepted Deliverables provided, subject to any rights of set-off and provided Consultant has submitted valid invoices.\n\n(e) If termination is due to Consultant’s material breach, Client may withhold payment for non-conforming Services and may recover any reasonable costs of re-procurement or remediation, subject to clause 8 (Limitation of Liability).\n\n5.6 Transition assistance (optional). If requested by Client within 30 days after termination, Consultant shall provide reasonable transition assistance for up to {{transition_assistance_days}} Business Days at the rates set out in the SoW (or, if none, at Consultant’s then-current standard rates agreed in writing), to ensure orderly handover.\n\n5.7 Survival. Any terms which by their nature are intended to survive termination shall survive, including clauses 6 (Intellectual Property), 7 (Confidentiality), 8 (Representations and Warranties), 9 (Data Protection), 10 (Indemnification and Limitation of Liability), 12 (Compliance and Ethics) (if included), 13 (Governing Law) and 14 (General Provisions)."},{"id":"intellectual_property","type":"negotiable","order":6,"title":"6. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; WORK PRODUCT; LICENCES","content":"6.1 Work Product. \"Work Product\" means all Deliverables and all other works, materials, and results created, written, developed, conceived or reduced to practice by or on behalf of Consultant in connection with the Services, whether alone or jointly with others, including inventions, source code, object code, scripts, databases, documents, diagrams, specifications, designs, reports, presentations, data compilations, and all IPR in any of the foregoing.\n\n6.2 Client ownership.\n\n(a) Subject to clause 6.4 (Background IPR) and clause 6.6 (Third-party materials and Open Source), Client shall own all right, title and interest in and to the Work Product and all IPR in the Work Product.\n\n(b) To the fullest extent permitted by law, Consultant hereby assigns to Client by way of present assignment of existing and future rights (including assignment of future copyright and design rights) all IPR in the Work Product, with full title guarantee, including all rights to sue for past, present and future infringements.\n\n(c) The assignment in clause 6.2(b) takes effect on creation of the relevant Work Product and, where relevant, upon payment of the Fees relating to that Work Product, to the extent required to ensure enforceability.\n\n6.3 Further assurance.\n\n(a) Consultant shall, at Client’s cost (and at Consultant’s cost where the need arises from Consultant’s breach), promptly execute and deliver such documents and do such things as Client may reasonably request to perfect, register, maintain or enforce Client’s rights in the Work Product.\n\n(b) Consultant shall maintain adequate records to enable identification of authorship/creation dates and shall provide such records to Client upon reasonable request.\n\n(c) If Consultant fails to execute a document required under clause 6.3(a) within 10 Business Days of request, Consultant irrevocably appoints Client (and any person nominated by Client) as its attorney to execute such documents on Consultant’s behalf, provided that Client may only exercise this power to give effect to this clause 6.\n\n6.4 Background IPR and Consultant tools.\n\n(a) Each Party retains ownership of its Background IPR.\n\n(b) If Consultant incorporates any Background IPR, tools, libraries, frameworks, methodologies, templates or know-how (\"Consultant Tools\") into the Work Product, Consultant grants to Client (and Client’s Affiliates and end customers where applicable) a perpetual, irrevocable, worldwide, royalty-free, non-exclusive, transferable and sublicensable licence to use, copy, modify, maintain, host, support and otherwise exploit such Consultant Tools solely to the extent necessary to use and exploit the Work Product for Client’s business purposes.\n\n(c) Consultant warrants that it has the right to grant the licence in clause 6.4(b).\n\n6.5 Moral rights.\n\n(a) To the fullest extent permitted by law, Consultant irrevocably waives (and shall procure that its personnel waive) all moral rights in the Work Product, including rights under Chapter IV of the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988.\n\n(b) Where waiver is not legally effective, Consultant irrevocably consents (and shall procure that its personnel consent) to any act or omission by Client (or its licensees/successors) which would otherwise infringe such moral rights.\n\n6.6 Third-party materials and Open Source.\n\n(a) Consultant shall not include in any Deliverable any third-party materials (including Open Source Software) in a manner that would: (i) require disclosure of Client source code; (ii) impose obligations on Client inconsistent with Client’s intended use; or (iii) restrict Client’s ability to exploit the Work Product, unless Client has given prior written approval.\n\n(b) Consultant shall provide Client with a written list of all third-party materials and Open Source Software included in the Work Product, including applicable licences and any attribution requirements.\n\n(c) Consultant shall comply with all licence terms for third-party materials and Open Source Software and shall indemnify Client for breach of such licence terms to the extent caused by Consultant.\n\n6.7 Client Materials. Client Materials are and shall remain the property of Client (or its licensors). Except to the extent necessary to perform the Services, no rights are granted to Consultant in Client Materials.\n\n6.8 Portfolio and publicity.\n\n(a) Consultant shall not issue press releases or public announcements relating to this Agreement or use Client’s name, trade marks or logos without Client’s prior written consent.\n\n(b) Client may grant consent subject to reasonable brand guidelines.\n\n6.9 Pre-existing work. Consultant warrants that, unless disclosed in writing to Client before the Effective Date (or before incorporation into the Work Product), the Work Product is newly created for Client and is not subject to any prior assignment, licence, lien, charge or encumbrance.\n\n6.10 Escrow (optional). If stated in the SoW, the Parties shall co-operate to place specified source code/materials into escrow on agreed terms."},{"id":"confidentiality","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS; INFORMATION SECURITY","content":"7.1 Confidential Information. \"Confidential Information\" means all information (whether in oral, written, visual, electronic or other form) disclosed or made available by or on behalf of a Party (\"Disclosing Party\") to the other Party (\"Receiving Party\") in connection with this Agreement, that is:\n\n(a) marked or stated to be confidential; or\n\n(b) by its nature or circumstances of disclosure ought reasonably to be regarded as confidential,\n\nincluding: (i) business plans, forecasts, pricing, financial information, customer/supplier information, marketing information; (ii) technical information, designs, specifications, code, architecture, product roadmaps; (iii) Client Materials; (iv) security measures, credentials, vulnerability information; (v) any Personal Data; and (vi) Trade Secrets.\n\n7.2 Trade secrets. Without limiting clause 7.1, the Parties acknowledge that certain Confidential Information may constitute Trade Secrets protected by the Trade Secrets (Enforcement, etc.) Regulations 2018. Consultant shall take reasonable steps (and not less than those it takes to protect its own trade secrets of similar importance) to preserve the secrecy and confidentiality of such Trade Secrets.\n\n7.3 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by contemporaneous written records:\n\n(a) is or becomes generally available to the public other than through a breach of this Agreement;\n\n(b) was lawfully in the Receiving Party’s possession without restriction before disclosure;\n\n(c) is lawfully disclosed to the Receiving Party by a third party without breach of any obligation of confidence; or\n\n(d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.\n\n7.4 Confidentiality obligations. The Receiving Party shall:\n\n(a) use the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information solely for the purposes of performing (for Consultant) or receiving/managing (for Client) the Services and exercising rights under this Agreement;\n\n(b) keep the Confidential Information secret and confidential;\n\n(c) not disclose Confidential Information to any person except as permitted by clause 7.5;\n\n(d) protect Confidential Information using appropriate technical and organisational measures, including (as appropriate): access controls, least privilege, encryption in transit, secure storage, and secure disposal;\n\n(e) promptly notify the Disclosing Party upon becoming aware of any unauthorised access, disclosure, loss or compromise of Confidential Information.\n\n7.5 Permitted disclosures.\n\n(a) The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information to its personnel, professional advisers, auditors, insurers, and (in Consultant’s case) approved subcontractors, who have a need to know for the purposes of this Agreement, provided that the Receiving Party ensures such persons are bound by written obligations of confidentiality no less protective than this clause 7.\n\n(b) The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information where required by law, regulation or court order, provided that (to the extent permitted) it gives the Disclosing Party prompt written notice and co-operates (at the Disclosing Party’s cost) to seek confidential treatment or a protective order.\n\n7.6 Security requirements (optional). If Client provides information security policies or minimum security requirements at {{client_security_policy_url}} (or otherwise in writing), Consultant shall comply with such requirements to the extent applicable to Consultant’s performance.\n\n7.7 Return, deletion and certification.\n\n(a) Upon the earlier of: (i) completion of the Services; (ii) termination/expiry; or (iii) the Disclosing Party’s written request, the Receiving Party shall promptly return or securely destroy (at the Disclosing Party’s option) all Confidential Information in its possession or control, including copies.\n\n(b) Notwithstanding clause 7.7(a), the Receiving Party may retain one archival copy solely for legal, regulatory, or insurance purposes, subject to continued confidentiality and secure storage.\n\n(c) Upon request, the Receiving Party shall provide written certification of destruction.\n\n7.8 Duration. The obligations in this clause 7 commence on the Effective Date and continue for the duration of the Term and for {{confidentiality_duration_years}} years thereafter, provided that obligations relating to Trade Secrets shall continue for so long as the relevant information remains a trade secret.\n\n7.9 Injunctive relief. The Receiving Party acknowledges that damages alone may be an inadequate remedy for breach of this clause 7. The Disclosing Party is entitled to seek injunctive or other equitable relief, without prejudice to any other rights or remedies.\n\n7.10 No licence. Except as expressly set out in this Agreement, no licence or other right is granted to Confidential Information by implication, estoppel or otherwise.\n\n7.11 Confidentiality of agreement. The Parties shall treat the existence and terms of this Agreement as Confidential Information, subject to clause 7.5 and to disclosures to professional advisers and financiers on a need-to-know basis."},{"id":"data_protection","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. DATA PROTECTION (UK GDPR; DATA PROTECTION ACT 2018)","content":"8.1 Roles of the Parties.\n\n(a) Each Party shall comply with its obligations under the UK GDPR and the Data Protection Act 2018.\n\n(b) The Parties acknowledge that, in connection with the Services, Consultant may Process Personal Data on behalf of Client. To the extent Consultant Processes Personal Data on behalf of Client, Client shall be the Controller and Consultant shall be the Processor, unless otherwise stated in the SoW.\n\n(c) Where the Parties act as independent Controllers (for example, for business contact details used for contract administration), each Party shall be independently responsible for compliance as Controller.\n\n8.2 Processor obligations (Article 28 UK GDPR). To the extent Consultant is a Processor, Consultant shall:\n\n(a) Process Personal Data only on documented instructions from Client (including as set out in this Agreement and any SoW), unless required by law to which Consultant is subject. Where required by law, Consultant shall (to the extent permitted) inform Client of that requirement before Processing;\n\n(b) ensure that persons authorised to Process the Personal Data are committed to confidentiality or are under an appropriate statutory obligation of confidentiality;\n\n(c) implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure a level of security appropriate to the risk in accordance with Article 32 UK GDPR, including, as appropriate, measures set out in clause 8.6;\n\n(d) not appoint any Sub-processor without complying with clause 8.5;\n\n(e) assist Client (by appropriate technical and organisational measures, insofar as possible) to fulfil Client’s obligation to respond to requests for exercising Data Subject rights under Chapter III UK GDPR;\n\n(f) assist Client in ensuring compliance with obligations pursuant to Articles 32 to 36 UK GDPR (security, Personal Data Breach notifications, DPIAs and prior consultation), taking into account the nature of Processing and information available to Consultant;\n\n(g) at Client’s choice, delete or return all Personal Data to Client after the end of the provision of Services relating to Processing, and delete existing copies, unless UK law requires storage; and\n\n(h) make available to Client all information reasonably necessary to demonstrate compliance with this clause 8 and allow for and contribute to audits and inspections as set out in clause 8.9.\n\n8.3 Details of Processing. The subject matter, nature and purpose of the Processing, the types of Personal Data and categories of Data Subjects, and the duration of the Processing are described in clause 8.14 (Processing Particulars) and/or the SoW.\n\n8.4 Client instructions. Client instructs Consultant to Process Personal Data only as necessary:\n\n(a) to perform the Services;\n\n(b) to comply with Client’s written instructions; and\n\n(c) as otherwise required by Applicable Law.\n\n8.5 Sub-processing.\n\n(a) Consultant shall not appoint a Sub-processor to Process Personal Data without Client’s prior written authorisation, which may be specific or general.\n\n(b) Where Client provides general authorisation, Consultant shall give Client at least 14 days’ prior notice of any intended changes concerning the addition or replacement of Sub-processors, thereby giving Client the opportunity to object on reasonable grounds.\n\n(c) Where Consultant appoints a Sub-processor, Consultant shall enter into a written contract with the Sub-processor imposing data protection obligations that are substantially the same as those imposed on Consultant under this clause 8, and Consultant shall remain fully liable for the Sub-processor’s performance.\n\n8.6 Security measures.\n\n(a) Consultant shall implement and maintain appropriate technical and organisational measures designed to protect Personal Data against accidental or unlawful destruction, loss, alteration, unauthorised disclosure of, or access to Personal Data.\n\n(b) Such measures shall include, as appropriate: (i) access controls and least-privilege; (ii) encryption of data in transit and, where appropriate, at rest; (iii) secure development practices; (iv) vulnerability management and patching; (v) backups and resilience; (vi) logging and monitoring; (vii) staff training.\n\n(c) Consultant shall ensure that any devices used to access Client systems comply with reasonable security requirements notified by Client.\n\n8.7 Personal Data Breaches.\n\n(a) Consultant shall notify Client without undue delay and in any event within {{data_breach_notice_hours}} hours after becoming aware of a Personal Data Breach affecting Personal Data Processed under this Agreement.\n\n(b) Such notification shall include, to the extent known, the nature of the breach, categories and approximate number of Data Subjects and records concerned, likely consequences, and measures taken or proposed to address the breach.\n\n(c) Consultant shall co-operate with Client and provide reasonable assistance to investigate, mitigate, and remediate the breach, and to support Client’s reporting obligations to the ICO and affected Data Subjects, where applicable.\n\n8.8 International transfers.\n\n(a) Consultant shall not transfer Personal Data outside the UK (and, where relevant, outside the EEA) unless authorised in writing by Client and such transfer is subject to appropriate safeguards under Chapter V UK GDPR.\n\n(b) Appropriate safeguards may include the UK International Data Transfer Agreement (IDTA), the UK Addendum to the EU Standard Contractual Clauses, adequacy regulations, or another valid transfer mechanism.\n\n8.9 Audits.\n\n(a) Upon reasonable notice, Client (or its independent auditor) may audit Consultant’s compliance with this clause 8 no more than once per year, unless a Personal Data Breach has occurred or the ICO requires otherwise.\n\n(b) Audits shall be limited to information and systems relevant to Processing under this Agreement and shall be conducted during normal business hours, subject to reasonable confidentiality and security requirements.\n\n(c) If an audit identifies material non-compliance, Consultant shall promptly remedy such non-compliance at its own cost.\n\n8.10 Data minimisation and Special Category Data.\n\n(a) Consultant shall only Process Personal Data that is necessary for the Services.\n\n(b) Consultant shall not Process Special Category Data or Personal Data relating to criminal convictions and offences unless expressly authorised in the SoW and subject to appropriate safeguards and a lawful basis.\n\n8.11 Data retention. Consultant shall not retain Personal Data for longer than necessary to perform the Services, except as required by Applicable Law or as agreed in the SoW.\n\n8.12 Return and deletion.\n\n(a) Upon termination or expiry of this Agreement, and in any event within 30 days of Client’s request, Consultant shall return to Client or securely delete all Personal Data Processed on behalf of Client, and certify deletion on request.\n\n(b) Where deletion is impracticable due to backups, Consultant shall ensure such Personal Data is protected and securely deleted in accordance with Consultant’s normal deletion cycles, and not otherwise accessed.\n\n8.13 Liability allocation. Nothing in this clause 8 limits either Party’s liability for its own non-compliance with data protection law. Any limitation of liability in clause 10 applies subject to clause 10.6.\n\n8.14 Processing Particulars (Annex).\n\n(a) Subject matter of Processing: provision of the Services.\n\n(b) Duration: the Term, and any retention period permitted by clause 8.11 and clause 8.12.\n\n(c) Nature of Processing: collection, recording, organisation, structuring, storage, consultation, use, disclosure by transmission where necessary for the Services, alignment/combination, restriction, erasure or destruction.\n\n(d) Purpose(s): performing the Services, administering the engagement, meeting Client instructions, and ensuring security and compliance.\n\n(e) Categories of Data Subjects: {{data_subject_categories}}.\n\n(f) Types of Personal Data: {{personal_data_types}}.\n\n(g) Special Category Data: {{special_category_data_details}} (or \"none\").\n\n(h) Sub-processors (if any): {{subprocessor_list}}.\n\n(i) Permitted locations: {{data_processing_locations}}.\n\n8.15 Controller-to-controller sharing (optional). Where the Parties share Personal Data as independent Controllers, each Party shall provide appropriate privacy information to Data Subjects and ensure a lawful basis for sharing and Processing."},{"id":"representations_warranties","type":"standard","order":9,"title":"9. REPRESENTATIONS; WARRANTIES; UNDERTAKINGS","content":"9.1 Mutual representations. Each Party represents and warrants to the other that:\n\n(a) it is duly organised and validly existing (where applicable) and has the power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement;\n\n(b) the person signing this Agreement on its behalf is duly authorised;\n\n(c) entering into and performing this Agreement does not violate any law, regulation, court order, or agreement to which it is a party.\n\n9.2 Consultant warranties. Consultant represents and warrants that:\n\n(a) it has and will maintain the skills, experience, personnel and resources necessary to perform the Services;\n\n(b) it shall perform the Services with reasonable skill and care and in accordance with good industry practice;\n\n(c) it shall comply with Applicable Law and Client’s reasonable policies notified under clause 2.4 and 7.6;\n\n(d) the Work Product (excluding Client Materials) will be original to Consultant or lawfully used, and Client’s receipt and use of the Work Product in accordance with this Agreement will not infringe any third-party IPR;\n\n(e) it will not knowingly introduce any malicious code, logic bombs, time bombs, ransomware, trojans, worms or other harmful or disruptive elements into Client systems or Deliverables;\n\n(f) it has obtained and will maintain all licences, permissions and consents necessary for performance of the Services and for granting the rights in clause 6.\n\n9.3 Reliance and due diligence. Consultant acknowledges that Client has entered into this Agreement in reliance on the warranties in this clause 9.\n\n9.4 Remedies.\n\n(a) Without prejudice to other rights, if Consultant breaches clause 9.2(d), Consultant shall, at its own cost and as Client may reasonably require: (i) procure the right for Client to continue using the affected Deliverable; (ii) modify or replace it so it becomes non-infringing without material loss of functionality; or (iii) if neither (i) nor (ii) is commercially reasonable, refund the Fees paid for the affected Deliverable.\n\n(b) Clause 9.4(a) does not apply to the extent the infringement arises from: (i) Client Materials; (ii) Client’s modifications not authorised by Consultant; or (iii) use contrary to this Agreement.\n\n9.5 Disclaimer. Except as expressly stated in this Agreement and to the fullest extent permitted by law, neither Party gives any warranties, conditions or other terms, whether express or implied, including implied warranties or conditions of satisfactory quality, fitness for a particular purpose, non-infringement, or accuracy.\n\n9.6 Consumer exclusion. The Parties agree they are contracting in the course of business and not as consumers."},{"id":"indemnification","type":"negotiable","order":10,"title":"10. INDEMNITIES; LIMITATION OF LIABILITY; CLAIMS PROCESS","content":"10.1 Consultant indemnity. Consultant shall indemnify and keep indemnified Client, its Affiliates, and their respective directors, officers, employees and agents (each an \"Indemnified Party\") against all losses, liabilities, damages, costs and expenses (including reasonable legal fees) suffered or incurred by an Indemnified Party arising from any third-party claim to the extent caused by:\n\n(a) Consultant’s breach of clause 6 (IP) or clause 7 (Confidentiality);\n\n(b) any allegation that the Work Product infringes a third party’s IPR (subject to clause 9.4(b));\n\n(c) Consultant’s negligence or wilful misconduct;\n\n(d) Consultant’s breach of Applicable Law.\n\n10.2 Client indemnity. Client shall indemnify and keep indemnified Consultant against all losses, liabilities, damages, costs and expenses (including reasonable legal fees) arising from any third-party claim that Client Materials infringe any third party’s IPR, provided Consultant used Client Materials strictly in accordance with this Agreement.\n\n10.3 Indemnity procedure.\n\n(a) The Party seeking indemnity (\"Claimant\") shall promptly notify the indemnifying Party (\"Indemnifier\") of any claim which may give rise to an indemnity under this clause 10.\n\n(b) The Indemnifier shall have the right to control the defence and settlement of the claim, provided that: (i) the Indemnifier shall not settle any claim in a manner that imposes any admission of liability, payment or obligation on the Claimant without the Claimant’s prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld); and (ii) the Indemnifier shall conduct the defence diligently using reasonably competent counsel.\n\n(c) The Claimant shall provide reasonable co-operation at the Indemnifier’s cost.\n\n(d) The Claimant may participate in the defence at its own expense.\n\n10.4 Limitation of liability (subject to clause 10.6).\n\n(a) Neither Party shall be liable to the other for any loss of profits, loss of revenue, loss of business, loss of goodwill, loss of anticipated savings, or any indirect or consequential loss arising out of or in connection with this Agreement.\n\n(b) Subject to clause 10.6, each Party’s total aggregate liability to the other arising out of or in connection with this Agreement (whether in contract, tort (including negligence), misrepresentation, restitution or otherwise) shall not exceed {{liability_cap_amount}}.\n\n(c) The cap in clause 10.4(b) shall not apply to: (i) Client’s obligation to pay undisputed Fees; and (ii) liability under clause 10.1 and clause 10.2 only to the extent expressly carved out in clause 10.6.\n\n10.5 Reasonableness and UCTA. The Parties agree that the limitations and exclusions of liability in this Agreement are fair and reasonable in the circumstances and have been taken into account in determining the Fees, and shall be construed (where applicable) subject to the Unfair Contract Terms Act 1977.\n\n10.6 Unlimited liability / non-excludable liability. Nothing in this Agreement limits or excludes liability for:\n\n(a) death or personal injury caused by negligence;\n\n(b) fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation;\n\n(c) any other liability that cannot legally be limited or excluded under Applicable Law;\n\n(d) breach of clause 7 (Confidentiality) in respect of Trade Secrets (to the extent such limitation would undermine protection);\n\n(e) deliberate or wilful breach of clause 12 (Compliance and Ethics) (if included).\n\n10.7 Mitigation. Each Party shall take reasonable steps to mitigate any loss or damage it suffers arising from the other Party’s breach.\n\n10.8 Time limit for claims (optional). No action arising out of this Agreement may be brought more than {{claims_time_limit_months}} months after the date on which the Party became aware (or ought reasonably to have become aware) of the circumstances giving rise to the claim, except in cases of fraud."},{"id":"insurance","type":"optional","order":11,"title":"11. INSURANCE (OPTIONAL)","content":"11.1 Insurance requirements. Where stated in the SoW or where {{insurance_required}} is \"yes\", Consultant shall maintain, with reputable insurers, the following insurance policies during the Term and for at least 6 years thereafter (or such longer period as required by law):\n\n(a) professional indemnity insurance with a limit of not less than {{professional_indemnity_amount}} per claim;\n\n(b) public liability insurance with a limit of not less than {{public_liability_amount}} per occurrence;\n\n(c) employers’ liability insurance (where required by law) with a limit of not less than £5,000,000; and\n\n(d) cyber/security liability insurance with a limit of not less than {{cyber_insurance_amount}} (if the Services involve access to Client systems or Personal Data).\n\n11.2 Evidence. Consultant shall, upon request, provide Client with certificates of insurance and evidence of payment of premiums.\n\n11.3 No limitation. Consultant’s insurance obligations do not limit Consultant’s liabilities under this Agreement."},{"id":"non_solicitation","type":"optional","order":12,"title":"12. NON-SOLICITATION; RESTRICTIVE COVENANTS (OPTIONAL)","content":"12.1 Purpose and reasonableness. The Parties agree that the restrictions in this clause 12 are reasonable and necessary to protect Client’s legitimate business interests, including Confidential Information, Trade Secrets, and the stability of Client’s workforce and customer relationships.\n\n12.2 Non-solicitation of employees and contractors. During the Term and for {{non_solicitation_months}} months thereafter, Consultant shall not, without Client’s prior written consent, directly or indirectly solicit or entice away, or attempt to solicit or entice away, any person who is employed or engaged by Client (or its Affiliates) with whom Consultant had material dealings in connection with the Services, for the purpose of employing or engaging such person.\n\n12.3 Non-solicitation of customers/suppliers (optional). During the Term and for {{non_solicitation_months}} months thereafter, Consultant shall not directly solicit business from any customer, prospective customer, or supplier of Client (or its Affiliates) with whom Consultant had material dealings during the Term, where such solicitation relates to services that are the same as or substantially similar to the Services.\n\n12.4 Non-dealing (optional). If and to the extent non-solicitation is unenforceable, the Parties agree that clause 12.2 and/or 12.3 shall be read as including a prohibition on dealing.\n\n12.5 Severance. If any restriction in this clause 12 is found unenforceable but would be enforceable if modified, it shall apply with such modifications as are necessary to make it enforceable.\n\n12.6 Carve-outs. This clause 12 shall not prohibit general recruitment advertising not specifically targeted at Client’s personnel, or dealing with customers where the approach was initiated solely by the customer and Consultant has not breached clause 7."},{"id":"governing_law","type":"standard","order":13,"title":"13. GOVERNING LAW; JURISDICTION","content":"13.1 Governing law. This Agreement and any Dispute shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of England and Wales.\n\n13.2 Jurisdiction. Subject to clause 14.12 (Dispute resolution), the courts of England and Wales shall have exclusive jurisdiction to settle any Dispute.\n\n13.3 Interim relief. Nothing in this Agreement prevents either Party from seeking interim or injunctive relief in any court of competent jurisdiction, particularly in relation to clause 6 (Intellectual Property), clause 7 (Confidentiality) and clause 8 (Data Protection)."},{"id":"general_provisions","type":"standard","order":14,"title":"14. GENERAL PROVISIONS (NOTICES; COMPLIANCE; THIRD PARTY RIGHTS; E-SIGNATURES; ETC.)","content":"14.1 Notices.\n\n(a) Any notice given under this Agreement shall be in writing and shall be delivered by hand, by pre-paid recorded delivery post, or by email.\n\n(b) Notices shall be sent to the addresses and emails set out in the signature block (or such other address notified in writing).\n\n(c) Notices are deemed received: (i) if delivered by hand, at the time of delivery; (ii) if posted, at 9.00 am on the second Business Day after posting; (iii) if emailed, at the time of transmission provided no delivery failure notification is received and the email is sent to the correct address.\n\n14.2 Assignment.\n\n(a) Consultant shall not assign, transfer, charge, subcontract or otherwise deal with any of its rights or obligations under this Agreement without Client’s prior written consent.\n\n(b) Client may assign, transfer, charge or deal with its rights and obligations under this Agreement to an Affiliate or in connection with a merger, acquisition, reorganisation or sale of all or substantially all of its assets, provided that it gives notice to Consultant.\n\n14.3 Subcontracting.\n\n(a) Consultant shall not subcontract any of the Services without Client’s prior written consent.\n\n(b) Where Client consents, Consultant remains fully responsible for the acts and omissions of its subcontractors.\n\n14.4 Conflicts of interest. Consultant shall avoid any conflict of interest or situation which may give rise to a conflict of interest in connection with the Services. Consultant shall promptly disclose to Client any actual or potential conflict and co-operate with Client to mitigate or resolve it.\n\n14.5 Compliance and ethics.\n\n(a) Each Party shall comply with Applicable Law.\n\n(b) Bribery and corruption: Consultant shall (and shall procure that its personnel shall) comply with the Bribery Act 2010 and shall not offer, promise, give, request or accept any bribe, facilitation payment, kickback or other improper advantage in connection with this Agreement.\n\n(c) Modern slavery and human trafficking: Where applicable to a Party, that Party shall comply with the Modern Slavery Act 2015 and maintain appropriate policies and due diligence procedures designed to prevent modern slavery and human trafficking in its business and supply chains. Upon reasonable request, a Party shall provide the other with information reasonably necessary to demonstrate compliance.\n\n(d) Sanctions and anti-money laundering (optional): Consultant represents that neither it nor its personnel is subject to sanctions that would prohibit performance. Consultant shall not cause Client to breach any applicable sanctions or anti-money laundering laws.\n\n14.6 Equality and harassment. Consultant shall not unlawfully discriminate and shall comply with the Equality Act 2010. Consultant shall ensure a safe working environment for its personnel and shall not engage in harassment or bullying towards Client personnel.\n\n14.7 Health and safety. If Consultant attends Client premises, Consultant shall comply with Client’s reasonable health and safety policies and instructions.\n\n14.8 Records and audit (non-data).\n\n(a) Consultant shall maintain accurate records relating to performance of the Services, Deliverables and Fees for at least 6 years.\n\n(b) Upon reasonable notice, Client may audit such records solely to verify invoices and compliance with the SoW, no more than once per year, subject to confidentiality.\n\n14.9 Intellectual property marking. Consultant shall not remove any proprietary notices from Client Materials. Client may add proprietary notices to Work Product.\n\n14.10 Third party rights. Except as expressly stated, a person who is not a Party shall not have any rights under the Third Party Rights Act to enforce any term of this Agreement. This clause does not affect any right or remedy of a third party that exists or is available otherwise than under that Act.\n\n14.11 Entire agreement.\n\n(a) This Agreement (together with any SoW) constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties in relation to its subject matter and supersedes all prior discussions, correspondence, representations and understandings.\n\n(b) Each Party acknowledges that it has not relied on any statement, promise or representation not expressly set out in this Agreement, except in the case of fraud.\n\n14.12 Dispute resolution (optional escalation).\n\n(a) The Parties shall use reasonable endeavours to resolve Disputes amicably. Either Party may give written notice of a Dispute.\n\n(b) Within 10 Business Days of notice, the Parties shall meet (remotely or in person) through senior representatives to attempt resolution.\n\n(c) If not resolved within 20 Business Days of notice, either Party may propose mediation through the Centre for Effective Dispute Resolution (CEDR) or another agreed provider. Mediation costs shall be shared equally.\n\n(d) Nothing in this clause prevents either Party seeking interim relief.\n\n14.13 Variation. No variation of this Agreement is effective unless in writing and signed by authorised representatives of both Parties.\n\n14.14 Waiver. A waiver of any right or remedy is only effective if in writing and shall not be deemed a waiver of any subsequent breach or default.\n\n14.15 Severability. If any provision (or part provision) is invalid, illegal or unenforceable, it shall be deemed modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it valid, legal and enforceable. If modification is not possible, it shall be deemed deleted. The remainder shall continue in full force.\n\n14.16 Counterparts; electronic execution. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which is an original and all of which together form one agreement. Execution and delivery by electronic signature and/or PDF is permitted and intended to be binding.\n\n14.17 Force majeure.\n\n(a) Neither Party shall be in breach nor liable for delay/failure caused by a Force Majeure Event.\n\n(b) The affected Party shall promptly notify the other and use reasonable endeavours to mitigate.\n\n(c) If a Force Majeure Event continues for more than 30 days, either Party may terminate the affected SoW on 10 days’ written notice.\n\n14.18 Relationship of the Parties. Nothing in this Agreement creates a partnership, joint venture or relationship of employer and employee. Each Party acts as principal.\n\n14.19 No implied exclusivity. Nothing in this Agreement prevents Client from obtaining similar services from third parties.\n\n14.20 Rights cumulative. The rights and remedies in this Agreement are cumulative and do not exclude any rights or remedies provided by law.\n\n14.21 Further assurance. Each Party shall execute such documents and do such acts as may reasonably be required to give full effect to this Agreement.\n\n14.22 Costs. Each Party shall bear its own costs in relation to negotiation and execution of this Agreement.\n\n14.23 Priority of purchase order terms. Any pre-printed terms on a purchase order or similar document are excluded and shall not apply, even if referenced in an invoice or other document, unless expressly agreed in writing by both Parties."}]'::jsonb,
  signature_block = 'IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Agreement as of {{signature_date}}.

