-- Update: One-Way Non-Disclosure Agreement (England and Wales)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This One-Way Non-Disclosure Agreement (the "Agreement") is made on {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date") between:

(A) {{party_a_company}}, a company incorporated in {{party_a_jurisdiction_of_incorporation}} with registered number {{party_a_company_number}} and registered office at {{party_a_address}} (the "Disclosing Party" or "{{party_a_name}}"); and

(B) {{party_b_company}}, a company incorporated in {{party_b_jurisdiction_of_incorporation}} with registered number {{party_b_company_number}} and registered office at {{party_b_address}} (the "Receiving Party" or "{{party_b_name}}").

Each a "party" and together the "parties".

Each party warrants that: (i) it has full capacity, power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement; (ii) the person signing this Agreement on its behalf is duly authorised; and (iii) this Agreement constitutes legal, valid and binding obligations enforceable in accordance with its terms. Where an individual signs on behalf of an organisation, they do so as an authorised signatory and not in their personal capacity.',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS:

(A) The Disclosing Party possesses and controls certain Confidential Information (including Trade Secrets) relating to its business, technology, products, services, finances, operations, customers, suppliers and/or strategic plans.

(B) The Receiving Party wishes to receive certain Confidential Information from the Disclosing Party solely for the purpose of {{purpose}} (the "Purpose").

(C) The parties wish to record the terms on which the Disclosing Party will disclose Confidential Information to the Receiving Party and the obligations of the Receiving Party in respect of such Confidential Information.

(D) The parties acknowledge that unauthorised use or disclosure of Confidential Information may cause the Disclosing Party significant harm, including loss of competitive advantage and the impairment of legal rights in Trade Secrets.

NOW IT IS AGREED as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATION","content":"1.1 Definitions. In this Agreement, unless the context otherwise requires:\n\n(a) \"Affiliate\" means, in relation to a party, any entity that directly or indirectly Controls, is Controlled by, or is under common Control with that party from time to time.\n\n(b) \"Business Day\" means a day other than a Saturday, Sunday or public holiday in England when banks in London are open for business.\n\n(c) \"Confidential Information\" means any information or matter (in whatever form and on whatever media, whether written, oral, visual, electronic, machine-readable or otherwise) disclosed or made available by or on behalf of the Disclosing Party to the Receiving Party (or its Representatives) before, on or after the Effective Date that:\n\n(i) is marked or otherwise identified as confidential or proprietary; or\n\n(ii) by its nature or the circumstances of disclosure, ought reasonably to be regarded as confidential,\n\nand includes (without limitation) information relating to: business plans, strategies and models; budgets and forecasts; financial information; pricing, margins and terms of supply; customer, prospective customer and supplier information; marketing plans and market research; product or service roadmaps; technical information (including inventions, discoveries, designs, drawings, specifications, formulae, source code, object code, algorithms, architecture, data models, documentation, processes and methods); research and development; security measures; operational procedures; personnel information; and any analyses, compilations, notes, summaries, extracts, copies or materials derived from or reflecting such information.\n\n(d) \"Control\" means the power (directly or indirectly) to direct the management and policies of an entity, whether through ownership of voting securities, contract or otherwise, and \"Controlled\" and \"Controls\" shall be construed accordingly.\n\n(e) \"Discloser Materials\" means all documents and materials (including copies) containing or embodying Confidential Information, including any notes, reports, analyses, compilations, studies or other materials prepared by or for the Receiving Party that contain or reflect Confidential Information.\n\n(f) \"Intellectual Property Rights\" means any and all intellectual property rights and related rights anywhere in the world, whether registered or unregistered, including patents, utility models, rights in inventions, copyright and neighbouring rights, trade marks, service marks, trade names, domain names, rights in get-up, goodwill and the right to sue for passing off, design rights, database rights, rights in confidential information (including Trade Secrets), and any applications for and renewals or extensions of any such rights.\n\n(g) \"Permitted Purpose\" means the Purpose and any activity strictly necessary and incidental to the Purpose.\n\n(h) \"Permitted Recipients\" means: (i) the Receiving Party’s Representatives who have a strict need to know the Confidential Information for the Permitted Purpose; and (ii) any other person expressly approved in advance in writing by the Disclosing Party.\n\n(i) \"Personal Data\" has the meaning given to it in the UK GDPR.\n\n(j) \"Professional Advisers\" means the Receiving Party’s external legal advisers, accountants, auditors, insurers and financial advisers.\n\n(k) \"Representatives\" means, in relation to a party, its and its Affiliates’ directors, officers, employees, agency workers, consultants, contractors (including independent contractors), Professional Advisers, and (where relevant) potential sources of finance, in each case who are bound by confidentiality obligations no less protective than those in this Agreement (whether by contract, professional duty or law).\n\n(l) \"Restricted Transfer\" means a transfer of Personal Data to a country outside the United Kingdom in respect of which the UK GDPR requires appropriate safeguards.\n\n(m) \"Security Incident\" means any actual or reasonably suspected unauthorised or unlawful access to, acquisition of, loss of, alteration of, disclosure of, or destruction of (i) Confidential Information or (ii) Personal Data, including any incident that compromises the confidentiality, integrity or availability of such information.\n\n(n) \"Trade Secret\" means information that qualifies as a trade secret for the purposes of the Trade Secrets (Enforcement, etc.) Regulations 2018, including information that (i) is secret in the sense that it is not, as a body or in the precise configuration and assembly of its components, generally known among or readily accessible to persons within the circles that normally deal with the kind of information in question; (ii) has commercial value because it is secret; and (iii) has been subject to reasonable steps under the circumstances, by the person lawfully in control of the information, to keep it secret.\n\n(o) \"UK GDPR\" means Regulation (EU) 2016/679 as it forms part of the law of England and Wales by virtue of section 3 of the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018, as amended, supplemented or replaced from time to time.\n\n1.2 Interpretation.\n\n(a) Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation.\n\n(b) A reference to a \"person\" includes an individual, firm, company, corporation, partnership, limited liability partnership, unincorporated association, government authority, state or agency of a state.\n\n(c) A reference to \"including\" or \"in particular\" shall not limit the generality of the preceding words.\n\n(d) A reference to a statute or statutory provision includes any subordinate legislation made under it and includes any modification, re-enactment or replacement of it.\n\n(e) References to \"writing\" include email and other electronic communications capable of being reproduced in legible form, provided that (unless otherwise stated) notices must comply with clause 10.1.\n\n(f) Where this Agreement states that the Receiving Party must do or not do something, it must procure that its Permitted Recipients do or do not do that thing (as applicable)."},{"id":"confidentiality_obligations","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. CONFIDENTIALITY OBLIGATIONS","content":"2.1 Core obligation. In consideration of the disclosure of Confidential Information by the Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party shall:\n\n(a) keep the Confidential Information strictly confidential;\n\n(b) use the Confidential Information solely for the Permitted Purpose;\n\n(c) not disclose the Confidential Information to any person except Permitted Recipients in accordance with this Agreement; and\n\n(d) protect the Confidential Information with the level of care and security measures required by this Agreement.\n\n2.2 Need-to-know and minimum disclosure. The Receiving Party shall ensure that:\n\n(a) access to Confidential Information is limited to Permitted Recipients who have a genuine need to know for the Permitted Purpose; and\n\n(b) any disclosure is limited to the minimum amount of Confidential Information necessary to achieve the Permitted Purpose.\n\n2.3 Conditions of disclosure to Permitted Recipients.\n\n(a) Before any disclosure to a Permitted Recipient, the Receiving Party shall ensure that the Permitted Recipient is bound by confidentiality obligations (by contract, professional duty or law) that are no less restrictive than the obligations in this Agreement.\n\n(b) The Receiving Party remains responsible and liable for any act or omission of its Permitted Recipients as if it were the Receiving Party’s own act or omission.\n\n2.4 No copying; permitted copies. The Receiving Party shall not copy, reproduce, reverse engineer, decompile, disassemble or otherwise reduce to practice any Confidential Information, except to the extent strictly necessary for the Permitted Purpose and then only provided that:\n\n(a) any copies are clearly marked as confidential (where practicable);\n\n(b) the number of copies is kept to a minimum; and\n\n(c) such copies are treated as Confidential Information and constitute Discloser Materials.\n\n2.5 No circumvention; no misuse. The Receiving Party shall not use Confidential Information to:\n\n(a) compete unfairly with the Disclosing Party;\n\n(b) solicit, induce or attempt to induce customers, suppliers or other counterparties of the Disclosing Party to reduce or cease their dealings with the Disclosing Party by improper means; or\n\n(c) circumvent the Disclosing Party in relation to the Purpose,\n\nprovided that nothing in this clause 2.5 restricts lawful competition based solely on information that falls within clause 3 (Exclusions) or is otherwise lawfully available to the Receiving Party without breach of this Agreement.\n\n2.6 Information disclosed orally or visually. Confidential Information disclosed orally, visually or by demonstration shall be treated as Confidential Information whether or not it is marked or later summarised in writing.\n\n2.7 Protection and security measures.\n\n(a) The Receiving Party shall implement and maintain appropriate technical and organisational measures to protect Confidential Information against unauthorised or unlawful processing, access, disclosure, alteration, loss, damage or destruction.\n\n(b) Without limiting clause 2.7(a), such measures shall (where appropriate to the nature of the Confidential Information) include: access controls; least-privilege permissions; multi-factor authentication; encryption in transit and at rest; secure storage; endpoint protection; segregation of duties; secure disposal; and staff training.\n\n(c) The Receiving Party shall promptly notify the Disclosing Party in writing if it becomes aware of any Security Incident affecting Confidential Information and shall: (i) provide reasonable information about the nature and scope of the incident; (ii) take steps to contain, remediate and mitigate the effects; and (iii) co-operate with the Disclosing Party (at the Disclosing Party’s reasonable cost where the incident was not caused by the Disclosing Party) in connection with any investigation and/or legal or regulatory steps.\n\n2.8 Compelled disclosure.\n\n(a) If the Receiving Party (or any of its Representatives) is required by applicable law, regulation, court order, or competent regulatory authority to disclose any Confidential Information, the Receiving Party shall, to the extent legally permitted:\n\n(i) give the Disclosing Party prompt written notice of such requirement;\n\n(ii) consult with the Disclosing Party as to the content of the disclosure;\n\n(iii) co-operate with the Disclosing Party (at the Disclosing Party’s reasonable request and expense) in seeking a protective order, confidential treatment or other appropriate remedy; and\n\n(iv) disclose only that portion of the Confidential Information which is strictly required and use reasonable efforts to ensure that confidential treatment is accorded to the disclosed Confidential Information.\n\n(b) Nothing in this Agreement requires the Receiving Party to act unlawfully or to breach any binding obligation imposed by a competent authority.\n\n2.9 No public announcement. The Receiving Party shall not make any public statement, press release or other announcement relating to the existence or subject matter of this Agreement, the Purpose or the Confidential Information without the Disclosing Party’s prior written consent, except to the extent required under clause 2.8.\n\n2.10 Protection of Trade Secrets. The parties acknowledge that the Disclosing Party considers certain Confidential Information to be Trade Secrets and that preserving their secrecy is essential. The Receiving Party shall not do anything that would (or might reasonably be expected to) jeopardise the confidentiality or trade secret status of any Trade Secret.\n\n2.11 No implied rights. Except for the limited right to use Confidential Information strictly for the Permitted Purpose, no licence or other right (whether by implication, estoppel or otherwise) is granted to the Receiving Party under any Intellectual Property Rights of the Disclosing Party.\n\n2.12 No obligation to disclose; no commitment. Nothing in this Agreement:\n\n(a) obliges the Disclosing Party to disclose any particular information; or\n\n(b) obliges either party to enter into any further agreement or business relationship.\n\n2.13 No warranty. All Confidential Information is disclosed \"as is\". To the fullest extent permitted by law, the Disclosing Party gives no representation or warranty (express or implied) as to the accuracy, completeness or fitness for purpose of the Confidential Information, and the Disclosing Party shall have no liability arising from the Receiving Party’s reliance on the Confidential Information, except in respect of fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation."},{"id":"exclusions","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. EXCLUSIONS FROM CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION","content":"3.1 Excluded information. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by written records (contemporaneous where reasonably practicable):\n\n(a) is or becomes generally available to the public other than as a result of a breach of this Agreement or any other duty of confidence owed to the Disclosing Party;\n\n(b) was lawfully in the Receiving Party’s possession before disclosure by the Disclosing Party, and was not acquired (directly or indirectly) from the Disclosing Party or any person owing a duty of confidence to the Disclosing Party;\n\n(c) is lawfully received by the Receiving Party from a third party who, to the Receiving Party’s reasonable knowledge and after reasonable enquiry where appropriate, is not under an obligation of confidence in respect of that information;\n\n(d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without reference to, use of or reliance on Confidential Information (and mere reliance on general skill and experience is not, by itself, prohibited by this Agreement);\n\n(e) is approved for release or disclosure by the Disclosing Party in writing (and only to the extent and for the purpose so approved).\n\n3.2 No combination exception. Information shall not be deemed to fall within clause 3.1 merely because individual features or elements are in the public domain or known to the Receiving Party, unless the combination of those features or elements and their arrangement is also in the public domain or otherwise falls within clause 3.1.\n\n3.3 Burden of proof. The Receiving Party bears the burden of proving that any information falls within an exclusion in clause 3.1.\n\n3.4 Continuing obligations for derived materials. Even where an exclusion applies to underlying information, any Discloser Materials that contain or reflect other Confidential Information remain subject to this Agreement.\n\n3.5 Privileged material. Disclosure of any information subject to legal professional privilege shall not constitute a waiver of privilege, and the Receiving Party shall not take any step inconsistent with the preservation of such privilege (including, where appropriate, co-operating with the Disclosing Party in maintaining privilege)."},{"id":"term_and_duration","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TERM, TERMINATION AND DURATION OF OBLIGATIONS","content":"4.1 Term. This Agreement commences on the Effective Date and continues until the earlier of:\n\n(a) {{expiration_date}} (if specified); or\n\n(b) termination by either party in accordance with clause 4.2,\n\nthe \"Term\".\n\n4.2 Termination for convenience. Either party may terminate this Agreement at any time by giving the other party not less than {{notice_period}} days’ written notice.\n\n4.3 Immediate termination. The Disclosing Party may terminate this Agreement immediately on written notice if the Receiving Party commits a material breach of this Agreement (including any breach of clause 2).\n\n4.4 Survival.\n\n(a) The obligations in clauses 2 (Confidentiality Obligations), 5 (Return or Destruction), 6 (Data Protection), 8 (Remedies), 9 (Governing Law and Jurisdiction) and 10 (General Provisions), and any other provision intended to survive, shall survive expiry or termination.\n\n(b) Subject to clause 4.4(c), the Receiving Party’s confidentiality and use restrictions in clause 2 shall continue for {{confidentiality_period}} years from the date of disclosure of the relevant Confidential Information.\n\n(c) In respect of any Trade Secret, the Receiving Party’s obligations shall continue for so long as that information remains a Trade Secret.\n\n4.5 Effect of termination. Termination or expiry shall not affect any rights, remedies, obligations or liabilities that have accrued up to the date of termination or expiry.\n\n4.6 Suspension of disclosures. The Disclosing Party may, at its discretion, suspend further disclosures of Confidential Information at any time without liability."},{"id":"return_of_information","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. RETURN OR DESTRUCTION OF INFORMATION","content":"5.1 Request and timing. Upon the Disclosing Party’s written request at any time, or upon termination/expiry of this Agreement (whichever occurs first), the Receiving Party shall promptly (and in any event within {{return_period_days}} days):\n\n(a) return to the Disclosing Party all Discloser Materials in its possession or control; or\n\n(b) destroy (or permanently erase) all Discloser Materials,\n\nas the Disclosing Party directs.\n\n5.2 Certification. If the Disclosing Party requests, the Receiving Party shall provide a written certificate signed by an authorised officer confirming compliance with clause 5.1 and describing, at a high level, the steps taken.\n\n5.3 Back-ups and routine archival. Notwithstanding clause 5.1, the Receiving Party may retain copies of Discloser Materials to the extent:\n\n(a) required by applicable law, regulation, a competent authority, or a bona fide internal compliance or document retention policy; or\n\n(b) stored in routine automated back-up systems that are not reasonably practicable to delete without disproportionate effort,\n\nprovided that: (i) such retained materials shall remain subject to this Agreement; (ii) access shall be restricted to those with a strict need to know for compliance purposes; and (iii) the Receiving Party shall not use such retained materials for any purpose.\n\n5.4 Legal hold. If the Receiving Party is required to preserve materials for litigation, investigation, audit or regulatory purposes, it may retain those materials for as long as required, subject to the ongoing obligations of confidentiality and security.\n\n5.5 No right to retain. Except as expressly permitted by clause 5.3 or 5.4, the Receiving Party shall not retain any Confidential Information in any form, including in notes, summaries or internal reports.\n\n5.6 No obligation to return tangible items that are not Confidential Information. The parties acknowledge that Confidential Information may include intangible knowledge; however, the Receiving Party remains bound by clause 2 in respect of any Confidential Information retained in memory (deliberately or inadvertently) and shall not use or disclose it."},{"id":"data_protection","type":"standard","order":6,"title":"6. DATA PROTECTION (UK GDPR AND DATA PROTECTION ACT 2018)","content":"6.1 Scope. This clause 6 applies to the extent that any Confidential Information includes Personal Data.\n\n6.2 Independent controllers (default position).\n\n(a) Unless the parties otherwise agree in writing, each party shall act as an independent controller in respect of any Personal Data it receives under or in connection with this Agreement.\n\n(b) Each party shall comply with its obligations under the UK GDPR and the Data Protection Act 2018, including (where applicable) obligations relating to transparency, lawful basis, data minimisation, storage limitation, security, and respect for data subjects’ rights.\n\n6.3 Purpose limitation and minimisation. The Receiving Party shall:\n\n(a) process Personal Data only to the extent necessary for the Permitted Purpose and in accordance with clause 2.1;\n\n(b) not use Personal Data for marketing, profiling, automated decision-making or any unrelated purpose; and\n\n(c) take reasonable steps to ensure that Personal Data is adequate, relevant and limited to what is necessary for the Permitted Purpose.\n\n6.4 Special category and criminal offence data. The Disclosing Party will not knowingly disclose special category data or data relating to criminal convictions and offences unless necessary for the Purpose. Where such data is disclosed, the Receiving Party shall process it only where lawful and subject to additional safeguards required by the UK GDPR and the Data Protection Act 2018.\n\n6.5 Security measures.\n\n(a) The Receiving Party shall implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure a level of security appropriate to the risk, taking into account the state of the art, costs of implementation, nature, scope, context and purposes of processing, and the risks to individuals.\n\n(b) Such measures shall include, where appropriate: pseudonymisation and encryption; confidentiality, integrity, availability and resilience of systems; ability to restore availability and access in a timely manner following an incident; and a process for regularly testing and evaluating the effectiveness of measures.\n\n6.6 Personal data breaches.\n\n(a) The Receiving Party shall notify the Disclosing Party without undue delay (and in any event within {{personal_data_breach_notice_hours}} hours) after becoming aware of a Security Incident involving Personal Data received from the Disclosing Party.\n\n(b) The Receiving Party shall provide reasonable assistance to the Disclosing Party to enable it to comply with its obligations relating to personal data breaches, including (where applicable) notifications to the Information Commissioner’s Office and communications to affected individuals.\n\n6.7 International transfers. The Receiving Party shall not make any Restricted Transfer of Personal Data received from the Disclosing Party unless it has ensured that appropriate safeguards are in place in accordance with the UK GDPR (for example, the UK International Data Transfer Agreement, the UK Addendum to the EU Standard Contractual Clauses, or an adequacy regulation), and it has provided the Disclosing Party with reasonable prior written notice of the proposed transfer and safeguards.\n\n6.8 Data subject rights and regulatory co-operation.\n\n(a) The Receiving Party shall, taking into account the nature of the processing, provide reasonable assistance to the Disclosing Party to respond to requests to exercise data subject rights under the UK GDPR, to the extent such requests relate to Personal Data disclosed under this Agreement.\n\n(b) The Receiving Party shall notify the Disclosing Party promptly if it receives a complaint, notice or communication from the Information Commissioner’s Office or another supervisory authority that relates to Personal Data disclosed under this Agreement (unless prohibited by law).\n\n6.9 Retention and deletion. The Receiving Party shall not retain Personal Data longer than necessary for the Permitted Purpose and shall securely delete or return it in accordance with clause 5, subject to the exceptions in clauses 5.3 and 5.4.\n\n6.10 Processor scenario (optional). If and to the extent the Receiving Party processes Personal Data on behalf of the Disclosing Party as a processor (rather than as an independent controller), the parties shall either (i) enter into a separate data processing agreement, or (ii) treat this clause 6.10 and Annex 1 as the required processor terms under Article 28 UK GDPR. In that scenario, the Receiving Party shall:\n\n(a) process Personal Data only on the documented instructions of the Disclosing Party (including with regard to transfers);\n\n(b) ensure persons authorised to process the Personal Data are subject to a duty of confidentiality;\n\n(c) implement appropriate technical and organisational measures as required by Article 32 UK GDPR;\n\n(d) not engage another processor without the Disclosing Party’s prior written authorisation (general or specific) and, where authorised, impose equivalent data protection obligations on such sub-processor;\n\n(e) assist the Disclosing Party by appropriate technical and organisational measures to fulfil its obligation to respond to requests for exercising data subject rights;\n\n(f) assist the Disclosing Party in ensuring compliance with obligations pursuant to Articles 32 to 36 UK GDPR (security, breach notification, DPIAs and prior consultation), taking into account the nature of processing and information available to the Receiving Party;\n\n(g) at the choice of the Disclosing Party, delete or return all Personal Data after the end of provision of services relating to processing, and delete existing copies except where UK law requires storage; and\n\n(h) make available to the Disclosing Party all information reasonably necessary to demonstrate compliance with this clause 6.10 and allow for and contribute to audits, including inspections, conducted by the Disclosing Party or an auditor mandated by the Disclosing Party, subject to reasonable confidentiality and security restrictions.\n\n6.11 Contacts. Data protection queries and notices under this clause 6 shall be directed to: (i) for the Disclosing Party, {{data_protection_contact_a}}; and (ii) for the Receiving Party, {{data_protection_contact_b}}.\n\n6.12 Precedence. If there is any conflict between this clause 6 and any other provision of this Agreement, this clause 6 shall prevail to the extent of the conflict in relation to Personal Data."},{"id":"non_solicitation","type":"optional","order":7,"title":"7. OPTIONAL NON-SOLICITATION AND NON-INTERFERENCE","content":"7.1 Applicability. This clause 7 applies only if {{include_non_solicitation}} is set to \"yes\".\n\n7.2 Non-solicitation of employees and consultants. During the Term and for a period of {{non_solicitation_period}} months thereafter, the Receiving Party shall not, without the Disclosing Party’s prior written consent, directly solicit for employment or engagement any employee or consultant of the Disclosing Party with whom the Receiving Party had material dealings in connection with the Purpose.\n\n7.3 Non-solicitation of customers and suppliers (optional). During the Term and for a period of {{non_solicitation_period}} months thereafter, the Receiving Party shall not, by use of Confidential Information, directly solicit the custom of, or seek to divert business from, any customer, prospective customer, supplier or prospective supplier of the Disclosing Party with whom the Receiving Party had material dealings through the Purpose.\n\n7.4 General advertising. Clauses 7.2 and 7.3 shall not prevent general recruitment advertising not targeted at the Disclosing Party’s personnel, nor the engagement of any person who responds to such advertising without direct solicitation.\n\n7.5 Reasonableness. The parties agree that the restrictions in this clause 7 are reasonable and necessary to protect the Disclosing Party’s legitimate interests, including its Confidential Information and business connections."},{"id":"remedies","type":"negotiable","order":8,"title":"8. REMEDIES","content":"8.1 Acknowledgement of harm. The Receiving Party acknowledges that:\n\n(a) the Confidential Information is of a unique and proprietary nature;\n\n(b) unauthorised use or disclosure may cause the Disclosing Party irreparable harm for which damages may not be an adequate remedy; and\n\n(c) unauthorised use or disclosure may result in the loss of protection for Trade Secrets.\n\n8.2 Injunctive and equitable relief. Without prejudice to any other rights or remedies, the Disclosing Party shall be entitled to seek interim, interlocutory and final injunctive relief, specific performance and/or other equitable relief to enforce this Agreement, without needing to prove actual loss, and (to the extent permitted by law) without the need to provide security.\n\n8.3 Trade secrets remedies. Nothing in this Agreement limits or excludes any rights or remedies available to the Disclosing Party under the Trade Secrets (Enforcement, etc.) Regulations 2018, including (as applicable) measures relating to confidentiality preservation in proceedings, delivery up, destruction, or injunctions against use or disclosure of Trade Secrets.\n\n8.4 Mitigation and co-operation. The Receiving Party shall, at its own cost (except where a breach is caused by the Disclosing Party), promptly co-operate with the Disclosing Party and take all reasonable steps to mitigate and remediate the effects of any actual or suspected breach, including assisting with:\n\n(a) tracing and recovering disclosed Confidential Information;\n\n(b) informing third parties who may have received Confidential Information in breach of this Agreement; and\n\n(c) implementing additional safeguards to prevent recurrence.\n\n8.5 Costs. The court may award costs as it sees fit. Nothing in this Agreement prevents the Disclosing Party from seeking recovery of reasonable costs and expenses incurred in enforcing this Agreement where permitted by law.\n\n8.6 Cumulative remedies. The rights and remedies provided in this Agreement are cumulative and not exclusive of any rights or remedies provided by law."},{"id":"governing_law","type":"standard","order":9,"title":"9. GOVERNING LAW AND JURISDICTION","content":"9.1 Governing law. This Agreement and any dispute or claim (including non-contractual disputes or claims) arising out of or in connection with it or its subject matter shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the law of England and Wales.\n\n9.2 Jurisdiction. Subject to clause 9.3, the parties irrevocably agree that the courts of England and Wales shall have exclusive jurisdiction to settle any dispute or claim (including non-contractual disputes or claims) arising out of or in connection with this Agreement or its subject matter.\n\n9.3 Interim relief. Nothing in this clause 9 prevents a party from seeking urgent interim or injunctive relief in any court of competent jurisdiction where such relief is necessary to protect that party’s Confidential Information or Trade Secrets.\n\n9.4 Service of proceedings. Each party agrees that proceedings may be served on it in accordance with the notice provisions in clause 10.1, provided that nothing in this Agreement limits any other lawful method of service."},{"id":"general_provisions","type":"standard","order":10,"title":"10. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"10.1 Notices.\n\n(a) Any notice given under or in connection with this Agreement shall be in writing and shall be delivered by hand, by pre-paid recorded delivery (or other next Business Day delivery service), or by email.\n\n(b) Notices shall be sent to the addresses and email addresses set out below (or to such other address or email address as a party notifies to the other in accordance with this clause 10.1):\n\n(i) Disclosing Party notices: Address: {{party_a_address}}. Email: {{notice_email_a}} (for the attention of {{party_a_name}}).\n\n(ii) Receiving Party notices: Address: {{party_b_address}}. Email: {{notice_email_b}} (for the attention of {{party_b_name}}).\n\n(c) A notice is deemed to have been received:\n\n(i) if delivered by hand, at the time the notice is left at the proper address;\n\n(ii) if sent by recorded delivery or next Business Day delivery service, at 9.00 am on the second Business Day after posting; and\n\n(iii) if sent by email, at the time of transmission provided that no delivery failure notification is received by the sender (but an auto-reply does not constitute receipt).\n\n(d) This clause does not apply to the service of legal proceedings or other documents in any legal action.\n\n10.2 Assignment and subcontracting.\n\n(a) The Receiving Party shall not assign, transfer, charge, subcontract, declare a trust over or deal in any other manner with any of its rights or obligations under this Agreement without the Disclosing Party’s prior written consent.\n\n(b) The Disclosing Party may assign or transfer its rights and obligations under this Agreement to an Affiliate or to a successor in connection with a merger, reorganisation, business transfer or sale of assets, provided that the Disclosing Party notifies the Receiving Party.\n\n10.3 Entire agreement. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the parties relating to its subject matter and supersedes any prior agreement, understanding or arrangement between them relating to that subject matter. Each party acknowledges that it does not rely on, and shall have no remedies in respect of, any statement, representation, assurance or warranty (whether made innocently or negligently) other than as set out in this Agreement, except in respect of fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation.\n\n10.4 Variation. No variation of this Agreement shall be effective unless it is in writing and signed by (or on behalf of) each party.\n\n10.5 Waiver. A waiver of any right or remedy under this Agreement (or by law) is only effective if given in writing and shall not be deemed a waiver of any subsequent breach or default. A failure or delay by a party to exercise any right or remedy shall not constitute a waiver of that or any other right or remedy.\n\n10.6 Severance.\n\n(a) If any provision (or part of a provision) of this Agreement is or becomes invalid, illegal or unenforceable, it shall be deemed modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it valid, legal and enforceable.\n\n(b) If such modification is not possible, the relevant provision (or part) shall be deemed deleted.\n\n(c) Any modification to or deletion of a provision (or part) under this clause 10.6 shall not affect the validity and enforceability of the rest of this Agreement.\n\n10.7 No partnership or agency. Nothing in this Agreement is intended to, or shall be deemed to, establish any partnership or joint venture between any of the parties, constitute any party the agent of another party, or authorise any party to make or enter into any commitments for or on behalf of any other party.\n\n10.8 Independent contractor; IR35/off-payroll working.\n\n(a) This Agreement does not create an employment relationship. Where the Purpose contemplates that the Receiving Party (or its personnel) may provide services to the Disclosing Party, the parties intend that any such services are provided as an independent contractor relationship unless and until a separate written contract is entered into.\n\n(b) Each party is responsible for its own tax affairs arising from this Agreement.\n\n(c) Where the off-payroll working rules (commonly referred to as \"IR35\") apply to any engagement connected with the Purpose, the parties shall co-operate reasonably to determine the correct status and to comply with their respective obligations (including any status determination statement obligations, where applicable). Nothing in this Agreement is intended to allocate IR35 liability contrary to mandatory law.\n\n10.9 Compliance with laws; ethical conduct.\n\n(a) Each party shall comply with all applicable laws and regulations in connection with this Agreement and the Purpose.\n\n(b) Anti-bribery and corruption. Each party shall (and shall procure that its associated persons shall) comply with the Bribery Act 2010. Without prejudice to the foregoing, neither party shall offer, promise, give, request or accept any financial or other advantage as an inducement for improper performance of a relevant function or activity in connection with the Purpose.\n\n(c) Modern slavery and human trafficking. Where applicable (including where a party is required to publish a slavery and human trafficking statement under section 54 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015), each party shall maintain policies and procedures to ensure that slavery and human trafficking are not taking place in its business or supply chains, and shall provide reasonable information to the other party on request to support compliance.\n\n(d) Sanctions and export controls (optional). The Receiving Party shall not use, export, re-export or transfer any Confidential Information in breach of applicable sanctions, trade controls or export control laws.\n\n10.10 No licence; ownership.\n\n(a) All Confidential Information and all Intellectual Property Rights in it remain the property of the Disclosing Party (or its licensors).\n\n(b) Any Discloser Materials created by the Receiving Party shall be owned by the Receiving Party, but they shall be treated as Confidential Information and subject to the Disclosing Party’s rights in the underlying Confidential Information.\n\n10.11 Third party rights. A person who is not a party to this Agreement shall not have any rights under the Contracts (Rights of Third Parties) Act 1999 to enforce any term of this Agreement.\n\n10.12 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in any number of counterparts, each of which, when executed, is an original, and all counterparts together form one agreement.\n\n10.13 Electronic signatures. This Agreement may be executed by electronic signature and each party agrees that electronic signatures shall be effective to bind that party, consistent with the Electronic Communications Act 2000 and applicable common law principles.\n\n10.14 Further assurance. Each party shall, at its own cost, do and execute or arrange the doing and executing of such acts, documents and things as may be reasonably required to give full effect to this Agreement.\n\n10.15 Rights and remedies. Except as expressly provided in this Agreement, the rights and remedies provided under this Agreement are in addition to, and not exclusive of, any rights or remedies provided by law.\n\n10.16 Order of precedence. If there is any inconsistency between the clauses of this Agreement and any annex, the clauses of this Agreement shall prevail unless the annex expressly states otherwise.\n\nAnnex 1 (Optional): Processing Details (Article 28 UK GDPR) if clause 6.10 applies\n\nA1.1 Subject matter and duration of processing: {{processing_subject_matter_and_duration}}\n\nA1.2 Nature and purpose of processing: processing for the Permitted Purpose\n\nA1.3 Types of Personal Data: {{processing_types_of_personal_data}}\n\nA1.4 Categories of data subjects: {{processing_categories_of_data_subjects}}\n\nA1.5 Special category data (if any): {{processing_special_category_data}}\n\nA1.6 Processing operations: receipt, storage, review, analysis, limited sharing with authorised Permitted Recipients, and deletion/return\n\nA1.7 Location(s) of processing: {{processing_locations}}\n\nA1.8 Sub-processors (if authorised): {{processing_subprocessors}}\n\nA1.9 Technical and organisational measures (summary): {{processing_toms_summary}}"}]'::jsonb,
