-- Update: Consulting Services Agreement (New York)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Consulting Services Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date") by and between (i) {{party_a_company}}, a {{party_a_entity_type}} organized under the laws of the State of {{party_a_state}}, with its principal place of business at {{party_a_address}} ("Client"), and (ii) {{party_b_company}}, a {{party_b_entity_type}} organized under the laws of the State of {{party_b_state}}, with its principal place of business at {{party_b_address}} ("Consultant"). Client and Consultant may be referred to herein individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties." 

This Agreement is intended to satisfy any applicable written contract requirements under New York law, including (as applicable) the New York City Freelance Isn’t Free Act (NYC Admin. Code § 20-927 et seq.) and/or New York Labor Law Article 44 (collectively, the "Freelance Worker Protections"), for covered engagements, including engagements valued at $800 or more (whether in the aggregate for a 120-day period or as otherwise defined by law).',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, Client desires to engage Consultant to provide certain professional consulting services related to {{project_name}} on the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement;

WHEREAS, Consultant represents that Consultant has the expertise, experience, and resources to perform such services in a timely, professional, and workmanlike manner;

WHEREAS, the Parties intend to set forth in writing the scope of services, compensation, deliverables (if any), ownership and licensing of work product, confidentiality obligations, data privacy and security requirements, and other terms customary for a consulting engagement governed by New York law;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises and covenants contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS; INTERPRETATION","content":"1.1 Definitions. For purposes of this Agreement, the following terms have the meanings set forth below:\n\n(a) \"Acceptance\" or \"Accepted\" means Client’s written acceptance of a Deliverable or milestone, or deemed acceptance pursuant to Section 3.4.\n\n(b) \"Affiliate\" means, with respect to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with such Party.\n\n(c) \"Background IP\" means all inventions, works of authorship, software (including source code and object code), documentation, know-how, methods, tools, templates, processes, algorithms, concepts, trade secrets, and other intellectual property that (i) were developed, conceived, created, or reduced to practice by Consultant (or its personnel) prior to the Effective Date, or (ii) are developed outside the scope of the Services without use of Client Confidential Information, in each case excluding Work Product.\n\n(d) \"Business Day\" means a day other than a Saturday, Sunday, or day on which banks in New York, New York are authorized or required to close.\n\n(e) \"Change Order\" means a written change order, statement of work, amendment, or other writing signed (including electronically) by both Parties that changes the Services, Deliverables, timeline, assumptions, personnel, fees, or other project terms.\n\n(f) \"Client Materials\" means any materials, data, content, specifications, software, systems access, documentation, or other items provided or made available by or on behalf of Client to Consultant in connection with the Services.\n\n(g) \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed by a Party (\"Disclosing Party\") to the other Party (\"Receiving Party\"), whether orally, visually, in writing, or by inspection of tangible objects, that is designated as confidential or that reasonably should be understood to be confidential given the nature of the information and the circumstances of disclosure. Confidential Information includes Trade Secrets and Personal Data. Confidential Information of Client includes Client Materials and any non-public information about Client’s business, customers, finances, pricing, products, roadmaps, systems, security, and operations.\n\n(h) \"Deliverables\" means the tangible and/or intangible outputs, reports, analyses, recommendations, designs, specifications, presentations, documentation, software, or other materials identified as deliverables in {{services_description}} and/or any applicable Change Order.\n\n(i) \"Dispute\" means any claim, controversy, or dispute arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the Services, the Deliverables, the Work Product, or the relationship of the Parties.\n\n(j) \"Freelance Worker Protections\" has the meaning set forth in the Preamble.\n\n(k) \"Hiring Party\" and \"Freelance Worker\" (or similar terms) will have the meanings assigned under applicable New York law (including NYC Admin. Code § 20-927 and/or NY Labor Law Article 44) to the extent such law applies to this engagement. For clarity, the Parties acknowledge that Consultant may be treated as a freelance worker for purposes of the Freelance Worker Protections even if Consultant is a business entity, to the extent permitted by applicable law.\n\n(l) \"Intellectual Property Rights\" means all intellectual property and proprietary rights of every kind, whether registered or unregistered, including rights in patents, patent applications, inventions, copyrights, mask works, moral rights (to the extent recognized), trademarks, service marks, trade names, trade dress, database rights, Trade Secrets, and all rights of attribution, integrity, disclosure, and withdrawal.\n\n(m) \"Martin Act\" means the New York General Business Law Article 23-A and related provisions and regulations concerning securities and related matters.\n\n(n) \"Personal Data\" means information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked (directly or indirectly) with an identified or identifiable natural person, including \"private information\" and \"personal information\" as defined under applicable New York law (including, as applicable, the New York SHIELD Act and New York breach notification laws).\n\n(o) \"Records\" means records relating to this Agreement and the engagement, including copies of this Agreement and any Change Orders, invoices, payment confirmations, and other documentation sufficient to demonstrate compliance with payment and other requirements. Where the Freelance Worker Protections apply, Records include those required to be retained for at least six (6) years.\n\n(p) \"Services\" means the consulting services described in {{services_description}}, as modified by any Change Order.\n\n(q) \"Trade Secrets\" means information that derives independent economic value from not being generally known and is the subject of reasonable efforts to maintain secrecy, including as recognized under New York common law and the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act.\n\n(r) \"Work Product\" means all Deliverables and any other materials, inventions, discoveries, developments, works of authorship, designs, analyses, documentation, notes, reports, and other results (whether or not patentable or copyrightable) that Consultant or its personnel conceives, creates, develops, authors, reduces to practice, or otherwise makes in the course of performing the Services, including any associated Intellectual Property Rights.\n\n1.2 Interpretation.\n\n(a) Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation.\n\n(b) The words \"including\" and \"include\" mean \"including, without limitation.\" \n\n(c) If there is a conflict between the body of this Agreement and {{services_description}} or any Change Order, the conflict will be resolved in the following order of precedence unless expressly stated otherwise in a signed writing: (i) a later-signed Change Order; (ii) this Agreement; (iii) an earlier-signed Change Order; (iv) {{services_description}}.\n\n(d) References to \"law\" include statutes, ordinances, rules, regulations, orders, and applicable guidance having the force of law.\n\n(e) The Parties intend this Agreement to be interpreted and enforced to the fullest extent permitted under New York law, including with respect to any equitable remedies."},{"id":"engagement","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. ENGAGEMENT AND SERVICES","content":"2.1 Engagement. Client hereby engages Consultant to perform the Services, and Consultant accepts such engagement, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement.\n\n2.2 Scope of Services. Consultant will perform the Services described in {{services_description}}. Any Services not expressly described therein are outside the scope unless added by Change Order.\n\n2.3 Standard of Performance. Consultant will perform the Services in a professional and workmanlike manner consistent with generally accepted industry standards for similar services and will use personnel with appropriate skill, training, and experience.\n\n2.4 No Authority to Bind; No Agency. Consultant has no authority to (and will not) enter into contracts, make commitments, issue refunds, or make representations or warranties on behalf of Client, unless Client expressly authorizes Consultant in a separate signed writing. Nothing in this Agreement creates a partnership, joint venture, fiduciary relationship, or agency relationship between the Parties.\n\n2.5 Key Personnel; Subcontractors.\n\n(a) Key Personnel. If the Services are materially dependent on specific individuals, such individuals will be identified in {{services_description}} (\"Key Personnel\"). Consultant will not replace Key Personnel without Client’s reasonable prior written approval, except due to circumstances beyond Consultant’s reasonable control.\n\n(b) Subcontractors. Consultant may not subcontract or delegate material portions of the Services without Client’s prior written consent, which will not be unreasonably withheld. Consultant remains responsible for the acts and omissions of any approved subcontractors and will ensure they are bound by written obligations no less protective than this Agreement with respect to confidentiality, data protection, intellectual property, and compliance.\n\n2.6 Client Responsibilities; Assumptions; Dependencies.\n\n(a) Access and Cooperation. Client will timely provide access to Client personnel, Client Materials, systems, and information reasonably necessary for Consultant to perform the Services. Client will designate a primary point of contact identified as {{client_primary_contact_name}} and/or {{client_primary_contact_email}}.\n\n(b) Decisions and Approvals. Client will provide timely decisions, feedback, and approvals reasonably required to meet any agreed schedule.\n\n(c) Delays. Consultant is not responsible for delays caused by Client’s failure to timely provide required access, information, approvals, or decisions. Any schedule and/or milestone dates will be adjusted equitably to reflect such delays.\n\n2.7 Change Control. Any change to the Services, Deliverables, assumptions, acceptance criteria, schedule, or fees must be set forth in a Change Order signed by both Parties. Consultant has no obligation to commence out-of-scope work without an executed Change Order.\n\n2.8 Location; Remote Work. Unless otherwise specified in {{services_description}}, Consultant may perform the Services remotely and using Consultant’s own equipment and work methods, subject to Client’s reasonable security requirements and any on-site requirements expressly stated in writing.\n\n2.9 Communications. The Parties will use commercially reasonable efforts to communicate regularly regarding status, risks, and dependencies. Unless otherwise specified, routine communications may be conducted by email and video conference.\n\n2.10 Compliance with Client Policies (Optional). To the extent Consultant performs work on Client premises or accesses Client systems, Consultant will comply with Client’s reasonable written security and safety policies provided to Consultant in advance, provided that such policies do not convert the relationship into employment or conflict with this Agreement."},{"id":"deliverables_milestones","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. DELIVERABLES; MILESTONES; ACCEPTANCE","content":"3.1 Deliverables and Milestones. If Deliverables and/or milestones apply, they are described in {{deliverables_and_milestones}}. Each milestone may include interim Deliverables, review meetings, and/or demonstrations.\n\n3.2 Delivery Method. Unless otherwise stated, Consultant will deliver Deliverables electronically to the delivery email or system designated by Client ({{delivery_method_details}}). Client will maintain appropriate access credentials and ensure receipt capability (including mailbox size and spam filtering).\n\n3.3 Acceptance Criteria. Unless otherwise specified in {{deliverables_and_milestones}}, a Deliverable will be evaluated for Acceptance based on conformity in all material respects with the written specifications, requirements, and acceptance criteria expressly set forth in this Agreement or the applicable Change Order.\n\n3.4 Review and Acceptance Process.\n\n(a) Review Period. Within {{acceptance_period_days}} Business Days after delivery of a Deliverable, Client will either (i) accept the Deliverable in writing, or (ii) provide written notice of rejection describing in reasonable detail the material nonconformities (\"Rejection Notice\").\n\n(b) Deemed Acceptance. If Client fails to provide an Acceptance or a Rejection Notice within the review period, the Deliverable will be deemed Accepted as of the last day of such review period.\n\n(c) Revisions. Upon receipt of a timely Rejection Notice, Consultant will use commercially reasonable efforts to correct the identified nonconformities and redeliver the Deliverable. Client will have an additional review period of {{acceptance_period_days}} Business Days for the corrected Deliverable. This correction-and-review cycle will repeat as necessary for the Deliverable to be Accepted, provided that Consultant is not required to correct issues caused by Client Materials, Client instructions, or changes in scope.\n\n(d) Limits. The acceptance process does not include free enhancements, new features, aesthetic preferences, or scope expansions not stated in the acceptance criteria. Such changes require a Change Order.\n\n3.5 Partial Acceptance; Segmentation. If a Deliverable contains severable components, Client may accept conforming components and reject only the nonconforming components, provided that partial acceptance does not materially impair the usefulness of the accepted portion.\n\n3.6 Dependencies on Third Parties. Consultant is not responsible for failures or delays caused by third-party platforms, vendors, app stores, hosting providers, AI model providers, payment processors, or other third parties not under Consultant’s control, unless Consultant expressly agreed in writing to assume such responsibility.\n\n3.7 Client Sign-Off for Milestones. If milestones are used for payment, Client’s acceptance/sign-off will not be unreasonably withheld or delayed. If a milestone is deemed Accepted under Section 3.4(b), the corresponding payment will be due under Section 4.\n\n3.8 No Guarantee of Specific Outcomes. Unless expressly stated as a deliverable, Consultant does not guarantee a particular business result (including revenue, funding, valuation, customer acquisition, regulatory approvals, or investment outcomes). Any projections, estimates, or forecasts are informational only and depend on factors outside Consultant’s control."},{"id":"fees_payment","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. FEES; INVOICING; EXPENSES; TAXES; FREELANCE WORKER PAYMENT PROTECTIONS","content":"4.1 Fees and Pricing Model. Client will pay Consultant the fees described in {{services_description}} and/or {{fee_schedule}}. The Parties may select one or more of the following fee structures (as applicable):\n\n(a) Fixed Fee. A fixed fee of {{payment_amount}}.\n\n(b) Hourly Fees. An hourly rate of {{hourly_rate}} billed in increments of {{billing_increment}} minutes, for time actually spent performing the Services.\n\n(c) Retainer (Optional). A retainer of {{retainer_amount}} due on {{retainer_due_date}}. Unless otherwise stated in writing, retainers are applied to fees as they accrue and are non-refundable once earned.\n\n(d) Milestone/Installment Payments (Optional). Payments tied to milestones described in {{deliverables_and_milestones}}.\n\n4.2 Invoicing.\n\n(a) Invoice Content. Each invoice will include, as applicable, a description of Services performed, dates of work, hours, rates, milestone references, and approved reimbursable expenses with receipts.\n\n(b) Invoice Delivery. Consultant will submit invoices to {{invoice_delivery_email}} (and/or as otherwise instructed by Client in writing).\n\n(c) Invoice Frequency. Unless otherwise specified in {{invoice_frequency}}, Consultant will invoice monthly in arrears for hourly Services and upon completion/Acceptance of milestone Deliverables for milestone-based work.\n\n4.3 Payment Timing; Due Date.\n\n(a) Contractual Due Date. Client will pay undisputed amounts within {{invoice_due_days}} days after receipt of an invoice, unless a different due date is stated in {{services_description}} or a Change Order.\n\n(b) Freelance Worker Protections – Outside Due Date. To the extent the Freelance Worker Protections apply and this Agreement does not specify a payment date, Client will pay Consultant no later than thirty (30) days after completion of the Services. If this Agreement specifies a payment date, Client will pay by such date, and if such date is later than permitted by applicable law, the earlier legally-required payment date will control.\n\n(c) Completion for Payment Purposes. \"Completion\" means the earliest of: (i) delivery of the final Deliverable required under the applicable scope; (ii) completion of the Services described in {{services_description}} if no Deliverables are required; or (iii) termination under Section 6, for Services performed through the effective date of termination.\n\n(d) No Conditioning on Waivers. Client will not condition timely payment on Consultant’s waiver of rights, release of claims unrelated to the scope, or agreement to additional terms not set forth in this Agreement, except as part of a mutually executed Change Order.\n\n4.4 Payment Method; No Setoff.\n\n(a) Payment Method. Client will pay via {{payment_method}} to {{payment_destination_details}}.\n\n(b) No Setoff. Client may not withhold, offset, or set off any amounts except for good-faith disputes communicated in writing pursuant to Section 4.6.\n\n4.5 Late Payments; Statutory Remedies.\n\n(a) Contract Interest. Late undisputed payments will accrue interest at {{late_interest_rate}} per month or the maximum rate permitted by New York law, whichever is less, from the due date until paid.\n\n(b) Freelance Worker Protections – Additional Remedies. To the extent the Freelance Worker Protections apply, the Parties acknowledge that applicable law may provide for additional remedies for late payment, including (as applicable) statutory damages and/or double damages, as well as attorneys’ fees and costs. Nothing in this Agreement waives any non-waivable statutory rights.\n\n4.6 Disputed Amounts.\n\n(a) Notice of Dispute. If Client disputes any portion of an invoice, Client will notify Consultant in writing within {{invoice_dispute_days}} days of receipt of the invoice, describing the dispute in reasonable detail.\n\n(b) Payment of Undisputed Portion. Client will timely pay all undisputed portions of the invoice.\n\n(c) Cooperation. The Parties will cooperate in good faith to resolve invoice disputes promptly.\n\n4.7 Expenses.\n\n(a) No Reimbursement Unless Approved. Consultant will not be reimbursed for expenses unless expressly approved in writing in advance by Client.\n\n(b) Expense Cap (Optional). If expenses are reimbursable, they will not exceed {{expenses_cap}} without Client’s prior written approval.\n\n(c) Receipts. Consultant will provide reasonable documentation/receipts for reimbursable expenses.\n\n4.8 Taxes; Reporting; No Withholding.\n\n(a) Consultant Taxes. Consultant is solely responsible for all taxes, withholdings, and other statutory or contractual obligations of any sort, including federal, New York State, and (where applicable) New York City income taxes, self-employment taxes, estimated tax payments, and any business taxes arising from amounts paid under this Agreement.\n\n(b) No Payroll Withholding. Client will not withhold payroll or employment taxes from payments to Consultant unless required by applicable law and after notice to Consultant.\n\n(c) Information Returns. Client may issue an IRS Form 1099 (or other applicable tax reporting form) to Consultant as required by law.\n\n4.9 Records; Six-Year Retention.\n\n(a) Retention. To the extent the Freelance Worker Protections apply, Client will retain Records relating to this Agreement for at least six (6) years, and will make such Records available as required by applicable law.\n\n(b) Consultant Records. Consultant will retain copies of invoices and documentation reasonably necessary to support amounts billed for at least six (6) years.\n\n4.10 Anti-Retaliation. To the extent the Freelance Worker Protections apply, Client will not retaliate against Consultant for exercising rights under applicable law, including by threatening, intimidating, disciplining, harassing, denying future work opportunities, or discriminating against Consultant because Consultant requested a written contract, timely payment, or otherwise asserted rights.\n\n4.11 Suspension for Non-Payment (Optional). If Client fails to pay undisputed amounts within {{suspension_after_days}} days after written notice of non-payment, Consultant may suspend performance until payment is received, and any schedule will be equitably adjusted. Consultant will not be liable for delays caused by such suspension."},{"id":"consultant_status","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. CONSULTANT STATUS; INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR; NEW YORK COMPLIANCE","content":"5.1 Independent Contractor Relationship. Consultant is and will remain an independent contractor to Client. Nothing in this Agreement will be construed to create an employer-employee relationship, joint venture, partnership, or agency relationship between the Parties.\n\n5.2 Control of Manner and Means. Consultant will determine the method, details, and means of performing the Services, subject to the requirements and specifications of this Agreement and any agreed Deliverables and deadlines. Client may provide input regarding desired outcomes and acceptance criteria but will not control day-to-day performance in a manner inconsistent with independent contractor status.\n\n5.3 No Employee Benefits. Consultant is not eligible for, and hereby waives any claim to, any of Client’s employee benefits, including health insurance, retirement benefits, paid time off, unemployment insurance coverage, workers’ compensation coverage, disability benefits, or any other benefit offered to employees.\n\n5.4 Equipment and Work Location. Unless otherwise agreed in writing, Consultant will supply Consultant’s own tools, equipment, and workspace necessary to perform the Services.\n\n5.5 No Exclusivity; Other Clients. Consultant may perform services for other clients during the Term, provided that such activities do not (a) use Client Confidential Information, (b) violate Section 9 (Confidentiality) or Section 8 (Intellectual Property), or (c) create a conflict of interest that materially impairs Consultant’s performance under this Agreement.\n\n5.6 Compliance with New York Worker Classification Rules. The Parties intend that Consultant be properly classified as an independent contractor under applicable New York law, including New York Labor Law and applicable standards used by New York agencies and courts (including, as applicable, the degree of control, opportunity for profit or loss, and other relevant factors). Each Party will refrain from taking actions that would be inconsistent with such classification.\n\n5.7 Consultant Personnel. Consultant is solely responsible for the direction, compensation, and conduct of its employees or contractors (if any) who perform the Services. Consultant will be responsible for all payroll taxes, insurance, and legal compliance for such personnel.\n\n5.8 No Immigration Sponsorship. Consultant is not authorized to bind Client to sponsor any immigration petition or employment authorization.\n\n5.9 Conflicts of Interest.\n\n(a) Disclosure. Consultant will promptly disclose to Client any actual or potential conflict of interest relating to the Services.\n\n(b) Mitigation. Upon notice, the Parties will cooperate in good faith to mitigate any conflict, which may include modification of scope, information barriers, or termination pursuant to Section 6.\n\n5.10 Non-Discrimination; Workplace Conduct (Optional). If Consultant performs Services on-site at Client premises, Consultant will comply with Client’s reasonable policies regarding harassment prevention, discrimination, safety, and workplace conduct, provided in writing in advance."},{"id":"term_termination","type":"standard","order":6,"title":"6. TERM; TERMINATION; SUSPENSION; EFFECTS","content":"6.1 Term. This Agreement commences on the Effective Date and continues until {{expiration_date}} (if specified) or until completion of the Services, unless terminated earlier in accordance with this Section 6 (the \"Term\").\n\n6.2 Termination for Convenience.\n\n(a) By Either Party. Either Party may terminate this Agreement for any reason upon {{notice_period}} days’ prior written notice to the other Party.\n\n(b) Change Orders. Termination of this Agreement will terminate all outstanding Change Orders unless otherwise stated in the termination notice or mutually agreed in writing.\n\n6.3 Termination for Cause. Either Party may terminate this Agreement immediately upon written notice if the other Party:\n\n(a) materially breaches this Agreement and fails to cure such breach within ten (10) days after receiving written notice describing the breach in reasonable detail; \n\n(b) becomes insolvent, makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, files or has filed against it a petition in bankruptcy that is not dismissed within sixty (60) days, or has a receiver appointed for substantially all of its assets; or\n\n(c) engages in fraud, gross negligence, willful misconduct, or unlawful conduct in connection with this Agreement.\n\n6.4 Suspension for Security or Legal Risk. Client may require Consultant to immediately suspend access to Client systems or facilities if Client reasonably believes Consultant’s continued access creates a material security risk or would violate applicable law. Client will provide notice describing the basis for the suspension and, where feasible, will cooperate in good faith to restore access when the risk is remediated.\n\n6.5 Effect of Termination.\n\n(a) Cessation of Services. Upon termination, Consultant will stop performing the Services as of the effective termination date.\n\n(b) Delivery of Work in Progress. Upon Client’s written request, Consultant will provide to Client, within a reasonable time, any completed Work Product and any in-progress Deliverables for which Client has paid or is obligated to pay under Section 6.6, subject to Client’s compliance with payment obligations.\n\n(c) Return/Destruction of Confidential Information. Each Party will comply with Section 9.8.\n\n6.6 Payment Upon Termination.\n\n(a) Fees Earned. Client will pay Consultant for (i) all Services properly performed through the effective date of termination, and (ii) approved reimbursable expenses incurred through such date.\n\n(b) Fixed Fee Proration (Optional). If a fixed fee applies, and termination occurs before completion, the Parties will in good faith determine the portion earned based on work completed, Deliverables produced, and milestones achieved.\n\n(c) Early Termination Fees (Optional). Any early termination fee must be expressly stated in {{termination_fee_terms}} to apply.\n\n6.7 Transition Assistance (Optional). For up to {{transition_assistance_days}} days after termination, Consultant will provide reasonable cooperation to transition the Services, at Consultant’s then-current rates, provided Client pays undisputed amounts due.\n\n6.8 Survival. The rights and obligations that by their nature should survive will survive termination or expiration, including Sections 4 (to the extent amounts remain due), 5 (status), 8 (Intellectual Property), 9 (Confidentiality), 10 (Data Privacy and Security), 11 (Representations; Warranties), 12 (Limitation of Liability), 13 (Indemnification), 14 (Dispute Resolution), and 15 (General Provisions)."},{"id":"intellectual_property","type":"negotiable","order":7,"title":"7. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; WORK PRODUCT; LICENSES","content":"7.1 Work Product Definition. Work Product is defined in Section 1.1(r) and includes Deliverables, drafts, and other results of the Services.\n\n7.2 Work Made for Hire; Assignment.\n\n(a) Work Made for Hire. To the maximum extent permitted under applicable law, Consultant agrees that the Work Product is \"work made for hire\" for Client.\n\n(b) Present Assignment. To the extent any Work Product does not qualify as a work made for hire, Consultant hereby irrevocably assigns, transfers, and conveys to Client, without additional consideration beyond the fees payable under this Agreement, all right, title, and interest in and to the Work Product and all associated Intellectual Property Rights, including all rights to sue and recover for past, present, and future infringements.\n\n(c) Scope of Assignment. The assignment in this Section 7.2 includes all rights throughout the world, for the full duration of such rights, and is not limited to any particular field of use.\n\n7.3 Further Assurances. Consultant will execute and deliver such documents and take such further actions reasonably requested by Client to evidence, perfect, maintain, enforce, or defend Client’s rights in the Work Product, including assignments, declarations, and other filings. If Consultant fails to execute a required document within a reasonable time, Consultant hereby appoints Client as Consultant’s attorney-in-fact solely for the purpose of executing such documents on Consultant’s behalf, coupled with an interest.\n\n7.4 Background IP; Consultant Tools.\n\n(a) Reservation. Consultant retains all right, title, and interest in and to Consultant’s Background IP. \n\n(b) License to Client. To the extent any Background IP is incorporated into, necessary to use, or is otherwise provided with the Work Product, Consultant grants to Client a perpetual, irrevocable, worldwide, royalty-free, fully paid-up, transferable, and sublicensable license to use, reproduce, modify, distribute, publicly display, publicly perform, make, have made, sell, offer for sale, import, and otherwise exploit such Background IP solely as part of, or in connection with, the Work Product and Client’s business.\n\n(c) Consultant Tools. Consultant may use general-purpose tools, templates, libraries, processes, know-how, and techniques of general applicability (\"Consultant Tools\") that do not contain Client Confidential Information. To the extent Consultant Tools are embedded in the Work Product, Consultant grants Client the license in Section 7.4(b).\n\n7.5 Client Materials. As between the Parties, Client retains all right, title, and interest in Client Materials. Client grants Consultant a limited, non-exclusive, non-transferable license to use Client Materials solely to perform the Services during the Term.\n\n7.6 Third-Party Materials; Open Source.\n\n(a) No Inclusion Without Approval. Consultant will not incorporate third-party materials (including open-source software) into Deliverables in a manner that would require disclosure of source code, impose copyleft obligations, or restrict Client’s use of the Work Product, unless Client has provided prior written approval.\n\n(b) Notice. If third-party materials are approved, Consultant will identify them in writing, including applicable licenses and attribution requirements, and will comply with such licenses.\n\n7.7 Moral Rights; Waiver. To the extent permitted under applicable law, Consultant waives and agrees not to assert any \"moral rights\" or similar rights (including rights of attribution and integrity) in the Work Product. If waiver is not permitted, Consultant agrees not to exercise such rights in a manner that interferes with Client’s full enjoyment of the Work Product.\n\n7.8 Portfolio and Publicity (Optional).\n\n(a) Portfolio. Unless prohibited in {{portfolio_restrictions}}, Consultant may list Client’s name and a high-level, non-confidential description of the Services in Consultant’s portfolio and marketing materials after public release of the related project by Client.\n\n(b) No Press Release. Consultant will not issue any press release or public statement regarding this engagement without Client’s prior written consent.\n\n7.9 Reservation of Rights. Except as expressly granted in this Agreement, each Party reserves all rights in its Intellectual Property Rights.\n\n7.10 IP Infringement Remedies (Optional). If Client reasonably believes any Work Product infringes a third party’s Intellectual Property Rights, Consultant will, at Consultant’s expense and as Client’s sole and exclusive remedy for such infringement (except to the extent arising from Client Materials or Client instructions), use commercially reasonable efforts to: (i) procure the right for Client to continue using the Work Product; (ii) replace or modify the Work Product so it becomes non-infringing while maintaining materially equivalent functionality; or (iii) if neither (i) nor (ii) is commercially reasonable, accept return of the infringing portion and refund fees paid for the infringing portion, pro-rated based on remaining useful life or the affected milestone."},{"id":"confidentiality","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS; DEFEND TRADE SECRETS ACT NOTICE","content":"8.1 Confidential Information. Confidential Information is defined in Section 1.1(g). Confidential Information may be disclosed in any form and includes information disclosed before the Effective Date in contemplation of this engagement.\n\n8.2 Confidentiality Obligations. The Receiving Party will:\n\n(a) use the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information solely to perform its obligations or exercise its rights under this Agreement;\n\n(b) protect the Confidential Information using at least the same degree of care it uses to protect its own confidential information of like importance, and in any event no less than reasonable care;\n\n(c) not disclose the Confidential Information to any third party except as expressly permitted under this Agreement; and\n\n(d) limit access to Confidential Information to its employees, officers, professional advisors, and approved subcontractors who have a need to know for purposes of this Agreement and who are bound by written confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those in this Agreement.\n\n8.3 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by contemporaneous written records:\n\n(a) is or becomes generally available to the public through no breach of this Agreement by the Receiving Party;\n\n(b) was known to the Receiving Party prior to disclosure by the Disclosing Party without breach of any obligation to the Disclosing Party;\n\n(c) is lawfully received from a third party without breach of any obligation owed to the Disclosing Party; or\n\n(d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.\n\n8.4 Compelled Disclosure. If the Receiving Party is required by law, regulation, or court order to disclose Confidential Information, it will (to the extent legally permitted) provide prompt written notice to the Disclosing Party and reasonably cooperate (at the Disclosing Party’s expense) with efforts to seek confidential treatment or a protective order. The Receiving Party will disclose only the portion of Confidential Information legally required.\n\n8.5 Trade Secrets; New York Common Law. The Parties acknowledge that unauthorized use or disclosure of Trade Secrets may cause irreparable harm. The Parties intend these confidentiality obligations to support protection of Trade Secrets under New York common law, and nothing in this Agreement limits either Party’s right to seek equitable relief to protect its Trade Secrets.\n\n8.6 Duration. The Receiving Party’s obligations with respect to Confidential Information will continue during the Term and for {{confidentiality_years}} years thereafter; provided that, with respect to Trade Secrets, such obligations will continue for so long as the information remains a trade secret under applicable law.\n\n8.7 No License. Except as expressly provided in this Agreement, no license or other rights are granted by either Party to the other under any Confidential Information or Intellectual Property Rights by implication, estoppel, or otherwise.\n\n8.8 Return or Destruction.\n\n(a) Upon Request or Termination. Upon the Disclosing Party’s request or upon termination or expiration of this Agreement, the Receiving Party will promptly return or destroy (at the Disclosing Party’s election) all Confidential Information in its possession or control, including copies.\n\n(b) Archival Copies. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Receiving Party may retain archival copies of Confidential Information solely as required to comply with legal, regulatory, or bona fide internal compliance requirements, provided that such retained information remains subject to this Agreement.\n\n8.9 Injunctive Relief. The Parties agree that a breach of this Section 8 may cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be an inadequate remedy. Accordingly, in the event of a threatened or actual breach, the non-breaching Party may seek injunctive or other equitable relief in addition to any other remedies available at law.\n\n8.10 Defend Trade Secrets Act (DTSA) Whistleblower Notice. Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b):\n\n(a) Immunity. An individual will not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that (i) is made in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (ii) is made in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal.\n\n(b) Anti-Retaliation Lawsuit. An individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding, if the individual (i) files any document containing the trade secret under seal; and (ii) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order.\n\n8.11 Confidentiality of Terms (Optional). Except as required by law or for professional advisors, neither Party will disclose the financial terms of this Agreement to third parties without the other Party’s prior written consent."},{"id":"data_privacy_security","type":"standard","order":9,"title":"9. DATA PRIVACY; DATA SECURITY; INCIDENT RESPONSE (NEW YORK)","content":"9.1 Scope. This Section 9 applies to the extent Consultant receives, accesses, stores, transmits, processes, or otherwise handles (a) Client Confidential Information in data form, (b) Personal Data, or (c) Client systems.\n\n9.2 Compliance with Law. Consultant will comply with applicable data privacy and security laws and regulations to the extent applicable to Consultant’s performance of the Services, including, where applicable, the New York SHIELD Act requirements regarding reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards, and New York’s data breach notification requirements (including, as applicable, N.Y. Gen. Bus. Law § 899-aa).\n\n9.3 Data Minimization and Purpose Limitation. Consultant will access and use Personal Data solely as necessary to perform the Services and for no other purpose, and will not sell, rent, disclose, or otherwise make Personal Data available to third parties except as permitted under this Agreement.\n\n9.4 Security Measures.\n\n(a) Baseline Controls. Consultant will maintain a written information security program appropriate to the nature of the data and the Services, including reasonable safeguards such as access controls, least-privilege permissions, authentication practices, malware protection, secure configuration management, and security awareness practices.\n\n(b) Encryption. Consultant will use encryption in transit (e.g., TLS) for transmission of Personal Data and Client Confidential Information over public networks and encryption at rest where reasonably appropriate given the sensitivity of the data.\n\n(c) Segregation. Consultant will use reasonable measures to prevent commingling of Client data with other clients’ data in a manner that could create unauthorized access.\n\n(d) Subprocessors. If Consultant uses subprocessors or third-party service providers to process Personal Data (e.g., cloud storage, project management tools), Consultant will (i) conduct reasonable diligence, (ii) ensure such providers are bound by appropriate written confidentiality and security obligations, and (iii) remain responsible for their acts and omissions.\n\n9.5 Access to Client Systems. If Client grants Consultant access to Client systems, Consultant will:\n\n(a) use such access solely for the Services;\n\n(b) comply with Client’s reasonable written access and security requirements provided in advance;\n\n(c) not attempt to bypass security controls; and\n\n(d) promptly notify Client if Consultant believes any access credential has been compromised.\n\n9.6 Data Incident; Notice.\n\n(a) \"Data Incident\" means any actual or reasonably suspected unauthorized access to, acquisition of, disclosure of, or loss of Personal Data or Client Confidential Information, or a material compromise of the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of Client systems caused by Consultant.\n\n(b) Notice. Consultant will notify Client without undue delay and in any event within {{incident_notice_hours}} hours after becoming aware of a Data Incident.\n\n(c) Content. Consultant’s notice will include, to the extent known and reasonably available, a description of the nature of the incident, the categories of data affected, the approximate number of affected individuals (if known), and the remediation steps taken or proposed.\n\n(d) Cooperation. Consultant will reasonably cooperate with Client’s investigation, remediation, and any legally required notifications, including providing relevant logs or reports to the extent available and legally permissible.\n\n(e) No Admission. Consultant’s notice under this Section 9.6 is not an admission of fault.\n\n9.7 Data Breach Notifications. Unless otherwise agreed in writing, Client will control decisions regarding external notifications to regulators, individuals, and third parties, except where Consultant is required by law to provide notice.\n\n9.8 Return/Deletion of Data. Upon termination or expiration, Consultant will, at Client’s election, return or securely delete Personal Data and Client Confidential Information in Consultant’s possession or control, except to the extent retention is required by law or bona fide internal compliance requirements, in which case Consultant will continue to protect such retained data under this Agreement.\n\n9.9 Special Categories; Regulated Data (Optional). If the Services involve regulated data (e.g., HIPAA data, GLBA data, payment card data, student records), the Parties will execute appropriate additional terms (e.g., a business associate agreement or data protection addendum) before Consultant receives such data.\n\n9.10 Cross-Border Transfers (Optional). If Consultant transfers Personal Data outside the United States in connection with the Services, Consultant will do so only with Client’s prior written consent and using reasonable safeguards appropriate for the destination jurisdiction.\n\n9.11 Disclaimer Regarding Client Security. Client is responsible for the security and lawful operation of Client’s own systems and for configuring third-party tools under Client’s control. Consultant is not responsible for Client’s security failures not caused by Consultant."},{"id":"warranties_liability","type":"negotiable","order":10,"title":"10. REPRESENTATIONS; WARRANTIES; REGULATORY AND LEGAL COMPLIANCE","content":"10.1 Mutual Authority. Each Party represents and warrants that (a) it is duly organized, validly existing, and in good standing (to the extent applicable) under the laws of its jurisdiction of formation; (b) it has full power and authority to enter into this Agreement and perform its obligations; and (c) this Agreement constitutes a legal, valid, and binding obligation of such Party enforceable against it in accordance with its terms, subject to bankruptcy, insolvency, and other laws affecting creditors’ rights and general principles of equity.\n\n10.2 Consultant Performance Warranty. Consultant represents and warrants that the Services will be performed in a professional and workmanlike manner consistent with generally accepted industry standards.\n\n10.3 Non-Infringement. Consultant represents and warrants that, to Consultant’s knowledge after reasonable inquiry, the Work Product as delivered and used in accordance with this Agreement will not infringe or misappropriate any third party Intellectual Property Rights. This warranty does not apply to infringement arising from (a) Client Materials, (b) specifications or instructions provided by Client, (c) modifications not made by Consultant, or (d) combination with products, services, or systems not provided by Consultant where the infringement would not have occurred absent such combination.\n\n10.4 Compliance with Laws.\n\n(a) General Compliance. Each Party will comply with all laws applicable to its performance under this Agreement.\n\n(b) Export Controls and Sanctions (Optional). Consultant will not provide Services in violation of applicable export control laws or sanctions programs (including OFAC programs), and will not knowingly provide Services to sanctioned persons or in sanctioned jurisdictions if prohibited.\n\n(c) Anti-Bribery. Consultant will not offer, promise, authorize, or provide any improper payment or thing of value to any person (including government officials) to obtain or retain business or secure an improper advantage in connection with this Agreement.\n\n10.5 No Legal or Investment Advice Unless Agreed. Unless expressly stated in {{services_description}}:\n\n(a) Consultant is not acting as a lawyer, accountant, broker-dealer, investment adviser, placement agent, or fiduciary.\n\n(b) Any business, financial, or fundraising-related feedback is general and informational and should not be relied upon as legal, tax, or investment advice.\n\n(c) Consultant will not solicit investors or offer or sell securities on Client’s behalf.\n\n10.6 Martin Act and Securities Compliance (Conditional). If the Services include work related to securities, capital raising, token offerings, investor communications, or similar activities that may implicate federal or state securities laws (including the Martin Act), the Parties will cooperate to ensure compliance, which may include: (a) engagement of qualified securities counsel; (b) written approval by Client of any investor-facing materials; and (c) restrictions on Consultant communications. Consultant will not make any representation regarding compliance unless expressly agreed in writing.\n\n10.7 Accessibility and Consumer Compliance (Optional). If the Services include customer-facing digital content, Client is responsible for determining and specifying required accessibility and consumer compliance standards (e.g., WCAG targets, disclosures). Consultant will implement such standards only if expressly included in scope.\n\n10.8 Disclaimer of Other Warranties. EXCEPT AS EXPRESSLY PROVIDED IN THIS AGREEMENT, NEITHER PARTY MAKES ANY OTHER WARRANTY OF ANY KIND, WHETHER EXPRESS, IMPLIED, STATUTORY, OR OTHERWISE, INCLUDING ANY IMPLIED WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, TITLE, OR NON-INFRINGEMENT, AND ALL SUCH WARRANTIES ARE HEREBY DISCLAIMED TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY NEW YORK LAW.\n\n10.9 Risk Allocation. The Parties acknowledge that fees reflect the allocation of risk set forth in this Agreement, including the limitations of liability in Section 12."},{"id":"limitation_of_liability","type":"negotiable","order":11,"title":"11. LIMITATION OF LIABILITY","content":"11.1 Exclusion of Certain Damages. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, IN NO EVENT WILL EITHER PARTY BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER PARTY FOR ANY INDIRECT, INCIDENTAL, CONSEQUENTIAL, SPECIAL, EXEMPLARY, OR PUNITIVE DAMAGES, OR FOR ANY LOSS OF PROFITS, LOSS OF REVENUE, LOSS OF BUSINESS, LOSS OF GOODWILL, OR LOSS OR CORRUPTION OF DATA, ARISING OUT OF OR RELATED TO THIS AGREEMENT, EVEN IF ADVISED OF THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH DAMAGES.\n\n11.2 Liability Cap. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, EACH PARTY’S TOTAL AGGREGATE LIABILITY ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT WILL NOT EXCEED THE TOTAL FEES PAID OR PAYABLE BY CLIENT TO CONSULTANT UNDER THIS AGREEMENT IN THE TWELVE (12) MONTHS IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING THE EVENT GIVING RISE TO THE CLAIM.\n\n11.3 Carve-Outs. Sections 11.1 and/or 11.2 do not limit liability to the extent liability cannot be limited under applicable law, and do not apply to:\n\n(a) a Party’s fraud or willful misconduct;\n\n(b) Consultant’s indemnification obligations under Section 13 for third-party claims (to the extent such obligations are included and enforceable);\n\n(c) Consultant’s breach of Section 8 (Confidentiality) or Section 9 (Data Privacy and Security), to the extent such breach results from gross negligence or willful misconduct (optional carve-out—apply only if selected in {{liability_carveouts}});\n\n(d) Client’s payment obligations under Section 4 for undisputed amounts.\n\n11.4 Essential Purpose. If any limited remedy is found to have failed of its essential purpose, the limitations in this Section 11 will nevertheless apply to the maximum extent permitted by law.\n\n11.5 Time Limitation (Optional). No action arising out of this Agreement may be brought more than {{claims_limitations_period_months}} months after the cause of action accrued, except where such limitation is prohibited by law or where a statutory period is longer and non-waivable."},{"id":"indemnification","type":"negotiable","order":12,"title":"12. INDEMNIFICATION","content":"12.1 Consultant Indemnification. Consultant will defend, indemnify, and hold harmless Client and its officers, directors, employees, and agents from and against any third-party claims, actions, suits, proceedings, damages, liabilities, penalties, fines, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) arising out of or relating to:\n\n(a) Consultant’s gross negligence or willful misconduct in performing the Services;\n\n(b) allegations that the Work Product, as delivered by Consultant and used in accordance with this Agreement, infringes or misappropriates a third party’s Intellectual Property Rights, excluding claims to the extent arising from Client Materials, Client instructions, or unauthorized modifications or combinations;\n\n(c) Consultant’s material breach of this Agreement.\n\n12.2 Client Indemnification. Client will defend, indemnify, and hold harmless Consultant and its officers, directors, employees, and agents from and against any third-party claims, actions, suits, proceedings, damages, liabilities, penalties, fines, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) arising out of or relating to:\n\n(a) allegations that Client Materials infringe or misappropriate a third party’s Intellectual Property Rights;\n\n(b) Client’s gross negligence or willful misconduct; or\n\n(c) Client’s material breach of this Agreement.\n\n12.3 Indemnification Procedures.\n\n(a) Notice. The indemnified Party will provide the indemnifying Party with prompt written notice of any claim for which indemnification is sought; provided that failure to provide prompt notice will not relieve the indemnifying Party of its obligations except to the extent materially prejudiced.\n\n(b) Control of Defense. The indemnifying Party will have the right to control the defense and settlement of the claim with counsel reasonably acceptable to the indemnified Party.\n\n(c) Cooperation. The indemnified Party will reasonably cooperate (at the indemnifying Party’s expense) in the defense and settlement.\n\n(d) Settlement Restrictions. The indemnifying Party will not settle any claim without the indemnified Party’s prior written consent if the settlement (i) imposes any obligation on the indemnified Party other than payment fully covered by the indemnifying Party, (ii) requires any admission of liability by the indemnified Party, or (iii) does not include a full release of the indemnified Party.\n\n12.4 Exclusive Remedy for IP Claims (Optional). If selected in {{ip_indemnity_exclusive_remedy}}, this Section 12 states Client’s sole and exclusive remedy for third-party intellectual property infringement claims, except for claims arising from Consultant’s fraud or willful misconduct.\n\n12.5 Mitigation. The indemnified Party will take reasonable steps to mitigate damages and costs associated with a claim."},{"id":"optional_restrictive_covenants","type":"optional","order":13,"title":"13. OPTIONAL CLAUSE — LIMITED RESTRICTIVE COVENANTS (NEW YORK; NON-COMPETES DISFAVORED)","content":"13.1 Purpose and Acknowledgement. The Parties acknowledge that New York courts scrutinize restrictive covenants, and non-compete provisions are disfavored and generally enforceable only to the extent reasonable in time and scope and necessary to protect legitimate business interests (such as trade secrets, confidential information, and customer relationships). The Parties intend any restrictions in this Section 13 to be narrowly tailored and enforceable to the maximum extent permitted by New York law.\n\n13.2 Non-Solicitation of Clients/Customers (Optional). During the Term and for {{non_solicit_months}} months thereafter, Consultant will not knowingly solicit for Consultant’s own benefit any customer or client of Client with whom Consultant had material direct contact through the Services, for the purpose of providing services that are substantially similar to the Services; provided that this restriction does not prohibit general advertising or solicitation not targeted at Client’s customers.\n\n13.3 Non-Solicitation of Employees/Contractors (Optional). During the Term and for {{non_solicit_months}} months thereafter, Consultant will not knowingly solicit to hire any employee of Client with whom Consultant had material interaction in connection with the Services; provided that this restriction does not prohibit (a) responding to unsolicited inquiries, or (b) general recruiting not specifically targeted at Client’s employees.\n\n13.4 No Disparagement (Optional). During the Term and thereafter, each Party agrees not to make any knowingly false statements of fact about the other Party that are reasonably likely to harm the other Party’s business reputation; provided that this does not restrict truthful statements, protected whistleblowing activity, or statements required by law.\n\n13.5 Non-Compete (Highly Optional; Use Only If Necessary). If selected in {{include_non_compete}}, during the Term and for {{non_compete_months}} months thereafter, Consultant will not perform services that are substantially similar to the Services for the following specifically identified competitor(s): {{identified_competitors}} within the following geographic area: {{non_compete_geography}}. The Parties acknowledge and agree that (a) this provision is intended to be limited to protection of Client’s legitimate interests, and (b) if a court finds the provision overbroad, the court may modify it to the minimum extent necessary to make it enforceable.\n\n13.6 Reasonableness; Blue-Penciling. If any provision of this Section 13 is determined to be unenforceable, the Parties request that a court reform or modify the provision to render it enforceable to the fullest extent permitted under New York law, and enforce the provision as so reformed.\n\n13.7 No Restriction on Consultant’s General Skills. Nothing in this Section 13 restricts Consultant from using general knowledge, skills, and experience retained in Consultant’s unaided memory, or from serving other clients in a manner that does not use or disclose Client Confidential Information or Trade Secrets."},{"id":"dispute_resolution","type":"standard","order":14,"title":"14. DISPUTE RESOLUTION; EQUITABLE RELIEF; ATTORNEYS’ FEES","content":"14.1 Good-Faith Negotiation. In the event of a Dispute, the Parties will first attempt in good faith to resolve the Dispute through informal negotiations between business representatives with authority to settle the Dispute.\n\n14.2 Optional Mediation. If the Dispute is not resolved within {{negotiation_days}} days after written notice of the Dispute, either Party may request non-binding mediation administered by {{mediation_provider}} in {{venue_county}} County, New York, unless the Parties agree otherwise. The Parties will share mediation fees equally and each bear its own attorneys’ fees.\n\n14.3 Litigation; Injunctive Relief.\n\n(a) Court Proceedings. Subject to Section 14.2 if selected, either Party may bring an action in the state or federal courts located in {{venue_county}} County, New York.\n\n(b) Equitable Relief. Notwithstanding the foregoing, either Party may seek temporary, preliminary, or permanent injunctive relief or other equitable relief in any court of competent jurisdiction to prevent or remedy a breach of Sections 7 (Intellectual Property), 8 (Confidentiality), or 9 (Data Privacy and Security).\n\n14.4 Attorneys’ Fees (Optional). If selected in {{fee_shifting_selected}}, the prevailing Party in any action or proceeding arising out of this Agreement will be entitled to recover its reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs.\n\n14.5 Jury Trial Waiver (Optional). IF SELECTED IN {{jury_waiver_selected}}, EACH PARTY KNOWINGLY AND VOLUNTARILY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT.\n\n14.6 Continued Performance. During the pendency of a Dispute, Consultant will continue to perform the Services and Client will continue to pay undisputed amounts, unless the Agreement has been terminated or performance is impracticable due to the nature of the Dispute."},{"id":"general","type":"standard","order":15,"title":"15. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"15.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and any Dispute will be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of New York, without regard to its conflicts of law rules that would apply another jurisdiction’s laws.\n\n15.2 Venue; Jurisdiction. The Parties irrevocably submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of the state and federal courts located in {{venue_county}} County, New York, for any action arising out of or relating to this Agreement, and waive any objection to venue or inconvenient forum.\n\n15.3 Notices.\n\n(a) Form. Notices under this Agreement must be in writing and will be deemed given when delivered by (i) personal delivery, (ii) nationally recognized overnight courier, (iii) certified or registered mail (return receipt requested), or (iv) email (with confirmation of transmission and without bounce-back), to the addresses below.\n\n(b) Notice Contacts. Notices will be sent to the following (or such other address as a Party may designate by notice):\n\nTo Client: {{party_a_company}}, Attn: {{party_a_name}}, {{party_a_title}}, {{party_a_address}}, Email: {{party_a_email}}\n\nTo Consultant: {{party_b_company}}, Attn: {{party_b_name}}, {{party_b_title}}, {{party_b_address}}, Email: {{party_b_email}}\n\n15.4 Assignment. Neither Party may assign or transfer this Agreement without the other Party’s prior written consent, except that either Party may assign this Agreement without consent to an Affiliate or in connection with a merger, acquisition, corporate reorganization, or sale of substantially all of its assets, provided that the assignee agrees in writing to assume all obligations.\n\n15.5 Subcontracting. Except as permitted under Section 2.5, Consultant may not subcontract material obligations without Client’s prior written consent.\n\n15.6 Entire Agreement. This Agreement (including any Change Orders) constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties with respect to its subject matter and supersedes all prior and contemporaneous agreements, proposals, negotiations, representations, and understandings.\n\n15.7 Amendments; Waivers. Any amendment, modification, or waiver must be in a writing signed by both Parties. No waiver of any breach will be deemed a waiver of any other breach.\n\n15.8 Severability. If any provision of this Agreement is held invalid or unenforceable, the remaining provisions will remain in full force and effect, and the invalid provision will be enforced to the maximum extent permitted so as to effect the Parties’ intent.\n\n15.9 Force Majeure. Neither Party will be liable for any failure or delay in performance (other than payment obligations for undisputed amounts) due to causes beyond its reasonable control, including acts of God, natural disasters, labor disputes, war, terrorism, civil unrest, governmental actions, utility outages, and widespread internet or cloud provider failures. The affected Party will provide prompt notice and use commercially reasonable efforts to resume performance.\n\n15.10 Counterparts; Electronic Signatures; ESRA/ESIGN. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which will be deemed an original. Signatures transmitted electronically (including via PDF, e-signature platform, or other electronic means) will be deemed original signatures and will be binding and enforceable under the New York Electronic Signatures and Records Act (ESRA) and the federal Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (E-SIGN).\n\n15.11 Relationship of the Parties. The Parties are independent contractors. Consultant is not authorized to bind Client, and Client is not responsible for Consultant’s debts, obligations, or acts except as expressly stated herein.\n\n15.12 No Third-Party Beneficiaries. This Agreement is for the sole benefit of the Parties and their permitted successors and assigns, and nothing herein creates any third-party beneficiary rights.\n\n15.13 Publicity. Neither Party will use the other Party’s name, trademarks, or logos in advertising, marketing, or publicity without prior written consent, except as permitted in Section 7.8 or as required by law.\n\n15.14 Insurance (Optional). During the Term, Consultant will maintain commercially reasonable insurance appropriate for the Services, which may include commercial general liability, professional liability/errors and omissions, and cyber liability insurance, with limits not less than {{insurance_limits}} upon request.\n\n15.15 Counterparty Verification (Optional). Each Party may reasonably request information necessary for vendor onboarding, payment processing, or compliance screening, including tax forms, business registration information, and sanctions screening.\n\n15.16 Non-Compete Acknowledgement (New York). The Parties acknowledge that restrictive covenants, and particularly non-compete provisions, are disfavored in New York and will be enforced only if reasonable and necessary to protect legitimate interests. Any non-compete provision must be expressly set forth in Section 13 (if selected) and is not created by implication.\n\n15.17 Further Assurances. Each Party will execute and deliver such further documents and take such further actions as may be reasonably necessary to carry out the intent of this Agreement.\n\n15.18 Construction; Drafting. This Agreement is the result of negotiations between the Parties and will not be construed against either Party as the drafter.\n\n15.19 Optional Order/Payment Compliance for Public Entities. If Client is a governmental or public authority subject to procurement or prompt payment rules, the Parties will cooperate in good faith to align invoicing and payment processes with such rules, provided that nothing herein waives Consultant’s non-waivable rights under applicable law.\n\n15.20 Signatures; Authority. Each signatory represents that they have authority to bind the Party on whose behalf they sign."}]'::jsonb,
