-- Update: Freelance Services Agreement (New York)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Freelance Services Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between {{party_a_company}} ("Hiring Party"), with its principal place of business and notice address at {{party_a_address}}, and {{party_b_name}} doing business as {{party_b_company}} ("Freelance Worker"), with a mailing address and notice address at {{party_b_address}}. Hiring Party and Freelance Worker may be referred to individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties."

This Agreement is intended to constitute a written contract that satisfies applicable freelance worker protection laws, including (as applicable) the New York City Freelance Isn’t Free Act (NYC Administrative Code § 20-927 et seq.) and/or New York Labor Law Article 44 (collectively, "FIFA" for purposes of this Agreement). The Parties intend that the information required by FIFA—including the Parties’ names and mailing addresses, an itemization/description of services, the value of services, the rate and method of compensation, and the date and manner of payment—be set forth in this Agreement and any applicable Statement of Work (as defined below).',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, Hiring Party desires to engage Freelance Worker to perform certain professional services described in this Agreement and/or an applicable Statement of Work;

WHEREAS, Freelance Worker represents that Freelance Worker has the experience, skill, and resources to perform the Services (as defined below) on the terms and conditions set forth herein;

WHEREAS, the Parties desire to establish a clear understanding regarding scope, deliverables, acceptance, fees, payment timing, confidentiality, intellectual property, and compliance with New York law, including FIFA’s payment timing and anti-retaliation protections;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS","content":"1.1 \"Acceptance\" or \"Accepted\" means Hiring Party’s written confirmation (including by email) that a Deliverable meets the Acceptance Criteria, or deemed acceptance under Section 3.\n\n1.2 \"Acceptance Criteria\" means the objective criteria for acceptance of the Deliverables, if any, stated in {{acceptance_criteria}} and/or in the applicable Statement of Work; if not stated, Acceptance Criteria means material conformity with the Deliverables description and requirements in the Statement of Work and performance consistent with applicable professional and industry standards.\n\n1.3 \"Affiliate\" means any entity that directly or indirectly controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with a Party, where \"control\" means ownership of more than 50% of the voting interests or the power to direct management.\n\n1.4 \"Applicable Law\" means all applicable laws, rules, regulations, ordinances, codes, and legally binding orders, including, as applicable, FIFA, New York Labor Law and related guidance on worker classification, New York General Business Law (including the SHIELD Act), breach-notification laws, and applicable federal laws.\n\n1.5 \"Background IP\" means, with respect to a Party, any inventions, works of authorship, software (including source code and object code), tools, templates, libraries, frameworks, methods, processes, know-how, trade secrets, and other intellectual property and proprietary materials that (a) were owned, developed, conceived, or reduced to practice by that Party prior to the Effective Date, or (b) are developed outside the scope of the Services without use of the other Party’s Confidential Information.\n\n1.6 \"Business Day\" means a day other than Saturday, Sunday, or a day on which banks in New York, New York are authorized or required by law to close.\n\n1.7 \"Change Order\" means a written change order, statement of work amendment, or other written document (including an email exchange) signed by or confirmed in writing by both Parties that modifies the scope, Deliverables, timeline, milestones, or fees.\n\n1.8 \"Client Materials\" means any materials, content, data, information, branding, trademarks, software, documentation, credentials, access tokens, systems access, or other items provided or made available by or on behalf of Hiring Party to Freelance Worker in connection with the Services.\n\n1.9 \"Confidential Information\" has the meaning set forth in Section 12 and includes Trade Secrets.\n\n1.10 \"Deliverables\" means the items, outputs, reports, files, designs, content, code, documentation, or other work product to be delivered by Freelance Worker as described in {{deliverables_description}} and/or an applicable Statement of Work.\n\n1.11 \"Disclosing Party\" means the Party disclosing Confidential Information.\n\n1.12 \"Dispute\" means any claim, controversy, or dispute arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the Services, the Deliverables, fees, payment, or the Parties’ relationship, whether sounding in contract, tort, statute, or otherwise.\n\n1.13 \"FIFA\" has the meaning set forth in the Preamble and includes the payment timing, written contract, anti-retaliation, and record retention requirements applicable to covered engagements.\n\n1.14 \"Milestone\" means a project checkpoint or partial deliverable described in {{milestones}} and/or a Statement of Work that may trigger review, partial payment, or both.\n\n1.15 \"Personal Information\" means information that identifies or can reasonably be linked to an individual and is protected under Applicable Law, including as defined under New York’s SHIELD Act (e.g., a name combined with a sensitive data element such as Social Security number, driver’s license number, financial account number, biometric information, or other data types covered by law).\n\n1.16 \"Receiving Party\" means the Party receiving Confidential Information.\n\n1.17 \"Services\" means the professional services described in Section 2 and in {{services_description}}, including any additional services agreed in a Change Order.\n\n1.18 \"Statement of Work\" or \"SOW\" means a written statement of work, scope document, or similar project document (including a Change Order) that is incorporated by reference and that may specify Deliverables, Milestones, Acceptance Criteria, schedule, fees, and other project-specific details.\n\n1.19 \"Subcontractor\" means any third party engaged by Freelance Worker to perform any portion of the Services.\n\n1.20 \"Trade Secrets\" means trade secrets protected under applicable law, including the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act (18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq.) and New York common law, including information that derives independent economic value from not being generally known and is subject to reasonable measures to maintain its secrecy.\n\n1.21 \"Work Product\" means all Deliverables and other work product created, authored, conceived, developed, or reduced to practice by Freelance Worker in the course of performing the Services, excluding Freelance Worker Background IP and Third-Party Materials.\n\n1.22 \"Third-Party Materials\" means software, fonts, stock images, plugins, libraries, datasets, models, tools, or other materials owned by a third party and incorporated into the Deliverables or used in performing the Services, including open-source components.\n\n1.23 \"Work Completion\" means (a) the date the Services are completed and all Deliverables due at completion are delivered to Hiring Party, or (b) if the Services are performed on a milestone basis, completion of the final Milestone, unless the SOW specifies a different completion event.\n\n1.24 \"Writing\" or \"Written\" includes email and other electronic records capable of retention and accurate reproduction, consistent with the New York Electronic Signatures and Records Act (ESRA) and the federal E-SIGN Act."},{"id":"services","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. SERVICES; ENGAGEMENT; SCOPE","content":"2.1 Engagement. Hiring Party hereby engages Freelance Worker to perform, and Freelance Worker agrees to perform, the Services.\n\n2.2 Scope Description. The Services are described in {{services_description}} and any applicable SOW. If there is a conflict between this Agreement and a SOW, the conflict will be resolved under Section 21.3 (Order of Precedence).\n\n2.3 Professional Standard; Duty of Care. Freelance Worker will perform the Services (a) in a professional and workmanlike manner, (b) using reasonable skill and care, and (c) consistent with applicable industry standards for similar services.\n\n2.4 Cooperation and Timely Inputs. Hiring Party will provide timely access to Client Materials, feedback, decisions, and approvals reasonably necessary for Freelance Worker to perform the Services. Delays caused by Hiring Party may require schedule adjustments and may result in additional fees via a Change Order.\n\n2.5 No Authority to Bind. Freelance Worker has no authority to enter into contracts, make representations, or incur obligations on Hiring Party’s behalf unless expressly authorized in a Writing signed by Hiring Party.\n\n2.6 Location and Means of Performance. Unless otherwise specified in a SOW, Freelance Worker will determine the manner and means of performing the Services, including the work location(s), subject to deadlines, Deliverables, and coordination requirements.\n\n2.7 Optional Onsite Work. If onsite work is required, the Parties will specify location, hours, access requirements, and security/safety rules in {{onsite_requirements}}. Hiring Party is responsible for providing a safe working environment for any onsite work required by Hiring Party.\n\n2.8 Subcontractors (Optional; Subject to Consent). Freelance Worker may engage Subcontractors only as permitted in {{subcontracting_policy}}. If consent is required, Freelance Worker remains responsible for Subcontractors’ acts and omissions and will ensure Subcontractors are bound by written obligations at least as protective as this Agreement regarding confidentiality, IP, and data security.\n\n2.9 Statements Required by FIFA. The Parties acknowledge that the Services are described in Writing herein and that the compensation and payment terms are described in Section 8 and/or the applicable SOW, intended to satisfy FIFA’s written-contract requirements for covered engagements."},{"id":"deliverables_acceptance","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. DELIVERABLES; REVIEW AND ACCEPTANCE","content":"3.1 Deliverables. Freelance Worker will deliver the Deliverables described in {{deliverables_description}} and/or the applicable SOW. Deliverables will be provided in the format(s) specified in the SOW or, if not specified, in a commercially reasonable format consistent with the Services.\n\n3.2 Delivery Method. Unless otherwise specified, Deliverables will be delivered via {{delivery_method}} (e.g., email, secure file transfer, repository, or Hiring Party’s collaboration tools). Hiring Party is responsible for maintaining access to its designated systems and promptly confirming receipt.\n\n3.3 Review Period. Hiring Party will review each Deliverable within {{acceptance_period_days}} Business Days after delivery (the \"Review Period\"). If {{acceptance_period_days}} is not specified, the Review Period will be five (5) Business Days.\n\n3.4 Acceptance or Rejection. Within the Review Period, Hiring Party will either (a) Accept the Deliverable in Writing, or (b) reject the Deliverable in Writing by providing reasonably specific reasons for rejection and a list of nonconformities relative to the Acceptance Criteria.\n\n3.5 Deemed Acceptance. A Deliverable will be deemed Accepted if Hiring Party (a) fails to provide a written rejection within the Review Period, or (b) uses the Deliverable in production, publishes it, distributes it, or otherwise materially exploits it for its intended purpose (excluding internal testing solely to evaluate acceptance).\n\n3.6 Corrections After Rejection. If a Deliverable is rejected for failure to meet the Acceptance Criteria, Freelance Worker will use commercially reasonable efforts to correct the identified nonconformities and re-deliver the Deliverable. The Parties acknowledge that correction cycles may affect the timeline.\n\n3.7 Scope Guardrails. Acceptance review is limited to the Deliverable’s conformity with the agreed Acceptance Criteria and scope. Requests that expand scope, add new features, require substantial redesign, or require additional Deliverables must be handled under Section 5 (Changes; Change Orders).\n\n3.8 Partial Acceptance. Hiring Party may accept a Deliverable in part and reject the remainder, provided that the rejected portion is identified with reasonable specificity.\n\n3.9 No Withholding for Unrelated Disputes. Hiring Party will not unreasonably withhold Acceptance or delay Acceptance for reasons unrelated to the Deliverable’s conformity with the Acceptance Criteria."},{"id":"timeline_milestones","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TIMELINE; MILESTONES; DEPENDENCIES","content":"4.1 Schedule. The anticipated schedule, if any, is set forth in {{project_timeline}} and/or the applicable SOW. Dates are estimates unless expressly stated as firm deadlines.\n\n4.2 Milestones. If Milestones apply, they are described in {{milestones}} and/or the SOW. Milestones may include interim deliverables, review checkpoints, or payment triggers.\n\n4.3 Hiring Party Dependencies. Hiring Party acknowledges that the timeline may depend on timely provision of Client Materials, access, and feedback. Hiring Party will provide feedback within the timeframes specified in the SOW or, if not specified, within a commercially reasonable time.\n\n4.4 Delays; Extensions. If either Party anticipates a delay, that Party will notify the other in Writing as soon as practicable. The Parties will cooperate in good faith to adjust the schedule. Where delays are caused by Hiring Party (including delays in feedback/approvals, access, or changes in requirements), Freelance Worker is entitled to a reasonable extension and, if applicable, additional fees via a Change Order.\n\n4.5 Suspension for Client Delay (Optional). If Hiring Party fails to provide required inputs for more than {{client_delay_days}} calendar days (or if not specified, ten (10) days), Freelance Worker may suspend work upon written notice until inputs are provided. Suspension does not waive payment obligations for work already performed.\n\n4.6 No Guarantee of Specific Business Outcomes. Unless expressly stated in an SOW, Freelance Worker does not guarantee any specific revenue, conversion rate, fundraising outcome, investment result, performance benchmark, regulatory approval, or other business result.\n\n4.7 Timekeeping (If Hourly). If Services are billed hourly, Freelance Worker will keep reasonable records of time worked and will provide summaries upon request consistent with the invoicing terms in Section 8."},{"id":"changes","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. CHANGES; CHANGE ORDERS","content":"5.1 Change Requests. Either Party may propose changes to the Services, Deliverables, Milestones, schedule, assumptions, or dependencies.\n\n5.2 No Obligation Without Written Change Order. Freelance Worker is not obligated to perform out-of-scope work unless the Parties execute or otherwise confirm a Change Order in Writing.\n\n5.3 Change Order Contents. A Change Order should, as applicable: (a) describe the requested change and revised scope; (b) identify new or revised Deliverables and Acceptance Criteria; (c) set forth any schedule impacts; (d) state additional fees (fixed or hourly), expenses, and payment timing; and (e) identify any additional Client Materials or access required.\n\n5.4 Effect on Fees and Schedule. Changes frequently affect fees and schedule. The Parties agree to negotiate Change Orders in good faith.\n\n5.5 Emergency Changes. If Hiring Party requests emergency work outside normal hours or with accelerated deadlines, Hiring Party acknowledges that additional fees may apply as specified in {{rush_fee_terms}} or a Change Order.\n\n5.6 Change Communications. The Parties may manage changes via email or project management tools; however, a clear written record of scope and fees is required before Freelance Worker will be expected to proceed.\n\n5.7 FIFA Compliance. For covered engagements under FIFA, the Parties intend that any material changes to services or compensation be documented in Writing (including by Change Order) to maintain a clear written record."},{"id":"revisions","type":"optional","order":6,"title":"6. REVISIONS; CLIENT FEEDBACK (OPTIONAL)","content":"6.1 Included Revisions. Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, the fees include up to {{revision_rounds_included}} rounds of reasonable revisions to each Deliverable, limited to adjustments consistent with the originally agreed scope and Acceptance Criteria.\n\n6.2 What Counts as a Revision. \"Revision\" means edits, refinements, or minor modifications to an existing Deliverable. Revisions do not include (a) new features, new deliverables, significant redesign, or changes in strategy, (b) changes resulting from new information or new requirements introduced after approval, or (c) work required due to Hiring Party-provided materials being inaccurate or incomplete.\n\n6.3 Feedback Timelines. Hiring Party will provide consolidated feedback within {{feedback_turnaround_days}} Business Days after receiving a Deliverable (or within a commercially reasonable time if not specified). Fragmented or serial feedback may require a Change Order.\n\n6.4 Excess Revisions. Revisions beyond the included rounds, or revisions that are out of scope, will be billed at {{hourly_rate}} (or per a Change Order).\n\n6.5 Content Approvals. Where Deliverables include factual claims, legal statements, or regulated content (e.g., health, financial, advertising, or employment-related statements), Hiring Party is responsible for reviewing and approving the content for accuracy and compliance."},{"id":"expenses","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. EXPENSES; CLIENT-PROVIDED ACCOUNTS; TOOLS","content":"7.1 No Expenses Unless Approved. Unless expressly stated in a SOW, Freelance Worker is responsible for its ordinary overhead and operating costs. Freelance Worker will not incur reimbursable expenses without Hiring Party’s prior written approval.\n\n7.2 Expense Cap (Optional). If an expense cap applies, it is {{expenses_cap}} in the aggregate unless otherwise stated in a Change Order.\n\n7.3 Reimbursable Expenses. Approved expenses may include, as applicable, travel requested by Hiring Party, shipping, printing, paid stock assets, third-party licenses, or specialized tools required solely for the project. Any reimbursable expenses must be supported by reasonable documentation.\n\n7.4 Payment Timing for Expenses. Reimbursements will be paid in accordance with Section 8 (Fees; Invoicing; Payment Terms) and in any event within the time required by Applicable Law for covered engagements.\n\n7.5 Client-Provided Accounts and Access. If Hiring Party requires Freelance Worker to use Hiring Party accounts or tools (e.g., advertising accounts, analytics, cloud services, design tools, or code repositories), Hiring Party will provide access credentials through a secure method and is responsible for maintaining appropriate licenses and permissions.\n\n7.6 Third-Party Purchases on Client Accounts. If Freelance Worker is authorized to make purchases on Hiring Party’s accounts, such authorization must be in Writing and will specify limits and approvals. Freelance Worker will not be liable for charges made by Hiring Party or by third parties unrelated to Freelance Worker’s authorized activity.\n\n7.7 Open Source and Third-Party Materials. If Deliverables include Third-Party Materials, Hiring Party’s rights may be subject to third-party terms. Freelance Worker will not knowingly incorporate Third-Party Materials that impose material restrictions inconsistent with Hiring Party’s intended use without first notifying Hiring Party in Writing."},{"id":"payment","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. FEES; INVOICING; PAYMENT TERMS (FIFA COMPLIANCE)","content":"8.1 Compensation Structure. Hiring Party will pay Freelance Worker the fees described in {{compensation_terms}}. Unless otherwise specified in a SOW, compensation is (a) a fixed project fee of {{payment_amount}}, and/or (b) {{hourly_rate}} per hour for hourly services.\n\n8.2 Not-to-Exceed (If Hourly; Optional). If a not-to-exceed cap applies, it is {{hourly_cap}} unless increased by Change Order.\n\n8.3 Deposit/Retainer (Optional). If a deposit or retainer applies, Hiring Party will pay {{deposit_amount}} by {{deposit_due_date}}. Unless otherwise stated, deposits are applied to the final invoice. If the project is canceled, the deposit is refundable only to the extent stated in Section 14 (Term; Termination; Cancellation).\n\n8.4 Invoicing. Freelance Worker will invoice Hiring Party according to {{invoice_frequency}} (e.g., upon completion, per milestone, weekly, biweekly, or monthly) or as stated in the SOW. Each invoice will describe the Services performed, applicable Deliverables or Milestones, and the amount due.\n\n8.5 Payment Method. Payments will be made via {{payment_method}} in {{payment_currency}}. Unless otherwise stated, Freelance Worker is not required to begin work until any required deposit is paid.\n\n8.6 Payment Due Date; FIFA Default Rule. \n(a) If the Parties specify a due date in a SOW or invoice and such due date complies with Applicable Law, Hiring Party will pay by that date.\n(b) If no payment date is specified, or if Applicable Law requires a shorter timeframe, Hiring Party will pay no later than thirty (30) days after Work Completion, or thirty (30) days after completion of the applicable Milestone for milestone-based work, as required by FIFA for covered engagements.\n(c) The Parties intend that this Section 8.6 satisfies FIFA’s requirement that the written contract specify the date or method of determining the date on which the Hiring Party must pay.\n\n8.7 No Retaliation; No Waiver of FIFA Rights. Hiring Party will not retaliate against Freelance Worker for requesting timely payment, asserting rights under FIFA, or reporting suspected violations. Nothing in this Agreement is intended to waive or limit any non-waivable rights or remedies available to Freelance Worker under Applicable Law.\n\n8.8 Late Payment; Statutory Remedies. \n(a) If payment is late, Freelance Worker may provide written notice of nonpayment and an opportunity to cure.\n(b) For covered engagements under FIFA, Freelance Worker may be entitled to remedies provided by Applicable Law, which may include double damages for late payment, injunctive relief, statutory damages, and reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs.\n(c) Any contractual late fee in {{late_fee_terms}} is intended to be in addition to (and not in limitation of) any statutory rights, to the extent permitted by law.\n\n8.9 Disputed Amounts. If Hiring Party disputes an invoice in good faith, Hiring Party will notify Freelance Worker in Writing within {{invoice_dispute_days}} days of receipt (or, if not specified, seven (7) days), pay any undisputed portion by the due date, and cooperate in good faith to resolve the dispute.\n\n8.10 Taxes; Information Returns. Freelance Worker is solely responsible for all taxes arising from amounts paid under this Agreement, including federal, New York State, and, where applicable, New York City income taxes, self-employment tax, and other assessments. Hiring Party will not withhold payroll taxes and may issue an IRS Form 1099-NEC or other applicable information return. Freelance Worker will provide a completed IRS Form W-9 or appropriate tax documentation upon request.\n\n8.11 No Setoff (Except for Agreed Credits). Hiring Party will not offset amounts due to Freelance Worker against unrelated amounts allegedly owed by Freelance Worker unless the Parties agree in Writing or a final, non-appealable order requires it.\n\n8.12 Record Retention. Hiring Party will retain a copy of this Agreement (and any SOWs/Change Orders) for at least six (6) years after the later of termination or completion of Services, consistent with FIFA’s record retention requirement (see also Section 21.16)."},{"id":"freelancer_status","type":"standard","order":9,"title":"9. FREELANCE WORKER STATUS; NEW YORK CLASSIFICATION","content":"9.1 Independent Contractor. The Parties intend that Freelance Worker is an independent contractor and not an employee, worker, partner, joint venturer, or agent of Hiring Party for any purpose.\n\n9.2 No Benefits. Freelance Worker is not eligible for and will not participate in any Hiring Party benefit plan or program, including health insurance, retirement plans, paid leave, unemployment insurance, or workers’ compensation coverage through Hiring Party.\n\n9.3 Control of Work. Subject to the scope, deadlines, and acceptance requirements in this Agreement and any SOW, Freelance Worker will determine the manner, means, and methods of performing the Services, including hours and work location.\n\n9.4 Tools and Equipment. Freelance Worker will supply its own tools, equipment, and workspace, except to the extent Hiring Party provides access to specific systems or tools under Section 7.\n\n9.5 Ability to Work for Others. Freelance Worker may provide services to other clients, including competitors of Hiring Party, provided that Freelance Worker complies with confidentiality obligations and avoids conflicts of interest as described in Section 21.14.\n\n9.6 No Authority. Freelance Worker will not represent that it has authority to bind Hiring Party, and will not sign agreements on Hiring Party’s behalf.\n\n9.7 New York Labor Law Considerations. The Parties acknowledge that New York agencies and courts may apply multifactor tests to determine worker classification (including factors relating to direction and control, provision of equipment, opportunity for profit or loss, integration into Hiring Party’s business, and ability to work for others). The Parties agree to structure their relationship consistent with independent contractor status.\n\n9.8 No Exclusivity; No Minimum Engagement. Unless expressly stated in a SOW, Hiring Party does not guarantee any minimum hours, minimum spend, or exclusivity.\n\n9.9 No Employment Relationship Created by FIFA. The Parties acknowledge that FIFA provides payment and anti-retaliation protections for freelance workers and does not, by itself, create an employment relationship.\n\n9.10 Optional Business Entity Representation. If Freelance Worker is operating as a business entity, Freelance Worker represents that it is duly organized/registered as applicable and in good standing where required, and that the individual signing has authority to bind the entity."},{"id":"compliance","type":"optional","order":10,"title":"10. COMPLIANCE WITH LAW; REGULATED ACTIVITIES (OPTIONAL)","content":"10.1 General Compliance. Each Party will comply with Applicable Law in connection with its performance under this Agreement.\n\n10.2 Hiring Party Responsible for Business Decisions. Hiring Party is solely responsible for its business decisions, including marketing claims, pricing, employment practices, consumer disclosures, and regulatory compliance applicable to Hiring Party’s products or services.\n\n10.3 No Legal, Tax, or Investment Advice. Unless explicitly stated in a SOW, Freelance Worker is not providing legal advice, tax advice, or investment advice, and no Deliverable should be construed as such.\n\n10.4 Securities and Martin Act Considerations. If the Services relate to fundraising, investor communications, token offerings, equity offerings, or other securities-related activities, Hiring Party represents that it will consult qualified counsel and comply with applicable federal and New York securities laws, including the New York Martin Act (General Business Law Article 23-A). Unless expressly agreed in Writing and permitted by Applicable Law, Freelance Worker will not (a) act as a broker-dealer, placement agent, or investment adviser, (b) solicit investments, (c) receive transaction-based compensation, or (d) make representations to investors on Hiring Party’s behalf.\n\n10.5 Anti-Corruption; Sanctions (Optional). Each Party represents that it will not offer, promise, authorize, or provide anything of value in violation of anti-corruption laws, and will comply with applicable sanctions and export control laws where relevant to the Services.\n\n10.6 Accessibility and Platform Policies (Optional). If Deliverables include websites, apps, or digital content, compliance with accessibility requirements (e.g., WCAG/ADA-related guidance) and platform policies (e.g., app stores, ad platforms, social platforms) will be addressed in the SOW. Unless expressly agreed, Freelance Worker does not warrant that Deliverables will satisfy any particular accessibility standard.\n\n10.7 AI-Assisted Tools (Optional). If Freelance Worker uses AI-assisted tools in performing the Services, Freelance Worker will use commercially reasonable care to avoid including Hiring Party Confidential Information in public prompts and will comply with any AI usage restrictions stated in {{ai_usage_terms}}."},{"id":"intellectual_property","type":"negotiable","order":11,"title":"11. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; OWNERSHIP; LICENSES","content":"11.1 Definitions. Capitalized IP terms used in this Section have the meanings in Section 1. Work Product is defined in Section 1.21.\n\n11.2 Ownership of Background IP. Each Party retains all right, title, and interest in and to its Background IP. No rights are granted except as expressly set forth in this Agreement.\n\n11.3 Work Product Ownership; Assignment Upon Payment. Subject to Sections 11.4 and 11.5, and upon Hiring Party’s full and final payment of all amounts due for the applicable Services and Deliverables, Freelance Worker hereby assigns to Hiring Party all right, title, and interest in and to the Work Product, including all intellectual property rights therein, to the maximum extent permitted by law.\n\n11.4 License to Freelance Worker Background IP. To the extent Freelance Worker incorporates Freelance Worker Background IP into the Work Product (including templates, frameworks, code libraries, tools, methods, or know-how), Freelance Worker grants Hiring Party a perpetual, worldwide, non-exclusive, royalty-free, fully paid, sublicensable license to use, reproduce, display, perform, distribute, modify, and create derivative works of such Freelance Worker Background IP solely as incorporated in, and as necessary to use, the Work Product for Hiring Party’s business purposes.\n\n11.5 Third-Party Materials. Deliverables may include Third-Party Materials subject to third-party license terms. Unless a SOW states otherwise, Freelance Worker will identify material Third-Party Materials known to Freelance Worker that are included in Deliverables. Hiring Party is responsible for complying with third-party license terms and for obtaining any additional licenses required for Hiring Party’s intended use.\n\n11.6 Work-Made-for-Hire (If Applicable). If any Work Product qualifies as a \"work made for hire\" under U.S. copyright law, it will be deemed a work made for hire for Hiring Party. To the extent any Work Product does not qualify as a work made for hire, Freelance Worker assigns it under Section 11.3.\n\n11.7 Further Assurances. Upon Hiring Party’s reasonable request and at Hiring Party’s expense, Freelance Worker will execute further documents and take further actions reasonably necessary to effectuate the assignment in Section 11.3, including assisting with registrations.\n\n11.8 Moral Rights; VARA. To the extent permitted by Applicable Law, Freelance Worker waives and agrees not to assert any \"moral rights\" or similar rights in the Work Product, including rights of attribution and integrity. Notwithstanding the foregoing, nothing in this Agreement requires a waiver to the extent prohibited by law (including rights that cannot be waived under the Visual Artists Rights Act, if applicable).\n\n11.9 Portfolio and Publicity (Optional). Unless prohibited in {{portfolio_restrictions}}, Freelance Worker may display non-confidential portions of the Work Product and use Hiring Party’s name and logo solely to identify Hiring Party as a client in Freelance Worker’s portfolio and marketing materials after public release of the Work Product by Hiring Party (or after Acceptance, whichever occurs first). Hiring Party may revoke portfolio permission for reasonable confidentiality or security concerns by written notice.\n\n11.10 Pre-Existing Client Materials. Hiring Party retains all rights in Client Materials. Hiring Party grants Freelance Worker a limited, non-exclusive, non-transferable license to use Client Materials solely to perform the Services during the Term.\n\n11.11 Reservation of Rights. Except as expressly provided, no implied rights are granted by either Party.\n\n11.12 Payment Condition; FIFA Rights Preserved. The Parties acknowledge that (a) ownership transfer under Section 11.3 is conditioned on full payment, and (b) nothing in this Section is intended to limit Freelance Worker’s statutory remedies for nonpayment under FIFA."},{"id":"confidentiality","type":"standard","order":12,"title":"12. CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS; DTSA NOTICE","content":"12.1 Confidential Information. \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed by or on behalf of a Party (the Disclosing Party) to the other Party (the Receiving Party), whether disclosed orally, visually, electronically, or in writing, that is designated as confidential or that a reasonable person would understand to be confidential given the nature of the information and the circumstances of disclosure. Confidential Information includes: (a) business plans, strategies, forecasts, pricing, and financial information; (b) customer lists and vendor information; (c) product roadmaps, designs, specifications, and prototypes; (d) non-public marketing plans and campaign data; (e) software, source code, architecture, and technical information; (f) security measures and vulnerabilities; (g) Personal Information to the extent protected by Applicable Law; and (h) Trade Secrets under New York common law and/or the Defend Trade Secrets Act.\n\n12.2 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by contemporaneous written records: (a) is or becomes publicly available through no breach of this Agreement; (b) was known by the Receiving Party without confidentiality restriction before receipt from the Disclosing Party; (c) is received from a third party without breach of any obligation of confidentiality; or (d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.\n\n12.3 Use and Non-Disclosure Obligations. The Receiving Party will: (a) use the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information solely as necessary to perform or receive the Services under this Agreement; (b) protect the Confidential Information using at least reasonable care and no less than the care it uses to protect its own confidential information of similar sensitivity; and (c) not disclose Confidential Information to any third party except as expressly permitted by this Agreement.\n\n12.4 Permitted Disclosures. The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information only to its employees, contractors, professional advisors, or Subcontractors who have a need to know for purposes of this Agreement and who are bound by written confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those in this Agreement. The Receiving Party is responsible for breaches by such persons.\n\n12.5 Compelled Disclosure. If the Receiving Party is required by law, subpoena, court order, or governmental request to disclose Confidential Information, the Receiving Party will (to the extent permitted) provide prompt written notice to the Disclosing Party to allow the Disclosing Party to seek a protective order or other remedy. The Receiving Party will disclose only the portion legally required and will use reasonable efforts to obtain confidential treatment.\n\n12.6 Return/Destruction. Upon termination or upon the Disclosing Party’s written request, the Receiving Party will promptly return or destroy the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information, except that the Receiving Party may retain copies (a) as required by law, (b) in routine backup systems not reasonably accessible in the ordinary course, and/or (c) to the extent necessary to document compliance or resolve disputes, provided that retained information remains subject to this Agreement.\n\n12.7 Injunctive Relief. The Parties acknowledge that unauthorized disclosure or use of Confidential Information may cause irreparable harm for which money damages may be inadequate, and that the Disclosing Party may seek injunctive or equitable relief in addition to any other remedies.\n\n12.8 Defend Trade Secrets Act (DTSA) Whistleblower Immunity Notice. Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b): (a) an individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that is made (i) in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (ii) in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal; and (b) an individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding if the individual (i) files any document containing the trade secret under seal and (ii) does not disclose the trade secret except pursuant to court order.\n\n12.9 Duration. Confidentiality obligations begin on the Effective Date and continue for {{confidentiality_period}} years after termination or expiration of this Agreement; if {{confidentiality_period}} is not specified, confidentiality obligations continue for five (5) years after termination or expiration. Trade Secrets will be protected for so long as they remain trade secrets under Applicable Law.\n\n12.10 Non-Disparagement (Optional). Any non-disparagement obligations, if applicable, are set forth in {{non_disparagement_terms}} and will not be interpreted to restrict truthful statements required by law or protected activity under Applicable Law."},{"id":"privacy_data","type":"optional","order":13,"title":"13. DATA PRIVACY; DATA SECURITY; INCIDENT NOTICE (NEW YORK)","content":"13.1 Scope. This Section applies to the extent Freelance Worker (a) accesses, receives, stores, processes, transmits, or otherwise handles Personal Information or other sensitive data on behalf of Hiring Party, or (b) accesses Hiring Party systems that store such data.\n\n13.2 Roles and Instructions. Hiring Party is responsible for determining the purposes and means of processing Personal Information in connection with Hiring Party’s business. Freelance Worker will process Personal Information only (a) as necessary to perform the Services, (b) in accordance with Hiring Party’s written instructions in the SOW or otherwise, and (c) in compliance with Applicable Law.\n\n13.3 Data Minimization. Freelance Worker will use commercially reasonable efforts to limit access to Personal Information to what is reasonably necessary for the Services and will not use Personal Information for Freelance Worker’s own purposes.\n\n13.4 Reasonable Safeguards (NY SHIELD Act Alignment). Freelance Worker will implement and maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards designed to protect Personal Information. Such safeguards may include, as appropriate: access controls; least privilege; strong authentication; secure storage and transmission; device security; patching; malware protection; and secure disposal. The Parties acknowledge that New York’s SHIELD Act (GBL § 899-bb) requires reasonable safeguards for covered Personal Information.\n\n13.5 Credentials and Access. Hiring Party will provide access through secure means and will promptly revoke access upon termination. Freelance Worker will not share credentials and will promptly notify Hiring Party if Freelance Worker suspects credentials are compromised.\n\n13.6 Subprocessors. Freelance Worker will not disclose Personal Information to Subcontractors or third-party service providers (subprocessors) except as necessary to perform the Services and only if such parties are bound by written obligations reasonably designed to protect the data. Upon request, Freelance Worker will identify material subprocessors used for project delivery.\n\n13.7 Security Incident. \"Security Incident\" means a suspected or actual unauthorized access, acquisition, use, disclosure, or loss of Personal Information or Hiring Party Confidential Information within Freelance Worker’s control.\n\n13.8 Incident Notice and Cooperation. Freelance Worker will notify Hiring Party in Writing without undue delay (and in any event within {{incident_notice_hours}} hours, if specified) after becoming aware of a Security Incident, and will reasonably cooperate with Hiring Party’s investigation, mitigation, and remediation efforts. Freelance Worker will not make public statements about a Security Incident related to Hiring Party without Hiring Party’s prior written consent unless required by law.\n\n13.9 Breach Notifications. Hiring Party is responsible for determining whether notice to individuals, regulators, or others is required under Applicable Law. Freelance Worker will provide information reasonably requested to support Hiring Party’s compliance with breach notification obligations.\n\n13.10 Data Return/Deletion. Upon termination or completion, Freelance Worker will return or delete Personal Information and Hiring Party Confidential Information in accordance with Section 12.6, subject to lawful retention.\n\n13.11 No HIPAA/GLBA Unless Agreed. Unless expressly stated in a SOW, the Parties do not intend Freelance Worker to create, receive, maintain, or transmit protected health information as a \"business associate\" under HIPAA, or to receive nonpublic personal information subject to GLBA. If such access is required, the Parties will execute appropriate addenda.\n\n13.12 Privacy Addendum (Optional). If the Parties require more detailed terms (e.g., controller/processor addendum, international transfers), they will execute a data processing addendum in {{data_processing_addendum_reference}}."},{"id":"term","type":"standard","order":14,"title":"14. TERM; TERMINATION; CANCELLATION","content":"14.1 Term. This Agreement begins on the Effective Date and continues until {{expiration_date}} (if specified) or until completion of the Services, unless terminated earlier in accordance with this Section.\n\n14.2 Termination for Convenience. Either Party may terminate this Agreement or any SOW for convenience by providing written notice at least {{notice_period}} days in advance. If {{notice_period}} is not specified, the notice period will be seven (7) calendar days.\n\n14.3 Termination for Cause. Either Party may terminate immediately upon written notice if the other Party: (a) materially breaches this Agreement and fails to cure within seven (7) days after written notice (or such longer cure period as may be reasonable if cure cannot be completed within seven (7) days and the breaching Party commences cure within the initial period); (b) becomes insolvent, makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, or has a receiver appointed; or (c) engages in fraud or willful misconduct related to this Agreement.\n\n14.4 Suspension for Nonpayment (Optional). If Hiring Party fails to pay undisputed amounts when due, Freelance Worker may, after providing written notice and a reasonable opportunity to cure (not less than five (5) Business Days unless Applicable Law requires otherwise), suspend Services until payment is made. Suspension does not extend deadlines unless the Parties agree in Writing.\n\n14.5 Effect of Termination. Upon termination or expiration: (a) Freelance Worker will stop performing Services as of the termination effective date; (b) each Party will return or destroy Confidential Information as provided in Section 12.6; and (c) Hiring Party will pay Freelance Worker for all Services performed and approved expenses incurred through the termination effective date, subject to the payment timing requirements in Section 8 and Applicable Law.\n\n14.6 Deliverables in Progress. Upon termination, Freelance Worker will deliver to Hiring Party any completed Deliverables for which Hiring Party has paid, and any partially completed work to the extent reasonably practicable, provided Hiring Party pays for such work at the agreed rates.\n\n14.7 Kill Fee / Cancellation Fee (Optional). If a cancellation fee applies, it is set forth in {{cancellation_fee_terms}}. Any cancellation fee must be reasonable and is not intended to limit Freelance Worker’s statutory rights to payment for work performed.\n\n14.8 Survival. The provisions that by their nature should survive termination will survive, including Sections 8 (amounts owed), 11 (IP), 12 (Confidentiality), 13 (Data obligations to the extent applicable), 16 (Indemnification), 17 (Liability limitations), 19 (Governing Law; Venue), 20 (Notices), and 21 (General Provisions)."},{"id":"warranties","type":"standard","order":15,"title":"15. WARRANTIES; DISCLAIMERS","content":"15.1 Mutual Authority. Each Party represents and warrants that (a) it has full power and authority to enter into this Agreement, (b) its execution and performance do not violate any other agreement to which it is bound, and (c) the person signing has authority to bind the Party.\n\n15.2 Freelance Worker Warranties. Freelance Worker represents and warrants that: (a) Services will be performed in a professional and workmanlike manner consistent with Section 2.3; (b) to Freelance Worker’s knowledge, Work Product (excluding Client Materials and Third-Party Materials) does not infringe any U.S. copyright, trademark, or trade secret rights of a third party; and (c) Freelance Worker has the right to grant the rights and licenses stated in Section 11.\n\n15.3 Hiring Party Warranties. Hiring Party represents and warrants that: (a) Client Materials and instructions provided by Hiring Party do not knowingly infringe third-party rights; and (b) Hiring Party has the rights and permissions necessary to provide Client Materials for use in the Services.\n\n15.4 Disclaimer. EXCEPT AS EXPRESSLY PROVIDED IN THIS AGREEMENT, THE SERVICES AND DELIVERABLES ARE PROVIDED \"AS IS\" AND \"AS AVAILABLE.\" TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, EACH PARTY DISCLAIMS ALL OTHER WARRANTIES, WHETHER EXPRESS, IMPLIED, OR STATUTORY, INCLUDING IMPLIED WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, TITLE, AND NON-INFRINGEMENT.\n\n15.5 Beta/Experimental Work (Optional). If Deliverables are labeled as beta, prototype, draft, or experimental in the SOW, the Parties acknowledge such Deliverables may contain defects and are provided for evaluation.\n\n15.6 Client Review and Approval. Hiring Party is responsible for reviewing and approving Deliverables before use, including for legal compliance, brand compliance, and accuracy of claims.\n\n15.7 No Guarantee of Results. Freelance Worker does not warrant that Deliverables will achieve any specific business, financial, SEO, marketing, fundraising, or operational result unless expressly stated in a SOW."},{"id":"indemnification","type":"negotiable","order":16,"title":"16. INDEMNIFICATION","content":"16.1 Freelance Worker Indemnity. Freelance Worker will indemnify, defend, and hold harmless Hiring Party and its Affiliates, and their respective officers, directors, employees, and agents, from and against any third-party claims, damages, liabilities, penalties, fines, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) arising out of or relating to: (a) allegations that the Work Product (excluding Client Materials and Third-Party Materials) infringes a third party’s U.S. intellectual property rights; or (b) Freelance Worker’s material breach of Section 12 (Confidentiality) or Section 13 (Data Privacy; Data Security), provided that Hiring Party (i) promptly notifies Freelance Worker of the claim, (ii) allows Freelance Worker to control the defense and settlement (subject to Section 16.4), and (iii) provides reasonable cooperation at Freelance Worker’s expense.\n\n16.2 Hiring Party Indemnity. Hiring Party will indemnify, defend, and hold harmless Freelance Worker and its Affiliates, and their respective officers, directors, employees, and agents, from and against any third-party claims, damages, liabilities, penalties, fines, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) arising out of or relating to: (a) Client Materials or Hiring Party instructions, including allegations that Client Materials or Hiring Party-directed use infringes third-party rights; (b) Hiring Party’s products or services, or the use of Deliverables in combination with items not provided by Freelance Worker, to the extent the claim would not have arisen but for such combination; or (c) Hiring Party’s violation of Applicable Law in connection with its use or publication of Deliverables.\n\n16.3 Mitigation; IP Infringement Remedy (Optional). If a Deliverable is alleged to infringe, Freelance Worker may, at its option: (a) obtain a license for Hiring Party’s continued use; (b) modify or replace the Deliverable so it becomes non-infringing while materially preserving functionality; or (c) if neither (a) nor (b) is commercially reasonable, refund fees paid for the allegedly infringing portion of the Deliverable, upon return of such Deliverable, subject to Section 17.\n\n16.4 Settlement Restrictions. No indemnifying Party may settle a claim in a manner that (a) imposes liability or obligations on the indemnified Party, or (b) admits wrongdoing by the indemnified Party, without the indemnified Party’s prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld).\n\n16.5 Exclusions. Freelance Worker has no indemnity obligation for claims arising from: (a) modifications not made by Freelance Worker; (b) use of Deliverables other than as contemplated by this Agreement or SOW; (c) use of outdated Deliverables where a non-infringing update was provided; (d) Client Materials; or (e) Third-Party Materials.\n\n16.6 Sole Remedy (Optional). If stated in {{indemnity_sole_remedy_terms}}, this Section 16 will be the sole and exclusive remedy for third-party IP infringement claims, except to the extent prohibited by Applicable Law."},{"id":"liability","type":"negotiable","order":17,"title":"17. LIMITATION OF LIABILITY","content":"17.1 Exclusion of Certain Damages. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, NEITHER PARTY WILL BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER FOR ANY INDIRECT, INCIDENTAL, SPECIAL, CONSEQUENTIAL, EXEMPLARY, OR PUNITIVE DAMAGES, OR FOR ANY LOSS OF PROFITS, REVENUE, DATA, OR BUSINESS OPPORTUNITY, ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT OR THE SERVICES, EVEN IF ADVISED OF THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH DAMAGES.\n\n17.2 Liability Cap. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, EACH PARTY’S TOTAL AGGREGATE LIABILITY ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT WILL NOT EXCEED THE TOTAL FEES PAID OR PAYABLE UNDER THIS AGREEMENT IN THE {{liability_cap_period}} MONTHS PRECEDING THE EVENT GIVING RISE TO THE CLAIM. If {{liability_cap_period}} is not specified, the period is twelve (12) months.\n\n17.3 Exceptions. Nothing in this Agreement limits or excludes liability for: (a) fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation; (b) willful misconduct or gross negligence to the extent such limitation is prohibited by law; (c) a Party’s indemnification obligations under Section 16 (subject to any stated limitations therein); or (d) any liability that cannot be limited or excluded under Applicable Law.\n\n17.4 FIFA Rights Not Limited. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary, nothing in this Section 17 is intended to limit (and will not be construed to limit) Freelance Worker’s rights or Hiring Party’s obligations under FIFA or other Applicable Law regarding timely payment, statutory damages (including potential double damages for late payment), attorneys’ fees, costs, or anti-retaliation protections.\n\n17.5 Allocation of Risk. The Parties acknowledge that the fees reflect the allocation of risk under this Agreement and that, absent this allocation, fees would be substantially higher.\n\n17.6 Insurance (Optional). Any insurance requirements are set forth in {{insurance_requirements}}. If not specified, each Party is responsible for maintaining insurance it deems appropriate for its business."},{"id":"dispute_resolution","type":"standard","order":18,"title":"18. DISPUTE RESOLUTION; EQUITABLE RELIEF; RETALIATION PROHIBITED","content":"18.1 Good-Faith Negotiation. The Parties will first attempt in good faith to resolve any Dispute by informal discussions. Either Party may initiate negotiations by written notice describing the issue and the requested resolution.\n\n18.2 Escalation (Optional). If the Dispute is not resolved within {{negotiation_days}} days (or, if not specified, ten (10) days) after notice under Section 18.1, the Parties may escalate the matter to designated representatives.\n\n18.3 Mediation (Optional). If specified in {{mediation_terms}}, the Parties will attempt to resolve the Dispute through non-binding mediation in {{mediation_location}} before filing suit, except for claims seeking injunctive relief or claims to enforce FIFA payment rights.\n\n18.4 Equitable Relief. Either Party may seek temporary, preliminary, or permanent injunctive relief in any court of competent jurisdiction to prevent or remedy a breach of Sections 11 (IP), 12 (Confidentiality), or 13 (Data), without the necessity of posting bond to the extent permitted by law.\n\n18.5 No Retaliation. Hiring Party shall not take any adverse action against Freelance Worker, including threatening, intimidating, disciplining, harassing, blacklisting, penalizing, denying future work opportunities, or otherwise discriminating against Freelance Worker for exercising any right under this Agreement or Applicable Law, including rights under FIFA.\n\n18.6 Administrative Complaint Rights. Freelance Worker has the right to file a complaint with the applicable agency regarding alleged FIFA violations, including (as applicable) the NYC Department of Consumer and Worker Protection and/or the New York State Department of Labor.\n\n18.7 Attorneys’ Fees Where Permitted. Nothing in this Agreement limits any right to attorneys’ fees or costs that may be available under Applicable Law (including FIFA)."},{"id":"governing_law_venue","type":"standard","order":19,"title":"19. GOVERNING LAW; VENUE; JURISDICTION","content":"19.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and any Dispute will be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of New York, without regard to its conflict-of-law principles.\n\n19.2 Venue in Specific New York County. The Parties agree that any legal action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement will be brought exclusively in the state or federal courts located in {{venue_county}} County, New York, and each Party irrevocably submits to the personal jurisdiction of such courts.\n\n19.3 Waiver of Inconvenient Forum. Each Party waives any objection that such courts are an inconvenient forum.\n\n19.4 FIFA and Public Policy. The Parties acknowledge that certain rights and remedies under Applicable Law may not be waived by contract. Nothing in this Agreement will be interpreted to require waiver of non-waivable statutory rights.\n\n19.5 Jury Trial Waiver (Optional). Any jury trial waiver is set forth in {{jury_trial_waiver_terms}} and will apply only to the extent enforceable under New York law."},{"id":"notices","type":"standard","order":20,"title":"20. NOTICES","content":"20.1 Form of Notice. Notices under this Agreement must be in Writing.\n\n20.2 Notice Addresses. Notices will be sent to the Parties at the addresses and emails below (or to any updated address/email provided by notice under this Section):\n(a) If to Hiring Party: {{party_a_company}}, Attn: {{party_a_name}}, {{party_a_address}}, Email: {{party_a_email}}.\n(b) If to Freelance Worker: {{party_b_company}}, Attn: {{party_b_name}}, {{party_b_address}}, Email: {{party_b_email}}.\n\n20.3 Permitted Delivery Methods. Notices may be delivered by (a) personal delivery, (b) nationally recognized overnight courier, (c) certified or registered mail (return receipt requested), or (d) email.\n\n20.4 Effective Date of Notice. \n(a) Personal delivery: upon delivery.\n(b) Overnight courier: upon confirmation of delivery.\n(c) Certified/registered mail: upon receipt or refusal.\n(d) Email: upon transmission if sent during normal business hours on a Business Day in New York, New York; otherwise on the next Business Day, provided that the sender does not receive an automated bounce-back or other notice of non-delivery.\n\n20.5 Copies; Courtesy Notices. A Party may request courtesy copies, but failure to send a courtesy copy does not invalidate notice.\n\n20.6 FIFA Notices. For purposes of FIFA compliance, the Parties agree that email notices constitute written notices if they are capable of being retained and reproduced."},{"id":"general","type":"standard","order":21,"title":"21. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"21.1 Entire Agreement. This Agreement, together with any SOWs and Change Orders, constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties with respect to the subject matter and supersedes all prior or contemporaneous agreements and understandings, whether written or oral.\n\n21.2 Amendments. Any amendment or modification must be in Writing and signed or confirmed in Writing by both Parties.\n\n21.3 Order of Precedence. In the event of a conflict: (a) a Change Order that expressly states it overrides a specific provision will control for that specific issue; (b) otherwise, a SOW will control over this Agreement solely with respect to project-specific details (scope, Deliverables, Milestones, schedule, fees); and (c) this Agreement controls over all other matters.\n\n21.4 Assignment. Neither Party may assign this Agreement without the other Party’s prior written consent, except that Hiring Party may assign this Agreement to an Affiliate or in connection with a merger, acquisition, reorganization, or sale of substantially all assets, provided the assignee assumes all obligations.\n\n21.5 Subcontracting. Subcontracting is governed by Section 2.8. Any permitted subcontracting does not relieve Freelance Worker of responsibility for performance.\n\n21.6 Independent Relationship. The Parties are independent contractors. Nothing in this Agreement creates a partnership, joint venture, fiduciary relationship, or employment relationship.\n\n21.7 Severability. If any provision of this Agreement is held invalid or unenforceable, the remaining provisions will remain in full force and effect, and the invalid provision will be reformed to the minimum extent necessary to make it enforceable while preserving the Parties’ intent.\n\n21.8 Waiver. A waiver of any provision is effective only if in Writing and will not operate as a waiver of any other provision or any subsequent breach.\n\n21.9 Force Majeure. Neither Party will be liable for delay or failure to perform due to causes beyond its reasonable control (e.g., natural disasters, war, terrorism, labor disputes, government orders, network outages), provided that the affected Party gives prompt notice and uses reasonable efforts to resume performance.\n\n21.10 Publicity. Any press release or public announcement regarding this Agreement requires the other Party’s prior written consent, except that portfolio use is governed by Section 11.9.\n\n21.11 Restrictive Covenants (Optional; NY Scrutiny). \n(a) Non-Compete. The Parties acknowledge that non-compete restrictions are disfavored and strictly scrutinized under New York law. Unless expressly stated in {{non_compete_terms}}, there is no non-compete obligation.\n(b) Non-Solicitation (Optional). If stated in {{non_solicit_terms}}, for the period stated therein, Freelance Worker agrees not to solicit specified customers or employees of Hiring Party, limited to the extent reasonable in duration, scope, and geography and necessary to protect legitimate business interests.\n(c) No-Hire (Optional). If stated in {{no_hire_terms}}, the Parties may agree to a narrowly tailored no-hire provision; any such provision will be interpreted narrowly to the extent enforceable.\n\n21.12 Counterparts; Electronic Signatures. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which is deemed an original. Signatures delivered electronically or via electronic signature platform are binding and effective under ESRA and the federal E-SIGN Act.\n\n21.13 Interpretation. Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation. The word \"including\" means \"including without limitation.\" References to \"days\" mean calendar days unless stated otherwise.\n\n21.14 Conflicts of Interest. Freelance Worker will use commercially reasonable efforts to avoid conflicts of interest that would materially impair performance. Freelance Worker will not use Hiring Party Confidential Information to benefit another client.\n\n21.15 Further Assurances. Each Party will execute and deliver such further documents and take such further actions as may be reasonably necessary to carry out the intent of this Agreement.\n\n21.16 Record Retention (FIFA). Hiring Party will retain a copy of this Agreement and any SOWs/Change Orders for at least six (6) years after the later of (a) termination/expiration or (b) completion of Services, consistent with FIFA requirements. Freelance Worker may also retain copies for its records.\n\n21.17 No Third-Party Beneficiaries. Except as expressly stated with respect to indemnified parties in Section 16, there are no third-party beneficiaries.\n\n21.18 Non-Reliance. Each Party acknowledges it has not relied on any statement or representation not expressly set forth in this Agreement.\n\n21.19 English Language. The Parties confirm that they have requested and agree that this Agreement and all related documents be drafted in English.\n\n21.20 Contact Information; Updates. Each Party will notify the other of changes to its contact information under Section 20.\n\n21.21 Optional Attachments. If applicable, the following may be attached and incorporated by reference: {{attachments_list}}."}]'::jsonb,
  signature_block = 'IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Agreement as of {{signature_date}}.

