-- Update: Independent Contractor Agreement (New York)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Independent Contractor Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between {{party_a_company}}, with an address at {{party_a_address}} ("Client"), and {{party_b_company}}, with an address at {{party_b_address}} ("Contractor"). Client and Contractor may be referred to herein individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties".

For purposes of New York Labor Law Article 44 (Freelance Worker Protection) and, if applicable, the New York City Freelance Isn’t Free Act (NYC Admin. Code § 20-927 et seq.), the Parties intend this Agreement to serve as the required written contract for covered freelance services in the amount of $800 or more, whether alone or when aggregated with other contracts for services between the Parties during the immediately preceding 120 days, and to include the terms required by applicable law (including, without limitation, the Parties’ names and mailing addresses, an itemization of services, the rate and method of compensation, and the date when payment is due or the mechanism by which such date will be determined).',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, Client desires to retain Contractor to perform certain services described in this Agreement and/or one or more statements of work, proposals, work orders, or similar written descriptions incorporated into this Agreement (each, a "SOW");

WHEREAS, Contractor represents that Contractor has the expertise, resources, and ability to perform such services in a professional and workmanlike manner as an independent contractor, and not as an employee of Client;

WHEREAS, the Parties desire to set forth in writing their agreement regarding the scope of services, compensation, intellectual property, confidentiality, data protection, and other terms and conditions governing their relationship;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"services","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. SERVICES","content":"1.1 Services. Contractor shall perform the services described in {{services_description}} (the \"Services\") in a timely, professional, and workmanlike manner, consistent with generally accepted industry standards, and in accordance with this Agreement and any applicable SOW.\n\n1.2 Deliverables; Milestones; Acceptance Criteria.\n(a) \"Deliverables\" (if any) shall be as described in {{services_description}} and/or an applicable SOW.\n(b) Any milestones, deadlines, service levels, acceptance criteria, formats, and technical or functional specifications shall be as stated in {{services_description}} and/or the applicable SOW.\n(c) If an acceptance period is specified in a SOW, Client shall have such period to review and either accept the applicable Deliverable or provide written notice of rejection describing in reasonable detail the nonconformities. If no acceptance period is specified, the acceptance period shall be {{acceptance_period_days}} business days from delivery (or, if blank, five (5) business days). Absent a timely notice of rejection, the Deliverable will be deemed accepted.\n\n1.3 Cooperation; Client Dependencies. Client shall provide timely access to Client personnel, information, facilities, and systems reasonably necessary for Contractor to perform the Services. Contractor’s performance deadlines are conditioned upon Client’s timely performance of such dependencies. Contractor shall promptly notify Client of any material delay caused by Client.\n\n1.4 Place and Manner of Performance. Contractor will determine the method, details, and means of performing the Services; provided that Contractor shall reasonably cooperate with Client’s operational, workplace, confidentiality, privacy, and security policies when accessing Client’s facilities, systems, networks, or data, including any policies provided to Contractor in writing.\n\n1.5 Meetings; Communications; Status Updates. Unless otherwise stated in a SOW, the Parties shall identify primary points of contact: {{client_project_contact}} for Client and {{contractor_project_contact}} for Contractor. Contractor shall provide status updates at the cadence described in {{services_description}} or, if not specified, upon Client’s reasonable request.\n\n1.6 Changes; Change Orders.\n(a) Either Party may request changes to the scope, Deliverables, milestones, assumptions, or requirements.\n(b) Any change that may reasonably be expected to affect fees, schedule, resource allocations, third-party costs, or risk profile (a \"Material Change\") shall be documented in a written change order or amended SOW signed (including electronically) by both Parties.\n(c) Contractor is not obligated to commence work on a Material Change until the Parties execute the applicable change order or amended SOW.\n\n1.7 Tools; Equipment; Substitutions. Except as expressly stated in a SOW, Contractor shall provide all tools, equipment, and materials necessary to perform the Services. Contractor may use qualified personnel (including Contractor’s employees or permitted subcontractors, if any) to perform the Services, subject to Section 11.6 (Subcontractors and Flow-Down).\n\n1.8 Onsite Work (If Applicable). If the Services require onsite work at Client locations, Contractor shall comply with Client’s reasonable access, safety, and visitor policies. Contractor acknowledges that Client may require reasonable security measures (e.g., badge access, escort rules, device restrictions). Nothing in this Section gives Client the right to control the manner and means of Contractor’s performance beyond legitimate safety, security, and operational requirements.\n\n1.9 No Authority. Contractor has no authority to bind Client, incur obligations on Client’s behalf, or make representations as an agent of Client unless expressly authorized in a writing signed by Client.\n\n1.10 Optional: Background Checks. If Contractor will have onsite access to Client facilities, systems, or sensitive data, Client may require that Contractor (and, if applicable, Contractor Personnel) complete reasonable background checks to the extent permitted by applicable law and consistent with Client’s policies. If required, such requirement shall be stated in a SOW or written notice, and the Parties shall allocate the cost in that writing.\n\n1.11 Optional: Suspension for Security/Compliance. Client may temporarily suspend Contractor’s access to Client systems or premises if Client reasonably believes such suspension is necessary to protect Client, its personnel, its data, or its customers, or to comply with law. Client shall use reasonable efforts to notify Contractor promptly and to restore access when the basis for suspension is resolved."},{"id":"compensation","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. COMPENSATION; INVOICING; EXPENSES; FREELANCE WORKER PAYMENT PROTECTIONS","content":"2.1 Fees; Rate and Method of Compensation. As full consideration for the Services, Client shall pay Contractor the fees described in {{services_description}}, which may include (as applicable): (a) a fixed fee of {{payment_amount}}; (b) an hourly rate of {{hourly_rate}}; and/or (c) another rate, method, or schedule described in a SOW (collectively, the \"Fees\"). If both a fixed fee and hourly rate are stated, the applicable SOW shall control.\n\n2.2 Invoicing Requirements.\n(a) Contractor shall invoice Client as stated in {{services_description}} or the applicable SOW.\n(b) Each invoice shall reasonably itemize the Services performed (and, if applicable, Deliverables delivered), include the date(s) or period covered, the Fees due, and any approved reimbursable expenses with supporting documentation.\n(c) Invoices shall be sent to {{invoice_delivery_email}} (or any updated billing contact Client designates in writing).\n\n2.3 Payment Due Date; New York Freelance Worker Protections.\n(a) Contractual Due Date. The Parties agree that payment for properly invoiced, undisputed Fees is due as follows: {{payment_due_terms}}.\n(b) Statutory Default and Maximum Timing (Article 44 / NYC Freelance Isn’t Free Act). To the extent New York Labor Law Article 44 and/or NYC Admin Code § 20-927 et seq. applies, Client shall pay Contractor on or before the payment due date specified in this Agreement or an applicable SOW; and if no such date is specified, Client shall pay no later than thirty (30) calendar days after Contractor’s completion of the Services covered by the invoice. The Parties intend this Agreement to be interpreted and administered in a manner consistent with those requirements.\n(c) Completion. For purposes of Section 2.3(b), \"completion\" occurs when Contractor has performed the Services and delivered any applicable Deliverables in accordance with the applicable SOW, subject to Client’s reasonable acceptance rights in Section 1.2.\n\n2.4 Disputed Amounts; No Improper Withholding.\n(a) If Client disputes an invoice in good faith, Client shall notify Contractor in writing within {{invoice_dispute_days}} calendar days of receipt (or, if blank, ten (10) calendar days), specifying in reasonable detail the basis for the dispute.\n(b) Client shall timely pay any undisputed portion of the invoice by the applicable due date, and the Parties shall cooperate in good faith to resolve the disputed portion.\n(c) Client shall not withhold payment as leverage to obtain additional services, concessions, or releases not required by this Agreement.\n\n2.5 Late Payments; Statutory Remedies; Interest.\n(a) Contractual Interest (Optional). If Client fails to pay an undisputed amount when due, then, in addition to any statutory remedies, Client shall pay interest on the overdue amount at {{late_interest_rate}} per month (or, if blank, the maximum rate permitted by applicable law), accruing from the due date until paid.\n(b) No Waiver of Freelance Worker Rights. Nothing in this Agreement is intended to waive or limit any rights or remedies available to Contractor under New York Labor Law Article 44 and/or the NYC Freelance Isn’t Free Act.\n(c) Statutory Damages and Fees (If Applicable). Where applicable law provides for liquidated damages, statutory damages (including, for example, double damages), attorneys’ fees, and costs for nonpayment or retaliation, such remedies shall be available as provided by law.\n\n2.6 Method of Payment; Setoff.\n(a) Payment shall be made by {{payment_method}} (e.g., ACH, check) to the account or address designated by Contractor on the invoice, unless the Parties agree otherwise in writing.\n(b) Client shall not offset or set off amounts allegedly owed by Contractor to Client against Fees due to Contractor unless (i) Contractor agrees in writing, or (ii) a final, non-appealable judgment authorizes such setoff.\n\n2.7 Expenses; Pre-Approval; Travel.\n(a) Unless expressly authorized in advance in writing, Contractor is responsible for all expenses incurred in performing the Services.\n(b) If reimbursable expenses are authorized in a SOW, such expenses must be reasonable, necessary, and consistent with any expense policy provided by Client in writing in advance. Reimbursement is subject to a cap of {{expense_cap}} (if any) as stated in the SOW.\n(c) No reimbursement is due for commuting, ordinary overhead, or Contractor’s standard tools and subscriptions unless expressly approved in writing.\n\n2.8 Taxes; Information Reporting; New York Taxes.\n(a) Contractor is solely responsible for all federal, state, and local taxes, assessments, and other governmental charges arising from compensation paid under this Agreement, including, as applicable, New York State income tax, New York City income tax (if applicable based on residency and allocation rules), self-employment tax, estimated taxes, and any business taxes.\n(b) Client will not withhold or pay payroll taxes for Contractor. Client may issue IRS Form 1099 (or other applicable tax reporting forms) as required by law.\n(c) If Contractor is a business entity, Contractor represents it is properly formed, registered, and in good standing as required.\n\n2.9 No Employee Benefits. Contractor acknowledges that Contractor is not eligible for Client-provided benefits, including health insurance, retirement benefits, paid leave, or unemployment insurance. To the extent workers’ compensation coverage is required by law for Contractor Personnel who are employees of Contractor, Contractor shall maintain such coverage.\n\n2.10 Records; Receipts; Retention (Freelance Worker Protections). Each Party shall retain records relating to this Agreement, the Services, invoices, and payments for at least six (6) years, or such longer period as may be required by applicable law, regulation, or a litigation hold notice.\n\n2.11 Anti-Retaliation (Freelance Worker Protections). Client shall not threaten, intimidate, discipline, withhold future work opportunities from, discriminate against, or take any other retaliatory action against Contractor for exercising rights under New York Labor Law Article 44 and/or, if applicable, the NYC Freelance Isn’t Free Act, including requesting a written contract, timely payment, or seeking to enforce rights under applicable law.\n\n2.12 Optional: Retainer/Deposit. If a retainer or deposit is required, the amount shall be {{retainer_amount}} and the application/refund terms shall be as stated in {{retainer_terms}}."},{"id":"independent_contractor_status","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR STATUS; NEW YORK LABOR LAW COMPLIANCE","content":"3.1 Independent Contractor Relationship. Contractor is an independent contractor and not an employee, partner, joint venturer, agent, or legal representative of Client. Contractor shall control the manner and means of performing the Services, subject to the requirements of this Agreement and any applicable SOW regarding deliverables, results, specifications, deadlines, and Client’s legitimate safety, confidentiality, and security requirements.\n\n3.2 No Employment Relationship; No Control Over Work Details.\n(a) Contractor is not entitled to and will not receive wages, overtime, meal/rest periods, reimbursement rights (except as expressly stated), or other protections applicable to employees under New York Labor Law or other laws.\n(b) Client will not provide training to Contractor (other than orientation to Client policies or project requirements), will not supervise Contractor in a manner consistent with an employment relationship, and will not require Contractor to work set hours, except as may be necessary for coordination, meetings, or site access windows.\n\n3.3 New York Worker Classification Intent; Factors. The Parties intend that Contractor be properly classified as an independent contractor under applicable federal, New York State, and local law. Contractor represents that, consistent with the factual relationship:\n(a) Contractor is free from Client’s control and direction in the performance of the Services, both under this Agreement and in fact (except as to results and required compliance with law and policies);\n(b) Contractor is customarily engaged in an independently established trade, occupation, profession, or business of the same nature as the Services;\n(c) Contractor offers services to others and/or is free to do so, subject to confidentiality and conflict-of-interest obligations;\n(d) Contractor has the opportunity for profit or loss depending upon managerial skill and business decisions;\n(e) Contractor has made and will maintain an investment in equipment, tools, software, facilities, education, training, marketing, and/or other resources used to perform the Services; and\n(f) Contractor is responsible for hiring, compensating, and controlling Contractor Personnel (if any) and for Contractor’s internal business operations.\n\n3.4 Contractor’s Business Operations; Licenses; Permits. Contractor is responsible for operating Contractor’s business in compliance with applicable law, including obtaining and maintaining any required business registrations, professional licenses, permits, and insurance.\n\n3.5 No Unemployment Insurance; Workers’ Compensation. Contractor understands that Contractor is not eligible for unemployment insurance benefits from Client and that Client does not provide workers’ compensation coverage for Contractor as an independent contractor. Contractor shall maintain any legally required workers’ compensation and disability coverage for Contractor’s employees (if any) and shall provide evidence upon request.\n\n3.6 Non-Exclusivity; Conflicts of Interest.\n(a) Unless otherwise stated in a SOW, Contractor may perform services for others during the Term, provided such services do not materially interfere with Contractor’s performance or breach this Agreement.\n(b) Contractor shall avoid conflicts of interest and shall promptly disclose to Client any actual or potential conflict that could reasonably be expected to impair Contractor’s objectivity or ability to perform the Services.\n\n3.7 No Authority to Hire or Bind. Contractor shall not (i) hire or engage any individual as an employee of Client, (ii) represent that Contractor has authority to make commitments on Client’s behalf, or (iii) represent to third parties that Contractor is an employee of Client.\n\n3.8 Misclassification Claims; Cooperation. If any governmental authority challenges the independent contractor status of Contractor, the Parties shall cooperate in good faith. Nothing in this Agreement requires either Party to take any position that is untrue or unlawful.\n\n3.9 Optional: Indemnity for Contractor’s Personnel. To the extent permitted by law, Contractor shall be responsible for and shall defend and indemnify Client from claims by Contractor Personnel (including any subcontractors) relating to compensation, benefits, taxes, or worker classification arising from Contractor’s failure to comply with applicable law; provided that this Section does not apply to the extent a claim results from Client’s direction that Contractor Personnel be treated as Client employees or Client’s exercise of control inconsistent with independent contractor status."},{"id":"term_termination","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TERM; TERMINATION; SUSPENSION; TRANSITION","content":"4.1 Term. This Agreement begins on the Effective Date and continues until {{expiration_date}}, unless earlier terminated in accordance with this Agreement (the \"Term\"). If no expiration date is specified, the Term continues until completion of the Services or termination.\n\n4.2 Statements of Work. The Parties may enter into one or more SOWs under this Agreement. Each SOW shall be incorporated by reference when signed (including electronically) by both Parties and shall specify, as applicable, Services, Deliverables, schedule, Fees, and any special terms. In the event of a conflict between this Agreement and a SOW, the following order of precedence applies unless the SOW expressly states otherwise: (i) the SOW, (ii) this Agreement.\n\n4.3 Termination for Convenience.\n(a) Either Party may terminate this Agreement or any SOW for convenience upon {{notice_period}} days’ written notice to the other Party.\n(b) If Client terminates for convenience, Client shall pay Contractor for all Services performed and accepted Deliverables delivered through the effective termination date, plus any non-cancellable, pre-approved commitments made by Contractor solely for the project, provided Contractor uses reasonable efforts to mitigate such costs.\n\n4.4 Termination for Cause. Either Party may terminate this Agreement (or any SOW) immediately upon written notice if the other Party:\n(a) materially breaches this Agreement and fails to cure such breach within ten (10) days after receiving written notice of breach (or, if the breach is not reasonably curable within ten (10) days, fails to commence cure within ten (10) days and diligently pursue cure to completion);\n(b) becomes insolvent, makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, has a receiver appointed, or files (or has filed against it) a petition in bankruptcy that is not dismissed within sixty (60) days; or\n(c) engages in fraud, willful misconduct, material violation of law, or conduct that materially harms the other Party’s business, reputation, or security.\n\n4.5 Suspension.\n(a) Client Suspension for Cause. Client may suspend performance under a SOW (in whole or part) upon written notice if Client reasonably believes Contractor has materially breached this Agreement, poses a material security risk, or is otherwise unable to perform. Client shall specify the basis and scope of the suspension.\n(b) Contractor Suspension for Nonpayment. If Client fails to pay an undisputed invoice amount when due, Contractor may, after providing written notice and a reasonable opportunity to cure (not less than five (5) business days), suspend performance until payment is made, without liability for resulting delays.\n(c) Effect of Suspension. During a suspension, Contractor shall use reasonable efforts to minimize costs, and the Parties shall cooperate to resume performance promptly. Any schedule impacts shall be addressed via a change order.\n\n4.6 Effect of Termination.\n(a) Upon expiration or termination, Contractor shall cease performing the terminated Services, promptly deliver to Client all completed Work Product and Deliverables paid for (or due to be paid for) through the effective date, and return or destroy Client property and Confidential Information in accordance with Section 6.\n(b) Client shall pay Contractor in accordance with Section 2 for Services properly performed through the termination date (and, where applicable, in compliance with New York freelance worker payment protections).\n\n4.7 Transition Assistance (Optional). If requested by Client within thirty (30) days after termination, Contractor shall provide reasonable transition assistance for up to {{transition_hours_cap}} hours at Contractor’s then-current hourly rate (or the rate in the applicable SOW), to support orderly handoff to Client or a replacement provider.\n\n4.8 Survival. The provisions that by their nature should survive termination shall survive, including Sections 2 (to the extent of payment obligations and statutory protections), 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 11, and 12."},{"id":"intellectual_property","type":"negotiable","order":5,"title":"5. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; WORK PRODUCT","content":"5.1 Definitions.\n(a) \"Work Product\" means all Deliverables and other work product, inventions, discoveries, developments, designs, works of authorship, documentation, reports, processes, data compilations, databases, notes, materials, drawings, specifications, software (including source code and object code), and other items created, conceived, reduced to practice, authored, or developed by Contractor (alone or jointly with others) in connection with the Services.\n(b) \"Background Technology\" means technology, tools, software, code, templates, frameworks, know-how, methods, processes, and other materials that (i) were owned or developed by Contractor prior to the Effective Date, or (ii) are developed by Contractor outside the scope of the Services without use of Client Confidential Information.\n(c) \"Client Materials\" means materials, content, data, software, documentation, trademarks, and other items provided by or on behalf of Client to Contractor.\n(d) \"Third-Party Materials\" means any materials (including open source software) not owned by either Party.\n\n5.2 Work Made for Hire; Assignment.\n(a) To the maximum extent permitted by applicable law, the Parties intend that the Work Product be deemed a \"work made for hire\" as that term is used in the U.S. Copyright Act.\n(b) To the extent any Work Product does not qualify as a work made for hire, Contractor hereby irrevocably assigns and transfers to Client, without additional consideration beyond the Fees, all right, title, and interest worldwide in and to such Work Product, including all intellectual property rights therein.\n(c) If Contractor is a business entity, Contractor shall cause its employees and contractors who contribute to the Work Product to assign their rights consistent with this Section 5.\n\n5.3 License to Client Materials. Client grants Contractor a limited, non-exclusive, non-transferable, non-sublicensable license to use Client Materials solely as necessary to perform the Services during the Term.\n\n5.4 Background Technology; License Grant. Contractor retains all rights in and to Background Technology. If Contractor incorporates Background Technology into the Work Product, Contractor grants to Client a perpetual, irrevocable, worldwide, royalty-free, transferable, sublicensable (through multiple tiers) license to use, reproduce, modify, create derivative works of, distribute, perform, display, host, and otherwise exploit such Background Technology as incorporated in or necessary to use the Work Product.\n\n5.5 Third-Party Materials; Open Source.\n(a) Contractor shall not include Third-Party Materials in Work Product unless (i) the Third-Party Materials are identified in writing to Client in advance (including the applicable license terms), and (ii) Client approves in writing.\n(b) Open Source Software. Contractor shall not incorporate any open source software into Work Product in a manner that would require disclosure of Client source code, impose \"copyleft\" obligations, or otherwise materially restrict Client’s use or commercial exploitation of the Work Product, unless expressly approved in writing by Client.\n(c) Contractor shall provide Client, upon request, a bill of materials or software composition analysis identifying Third-Party Materials included in the Work Product.\n\n5.6 Further Assurances; Power of Attorney. Contractor shall execute and deliver documents and take actions reasonably requested by Client to perfect, register, evidence, or enforce Client’s rights in the Work Product. If Contractor fails to do so after reasonable notice, Contractor appoints Client as Contractor’s attorney-in-fact solely for the purpose of executing such documents on Contractor’s behalf, coupled with an interest, to the extent permitted by law.\n\n5.7 Moral Rights Waiver. To the extent permitted by applicable law, Contractor irrevocably waives and agrees not to assert any \"moral rights\" or similar rights in the Work Product, including rights of attribution or integrity.\n\n5.8 Portfolio Use (Optional).\n(a) Subject to Section 6 (Confidentiality) and Client’s trademark guidelines (if provided), Contractor may include non-confidential, publicly released portions of the Work Product in Contractor’s portfolio solely to describe the general nature of services performed.\n(b) Contractor shall not disclose non-public Client information, security details, or Client customer information in any portfolio or marketing material.\n\n5.9 No Implied License. Except as expressly set forth in this Agreement, no license or other rights are granted by either Party to the other Party, whether by implication, estoppel, or otherwise.\n\n5.10 Infringement Allegations (Optional Cooperation). Contractor shall promptly notify Client if Contractor becomes aware of any claim that the Work Product infringes a third party’s intellectual property rights and shall reasonably cooperate with Client’s response at Client’s expense.\n\n5.11 Equitable Relief. Contractor acknowledges that unauthorized use, disclosure, or transfer of Work Product or Client’s intellectual property may cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be inadequate, and Client shall be entitled to seek injunctive relief without posting bond to the extent permitted by law."},{"id":"confidentiality","type":"standard","order":6,"title":"6. CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS (NY COMMON LAW); DATA PROTECTION (NY SHIELD ACT)","content":"6.1 Confidential Information. \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed by or on behalf of Client (or Client’s affiliates, customers, vendors, investors, or other business partners) to Contractor, whether disclosed orally, visually, electronically, or in writing, that is designated as confidential or that reasonably should be understood to be confidential given the nature of the information or the circumstances of disclosure. Confidential Information includes, without limitation: business plans, pricing, product roadmaps, customer lists, financial information, technical information, source code, security information, designs, inventions, trade secrets protectable under New York common law, and trade secrets as defined under the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act (18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq.) (\"DTSA\").\n\n6.2 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that Contractor can demonstrate by competent written records: (a) is or becomes publicly available through no breach of this Agreement; (b) was lawfully known to Contractor without restriction before disclosure; (c) is received from a third party without breach of a confidentiality obligation; or (d) is independently developed without use of or reference to Client Confidential Information.\n\n6.3 Confidentiality Obligations. Contractor shall:\n(a) use Confidential Information solely as necessary to perform the Services for Client;\n(b) protect Confidential Information using at least reasonable care and no less than the degree of care Contractor uses to protect its own confidential information of similar sensitivity;\n(c) not disclose Confidential Information to any third party except to Contractor Personnel who have a need to know for the Services and are bound by written confidentiality obligations at least as protective as this Agreement; and\n(d) promptly notify Client of any suspected or actual unauthorized access, disclosure, loss, or misuse of Confidential Information.\n\n6.4 Permitted Disclosures; Legal Process.\n(a) Contractor may disclose Confidential Information to the extent required by law, subpoena, court order, or governmental request, provided that, to the extent legally permitted, Contractor gives Client prompt written notice and reasonably cooperates (at Client’s expense) with Client’s efforts to seek protective treatment.\n(b) Contractor shall disclose only the minimum Confidential Information legally required and shall request confidential treatment where available.\n\n6.5 Trade Secret Protection Duration. Confidentiality obligations regarding trade secrets shall continue for so long as the information remains a trade secret under applicable law. All other Confidential Information shall remain confidential for {{confidentiality_years}} years after termination or expiration (or, if blank, five (5) years).\n\n6.6 Return or Destruction. Upon Client’s request or upon termination/expiration of this Agreement, Contractor shall promptly return or destroy (and certify destruction upon request) all Confidential Information, including copies, extracts, and summaries, except that Contractor may retain one archival copy solely for legal, regulatory, insurance, or dispute purposes, provided it remains subject to this Agreement.\n\n6.7 Data Protection; New York SHIELD Act; Reasonable Safeguards.\n(a) To the extent Contractor receives, accesses, stores, transmits, processes, or otherwise handles Personal Data or Private Information (each as defined in Section 12), Contractor shall implement and maintain a written information security program with reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards designed to protect the security, confidentiality, and integrity of such data, consistent with New York General Business Law § 899-bb (the \"SHIELD Act\") and other applicable law.\n(b) Without limiting the foregoing, Contractor shall implement safeguards appropriate to the size and complexity of Contractor’s business and the nature and scope of the Services, which may include, as appropriate: access controls and least privilege, unique user IDs, multi-factor authentication for remote access and privileged accounts, encryption in transit and at rest where feasible, secure development practices, vulnerability management, logging and monitoring, and secure disposal.\n(c) Contractor shall ensure that any subcontractor or service provider with access to such data is bound by written obligations at least as protective as this Agreement and that Contractor remains responsible for their acts and omissions.\n\n6.8 Security Incident Response; Cooperation.\n(a) \"Security Incident\" means any actual or reasonably suspected unauthorized access to, acquisition of, disclosure of, alteration of, loss of, or inability to access Confidential Information or Personal Data.\n(b) Contractor shall notify Client without undue delay and in any event within {{security_notice_hours}} hours (or, if blank, seventy-two (72) hours) after becoming aware of a Security Incident.\n(c) Contractor shall promptly take reasonable steps to contain, investigate, mitigate, and remediate the Security Incident and shall provide Client with timely information reasonably requested by Client, including the nature of the incident, data affected, timeline, and corrective actions.\n(d) Contractor shall not notify any third party (including data subjects, regulators, or the media) of a Security Incident involving Client data without Client’s prior written approval, unless required by law. Where legally required notice is necessary, Contractor shall coordinate in good faith with Client regarding timing and content.\n\n6.9 Data Minimization; Deletion. Contractor shall only collect, access, use, and retain Personal Data to the extent necessary to perform the Services, and shall delete or return such data upon completion or termination as instructed by Client, subject to legal retention requirements.\n\n6.10 DTSA Whistleblower Immunity Notice. Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b), an individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that: (a) is made in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (b) is made in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal. An individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding if the individual: (i) files any document containing the trade secret under seal; and (ii) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order.\n\n6.11 Injunctive Relief. Contractor acknowledges that breach of this Section 6 may cause irreparable harm to Client. Client is entitled to seek injunctive or other equitable relief, in addition to any other remedies available at law, without the necessity of posting bond to the extent permitted by law.\n\n6.12 Optional: Residual Knowledge. If the Parties elect to allow residual knowledge, the Parties may specify in a SOW whether Contractor may use generalized, non-confidential know-how retained in unaided memory, provided Contractor does not disclose or use Client Confidential Information or trade secrets."},{"id":"representations_warranties","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES","content":"7.1 Mutual Authority. Each Party represents and warrants that: (a) it has full power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement; (b) the execution, delivery, and performance of this Agreement has been duly authorized; and (c) this Agreement constitutes a valid and binding obligation enforceable against it in accordance with its terms, subject to applicable bankruptcy and equitable principles.\n\n7.2 Contractor Performance Warranties. Contractor represents and warrants that:\n(a) Contractor has the skills, experience, and resources to perform the Services in a professional and workmanlike manner consistent with industry standards;\n(b) Contractor will perform the Services in compliance with all applicable federal, state, and local laws, rules, and regulations, including those relating to data protection, intellectual property, anti-discrimination, and workplace safety when onsite;\n(c) Contractor will not knowingly introduce viruses, malware, time bombs, back doors, or other malicious code into Client systems, networks, or Deliverables;\n(d) Work Product and Deliverables will be original to Contractor (except for approved Third-Party Materials) and, to Contractor’s knowledge, will not infringe, misappropriate, or otherwise violate any third party’s intellectual property rights;\n(e) Contractor’s performance of this Agreement does not and will not violate any agreement with a third party or any obligation owed to a current or former employer or client;\n(f) Contractor will not use Client Confidential Information to create or improve a competing product or service, or for any purpose other than performing the Services;\n(g) Contractor has obtained and will maintain all necessary rights, permissions, consents, and licenses required for materials Contractor supplies, including any Third-Party Materials incorporated with Client’s consent.\n\n7.3 Securities Law / Martin Act Compliance (If Applicable).\n(a) If the Services involve fundraising, investor communications, capital raising materials, tokenization, marketing of investment opportunities, or introductions to potential investors, Contractor represents and warrants that Contractor will not act as a broker-dealer, \"finder,\" investment adviser, or other regulated intermediary unless properly registered or exempt, and will comply with applicable securities laws.\n(b) Contractor will not make any offer, sale, solicitation, recommendation, or representation regarding securities on Client’s behalf unless expressly authorized in writing and lawfully permitted.\n(c) Contractor acknowledges that New York’s Martin Act (N.Y. Gen. Bus. Law art. 23-A) may impose broad antifraud obligations in connection with securities and commodities, and Contractor will not engage in deceptive or misleading practices.\n\n7.4 Disclaimer. Except as expressly stated in this Agreement, neither Party makes any other warranties, express or implied, including any implied warranties of merchantability, fitness for a particular purpose, title, or non-infringement (except to the extent non-infringement is expressly warranted above)."},{"id":"indemnification","type":"negotiable","order":8,"title":"8. INDEMNIFICATION; LIMITATION OF LIABILITY","content":"8.1 Contractor Indemnification. Contractor shall defend (with counsel reasonably acceptable to Client), indemnify, and hold harmless Client and its affiliates, and each of their respective directors, officers, employees, agents, and representatives (collectively, \"Client Indemnitees\") from and against any third-party claims, demands, actions, suits, proceedings, damages, losses, liabilities, penalties, fines, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) arising out of or relating to:\n(a) Contractor’s negligence, gross negligence, or willful misconduct;\n(b) Contractor’s breach of this Agreement;\n(c) allegations that the Work Product infringes or misappropriates a third party’s intellectual property rights (excluding to the extent the claim arises from Client Materials or Client’s modification not directed by Contractor);\n(d) Contractor’s violation of applicable law, including data protection or privacy laws, to the extent caused by Contractor; or\n(e) bodily injury, death, or property damage caused by Contractor in connection with onsite performance.\n\n8.2 Client Indemnification. Client shall defend (with counsel reasonably acceptable to Contractor), indemnify, and hold harmless Contractor and its directors, officers, employees, and agents (collectively, \"Contractor Indemnitees\") from and against third-party claims arising out of allegations that Client Materials, in the form provided by Client and used as authorized, infringe a third party’s intellectual property rights.\n\n8.3 Indemnification Procedure.\n(a) The Indemnified Party shall promptly notify the Indemnifying Party in writing of any claim for which it seeks indemnification; provided that failure to provide prompt notice shall not relieve the Indemnifying Party of its obligations except to the extent materially prejudiced.\n(b) The Indemnifying Party shall have the right to control the defense and settlement of the claim; provided that the Indemnifying Party may not settle any claim in a manner that (i) admits liability on behalf of the Indemnified Party, (ii) imposes non-monetary obligations on the Indemnified Party, or (iii) fails to include a full release of the Indemnified Party, in each case without the Indemnified Party’s prior written consent (not unreasonably withheld).\n(c) The Indemnified Party may participate in the defense with counsel of its choice at its own expense.\n\n8.4 IP Infringement Mitigation (Optional). If a Deliverable is (or in Client’s reasonable opinion is likely to be) enjoined or held to infringe, Contractor may, at its expense and as Client’s exclusive remedy for such injunction (except for indemnification obligations and confidentiality/data breach obligations), (a) procure the right for Client to continue using the Deliverable, (b) modify or replace it to be non-infringing while preserving materially equivalent functionality, or (c) if neither (a) nor (b) is commercially reasonable, refund the portion of Fees paid for the infringing Deliverable not usable by Client.\n\n8.5 Limitation of Liability.\n(a) Exclusion of Certain Damages. Except for Excluded Claims (defined below), neither Party shall be liable to the other for any indirect, incidental, special, consequential, exemplary, or punitive damages, or for loss of profits, loss of revenue, loss of goodwill, or business interruption, arising out of or related to this Agreement, whether in contract, tort, or otherwise, even if advised of the possibility of such damages.\n(b) Liability Cap. Except for Excluded Claims, each Party’s total aggregate liability arising out of or related to this Agreement shall not exceed {{liability_cap_amount}} (or, if blank, the total Fees paid or payable under the applicable SOW giving rise to the claim during the twelve (12) months preceding the event).\n(c) Excluded Claims. \"Excluded Claims\" means: (i) a Party’s fraud or willful misconduct; (ii) Contractor’s breach of Section 6 (Confidentiality/Data Protection) or Section 5 (IP ownership/assignment), including Security Incidents caused by Contractor’s failure to maintain required safeguards; (iii) amounts owed under Section 2 (Fees) and statutory remedies for nonpayment where applicable; and (iv) indemnification obligations under Sections 8.1 and 8.2 (to the extent they cover third-party claims).\n(d) Non-Waivable Rights. Nothing in this Agreement limits liability to the extent such limitation is prohibited by applicable law.\n\n8.6 Allocation of Risk. The Parties acknowledge that the limitations of liability reflect the allocation of risk set forth in this Agreement and that, absent such limitations, the Fees would be higher.\n\n8.7 Optional: Attorneys’ Fees for Contract Claims. Except as otherwise required by applicable law (including any mandatory fee-shifting under New York Labor Law Article 44 and/or the NYC Freelance Isn’t Free Act where applicable), in any action between the Parties arising out of this Agreement, the prevailing Party may recover its reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs if {{prevailing_party_fees}} is set to \"yes\"."},{"id":"insurance","type":"optional","order":9,"title":"9. INSURANCE (OPTIONAL)","content":"9.1 Required Coverage (If Applicable). If required by Client in writing or in a SOW, Contractor shall procure and maintain, at its own expense, insurance with carriers reasonably acceptable to Client, which may include:\n(a) Commercial General Liability insurance with limits of not less than {{cgl_limit}} per occurrence and {{cgl_aggregate}} aggregate;\n(b) Professional Liability / Errors & Omissions insurance with limits of not less than {{eo_limit}};\n(c) Cyber/Privacy Liability insurance with limits of not less than {{cyber_limit}}, covering Security Incidents, privacy liability, and data breach response costs;\n(d) Workers’ Compensation insurance as required by New York law (for Contractor’s employees, if any) and Employer’s Liability insurance with limits of not less than {{employers_liability_limit}}; and\n(e) Automobile Liability insurance (if vehicles are used in performance) with limits of not less than {{auto_limit}}.\n\n9.2 Certificates; Additional Insured (If Applicable).\n(a) Upon request, Contractor shall provide certificates of insurance evidencing required coverage.\n(b) If stated in a SOW, Contractor shall name Client as an additional insured on Commercial General Liability and Automobile Liability policies on a primary and non-contributory basis.\n\n9.3 No Limitation. Insurance maintained by Contractor shall not limit Contractor’s obligations or liability under this Agreement.\n\n9.4 Notice of Cancellation. Contractor shall use commercially reasonable efforts to provide Client with advance notice of cancellation or material reduction in coverage when Contractor receives such notice from the insurer."},{"id":"governing_law","type":"standard","order":10,"title":"10. GOVERNING LAW; VENUE; JURISDICTION","content":"10.1 Governing Law. This Agreement, and any dispute arising out of or related to this Agreement, the Services, or the Parties’ relationship, shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of New York, without regard to its conflict of laws principles.\n\n10.2 Exclusive Venue in Specified County. Subject to Section 11.13 (Optional Dispute Resolution) if elected, the Parties consent to the exclusive jurisdiction and venue of the state and federal courts located in {{venue_county}} County, New York, for any action arising out of or related to this Agreement, and each Party waives any objection based on forum non conveniens or improper venue.\n\n10.3 Service of Process. Each Party consents to service of process by (a) personal delivery, (b) nationally recognized overnight courier, (c) certified mail (return receipt requested), or (d) email to the notice addresses in Section 11.2, in each case in accordance with applicable law.\n\n10.4 Injunctive Relief in Aid of Jurisdiction. Notwithstanding Section 10.2, a Party may seek temporary, preliminary, or injunctive relief in any court of competent jurisdiction to prevent imminent harm or preserve the status quo, including for threatened breach of Sections 5 or 6.\n\n10.5 Waiver of Jury Trial. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, EACH PARTY KNOWINGLY AND VOLUNTARILY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION OR PROCEEDING ARISING OUT OF OR RELATED TO THIS AGREEMENT.\n\n10.6 UN Convention Excluded. The United Nations Convention on Contracts for the International Sale of Goods does not apply to this Agreement."},{"id":"general_provisions","type":"standard","order":11,"title":"11. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"11.1 Interpretation.\n(a) Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation.\n(b) \"Including\" means \"including without limitation.\" \"Or\" is not exclusive.\n(c) Any reference to a \"day\" means a calendar day unless expressly stated as a business day.\n\n11.2 Notices.\n(a) Form. Notices under this Agreement must be in writing.\n(b) Delivery Methods. Notices will be deemed given when delivered by (i) personal delivery, (ii) nationally recognized overnight courier, (iii) certified mail (return receipt requested), or (iv) email with confirmation of transmission and no bounceback.\n(c) Notice Addresses. Notices shall be sent to the Parties at the addresses and emails in the signature block (or such other address a Party designates in writing). For billing notices, Contractor shall send to {{invoice_delivery_email}}.\n\n11.3 Entire Agreement; Amendments. This Agreement (together with each executed SOW, change order, and any attachments expressly incorporated) constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties regarding its subject matter and supersedes prior and contemporaneous understandings. Any amendment or waiver must be in a writing signed (including electronically) by both Parties.\n\n11.4 Counterparts; Electronic Signatures. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which is deemed an original. Signatures delivered electronically (including via PDF, click-through, or e-signature platform) are binding and enforceable under the New York Electronic Signatures and Records Act (ESRA) and the federal E-SIGN Act.\n\n11.5 Assignment.\n(a) Contractor may not assign or transfer this Agreement, in whole or in part, without Client’s prior written consent.\n(b) Client may assign this Agreement without Contractor’s consent to an affiliate or in connection with a merger, acquisition, corporate reorganization, or sale of substantially all assets related to this Agreement, provided that such assignee assumes Client’s obligations.\n\n11.6 Subcontractors and Flow-Down.\n(a) Contractor may not use subcontractors to perform Services without Client’s prior written consent, except for administrative or ministerial services that do not involve access to Confidential Information.\n(b) Contractor remains responsible for all acts and omissions of subcontractors and shall ensure subcontractors are bound by written obligations at least as protective as this Agreement, including confidentiality, IP assignment (as applicable), and data protection obligations.\n\n11.7 Non-Solicitation (Optional; New York Scrutiny).\n(a) If {{non_solicit_enabled}} is set to \"yes\", during the Term and for {{non_solicit_months}} months thereafter (or, if blank, twelve (12) months), Contractor shall not, directly and knowingly, solicit for employment any employee of Client with whom Contractor had material interaction through the Services.\n(b) This Section does not prohibit general solicitations not targeted at Client employees.\n(c) The Parties acknowledge that restrictive covenants are subject to heightened scrutiny in New York and agree this provision shall be interpreted narrowly to the extent necessary to be enforceable.\n\n11.8 No Non-Compete Unless Expressly Agreed. The Parties acknowledge that non-compete provisions are disfavored and strictly scrutinized under New York law. Unless the Parties execute a separate, written non-competition agreement that is reasonable in scope, duration, geography, and necessary to protect legitimate business interests, nothing in this Agreement prohibits Contractor from providing services to others, including competitors, subject to Sections 6 (Confidentiality) and 11.9 (Conflicts).\n\n11.9 Publicity; Use of Names (Optional).\n(a) Unless {{publicity_allowed}} is set to \"yes\", neither Party shall issue press releases or public announcements referencing the other Party or the relationship without the other Party’s prior written consent.\n(b) Unless otherwise agreed in writing, Contractor shall not use Client’s name, trademarks, or logos in marketing materials.\n\n11.10 Compliance with Laws; Ethics.\n(a) Each Party shall comply with applicable laws and regulations relating to its performance under this Agreement.\n(b) Without limiting the foregoing, Contractor shall comply with applicable anti-bribery, anti-corruption, and sanctions laws, and shall not offer or provide anything of value to secure an improper advantage on Client’s behalf.\n\n11.11 Independent Development; No Restriction on General Skills. Nothing in this Agreement prevents Contractor from using general skills and experience (so long as Contractor does not use or disclose Client Confidential Information or trade secrets) or from independently developing materials similar to those developed for Client.\n\n11.12 Force Majeure. Neither Party shall be liable for failure or delay in performance (excluding payment obligations) due to events beyond the Party’s reasonable control, including acts of God, natural disasters, terrorism, war, labor disputes, governmental actions, or internet/service provider outages, provided the affected Party uses reasonable efforts to mitigate and resumes performance promptly.\n\n11.13 Optional Dispute Resolution; Preservation of Statutory Rights.\n(a) If {{dispute_resolution_method}} is set to \"mediation\", the Parties shall first attempt in good faith to resolve disputes through non-binding mediation in {{venue_county}} County, New York before filing suit.\n(b) If {{dispute_resolution_method}} is set to \"arbitration\", any dispute shall be resolved by binding arbitration administered by {{arbitration_provider}} in {{venue_county}} County, New York, before a single arbitrator, and judgment on the award may be entered in any court of competent jurisdiction.\n(c) No Waiver of Freelance Worker Protections. Any mediation/arbitration provision is intended to be interpreted in a manner that does not waive or reduce any non-waivable rights or remedies available under New York Labor Law Article 44 and/or, if applicable, the NYC Freelance Isn’t Free Act.\n\n11.14 Severability; Reformation. If any provision of this Agreement is held invalid, illegal, or unenforceable, the remaining provisions remain in full force and effect. To the extent permitted by law, the invalid provision shall be deemed modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it enforceable while preserving the Parties’ intent.\n\n11.15 Waiver. No waiver is effective unless in writing and signed by the waiving Party. A waiver of one breach is not a waiver of any other breach.\n\n11.16 Relationship of the Parties. The Parties are independent contracting parties. Nothing in this Agreement creates a partnership, joint venture, fiduciary relationship, or agency relationship.\n\n11.17 Third-Party Beneficiaries. Except as expressly provided for indemnified parties in Section 8, there are no third-party beneficiaries to this Agreement.\n\n11.18 Further Assurances. Each Party shall execute and deliver such documents and take such actions as may be reasonably necessary to carry out the intent of this Agreement.\n\n11.19 Record Retention (Freelance Worker Protections). Without limiting Section 2.10, to the extent required by New York Labor Law Article 44 and/or the NYC Freelance Isn’t Free Act, Client shall retain a copy of this Agreement and related records for at least six (6) years and shall make such records available to governmental agencies to the extent required by law."},{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":12,"title":"12. DEFINITIONS","content":"12.1 \"Acceptance\" has the meaning set forth in Section 1.2.\n\n12.2 \"Client Materials\" has the meaning set forth in Section 5.1.\n\n12.3 \"Confidential Information\" has the meaning set forth in Section 6.1.\n\n12.4 \"Deliverables\" means the items, outputs, and work product (if any) that Contractor is required to deliver to Client as part of the Services, as specified in {{services_description}} and/or a SOW.\n\n12.5 \"DTSA\" has the meaning set forth in Section 6.1.\n\n12.6 \"Effective Date\" has the meaning set forth in the Preamble.\n\n12.7 \"Freelance Worker\" means, to the extent applicable, a natural person or an organization composed of no more than one natural person that is hired or retained as an independent contractor to provide services in exchange for compensation, as that term is defined under New York Labor Law Article 44 and/or the NYC Freelance Isn’t Free Act, as applicable.\n\n12.8 \"Personal Data\" means any information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked (directly or indirectly) with a particular individual or household, including \"personal information\" and similar terms under applicable U.S. state privacy or breach notification laws, to the extent Contractor processes such information for Client.\n\n12.9 \"Private Information\" means \"private information\" as defined under New York General Business Law § 899-aa and/or § 899-bb, including any combination of an individual’s identifier with certain data elements (e.g., Social Security number, driver’s license number, account credentials) or other covered data, to the extent applicable.\n\n12.10 \"Security Incident\" has the meaning set forth in Section 6.8.\n\n12.11 \"Services\" has the meaning set forth in Section 1.1.\n\n12.12 \"SOW\" means any statement of work, proposal, work order, or similar document describing Services, Deliverables, schedule, and/or Fees that is signed (including electronically) by both Parties and expressly incorporated into this Agreement.\n\n12.13 \"Term\" has the meaning set forth in Section 4.1.\n\n12.14 \"Third-Party Materials\" has the meaning set forth in Section 5.1.\n\n12.15 \"Work Product\" and \"Background Technology\" have the meanings set forth in Section 5.1."}]'::jsonb,
