-- Update: Mutual Non-Disclosure Agreement (New York)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Mutual Non-Disclosure Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date") by and between (i) {{party_a_company}}, with a mailing address of {{party_a_address}} ("Party A" or "{{party_a_name}}"), and (ii) {{party_b_company}}, with a mailing address of {{party_b_address}} ("Party B" or "{{party_b_name}}"). Party A and Party B may be referred to individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties".

Each Party represents that the individual signing this Agreement on its behalf is duly authorized to bind that Party to this Agreement. This Agreement may be executed and delivered by electronic means and electronic signatures in accordance with Section 8.13 (Electronic Signatures; ESRA).',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, the Parties wish to explore a potential business relationship concerning {{purpose}} (the "Purpose");

WHEREAS, in connection with the Purpose, each Party may disclose to the other certain confidential and proprietary information, including information that may constitute Trade Secrets (as defined below);

WHEREAS, the Parties wish to protect such information in accordance with the terms of this Agreement and applicable New York and federal law;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises and covenants contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS","content":"1.1 \"Affiliate\" means, with respect to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with such Party. \"Control\" means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management or policies of an entity, whether through ownership of voting securities, by contract, or otherwise.\n\n1.2 \"Business Day\" means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday, or day on which banks in New York, New York are authorized or required by law to close.\n\n1.3 \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed by or on behalf of a Party (the \"Disclosing Party\") to the other Party (the \"Receiving Party\"), whether disclosed before or after the Effective Date, and whether disclosed in writing, orally, visually, electronically, by inspection of tangible objects, or in any other form, that (a) is designated as confidential or proprietary, (b) is disclosed in circumstances that reasonably indicate it is confidential, or (c) reasonably should be understood to be confidential given the nature of the information or the circumstances of disclosure.\n\n1.4 Confidential Information includes, without limitation: (a) business, strategic, and operational plans; (b) budgets, forecasts, pricing, margins, and financial information; (c) customer, user, and supplier identities and related terms; (d) product roadmaps, requirements, designs, drawings, specifications, and prototypes; (e) research and development, inventions (whether patentable or not), discoveries, and know-how; (f) software (including source code and object code), algorithms, models, datasets, documentation, architecture, and technical roadmaps; (g) information security materials, vulnerability information, penetration test results, and incident reports; (h) marketing plans and analytics; (i) contracts and deal terms; (j) personnel information, compensation information, and organizational information; and (k) all notes, extracts, analyses, summaries, compilations, studies, reports, reproductions, and other materials prepared by the Receiving Party or its Representatives that contain, reflect, or are derived from any Confidential Information (collectively, \"Evaluation Material\").\n\n1.5 \"Disclosing Party\" means the Party disclosing Confidential Information.\n\n1.6 \"Receiving Party\" means the Party receiving Confidential Information.\n\n1.7 \"Representatives\" means, with respect to a Party, such Party and its Affiliates'' directors, officers, employees, agents, consultants, contractors, and professional advisors (including attorneys, accountants, financial advisors, and insurers) who have a bona fide need to know Confidential Information for the Purpose. Representatives also includes potential sources of financing or strategic partners solely to the extent necessary for the Purpose, provided they are bound by written confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those contained in this Agreement.\n\n1.8 \"Permitted Purpose\" means the Purpose stated in the Recitals and any activities reasonably necessary to evaluate, negotiate, and (if agreed) implement a transaction or relationship consistent with such Purpose.\n\n1.9 \"Trade Secret\" means information that qualifies as a trade secret under applicable law, including New York common law and/or the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act of 2016 (18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq.) (\"DTSA\"). Trade Secrets are included within Confidential Information.\n\n1.10 \"Personal Data\" means information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked (directly or indirectly) to an identified or identifiable natural person. Personal Data includes \"private information\" as defined under New York General Business Law § 899-aa to the extent applicable.\n\n1.11 \"Sensitive Data\" means (a) Social Security numbers, driver’s license numbers, non-driver identification card numbers, passport numbers, financial account numbers (with or without access codes), biometric information, medical information, health insurance information, and account credentials; (b) any information defined as \"private information\" under New York General Business Law § 899-aa; and (c) any other information subject to heightened protection under applicable law (including, as applicable, GLBA, HIPAA, FERPA, and the NYDFS Cybersecurity Regulation (23 NYCRR Part 500)).\n\n1.12 \"NYC Freelance Isn''t Free Act\" or \"FIFA\" means, as applicable, (a) NYC Administrative Code § 20-927 et seq., and/or (b) New York Labor Law Article 44 (Freelance Isn''t Free Act), as amended from time to time.\n\n1.13 \"Work Product\" means any deliverables, work product, inventions, discoveries, developments, works of authorship, designs, documentation, reports, materials, or other outputs created by or for a Party in connection with the Purpose.\n\n1.14 \"Residuals\" means information that is retained in the unaided memory of a Receiving Party’s Representatives who have had access to Confidential Information, provided that such Representatives have not intentionally memorized such information for the purpose of circumventing this Agreement. \"Unaided memory\" means without reference to notes, documents, electronic files, or other tangible embodiments of Confidential Information.\n\n1.15 \"Including\" means including without limitation, and terms such as \"include\" and \"includes\" shall be construed accordingly."},{"id":"confidentiality_obligations","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. CONFIDENTIALITY OBLIGATIONS","content":"2.1 Use Restriction. The Receiving Party shall use the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information solely for the Permitted Purpose and shall not use Confidential Information for any other purpose, including without limitation to compete with the Disclosing Party, to solicit the Disclosing Party’s customers or employees, to reverse engineer products or services, or to develop or improve competing products or services.\n\n2.2 Non-Disclosure. The Receiving Party shall not disclose the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information to any person or entity except to its Representatives who (a) have a need to know such Confidential Information for the Permitted Purpose, and (b) are bound by written confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those contained in this Agreement. The Receiving Party is responsible for any breach of this Agreement by its Representatives.\n\n2.3 Standard of Care. The Receiving Party shall protect the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information using at least the same degree of care it uses to protect its own confidential information of a similar sensitivity and importance, but in no event less than a reasonable standard of care.\n\n2.4 Need-to-Know; Minimization. The Receiving Party shall limit access to Confidential Information to those Representatives who satisfy Section 2.2. The Receiving Party shall take reasonable steps to minimize the amount of Confidential Information disclosed or copied to the extent consistent with the Permitted Purpose.\n\n2.5 Security Measures. The Receiving Party shall maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards designed to (a) protect the confidentiality and integrity of Confidential Information, (b) prevent unauthorized access, use, disclosure, alteration, or destruction, and (c) comply with applicable data security requirements, including, to the extent applicable, the New York SHIELD Act (General Business Law § 899-bb) and industry-standard practices. Such safeguards shall include, where appropriate to the nature of the Confidential Information: access controls, authentication, encryption in transit and at rest, secure disposal, logging/monitoring, and security awareness measures.\n\n2.6 No Reverse Engineering; No Circumvention. Except to the extent expressly permitted in a separate written agreement signed by the Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party shall not (and shall not permit Representatives to) disassemble, decompile, or reverse engineer any prototypes, samples, software, or other tangible embodiments of Confidential Information. The Receiving Party shall not circumvent or bypass any access controls, technical protections, or usage restrictions applied to Confidential Information.\n\n2.7 Compelled Disclosure.\n(a) If the Receiving Party is required by law, regulation, court order, subpoena, civil investigative demand, governmental request, or other legal process to disclose any Confidential Information (each, a \"Legal Demand\"), the Receiving Party shall, to the extent legally permitted, provide the Disclosing Party with prompt written notice of the Legal Demand sufficient to allow the Disclosing Party to seek a protective order or other appropriate remedy.\n(b) The Receiving Party shall reasonably cooperate, at the Disclosing Party’s expense, with the Disclosing Party’s efforts to obtain a protective order or other confidential treatment.\n(c) If disclosure is nonetheless required, the Receiving Party shall disclose only that portion of the Confidential Information that is legally required and shall use commercially reasonable efforts to ensure confidential treatment for any disclosed Confidential Information.\n\n2.8 Control of Copies; Markings. The Receiving Party may reproduce Confidential Information only as necessary for the Permitted Purpose and shall reproduce any confidentiality legends or markings contained in the original, where practicable.\n\n2.9 Notice of Unauthorized Access or Disclosure. The Receiving Party shall promptly (and in any event within {{security_notice_hours}} hours after becoming aware) notify the Disclosing Party in writing of any unauthorized access, use, acquisition, or disclosure of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information (a \"Security Incident\") and shall (a) take reasonable steps to contain and remediate the Security Incident, (b) cooperate with the Disclosing Party’s reasonable requests regarding investigation and mitigation, and (c) not make any legally required notifications that reference the Disclosing Party without the Disclosing Party’s prior consent, except where prohibited by law.\n\n2.10 Residuals. Unless the Parties initial or otherwise indicate in writing that this Section 2.10 applies (\"Residuals Allowed\"), no Residuals rights are granted. If Residuals Allowed, the Receiving Party may use Residuals for internal purposes, provided that the Receiving Party does not knowingly use Residuals to recreate or replicate the Disclosing Party’s Trade Secrets, and provided further that this Section 2.10 does not grant the Receiving Party any license under the Disclosing Party’s intellectual property rights.\n\n2.11 Trade Secret Protection Preserved. The Parties acknowledge that New York provides trade secret protections under common law and that the DTSA provides federal civil remedies for misappropriation. Nothing in this Agreement limits any rights or remedies available to the Disclosing Party under applicable law, subject to the limitations expressly stated herein."},{"id":"exclusions","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. EXCLUSIONS FROM CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION","content":"3.1 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by contemporaneous written records or other competent evidence:\n(a) is or becomes publicly available through no breach of this Agreement by the Receiving Party or its Representatives;\n(b) was lawfully in the Receiving Party’s possession, without restriction on disclosure, prior to disclosure by the Disclosing Party;\n(c) is lawfully received by the Receiving Party from a third party who, to the Receiving Party’s knowledge after reasonable inquiry, is not under an obligation of confidentiality with respect to such information;\n(d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information; or\n(e) is approved for release in writing by the Disclosing Party.\n\n3.2 Combination; Burden of Proof. Information shall not be deemed within an exclusion merely because individual elements are publicly available. A combination of features, data, or components will be considered Confidential Information if the combination itself is non-public and confers actual or potential economic value or competitive advantage.\n\n3.3 No Implied Exclusion. The Receiving Party’s general knowledge, skills, and experience (including knowledge gained in the ordinary course of employment) do not, by themselves, create an exclusion for specific Confidential Information or Trade Secrets of the Disclosing Party."},{"id":"term_and_duration","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TERM AND DURATION","content":"4.1 Term. This Agreement shall commence on the Effective Date and shall continue until the earlier of: (a) {{expiration_date}}, or (b) termination by either Party upon {{notice_period}} days’ written notice to the other Party (the \"Term\").\n\n4.2 Survival of Obligations. Except as set forth in Section 4.3, the Receiving Party’s obligations under this Agreement with respect to Confidential Information disclosed during the Term shall survive expiration or termination for a period of {{confidentiality_period}} years from the date of disclosure of the applicable Confidential Information.\n\n4.3 Trade Secrets. Notwithstanding Section 4.2, the Receiving Party’s obligations with respect to any Trade Secret shall continue for so long as such information remains a Trade Secret under applicable law.\n\n4.4 No Effect on Other Agreements. Termination or expiration of this Agreement shall not relieve either Party of obligations under any other written agreement between the Parties that governs confidentiality, intellectual property, services, or other matters, to the extent applicable.\n\n4.5 Suspension of Disclosures. Either Party may, at any time, elect to stop further disclosures of Confidential Information without terminating this Agreement."},{"id":"return_of_information","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. RETURN OR DESTRUCTION OF INFORMATION","content":"5.1 Return/Destruction. Upon the written request of the Disclosing Party or upon termination of this Agreement, the Receiving Party shall promptly (and in any event within {{return_destroy_days}} days) return to the Disclosing Party or destroy (at the Disclosing Party’s election) all Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party in the Receiving Party’s possession or control, including all Evaluation Material, copies, summaries, extracts, and other derivatives, whether in hard copy or electronic form.\n\n5.2 Certification. Upon request, the Receiving Party shall certify in writing, signed by an authorized representative, that it has complied with Section 5.1; provided that the Receiving Party is not required to identify privileged information or disclose attorney work product.\n\n5.3 Archival Copies; System Backups. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Receiving Party may retain Confidential Information (a) to the extent required by applicable law, regulation, or bona fide internal compliance obligations, or (b) in routine, automated system backups that are not reasonably accessible in the ordinary course, provided that (i) any retained information remains subject to this Agreement, (ii) such backups are not restored for the purpose of accessing Confidential Information, and (iii) the Receiving Party deletes such Confidential Information from backups in accordance with its ordinary backup lifecycle.\n\n5.4 Return of Tangible Items. The Receiving Party shall return or destroy, as directed, all tangible objects embodying Confidential Information (including prototypes, devices, hardware, samples, and media). If destruction is elected, destruction shall be performed in a manner reasonably designed to prevent reconstruction.\n\n5.5 Litigation Hold. If the Receiving Party is required to preserve information under a legal hold, regulatory requirement, or court order, the Receiving Party may retain the minimum necessary Confidential Information for that purpose, subject to continued confidentiality and restricted access."},{"id":"remedies","type":"negotiable","order":6,"title":"6. REMEDIES","content":"6.1 Injunctive and Equitable Relief. Each Party acknowledges that any unauthorized use or disclosure of Confidential Information or Trade Secrets may cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be inadequate. Accordingly, the Disclosing Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive or other equitable relief in any court of competent jurisdiction, without the requirement to prove actual damages and without posting a bond or other security to the maximum extent permitted by New York law.\n\n6.2 Monetary Damages; Accounting. In addition to equitable relief, the Disclosing Party may seek all damages available at law or in equity, including direct damages and, to the extent permitted by law, recovery based on unjust enrichment and/or an accounting of profits attributable to the breach.\n\n6.3 Attorneys’ Fees and Costs. In any action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the prevailing party shall be entitled to recover its reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs if (and only to the extent) such recovery is permitted by applicable law, court rule, or contract.\n\n6.4 DTSA Whistleblower Immunity Notice (Required Notice). Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b): (a) An individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that is made (i) in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (ii) in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal. (b) An individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding, if the individual (i) files any document containing the trade secret under seal, and (ii) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order.\n\n6.5 Remedies Cumulative. All rights and remedies of a Party under this Agreement are cumulative and in addition to any other rights and remedies available at law or in equity."},{"id":"governing_law","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. GOVERNING LAW AND VENUE","content":"7.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and any dispute, claim, or controversy arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the Confidential Information, or the Permitted Purpose shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of New York, without regard to conflict of laws principles that would apply the law of another jurisdiction.\n\n7.2 Exclusive Venue. Except as set forth in Section 7.3, the Parties irrevocably consent to exclusive jurisdiction and venue in the state and federal courts located in {{venue_county}} County, New York, and waive any objection based on forum non conveniens or improper venue.\n\n7.3 Injunctive Relief Carve-Out. Notwithstanding Section 7.2, either Party may seek temporary, preliminary, or permanent injunctive or other equitable relief in any court of competent jurisdiction to prevent or remedy actual or threatened misappropriation of Trade Secrets or unauthorized disclosure of Confidential Information.\n\n7.4 Waiver of Jury Trial. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, EACH PARTY KNOWINGLY, VOLUNTARILY, AND INTENTIONALLY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION OR PROCEEDING ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT."},{"id":"general_provisions","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"8.1 Notices.\n(a) Form. All notices, demands, approvals, consents, waivers, and other communications under this Agreement (each, a \"Notice\") must be in writing.\n(b) Delivery Methods. Notices shall be deemed duly given when (i) delivered personally, (ii) sent by nationally recognized overnight courier with tracking, (iii) mailed by certified or registered mail (return receipt requested, postage prepaid), or (iv) sent by email to the addresses below with confirmation of transmission (excluding out-of-office replies), provided that Notices of breach, termination, or legal process shall also be sent by one of the methods in (i)-(iii).\n(c) Notice Addresses. Notices shall be sent to the contacts set forth in the signature block (or to any updated contact provided by Notice).\n\n8.2 No License; Ownership.\n(a) All Confidential Information remains the property of the Disclosing Party. As between the Parties, the Disclosing Party retains all right, title, and interest in and to its Confidential Information and any intellectual property embodied therein.\n(b) No rights are granted by this Agreement, whether by license, estoppel, implication, or otherwise, except the limited right to use Confidential Information solely for the Permitted Purpose.\n\n8.3 No Obligation to Proceed; No Exclusivity. This Agreement does not obligate either Party to (a) disclose any Confidential Information, (b) enter into any transaction, engagement, or other relationship, or (c) proceed with discussions or negotiations. Unless expressly stated in a separate written agreement, nothing in this Agreement creates exclusivity.\n\n8.4 No Warranty. ALL CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION IS PROVIDED \"AS IS\". THE DISCLOSING PARTY MAKES NO REPRESENTATION OR WARRANTY, EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, AS TO THE ACCURACY, COMPLETENESS, MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR NON-INFRINGEMENT OF ANY CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION, EXCEPT THAT THE DISCLOSING PARTY WARRANTS IT HAS THE RIGHT TO DISCLOSE THE CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION AS CONTEMPLATED HEREIN.\n\n8.5 No Partnership; No Agency. Nothing in this Agreement creates any partnership, joint venture, fiduciary, employment, or agency relationship between the Parties. Neither Party has authority to bind the other Party.\n\n8.6 Compliance With Law; Export Controls. Each Party shall comply with applicable laws and regulations in connection with its performance under this Agreement, including applicable U.S. export control and sanctions laws. The Receiving Party shall not export, re-export, or transfer Confidential Information in violation of law.\n\n8.7 Publicity. Neither Party shall issue press releases or public statements or otherwise disclose the existence or the terms of this Agreement, the fact that discussions are occurring, or the identity of the other Party (including use of names, marks, or logos) without the other Party’s prior written consent, except as required by law or regulation.\n\n8.8 Securities and Regulatory Disclosures; Martin Act Considerations.\n(a) No Offer or Sale of Securities. The Parties acknowledge that the exchange of Confidential Information may include business and financial information. Nothing in this Agreement constitutes an offer to sell, solicitation of an offer to buy, or recommendation with respect to any security.\n(b) No Reliance for Investment Decisions. Each Party agrees it will not rely on Confidential Information as the sole basis for any investment decision, and will perform its own independent investigation and diligence.\n(c) Required Disclosures. Nothing in this Agreement prohibits a Party from making disclosures required under applicable securities laws, regulations, or self-regulatory organization rules (including SEC or FINRA rules). Where legally permitted, the disclosing Party shall provide notice consistent with Section 2.7.\n(d) No Limitation of Enforcement. Nothing herein is intended to limit the application of the New York Martin Act (General Business Law Article 23-A) or other applicable securities laws.\n\n8.9 No Restrictive Covenant Implied. The Parties acknowledge that restrictive covenants (including non-competition provisions) are disfavored and strictly scrutinized under New York law. This Agreement is intended solely to protect Confidential Information and Trade Secrets, and does not restrict either Party from engaging in lawful competition, except as expressly provided herein with respect to the use and disclosure of Confidential Information.\n\n8.10 Non-Disparagement (Optional). If the Parties elect in writing to include non-disparagement, each Party shall refrain from making false statements of fact that are reasonably likely to harm the other Party’s reputation in connection with the Purpose. This Section 8.10 shall not restrict truthful statements required by law, subpoena, court order, or to governmental authorities.\n\n8.11 Severability; Blue Pencil. If any provision of this Agreement is held to be invalid, illegal, or unenforceable, the Parties intend that such provision be enforced to the maximum extent permitted under applicable law. The court may modify (or \"blue pencil\") such provision to the minimum extent necessary to make it enforceable, and the remaining provisions shall continue in full force and effect.\n\n8.12 Waiver. No failure or delay by a Party in exercising any right, power, or remedy under this Agreement shall operate as a waiver. Any waiver must be in a writing signed by the Party granting the waiver and shall be effective only as to the specific instance and purpose stated.\n\n8.13 Electronic Signatures; ESRA. This Agreement may be executed and delivered by electronic means (including PDF, electronic signature platform, or other electronic records). Electronic signatures and records shall be valid and enforceable under the New York Electronic Signatures and Records Act (State Technology Law Article 3) and the federal Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (E-SIGN).\n\n8.14 Assignment. Neither Party may assign or transfer this Agreement, in whole or in part, without the prior written consent of the other Party, except that either Party may assign this Agreement without consent to an Affiliate or to a successor in interest in connection with a merger, acquisition, reorganization, or sale of all or substantially all of its assets, provided that the assignee agrees in writing to be bound by this Agreement.\n\n8.15 Entire Agreement; Amendments. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties with respect to its subject matter and supersedes all prior or contemporaneous agreements, understandings, negotiations, and discussions, whether oral or written, regarding such subject matter. No amendment or modification shall be effective unless in writing and signed by both Parties.\n\n8.16 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which shall be deemed an original, and all of which together shall constitute one instrument.\n\n8.17 Headings; Interpretation. Headings are for convenience only and shall not affect interpretation. This Agreement shall be construed as jointly drafted by the Parties and no presumption shall arise favoring or disfavoring any Party by virtue of authorship.\n\n8.18 Taxes. Each Party is responsible for its own federal, state, and local taxes (including, where applicable, New York State and New York City income taxes) arising from its operations and obligations, and nothing in this Agreement shall be construed as tax advice or as allocating tax responsibilities except as expressly stated in a separate written agreement."},{"id":"non_solicitation","type":"optional","order":9,"title":"9. NON-SOLICITATION (OPTIONAL)","content":"9.1 Optional Election. This Section 9 applies only if the Parties expressly elect it in writing (including by initialing this Section or stating \"Non-Solicitation Applies\" in an addendum).\n\n9.2 Non-Solicitation of Employees and Contractors. During the term of this Agreement and for {{non_solicitation_period}} months thereafter, neither Party shall, directly or indirectly, solicit for employment or engagement any employee or individual independent contractor of the other Party with whom the soliciting Party had material contact through the Permitted Purpose or who was identified through the other Party’s Confidential Information.\n\n9.3 Carve-Outs. Section 9.2 shall not prohibit: (a) general solicitations not specifically targeted at the other Party’s personnel (including generalized advertisements, job postings, or recruiter outreach not directed at such personnel), (b) hiring of an individual who responds to such general solicitation without targeted encouragement, or (c) solicitations or hires occurring with the other Party’s prior written consent.\n\n9.4 Reasonableness; Narrow Construction. The Parties acknowledge that this Section 9 is intended to be narrowly tailored to protect legitimate business interests and not to impose an unreasonable restraint of trade under New York law. If any portion is found unenforceable, it shall be modified to the minimum extent necessary to be enforceable.\n\n9.5 No Non-Compete. For the avoidance of doubt, this Section 9 does not restrict either Party from competing with the other Party, provided that it complies with this Agreement’s confidentiality obligations."},{"id":"privacy_data_security","type":"standard","order":10,"title":"10. PRIVACY; DATA PROTECTION; CYBERSECURITY","content":"10.1 Scope. This Section 10 applies to the extent Confidential Information includes Personal Data or Sensitive Data.\n\n10.2 Role of the Parties. Unless otherwise agreed in writing, each Party is an independent controller/business with respect to any Personal Data it discloses and shall disclose only such Personal Data as is reasonably necessary for the Permitted Purpose.\n\n10.3 Safeguards. In addition to Section 2.5, the Receiving Party shall implement and maintain a written information security program containing reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards appropriate to the nature of the Personal Data and Sensitive Data, and designed to: (a) protect against unauthorized access, use, modification, disclosure, or destruction; and (b) meet applicable requirements under New York law, including the SHIELD Act (General Business Law § 899-bb), as applicable.\n\n10.4 Prohibited Data; Minimization. Unless the Parties agree otherwise in writing, neither Party shall disclose Sensitive Data to the other Party. If Sensitive Data must be disclosed for the Permitted Purpose, the Parties shall agree in writing on additional safeguards, transmission methods, and access restrictions.\n\n10.5 Breach Notification and Cooperation. If a Security Incident involves Personal Data or Sensitive Data, the Receiving Party shall: (a) provide notice as required by Section 2.9; (b) cooperate with the Disclosing Party to assess legal obligations under New York General Business Law § 899-aa and other applicable laws; (c) provide reasonable information relating to the nature and scope of the incident, the affected data elements (to the extent known), and remediation actions; and (d) preserve evidence and logs to the extent reasonably necessary for investigation and compliance.\n\n10.6 Cross-Border Transfers. The Receiving Party shall not transfer Personal Data across national borders in a manner that violates applicable law. If cross-border transfer is necessary, the Parties shall implement appropriate safeguards.\n\n10.7 Subprocessors and Third Parties. The Receiving Party shall not provide Personal Data received from the Disclosing Party to third parties except to Representatives permitted under this Agreement and subject to confidentiality and security obligations at least as protective as those in this Agreement.\n\n10.8 Data Subject Requests. If the Receiving Party receives a request from an individual or regulator relating to Personal Data disclosed under this Agreement (e.g., access, deletion, or inquiry), the Receiving Party shall, to the extent legally permitted, promptly notify the Disclosing Party and reasonably cooperate with the Disclosing Party’s response.\n\n10.9 No HIPAA/GLBA/23 NYCRR 500 Undertaking Unless Agreed. Unless expressly agreed in a separate written agreement (e.g., a business associate agreement, customer security addendum, or data processing addendum), this Agreement does not impose HIPAA business associate obligations, GLBA service provider obligations, or NYDFS 23 NYCRR Part 500 obligations; provided that each Party remains responsible for compliance with laws applicable to it.\n\n10.10 Survival. The obligations in this Section 10 shall survive termination or expiration of this Agreement for so long as the Receiving Party retains Personal Data or Sensitive Data of the Disclosing Party."},{"id":"freelance_isnt_free","type":"optional","order":11,"title":"11. FREELANCE ISN''T FREE ACT; INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR; RECORDS (OPTIONAL)","content":"11.1 Applicability; Optional Addendum. This Section 11 applies only if (a) one Party (the \"Hiring Party\") retains the other Party or its personnel as a freelance worker/independent contractor to perform services in connection with the Permitted Purpose, and (b) such engagement is covered by the NYC Freelance Isn''t Free Act or New York Labor Law Article 44 (as applicable). The Parties may document such engagement in a separate statement of work or addendum (an \"Engagement Addendum\").\n\n11.2 Written Terms (FIFA). If applicable, the Engagement Addendum shall include, at minimum, the information required by FIFA, which may include: (a) the Parties’ legal names and mailing addresses; (b) an itemization and description of services; (c) the value of services and the rate and method of compensation; and (d) the date on which payment is due or the mechanism by which such date will be determined.\n\n11.3 Payment Timing; Default Rule. If FIFA applies and the Parties do not specify a payment due date in the Engagement Addendum, the Hiring Party shall pay the freelance worker no later than thirty (30) days after completion of the services. If a payment due date is specified, payment shall be made on or before such date.\n\n11.4 Late Payment; Statutory Remedies. The Parties acknowledge that FIFA may provide for statutory remedies for late payment (which may include double damages, attorneys’ fees, and costs) and that nothing in this Agreement is intended to waive or limit any non-waivable rights under FIFA.\n\n11.5 No Retaliation. The Hiring Party shall not retaliate against a freelance worker for exercising rights under FIFA, including requesting a written contract or timely payment, or for filing a complaint.\n\n11.6 Records Retention. To the extent required by FIFA, the Hiring Party shall retain records relating to the engagement for at least six (6) years (or such longer period as required by law). The Parties may satisfy this requirement by retaining executed electronic records in compliance with ESRA.\n\n11.7 Worker Classification; No Employment Created. Unless expressly agreed otherwise in a separate written agreement, nothing in this Agreement creates an employment relationship. Each Party is solely responsible for its own tax reporting and withholding obligations, and for compliance with applicable federal, state, and local labor and employment laws, including New York Labor Law provisions governing worker classification.\n\n11.8 Priority. In the event of conflict between this Agreement and an Engagement Addendum regarding payment or work terms governed by FIFA, the Engagement Addendum shall control with respect to those payment/work terms, and this Agreement shall control with respect to confidentiality unless expressly stated otherwise."},{"id":"restrictive_covenants_notice","type":"optional","order":12,"title":"12. RESTRICTIVE COVENANTS; NO NON-COMPETE (NEW YORK NOTICE)","content":"12.1 Intent. The Parties acknowledge and agree that this Agreement is a confidentiality agreement and is not intended to restrict lawful competition. Any restrictions herein are limited to the use and disclosure of Confidential Information and protection of Trade Secrets.\n\n12.2 No Non-Compete. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed to prohibit either Party, its Affiliates, or Representatives from engaging in any lawful business activities, including activities that may be competitive, provided that such activities do not involve use or disclosure of the other Party’s Confidential Information in violation of this Agreement.\n\n12.3 Optional Narrowly Tailored Restrictions. If the Parties include any additional restrictive covenants (such as non-solicitation under Section 9), the Parties intend such restrictions to be narrowly tailored in duration, geography (if applicable), and scope, and to protect legitimate business interests recognized under New York law (including protection of Trade Secrets and Confidential Information).\n\n12.4 Construction. If any restrictive covenant is determined to be overbroad or unenforceable, it shall be enforced only to the extent permitted by applicable law and modified to the minimum extent necessary to be enforceable.\n\n12.5 No Waiver of Employee Mobility Rights. Nothing in this Agreement is intended to interfere with lawful employee mobility or to restrict any person from reporting suspected unlawful conduct as permitted by law, including under the DTSA whistleblower immunity provisions set forth in Section 6.4."}]'::jsonb,
