-- Update: One-Way Non-Disclosure Agreement (New York)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This One-Way Non-Disclosure Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between (i) {{party_a_company}}, with a mailing address of {{party_a_address}} (the "Disclosing Party" and, if applicable under Clause 9, the "Hiring Party") and (ii) {{party_b_company}}, with a mailing address of {{party_b_address}} (the "Receiving Party" and, if applicable under Clause 9, the "Freelance Worker"). The Disclosing Party and the Receiving Party may be referred to herein individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties."',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, the Disclosing Party possesses Confidential Information (as defined below), including information that may constitute Trade Secrets under New York common law and/or the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act of 2016, that the Disclosing Party wishes to disclose to the Receiving Party in connection with {{purpose}} (the "Purpose");

WHEREAS, the Receiving Party desires to receive such Confidential Information for the Purpose and agrees to protect and restrict the use and disclosure of the Confidential Information in accordance with this Agreement and applicable law, including New York law;

WHEREAS, the Parties intend that this Agreement will (a) facilitate candid discussions and/or evaluation activities related to the Purpose, and (b) define the Parties’ respective rights and obligations with respect to Confidential Information;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises and covenants contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS","content":"1.1 \"Affiliate\" means, with respect to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly Controls, is Controlled by, or is under common Control with that Party. \"Control\" means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct the management or policies of an entity, whether through ownership of voting securities, by contract, or otherwise.\n\n1.2 \"Business Day\" means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday, or day on which banks located in the State of New York are authorized or required by law to close.\n\n1.3 \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information or material disclosed or made available by or on behalf of the Disclosing Party to the Receiving Party or its Representatives, whether before or after the Effective Date, in any form (including oral, written, visual, electronic, digital, machine-readable, or tangible), that: (a) is designated as confidential or proprietary at the time of disclosure; (b) is disclosed under circumstances that reasonably indicate it is confidential; or (c) by its nature or the context of disclosure reasonably should be understood to be confidential.\n\n1.4 Confidential Information includes, without limitation, information relating to: (a) the Disclosing Party’s business, operations, strategies, plans, budgets, forecasts, pricing, costs, margins, and financial information; (b) products and services, roadmaps, prototypes, designs, inventions, discoveries, specifications, processes, methods, formulas, models, source code, object code, software, firmware, architectures, algorithms, documentation, and research and development; (c) customers, prospective customers, vendors, suppliers, partners, and pipeline information; (d) marketing, advertising, branding, and go-to-market strategies; (e) personnel information, organizational structure, compensation structures, and hiring plans (subject to applicable law and Clause 2.11); (f) legal affairs, litigation, compliance matters, and regulatory communications; (g) the existence and terms of this Agreement and the fact and substance of discussions between the Parties relating to the Purpose, except as required by law; and (h) any analyses, compilations, studies, notes, summaries, interpretations, derivatives, or other materials prepared by or for the Receiving Party that contain, reflect, or are based upon Confidential Information (collectively, \"Derived Materials\").\n\n1.5 \"Trade Secret\" means information that qualifies as a trade secret under applicable law, including New York common law (including, without limitation, information that derives independent economic value, actual or potential, from not being generally known and that is subject to reasonable efforts to maintain its secrecy) and, where applicable, the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act, 18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq. Trade Secrets are a subset of Confidential Information.\n\n1.6 \"Evaluation Material\" means Confidential Information and Derived Materials, and any other information furnished by the Disclosing Party or its Representatives to the Receiving Party or its Representatives in connection with the Purpose.\n\n1.7 \"Personal Data\" means information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked, directly or indirectly, with an identified or identifiable natural person, including where applicable \"private information\" as defined under New York General Business Law § 899-aa and related laws. Personal Data may be Confidential Information.\n\n1.8 \"Representatives\" means, with respect to the Receiving Party, its and its Affiliates’ directors, officers, employees, agents, independent contractors, subcontractors, consultants, attorneys, accountants, and other professional advisors, in each case who (a) have a bona fide need to know Confidential Information for the Purpose, and (b) are bound by written confidentiality and non-use obligations at least as protective as those set forth in this Agreement (or, for professional advisors, by ethical or professional duties of confidentiality).\n\n1.9 \"Permitted Use\" means use of Confidential Information strictly and solely to evaluate, discuss, or carry out the Purpose, and for no other purpose.\n\n1.10 \"Law\" means any applicable federal, state, or local law, statute, regulation, rule, ordinance, directive, or order, including any guidance having the force of law, and any requirement of any governmental, regulatory, judicial, or self-regulatory authority.\n\n1.11 \"Disclose\" and \"Disclosure\" include any transfer, dissemination, publication, release, communication, transmission, display, inspection, access, or other making available of Confidential Information, whether intentional or unintentional.\n\n1.12 \"Security Incident\" means any actual or reasonably suspected (a) unauthorized access to or acquisition of Confidential Information or Personal Data; (b) unauthorized use, disclosure, alteration, loss, or destruction of Confidential Information; or (c) material compromise of the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of systems storing or processing Confidential Information.\n\n1.13 \"Work Product\" means any deliverables, materials, inventions, works of authorship, documentation, code, analyses, reports, or other outputs created by the Receiving Party specifically for the Disclosing Party in connection with the Purpose, if any. Unless the Parties execute a separate written agreement addressing ownership, Work Product is not automatically included within Confidential Information solely by virtue of creation; however, Work Product may contain or reflect Confidential Information.\n\n1.14 \"Prohibited Securities Use\" means buying, selling, recommending, or otherwise trading (or tipping others to trade) in any security (including equity, debt, options, or derivatives) while in possession of material nonpublic information, or in violation of applicable securities laws (including, as applicable, the federal securities laws and New York’s Martin Act (General Business Law Article 23-A)).\n\n1.15 \"NYC Freelance Isn’t Free Act\" or \"FIFAA\" refers collectively to NYC Administrative Code § 20-927 et seq. and New York Labor Law Article 44 (Freelance Worker Protection Act), as applicable.\n\n1.16 \"Electronic Signature\" has the meaning under the New York Electronic Signatures and Records Act (\"ESRA\"), State Technology Law § 301 et seq., and includes an electronic sound, symbol, or process attached to or logically associated with a record and executed or adopted by a person with intent to sign the record."},{"id":"confidentiality_obligations","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. CONFIDENTIALITY OBLIGATIONS","content":"2.1 Permitted Use; No Other Use. The Receiving Party shall use the Confidential Information solely for the Permitted Use and shall not use the Confidential Information for any other purpose, including without limitation: (a) to compete with the Disclosing Party; (b) to circumvent the Disclosing Party in dealings with any customer, prospective customer, vendor, supplier, or other business relationship of the Disclosing Party; (c) for any personal benefit; or (d) for any unlawful purpose.\n\n2.2 Non-Disclosure. The Receiving Party shall not Disclose any Confidential Information to any person or entity except to its Representatives who have a need to know for the Purpose and who are subject to confidentiality obligations as set forth in this Agreement.\n\n2.3 Responsibility for Representatives. The Receiving Party shall be responsible for any breach of this Agreement by its Representatives. The Receiving Party shall ensure that access to Confidential Information is limited to those Representatives who require access for the Purpose.\n\n2.4 Standard of Care. The Receiving Party shall protect Confidential Information using at least the same degree of care it uses to protect its own confidential information of a similar nature, but in no event less than reasonable care.\n\n2.5 Security Safeguards.\n(a) The Receiving Party shall maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards designed to protect Confidential Information against unauthorized access, acquisition, disclosure, alteration, or destruction, and to comply with applicable Law, including, where applicable, the New York SHIELD Act requirements for reasonable data security safeguards.\n(b) Without limiting the foregoing, the Receiving Party shall, as appropriate to the nature of the Confidential Information: implement access controls; use strong authentication; apply encryption in transit and, where appropriate, at rest; maintain malware protection; keep systems reasonably up to date with security patches; and maintain reasonable logging and monitoring.\n\n2.6 Copying; Minimization. The Receiving Party shall not copy, reproduce, or summarize Confidential Information except to the extent reasonably necessary for the Purpose. The Receiving Party shall use reasonable efforts to minimize the amount of Confidential Information stored and the number of locations where Confidential Information is stored.\n\n2.7 No Reverse Engineering; No Decompilation. Except to the extent expressly permitted by applicable Law that cannot be waived by contract, the Receiving Party shall not, and shall not permit any third party to, (a) reverse engineer, decompile, disassemble, or otherwise attempt to derive the composition, source code, underlying ideas, structure, or algorithms of any prototypes, software, models, samples, or other tangible embodiments of Confidential Information; or (b) analyze Confidential Information for the purpose of creating competing products or services.\n\n2.8 Marking and Oral Disclosures.\n(a) The Disclosing Party may mark written or tangible Confidential Information as \"Confidential\" or \"Proprietary\"; however, failure to mark does not negate confidentiality if the information otherwise meets the definition of Confidential Information.\n(b) For oral disclosures, the Disclosing Party may identify the information as confidential at the time of disclosure and, if reasonably practicable, summarize or confirm the confidential nature of the oral disclosure in writing within a reasonable period.\n\n2.9 Compelled Disclosure.\n(a) If the Receiving Party or any of its Representatives is required by Law, subpoena, court order, discovery request, governmental demand, or similar legal process to Disclose any Confidential Information (a \"Legal Demand\"), the Receiving Party shall, to the extent legally permitted, provide the Disclosing Party with prompt written notice of the Legal Demand, including sufficient information to allow the Disclosing Party to seek a protective order or other remedy.\n(b) The Receiving Party shall reasonably cooperate, at the Disclosing Party’s expense, with the Disclosing Party’s efforts to obtain confidential treatment for the Confidential Information.\n(c) If Disclosure is ultimately required, the Receiving Party shall disclose only that portion of the Confidential Information that is legally required to be disclosed and shall use reasonable efforts to ensure that such disclosed Confidential Information is accorded confidential treatment.\n\n2.10 Security Incidents.\n(a) The Receiving Party shall notify the Disclosing Party in writing without undue delay, and in any event within {{security_incident_notice_hours}} hours after becoming aware of a Security Incident involving the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.\n(b) The Receiving Party shall (i) take reasonable steps to contain and remediate the Security Incident; (ii) provide reasonable information regarding the nature and scope of the Security Incident as it becomes available; (iii) cooperate with the Disclosing Party in investigating and responding to the Security Incident; and (iv) not notify any third party (including any governmental authority or affected individuals) regarding the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information without the Disclosing Party’s prior written consent, except to the extent required by Law.\n(c) This Clause 2.10 does not limit any obligations that may exist under applicable data breach notification Laws.\n\n2.11 Protected Disclosures; Employee Rights; No Restriction on Lawful Activity.\n(a) Nothing in this Agreement prohibits or restricts the Receiving Party from: (i) making disclosures that are protected under applicable whistleblower laws; (ii) communicating with any governmental agency or law enforcement entity for the purpose of reporting suspected violations of law; (iii) participating in any investigation or proceeding by a governmental agency; or (iv) exercising any rights under the National Labor Relations Act or other applicable labor or employment laws.\n(b) The Parties intend this Agreement to be interpreted in a manner consistent with New York law disfavoring overly broad restraints on trade. This Agreement does not create a non-competition obligation. Any optional restrictive covenant included in this Agreement (such as a non-solicitation covenant) shall be construed narrowly to the minimum extent necessary to protect legitimate interests.\n\n2.12 No Insider Trading; Securities Compliance; Martin Act Considerations.\n(a) The Receiving Party acknowledges that Confidential Information may include material nonpublic information. The Receiving Party agrees not to engage in any Prohibited Securities Use.\n(b) The Receiving Party shall not use Confidential Information to solicit investments, make offering materials, or otherwise conduct any securities-related activity concerning the Disclosing Party without the Disclosing Party’s prior written consent and appropriate legal compliance.\n\n2.13 Reservation of Rights. All Confidential Information remains the property of the Disclosing Party (or its licensors). No license or other rights are granted by implication, estoppel, or otherwise except as expressly set forth in this Agreement for the Permitted Use.\n\n2.14 No Obligation to Disclose; No Warranty. The Disclosing Party has no obligation to disclose any particular information. All Confidential Information is provided \"AS IS\" without any representation or warranty, express or implied, including any warranty of accuracy, completeness, merchantability, fitness for a particular purpose, title, or non-infringement, except to the extent such disclaimer is prohibited by Law.\n\n2.15 Non-Disparagement; Publicity (Optional).\n(a) Optional: The Receiving Party shall not make any public statement (including on social media) regarding the Purpose, the relationship between the Parties, or the receipt of Confidential Information without the Disclosing Party’s prior written consent.\n(b) Optional: The Receiving Party shall not knowingly make false statements that are intended to harm the Disclosing Party’s business reputation in connection with the Purpose."},{"id":"exclusions","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. EXCLUSIONS FROM CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION","content":"3.1 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by contemporaneous written records:\n(a) is or becomes generally available to the public through no act or omission of the Receiving Party or its Representatives in breach of this Agreement;\n(b) was lawfully in the Receiving Party’s possession, without restriction as to use or disclosure, prior to receipt from the Disclosing Party;\n(c) is lawfully disclosed to the Receiving Party by a third party who, to the Receiving Party’s knowledge after reasonable inquiry, had the right to disclose the information without restriction and without breach of any confidentiality obligation to the Disclosing Party;\n(d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to Confidential Information, as shown by written records of such independent development; or\n(e) is approved for release by the Disclosing Party in a writing signed by the Disclosing Party.\n\n3.2 No Implied Exclusion for Combination. Information shall not be deemed within an exclusion merely because individual components are public or otherwise non-confidential, if the combination, compilation, or configuration is confidential.\n\n3.3 Burden of Proof. The Receiving Party bears the burden of proving that an exclusion applies. If only a portion of Confidential Information is excluded, the remaining portion remains subject to this Agreement.\n\n3.4 Residual Knowledge (Optional).\n(a) Optional: Notwithstanding anything to the contrary, the Receiving Party may use information retained in the unaided memory of its Representatives who had access to Confidential Information (\"Residuals\"), provided that (i) such Representatives do not intentionally memorize Confidential Information for the purpose of circumventing this Agreement, and (ii) such use does not involve Disclosure of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.\n(b) Optional: Residuals do not include Trade Secrets to the extent prohibited by applicable Law.\n\n3.5 Required Disclosures Not Exclusions. Disclosure pursuant to Clause 2.9 (Compelled Disclosure) does not render the disclosed information non-confidential, and all other Confidential Information remains subject to this Agreement."},{"id":"term_and_duration","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TERM AND DURATION","content":"4.1 Term. This Agreement commences on the Effective Date and continues until the earlier of: (a) {{expiration_date}} (if provided); or (b) termination by either Party upon {{notice_period}} days’ prior written notice to the other Party. If {{notice_period}} is not provided, the notice period shall be ten (10) days.\n\n4.2 Duration of Confidentiality Obligations.\n(a) Except as provided in Clause 4.2(b) and Clause 4.3, the Receiving Party’s confidentiality and non-use obligations under this Agreement shall continue for {{confidentiality_period}} years from the date of each disclosure of the applicable Confidential Information. If {{confidentiality_period}} is not provided, the period shall be three (3) years.\n(b) To the extent any Confidential Information constitutes Personal Data, the obligations under this Agreement shall apply for so long as required by applicable Law and, in any event, for so long as the Receiving Party retains such Personal Data.\n\n4.3 Trade Secrets. With respect to any Trade Secret, the Receiving Party’s obligations under this Agreement shall continue for as long as such information remains a trade secret under applicable Law.\n\n4.4 Survival. Clauses 1 (Definitions), 2 (Confidentiality Obligations), 3 (Exclusions), 4 (Term and Duration), 5 (Return or Destruction), 6 (Remedies), 7 (Governing Law; Venue), 8 (General Provisions), and any other provisions that by their nature should survive, shall survive expiration or termination of this Agreement.\n\n4.5 No Automatic Termination Upon Discussions. The Parties acknowledge that discussions may cease without notice; termination of discussions does not, by itself, terminate this Agreement or the Receiving Party’s obligations with respect to Confidential Information."},{"id":"return_of_information","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. RETURN OR DESTRUCTION OF INFORMATION","content":"5.1 Return or Destruction Upon Request. Upon the Disclosing Party’s written request, the Receiving Party shall promptly (and in any event within ten (10) Business Days unless otherwise agreed in writing) return to the Disclosing Party or destroy all Evaluation Material in the Receiving Party’s possession or control, including all copies, excerpts, and summaries, and all Derived Materials.\n\n5.2 Certification. Upon request, the Receiving Party shall provide a written certification executed by an authorized representative of the Receiving Party confirming compliance with Clause 5.1, including a description of the categories of materials returned or destroyed.\n\n5.3 Secure Deletion Standard. If destruction is requested or elected, the Receiving Party shall destroy the Evaluation Material in a manner reasonably designed to prevent its reconstruction or retrieval (e.g., shredding for paper records; secure wipe or cryptographic erase for electronic records), taking into account the sensitivity of the information.\n\n5.4 Archival and Legal Retention Copies.\n(a) The Receiving Party may retain copies of Evaluation Material to the extent required by Law, court order, or bona fide internal document retention policies, including routine system backups, provided that such retained materials remain subject to this Agreement and are not accessed except as required for compliance purposes.\n(b) If the Receiving Party retains any Evaluation Material under this Clause 5.4, the Receiving Party shall continue to protect it in accordance with this Agreement.\n\n5.5 Return Not Required for Intangible Knowledge. Return or destruction obligations do not require the Receiving Party to delete intangible knowledge retained in the unaided memory of its Representatives, provided that such knowledge remains subject to the non-use and non-disclosure obligations of this Agreement.\n\n5.6 No Lien. The Receiving Party shall not assert any lien, setoff, or other encumbrance over the Evaluation Material as a basis to retain it."},{"id":"remedies","type":"negotiable","order":6,"title":"6. REMEDIES","content":"6.1 Injunctive and Equitable Relief. The Receiving Party acknowledges and agrees that any breach of this Agreement may cause the Disclosing Party irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be an inadequate remedy. Accordingly, in the event of an actual or threatened breach, the Disclosing Party shall be entitled to seek immediate injunctive relief, specific performance, and other equitable relief in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity.\n\n6.2 No Waiver of Other Remedies. Except as expressly provided in this Agreement, the rights and remedies of the Disclosing Party are cumulative and not exclusive.\n\n6.3 Bond. To the maximum extent permitted by Law, the Receiving Party waives any requirement that the Disclosing Party post a bond or other security to obtain injunctive or equitable relief; provided, however, that nothing in this Clause 6.3 shall limit a court’s discretion where such waiver is not enforceable.\n\n6.4 Damages. The Receiving Party shall be liable for all damages, losses, liabilities, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs) arising out of or relating to any breach of this Agreement by the Receiving Party or its Representatives.\n\n6.5 Attorneys’ Fees (Optional). Optional: In any action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the prevailing Party shall be entitled to recover its reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs, to the extent permitted by New York law and subject to any statutory fee-shifting limitations.\n\n6.6 Defend Trade Secrets Act (DTSA) Whistleblower Immunity Notice. Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b):\n(a) An individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that (i) is made in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney; and (ii) is solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law.\n(b) An individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that is made in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal.\n(c) If an individual files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law, the individual may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding, if the individual (i) files any document containing the trade secret under seal, and (ii) does not disclose the trade secret except pursuant to court order.\n\n6.7 Acknowledgment Regarding New York Common Law. The Receiving Party acknowledges that New York provides common law protection for trade secrets and confidential information. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed to diminish any rights or remedies the Disclosing Party may have under New York common law, including claims for misappropriation, unfair competition, or breach of fiduciary duty, where applicable.\n\n6.8 Limitation of Liability (Optional). Optional: Except for (i) breach of Clauses 2.1 (Permitted Use), 2.2 (Non-Disclosure), 2.5 (Security Safeguards), 2.7 (No Reverse Engineering), 2.10 (Security Incidents), 2.12 (No Insider Trading), or (ii) misappropriation of Trade Secrets, neither Party shall be liable to the other for indirect, incidental, special, consequential, or punitive damages arising out of this Agreement."},{"id":"governing_law","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. GOVERNING LAW; VENUE","content":"7.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and any dispute, claim, or controversy arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the Purpose, or the Parties’ relationship (whether in contract, tort, statute, or otherwise) shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of New York, without regard to any choice-of-law or conflict-of-law rules that would result in the application of another jurisdiction’s laws.\n\n7.2 Exclusive Venue; County Requirement. Subject to Clause 7.4, the Parties agree that any action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement shall be brought exclusively in (a) the Supreme Court of the State of New York located in {{venue_county}} County, New York, or (b) if there is federal subject matter jurisdiction, the United States District Court sitting in or serving {{venue_county}} County, New York. Each Party irrevocably submits to the personal jurisdiction of such courts and waives any objection based on inconvenient forum.\n\n7.3 Service of Process. Each Party consents to service of process by (a) personal service, (b) nationally recognized overnight courier, or (c) certified mail, return receipt requested, in each case to the addresses set forth in the Preamble (or to any updated address designated by notice under Clause 8.2). Nothing herein limits any other lawful means of service.\n\n7.4 Injunctive Relief Carve-Out. Notwithstanding Clause 7.2, the Disclosing Party may seek temporary, preliminary, or permanent injunctive relief or other equitable relief in any court of competent jurisdiction to prevent or curtail an actual or threatened breach of Clauses 2.1, 2.2, 2.5, 2.7, 2.10, or 2.12.\n\n7.5 Waiver of Jury Trial (Optional). Optional: EACH PARTY KNOWINGLY AND VOLUNTARILY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION OR PROCEEDING ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT."},{"id":"general_provisions","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"8.1 Relationship of the Parties. The Parties are independent contracting parties. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed to create any partnership, joint venture, fiduciary relationship, employment relationship, agency relationship, or franchise relationship between the Parties.\n\n8.2 Notices.\n(a) Form of Notice. All notices and other communications required or permitted under this Agreement shall be in writing and shall be deemed given when: (i) delivered personally; (ii) sent by a nationally recognized overnight courier (with written confirmation of receipt); (iii) sent by certified or registered mail, return receipt requested, postage prepaid; or (iv) sent by email with confirmation of transmission and, if requested, confirmation of receipt.\n(b) Notice Addresses. Notices shall be sent to the addresses and emails listed in the signature block (or such other address or email as a Party designates by notice).\n\n8.3 Entire Agreement; Order of Precedence. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties with respect to the subject matter hereof and supersedes all prior or contemporaneous understandings, representations, and agreements, whether written or oral, relating to such subject matter. In the event of a conflict between this Agreement and any other document regarding confidentiality executed by the Parties for the Purpose, the most recently executed document shall control solely with respect to the conflict, unless the document expressly states otherwise.\n\n8.4 Amendments; Waivers. No amendment, modification, or waiver of any provision of this Agreement shall be effective unless in a writing signed by both Parties. A waiver of any breach shall not be deemed a waiver of any subsequent breach.\n\n8.5 Severability; Reformation. If any provision of this Agreement is held invalid, illegal, or unenforceable, the remaining provisions shall remain in full force and effect. The Parties intend that any invalid or unenforceable provision be reformed to the minimum extent necessary to render it valid and enforceable while preserving the Parties’ intent.\n\n8.6 Assignment. Neither Party may assign or transfer this Agreement, in whole or in part, without the prior written consent of the other Party, except that either Party may assign this Agreement without consent to an Affiliate or to a successor in interest in connection with a merger, acquisition, reorganization, or sale of substantially all of its assets, provided that the assignee agrees in writing to be bound by this Agreement.\n\n8.7 No Implied License; IP Reservation.\n(a) Except for the limited right to use Confidential Information for the Permitted Use, no license or other right (whether by implication, estoppel, or otherwise) is granted under any patent, copyright, trade secret, trademark, or other intellectual property right.\n(b) The Receiving Party shall not remove, alter, or obscure any proprietary notices on Confidential Information.\n\n8.8 No Obligation to Proceed; No Exclusivity. Nothing in this Agreement obligates either Party to proceed with any transaction, relationship, or arrangement, and either Party may cease discussions at any time. Unless expressly stated in a separate writing, this Agreement does not create exclusivity.\n\n8.9 Compliance With Law. Each Party shall comply with applicable Law in connection with its performance under this Agreement, including applicable export control and sanctions laws. The Receiving Party shall not export, re-export, or transfer any Confidential Information in violation of Law.\n\n8.10 Non-Solicitation (Optional; Narrowly Tailored).\n(a) Optional: For a period of {{non_solicit_period_months}} months after the Effective Date, the Receiving Party shall not, directly and knowingly, solicit for employment any person who is then a full-time employee of the Disclosing Party and with whom the Receiving Party had direct contact in connection with the Purpose; provided that general solicitations not targeted at such employees (e.g., public advertisements) shall not violate this Clause.\n(b) Optional: The Parties acknowledge that New York courts scrutinize restrictive covenants. The Parties intend this Clause 8.10, if included, to be interpreted narrowly and enforced only to the extent reasonable and necessary to protect legitimate interests.\n\n8.11 Non-Competition. No provision of this Agreement shall be interpreted as restricting the Receiving Party from engaging in any lawful profession, trade, or business, except that the Receiving Party remains bound by its obligations not to use or disclose Confidential Information.\n\n8.12 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in any number of counterparts, each of which shall be deemed an original, and all of which together shall constitute one instrument.\n\n8.13 Electronic Signatures; ESRA. The Parties agree that this Agreement and any signatures hereon may be executed and delivered by electronic means. Electronic Signatures shall be valid and enforceable to the fullest extent permitted by the New York Electronic Signatures and Records Act (ESRA) and the federal Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (E-SIGN).\n\n8.14 Interpretation. Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation. The terms \"including\" and \"include\" mean \"including without limitation.\" No presumption shall arise favoring or disfavoring a Party by virtue of authorship.\n\n8.15 Further Assurances. Each Party shall, upon reasonable request of the other Party, execute and deliver such additional documents and take such further actions as may be reasonably necessary to carry out the intent of this Agreement.\n\n8.16 Taxes (Informational; If Applicable). If the Receiving Party is an individual providing services as a freelance worker or independent contractor, the Receiving Party acknowledges that it is generally responsible for its own federal, New York State, and (if applicable) New York City income taxes and other assessments, and that the Disclosing Party is not responsible for withholding taxes except as required by Law.\n\n8.17 No Retaliation (If Applicable). To the extent FIFAA applies, the Disclosing Party shall not threaten, intimidate, discipline, penalize, or otherwise retaliate against the Receiving Party for exercising rights protected by FIFAA, including requesting a written contract, timely payment, or filing a complaint."},{"id":"freelance_terms_optional","type":"negotiable","order":9,"title":"9. FREELANCE ENGAGEMENT; PAYMENT; CLASSIFICATION (OPTIONAL)","content":"9.1 Applicability and Purpose of Clause. This Clause 9 applies only if (and to the extent) the Receiving Party is engaged by the Disclosing Party to perform services described in {{services_description}} (the \"Services\") in connection with the Purpose. If the Parties are not entering into a services arrangement, this Clause 9 may be deleted without affecting the remainder of the Agreement.\n\n9.2 Written Contract Requirement (FIFAA). The Parties acknowledge that under FIFAA a written contract is required for certain freelance work arrangements meeting applicable thresholds (including, where applicable, work valued at $800 or more in the aggregate). This Agreement is intended to satisfy the written contract requirement only as to the items expressly addressed herein; the Parties may execute a separate statement of work, purchase order, or services agreement addressing additional terms.\n\n9.3 Itemization of Services; Timing.\n(a) Services. The Services are: {{services_description}}.\n(b) Schedule/Deadline (if any). The Services are expected to be completed by {{services_completion_date}} or as otherwise mutually agreed in writing.\n(c) Deliverables (if any). Deliverables, if applicable, are: {{deliverables_description}}.\n\n9.4 Compensation.\n(a) Fee. The Disclosing Party shall pay the Receiving Party total compensation of {{compensation_amount}} for the Services (the \"Fee\"), unless the Parties agree in a separate signed writing to a different amount.\n(b) Expenses (Optional). Optional: The Disclosing Party will reimburse pre-approved, reasonable out-of-pocket expenses in accordance with {{expense_policy_summary}} upon receipt of reasonable documentation.\n(c) No Other Compensation. Except as expressly provided, no other compensation is due.\n\n9.5 Invoicing and Payment Timing.\n(a) Invoice. The Receiving Party shall submit an invoice to {{invoice_email}} (or another email designated by the Disclosing Party by notice) upon completion of the Services or at the following milestones: {{payment_milestones}}.\n(b) Due Date. Unless a different payment date is expressly stated in a signed writing, payment shall be due no later than thirty (30) calendar days after (i) completion of the Services, or (ii) delivery of the invoice, whichever is later, consistent with FIFAA requirements.\n(c) Method. Payment shall be made by {{payment_method}}.\n\n9.6 Late Payment; Statutory Remedies; No Waiver.\n(a) The Parties acknowledge that FIFAA may provide for statutory damages and other remedies for late payment (including, where applicable, double damages and attorneys’ fees and costs) and prohibits retaliation.\n(b) Nothing in this Agreement waives or limits any rights or remedies available under FIFAA or other applicable Law.\n\n9.7 Records Retention (FIFAA). To the extent required by FIFAA, each Party shall retain a copy of this Agreement (and any related written scope, invoice records, and payment records) for at least six (6) years from the later of the date of final payment or completion of the Services.\n\n9.8 Independent Contractor; No Employment Relationship.\n(a) The Parties intend that the Receiving Party, if providing Services, is an independent contractor and not an employee of the Disclosing Party for purposes of New York Labor Law, tax withholding, unemployment insurance, workers’ compensation, or any benefit plan. The Receiving Party is responsible for its own taxes, filings, insurance, permits, and compliance obligations, except to the extent required by Law.\n(b) The Disclosing Party will not provide employee benefits to the Receiving Party. The Receiving Party is not authorized to bind the Disclosing Party.\n(c) Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed as an attempt to misclassify any worker. The actual classification of the Receiving Party, if disputed, will be determined under applicable Law based on the facts and circumstances.\n\n9.9 Confidentiality Not a Substitute for Work-for-Hire Terms. The Parties acknowledge that confidentiality obligations in this Agreement do not, by themselves, determine ownership of Work Product or intellectual property. Any assignment of Work Product or IP must be set forth in a separate written agreement signed by both Parties.\n\n9.10 Anti-Retaliation Statement (FIFAA). If FIFAA applies, the Disclosing Party shall not retaliate against the Receiving Party for (a) requesting or negotiating a written contract, (b) requesting timely payment, (c) exercising rights under FIFAA, or (d) filing a complaint or participating in an investigation related to FIFAA."},{"id":"privacy_data_protection","type":"standard","order":10,"title":"10. PRIVACY; DATA PROTECTION; PERSONAL DATA","content":"10.1 Scope. This Clause 10 applies to the extent Confidential Information includes Personal Data, or to the extent the Receiving Party processes Personal Data on behalf of the Disclosing Party in connection with the Purpose.\n\n10.2 Permitted Processing. The Receiving Party shall process Personal Data only as necessary for the Permitted Use and in compliance with applicable Law. The Receiving Party shall not (a) sell Personal Data, (b) retain, use, or disclose Personal Data outside the scope of the Purpose, or (c) combine Personal Data with other data sets to re-identify individuals, except as required for the Permitted Use.\n\n10.3 Safeguards; SHIELD Act Alignment. The Receiving Party shall implement and maintain reasonable safeguards appropriate to the nature of the Personal Data, including safeguards aligned with New York’s SHIELD Act requirements for reasonable administrative, technical, and physical protections.\n\n10.4 Subprocessors. The Receiving Party shall not permit any subcontractor, cloud provider, or other third party (each, a \"Subprocessor\") to process Personal Data unless: (a) such Subprocessor is bound by written obligations at least as protective as those in this Agreement; and (b) the Receiving Party remains responsible for the Subprocessor’s acts and omissions.\n\n10.5 Cross-Border Transfers (Optional). Optional: The Receiving Party shall not transfer Personal Data outside the United States without the Disclosing Party’s prior written consent.\n\n10.6 Data Subject and Regulatory Requests. If the Receiving Party receives any request, complaint, or inquiry from a data subject or governmental authority relating to Personal Data received from the Disclosing Party (including requests for access, deletion, correction, or disclosure), the Receiving Party shall promptly notify the Disclosing Party (unless prohibited by Law) and reasonably cooperate with the Disclosing Party’s response.\n\n10.7 Incident Response and Cooperation. In addition to Clause 2.10, the Receiving Party shall reasonably cooperate with the Disclosing Party in meeting any legal obligations related to a Security Incident, including obligations under New York General Business Law § 899-aa and other applicable breach notification laws, and shall provide information reasonably requested to assess impact and required notifications.\n\n10.8 Data Retention. The Receiving Party shall not retain Personal Data longer than necessary for the Purpose, except as required by Law or permitted under Clause 5.4 (Archival and Legal Retention Copies). Upon completion of the Purpose or upon request, the Receiving Party shall return or securely delete Personal Data consistent with Clause 5.\n\n10.9 No HIPAA/GLBA/Other Regulated Data Unless Agreed (Optional). Optional: The Disclosing Party will not disclose to the Receiving Party any protected health information regulated by HIPAA, payment card data subject to PCI-DSS, or nonpublic personal information subject to GLBA, unless the Parties first execute a separate written agreement (e.g., BAA or data protection addendum) addressing such regulated data.\n\n10.10 Privacy Contact (Optional). Optional: Notices under this Clause 10 may also be sent to the Disclosing Party’s privacy/security contact at {{privacy_contact_email}}."}]'::jsonb,
  signature_block = 'IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Agreement as of {{signature_date}}.

