-- Update: Simple Agreement for Future Equity - SAFE (New York)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Simple Agreement for Future Equity (this "SAFE") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between {{party_a_company}}, a New York {{entity_type}} (the "Company"), and {{party_b_name}} (the "Investor"). The Company and the Investor may be referred to herein individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties."',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, the Company is seeking to raise capital to fund its business operations and growth;

WHEREAS, the Investor desires to provide capital to the Company, and the Company desires to accept such capital, in each case on the terms set forth herein;

WHEREAS, the Parties intend that this SAFE constitutes a contract that provides the Investor with the right to receive equity securities of the Company upon the occurrence of certain triggering events, subject to the terms and conditions of this SAFE;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises and covenants contained herein and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS","content":"1.1 \"Affiliate\" means, with respect to any Person, any other Person that directly or indirectly Controls, is Controlled by, or is under common Control with such Person.\n\n1.2 \"Applicable Law\" means all applicable federal, New York State, and (if applicable) New York City laws, rules, regulations, orders, codes, ordinances, and other legal requirements, including securities laws and regulations and applicable tax laws.\n\n1.3 \"Board\" means the Company’s board of directors or other governing body, as applicable.\n\n1.4 \"Business Day\" means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday, or day on which banks in New York, New York are authorized or required by law to close.\n\n1.5 \"Capital Stock\" means the shares of the Company’s capital stock or other equity interests, including any class or series of common stock, preferred stock, membership interests, or other equity securities, and any rights, options, warrants, or other securities convertible into or exercisable or exchangeable for any of the foregoing.\n\n1.6 \"Change of Control\" means (a) any merger, consolidation, or reorganization of the Company after which the stockholders (or other equity holders) of the Company immediately prior to such transaction do not, as a group, beneficially own a majority of the voting power of the surviving or acquiring entity (or its ultimate parent), (b) any Person or group (as such terms are used under Section 13(d) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended) becomes the beneficial owner (directly or indirectly) of a majority of the voting power of the Company, or (c) a sale, transfer, exclusive license, or other disposition of all or substantially all of the Company’s assets, determined in each case in accordance with New York law and customary venture financing practice.\n\n1.7 \"Common Stock\" means the Company’s common stock or analogous equity securities designated as common equity, as set forth in the Company’s certificate of incorporation (as amended and restated from time to time) or other organizational documents.\n\n1.8 \"Company Capitalization\" means, as of immediately prior to the applicable event (e.g., the closing of the Equity Financing or the Liquidity Event), the fully-diluted capitalization of the Company, including: (a) all issued and outstanding shares (or units) of Capital Stock; (b) all shares (or units) reserved for issuance under any employee or consultant equity incentive or similar plan; (c) all shares (or units) issuable upon conversion, exercise, or settlement of any options, warrants, convertible securities, SAFEs, notes, or other instruments convertible into or exercisable or exchangeable for Capital Stock (whether or not then exercisable), but excluding, unless otherwise provided herein, (i) shares issuable upon conversion of this SAFE and (ii) shares issuable upon conversion of other SAFEs of substantially similar form that are excluded by the Company in good faith for purposes of calculating the conversion price consistent with customary venture financing practice; and (d) any other shares that, in accordance with the terms of the definitive financing documents for the Equity Financing, are included in a fully-diluted capitalization calculation for pricing purposes.\n\n1.9 \"Company Notice Address\" means the notice information for the Company set forth in Section 12.4.\n\n1.10 \"Control\" (including the terms \"Controlled by\" and \"under common Control\") means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management or policies of a Person, whether through ownership of voting securities, by contract, or otherwise.\n\n1.11 \"Conversion Shares\" means the shares of Capital Stock issued to the Investor upon conversion or settlement of this SAFE.\n\n1.12 \"Discount Rate\" means {{discount_rate}}% expressed as a percentage discount to the price per share (or unit) paid by the investors purchasing the Equity Financing Securities (as defined below) in the Equity Financing.\n\n1.13 \"Dissolution Event\" means (a) a voluntary termination of operations and winding up of the Company, (b) a general assignment for the benefit of the Company’s creditors, (c) the appointment of a receiver or similar officer for the Company or substantially all of its property that is not dismissed within sixty (60) days, or (d) any other liquidation, dissolution, or winding up of the Company (other than a Liquidity Event).\n\n1.14 \"Equity Financing\" means a bona fide transaction or series of related transactions in which the Company issues and sells shares of its Preferred Stock (or other equity securities that are substantially similar) for the primary purpose of raising capital, in each case with aggregate gross proceeds to the Company (excluding the conversion of this SAFE and other SAFEs and excluding conversion/exercise of outstanding securities) of not less than {{qualifying_round_threshold}} (a \"Qualified Equity Financing\").\n\n1.15 \"Equity Financing Price\" means the price per share (or unit), as applicable, paid by the investors for the Equity Financing Securities in the Equity Financing (excluding any price paid for convertible securities that later convert in such financing).\n\n1.16 \"Equity Financing Securities\" means the shares of Preferred Stock (or other equity securities) issued by the Company in the Equity Financing.\n\n1.17 \"Excluded Issuances\" means issuances of Capital Stock (a) pursuant to equity incentive, compensation, or similar plans approved by the Board (and, if required, stockholders), (b) upon conversion or exercise of outstanding options, warrants, convertible notes, SAFEs, or other convertible securities outstanding as of immediately prior to the Equity Financing, (c) in connection with bona fide acquisitions, strategic transactions, equipment financings, bank financings, leasing arrangements, or commercial arrangements, in each case not primarily for the purpose of raising equity capital, and (d) issuances as a dividend or distribution on Capital Stock.\n\n1.18 \"Governmental Authority\" means any federal, state, local, or foreign government or governmental or regulatory body, agency, commission, department, tribunal, or other authority.\n\n1.19 \"Initial Public Offering\" or \"IPO\" means the closing of the Company’s first firm-commitment underwritten public offering pursuant to an effective registration statement under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended (the \"Securities Act\"), covering the offer and sale of the Company’s Common Stock (or other substantially similar equity securities), resulting in the Common Stock being listed for trading on a national securities exchange in the United States.\n\n1.20 \"Investor Notice Address\" means the notice information for the Investor set forth in Section 12.4.\n\n1.21 \"Liquidity Event\" means (a) a Change of Control or (b) an IPO.\n\n1.22 \"Major Investor\" (if applicable) means an investor (including the Investor) that holds SAFEs and/or convertible notes issued by the Company with an aggregate purchase amount of at least the threshold amount, if any, specified by the Company in writing to the Investor (or, if no threshold is specified, then no Major Investor concept applies under this SAFE).\n\n1.23 \"Person\" means an individual, corporation, limited liability company, partnership, trust, association, unincorporated organization, governmental authority, or other entity.\n\n1.24 \"Preferred Stock\" means the Company’s preferred stock or analogous equity securities designated as preferred equity, as set forth in the Company’s organizational documents.\n\n1.25 \"Purchase Amount\" means {{investment_amount}}.\n\n1.26 \"SAFE Preferred Stock\" means the shares of a series of Preferred Stock issued to the Investor upon conversion of this SAFE in connection with an Equity Financing, having the same rights, privileges, preferences, and restrictions as the Equity Financing Securities, except as otherwise provided in this SAFE.\n\n1.27 \"SAFE Securities\" means the Conversion Shares and any other securities or rights issued or delivered to the Investor pursuant to the terms of this SAFE.\n\n1.28 \"SAFE Price\" means the conversion price per share (or per unit) applicable to this SAFE, determined in accordance with Section 3.\n\n1.29 \"Securities Act\" has the meaning set forth in Section 1.19.\n\n1.30 \"State\" means the State of New York.\n\n1.31 \"Tax\" or \"Taxes\" means any and all federal, state, local, and foreign taxes, levies, duties, assessments, and charges of any kind (including income, franchise, gross receipts, payroll, employment, withholding, sales and use, value-added, transfer, and excise taxes), together with any interest, penalties, additions to tax, and related amounts.\n\n1.32 \"Valuation Cap\" means {{valuation_cap}}.\n\n1.33 \"Valuation Cap Price\" means the price per share (or per unit) equal to (a) the Valuation Cap divided by (b) the Company Capitalization.\n\n1.34 \"Whistleblower Notice\" means the notice of immunity required by the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act of 2016, as set forth in Section 11.6.\n\n1.35 Interpretation. (a) The words \"include,\" \"includes,\" and \"including\" are deemed to be followed by \"without limitation.\" (b) The headings in this SAFE are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation. (c) Unless the context otherwise requires, references to Sections refer to sections of this SAFE. (d) References to any statute or regulation include any successor or amended statute or regulation.\n\n1.36 No Presumption Against Drafting Party. The Parties acknowledge that each Party has had the opportunity to participate in the drafting and negotiation of this SAFE (or to consult counsel regarding the same). Accordingly, no presumption shall arise favoring any Party by virtue of the authorship of any provision of this SAFE."},{"id":"investment","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. PURCHASE AMOUNT; ISSUANCE; CLOSING MECHANICS","content":"2.1 Issuance of SAFE; Consideration. In consideration of the Investor’s payment of the Purchase Amount, the Company hereby issues and delivers to the Investor this SAFE. This SAFE evidences the Investor’s contractual right to receive SAFE Securities upon the occurrence of certain events, subject to and in accordance with the terms of this SAFE.\n\n2.2 Payment of Purchase Amount.\n(a) Timing. The Investor shall pay the Purchase Amount to the Company on or before the date specified by the Company in writing, and in any event no later than five (5) Business Days following the Effective Date unless the Parties agree otherwise in writing.\n(b) Method. Payment shall be made by wire transfer of immediately available funds or other method reasonably acceptable to the Company.\n(c) No Interest. The Purchase Amount does not bear interest and is not repayable except as expressly provided in Sections 4 and 5.\n\n2.3 Closing; Book-Entry. The issuance of this SAFE may be effected in certificated or book-entry form. The Company may maintain a ledger or capitalization table reflecting the outstanding SAFEs; provided, however, that any such ledger is for administrative convenience and does not supersede the terms of this SAFE.\n\n2.4 Use of Proceeds. The Company shall use the Purchase Amount for general working capital and other proper corporate purposes, as determined by the Company in its discretion, subject to Applicable Law and any fiduciary duties of the Board.\n\n2.5 No Setoff. Except as required by Applicable Law (including tax withholding) or as expressly agreed in writing by the Investor, the Company shall not set off any amounts purportedly owed by the Investor against amounts, if any, payable to the Investor under this SAFE.\n\n2.6 Taxes; Withholding; Forms.\n(a) The Investor shall provide any reasonably requested tax documentation (including an IRS Form W-9 or appropriate Form W-8) to the Company in connection with the issuance or settlement of this SAFE.\n(b) The Company may withhold from any payments (including cash payable under Sections 4 or 5) any amounts required to be withheld under Applicable Law, and any such withheld amounts shall be treated as paid to the Investor.\n(c) The Investor acknowledges that the Company does not provide tax advice and that the Investor should consult their own tax advisors regarding federal, New York State, and (if applicable) New York City tax consequences.\n\n2.7 No Rights as Stockholder. This SAFE does not confer on the Investor any right to vote, receive dividends, or exercise any other rights of a stockholder (or other equity holder) of the Company until and unless SAFE Securities are issued to the Investor in accordance with this SAFE.\n\n2.8 No Employment; No Services. The Parties acknowledge and agree that this SAFE is an investment instrument and does not create any employment, consulting, or other service relationship between the Company and the Investor. Any services, if any, must be governed by a separate written agreement."},{"id":"conversion","type":"negotiable","order":3,"title":"3. CONVERSION UPON EQUITY FINANCING","content":"3.1 Automatic Conversion. Upon the closing of an Equity Financing, this SAFE shall automatically convert into shares of SAFE Preferred Stock, without any further action by the Company or the Investor, except as may be required to issue the SAFE Preferred Stock and to reflect the conversion on the Company’s books and records.\n\n3.2 Conversion Amount. The amount to be converted shall be equal to the Purchase Amount (the \"Conversion Amount\").\n\n3.3 Conversion Price; Determination of SAFE Price.\n(a) Discount Price. The \"Discount Price\" means the Equity Financing Price multiplied by (1 - Discount Rate).\n(b) Valuation Cap Price. The \"Valuation Cap Price\" means the Valuation Cap Price as defined in Section 1.33.\n(c) SAFE Price. The \"SAFE Price\" shall be the lesser of (i) the Discount Price and (ii) the Valuation Cap Price.\n\n3.4 Number of Shares Issued. The number of shares of SAFE Preferred Stock to be issued upon conversion shall equal the Conversion Amount divided by the SAFE Price, rounded down to the nearest whole share (or, if the Company’s Equity Financing documents permit, the Company may issue fractional shares or pay cash in lieu of fractional shares based on the SAFE Price).\n\n3.5 Treatment in the Equity Financing.\n(a) Same Terms as Equity Financing Securities. Except as set forth in this SAFE, the SAFE Preferred Stock shall have the same rights, privileges, preferences, and restrictions as the Equity Financing Securities.\n(b) Liquidation Preference and Dividends. If the Equity Financing Securities include a liquidation preference and/or dividend rate, then for purposes of the SAFE Preferred Stock, the per share liquidation preference (and any dividend basis that is expressly tied to the original issue price) shall be based on the SAFE Price rather than the Equity Financing Price.\n(c) Anti-Dilution. If the Equity Financing Securities include price-based anti-dilution protection, the basis for such protection with respect to the SAFE Preferred Stock shall be consistent with the Equity Financing Securities but using the SAFE Price as the original issue price.\n\n3.6 Company Capitalization Determination.\n(a) Good Faith Determination. Company Capitalization shall be determined in good faith by the Board (or the Company’s authorized officer(s) pursuant to delegated authority) consistent with customary venture financing practice and the structure of the Equity Financing.\n(b) Exclusions and Clarifications. For avoidance of doubt, Company Capitalization may include the shares underlying convertible instruments that are converting in the Equity Financing (including other SAFEs), if the Equity Financing documentation treats such instruments as part of fully-diluted capitalization for pricing purposes.\n\n3.7 Simultaneous Closing; Multiple Closings. If the Equity Financing occurs in multiple closings, conversion shall occur at the first closing, unless the definitive financing documents provide that SAFE conversions occur at a later closing and the Investor is treated no less favorably than other SAFE holders converting in such financing.\n\n3.8 Mechanics; Documentation.\n(a) Required Documents. As a condition to receiving SAFE Preferred Stock, the Investor shall execute and deliver customary definitive financing documents (e.g., stock purchase agreement, investors’ rights agreement, right of first refusal and co-sale agreement, voting agreement) that are executed by the purchasers of Equity Financing Securities, provided that such documents (i) contain customary representations, warranties, and covenants for similarly situated investors, and (ii) do not impose personal liability on the Investor beyond the Investor’s investment amount (other than for breaches of the Investor’s own representations, warranties, or covenants).\n(b) Power of Attorney (Optional). To facilitate conversion, the Company may request that the Investor grant a limited power of attorney solely for purposes of executing ministerial conversion documentation substantially consistent with market practice, provided that the Investor is afforded reasonable notice and an opportunity to execute documents directly.\n\n3.9 Termination upon Conversion. Upon issuance of the SAFE Preferred Stock to the Investor pursuant to this Section 3, this SAFE shall be deemed converted and terminated, and the Company shall have no further obligations under this SAFE except for obligations that expressly survive conversion.\n\n3.10 No Impairment. The Company shall not take any action (including amendment of its charter documents) with the primary purpose of avoiding, delaying, or impairing the conversion rights of the Investor under this SAFE, except as required by Applicable Law or undertaken in good faith for bona fide corporate purposes."},{"id":"liquidity_event","type":"negotiable","order":4,"title":"4. LIQUIDITY EVENT","content":"4.1 Liquidity Event Before Conversion. If a Liquidity Event occurs prior to the conversion of this SAFE pursuant to Section 3, then, subject to Section 4.6, the Investor shall be entitled to receive, at the Investor’s election, either (a) a cash payment or (b) Conversion Shares, as described below.\n\n4.2 Investor Election.\n(a) Election Notice. The Company shall provide the Investor with written notice of the anticipated Liquidity Event not less than five (5) Business Days prior to the closing of such Liquidity Event (or, if not practicable, as soon as reasonably practicable). The Investor shall deliver written notice of its election to the Company within the period specified in the Company’s notice (which shall be at least three (3) Business Days).\n(b) Default Election. If the Investor does not timely deliver an election, then the default treatment shall be (i) conversion into Common Stock pursuant to Section 4.4 if the Liquidity Event consideration is primarily equity consideration or (ii) cash payment pursuant to Section 4.3 if the Liquidity Event consideration is primarily cash consideration, in each case as determined by the Company in good faith.\n\n4.3 Cash-Out Option. If the Investor elects (or is deemed to elect) the cash-out option, the Company shall pay the Investor an amount equal to the Purchase Amount (the \"Liquidity Cash Amount\"), subject to Section 4.6. Payment shall be made at the closing of the Liquidity Event or, if not paid at closing for administrative reasons, within thirty (30) days following the closing, subject to any escrow, holdback, or similar arrangement applied generally to holders of Common Stock.\n\n4.4 Conversion Option.\n(a) Conversion into Common Stock. If the Investor elects (or is deemed to elect) the conversion option, the Purchase Amount shall convert into shares of Common Stock at a conversion price per share equal to the Valuation Cap Price calculated immediately prior to the closing of the Liquidity Event (using Company Capitalization immediately prior to the Liquidity Event).\n(b) Participation in Liquidity Event. The Conversion Shares shall participate in the Liquidity Event on the same terms and conditions as the shares of Common Stock held by other holders of Common Stock, including being subject to the same treatment regarding escrow, indemnity, earnouts, and transaction expenses, pro rata based on their holdings.\n\n4.5 IPO Treatment. If the Liquidity Event is an IPO, this SAFE shall convert into shares of Common Stock immediately prior to the closing of the IPO at a conversion price per share equal to the lesser of (a) the price per share paid by the public in the IPO multiplied by (1 - Discount Rate) and (b) the Valuation Cap Price. The Company may require customary lock-up arrangements consistent with market practice and underwriting requirements.\n\n4.6 Priority; Limitations; Senior Securities.\n(a) Seniority. Any cash payment pursuant to this Section 4 shall be made subject to the prior rights (if any) of creditors and holders of any class or series of Capital Stock that is senior to Common Stock in liquidation.\n(b) Insufficient Proceeds. If there are insufficient proceeds legally available to pay the Liquidity Cash Amount in full to all SAFE holders electing cash, the Company shall pay the available proceeds to such SAFE holders pro rata based on their respective Purchase Amounts.\n\n4.7 Company Cooperation. The Company shall use commercially reasonable efforts to structure the Liquidity Event documentation so that the Investor receives the treatment elected pursuant to this Section 4, subject to Applicable Law and the requirements of the counterparty and/or underwriters.\n\n4.8 No Waiver of Statutory Rights. Nothing in this SAFE is intended to waive any nonwaivable rights that may apply to a party under Applicable Law with respect to payment timing or remedies; provided that this SAFE is an investment contract and not intended to be a contract for services."},{"id":"dissolution_event","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. DISSOLUTION EVENT","content":"5.1 Dissolution Before Conversion. If a Dissolution Event occurs prior to the conversion of this SAFE pursuant to Section 3, then, subject to Section 5.3, the Company shall pay the Investor an amount equal to the Purchase Amount.\n\n5.2 Timing of Payment. The Company shall pay the amount due under Section 5.1 as soon as reasonably practicable following the Dissolution Event and, in any event, to the extent legally available, within thirty (30) days after the date the Company completes the winding up of its affairs and is able to determine distributable proceeds; provided that the Company may delay payment to the extent required by Applicable Law or court order.\n\n5.3 Priority and Pro Rata Distribution.\n(a) Senior Claims. Payments under this Section 5 are subject to the prior rights of the Company’s creditors and any security holders with liquidation preferences senior to this SAFE by contract or by law.\n(b) Pro Rata. If there are insufficient funds to pay the full Purchase Amount to all holders of SAFEs and other instruments of equal priority, the Company shall distribute the available funds among such holders pro rata in proportion to their respective purchase amounts.\n\n5.4 Termination. Upon payment in full of the amount due under this Section 5, this SAFE shall terminate and be of no further force or effect.\n\n5.5 No Other Amounts. Except as expressly provided in this Section 5, the Investor shall not be entitled to any additional payment, interest, or return in connection with a Dissolution Event."},{"id":"valuation_cap_discount","type":"negotiable","order":6,"title":"6. VALUATION CAP AND DISCOUNT; CERTAIN ADJUSTMENTS","content":"6.1 Valuation Cap. The Valuation Cap is intended to provide the Investor with conversion pricing that reflects an agreed maximum valuation for purposes of determining the Valuation Cap Price. The Valuation Cap is not a representation, warranty, or estimate of the Company’s actual value at any time.\n\n6.2 Discount Rate. The Discount Rate is intended to provide the Investor with a conversion discount relative to the Equity Financing Price and/or IPO price, as applicable.\n\n6.3 Adjustments for Stock Splits and Similar Events. If, prior to the conversion or settlement of this SAFE, the Company effects any subdivision (stock split), combination (reverse stock split), reclassification, stock dividend, or similar recapitalization with respect to its Capital Stock without receipt of consideration, then the Valuation Cap shall be equitably adjusted in good faith by the Company to preserve the economic intent of this SAFE.\n\n6.4 Broadly Similar Instruments. If the Company issues other SAFEs or convertible instruments and applies capitalization definitions or pricing mechanics that differ from those set forth herein, the Company shall apply the definitions and mechanics in this SAFE consistently for purposes of determining the Investor’s conversion, unless the Investor elects more favorable terms pursuant to Section 7.6 (MFN) or otherwise agrees in writing.\n\n6.5 No Implied Most Favored Nation. Except as expressly set forth in Section 7.6, no other most favored nation or parity rights are implied.\n\n6.6 Optional Side Letter. The Parties may agree to an investor side letter addressing additional rights (e.g., information rights, pro rata participation, board observer rights) provided such side letter does not amend this SAFE unless it expressly states that it does."},{"id":"investor_rights","type":"optional","order":7,"title":"7. OPTIONAL — INVESTOR RIGHTS (INFORMATION; PRO RATA; MFN)","content":"7.1 Information Rights (Optional).\n(a) Delivery. Until the earlier of (i) conversion or termination of this SAFE or (ii) the Company’s IPO, the Company shall provide the Investor (so long as the Investor holds this SAFE and/or SAFE Securities) with the following:\n(i) Annual financial statements (balance sheet, income statement, and cash flow statement) within one hundred twenty (120) days after the end of each fiscal year; and\n(ii) A notice reasonably describing any anticipated Equity Financing, Liquidity Event, or Dissolution Event at least five (5) Business Days prior to the closing thereof (or as soon as reasonably practicable if earlier notice is not feasible).\n(b) Confidentiality Condition. The Company may require the Investor to keep such information confidential pursuant to Section 11.\n(c) Limitation. The Company shall have no obligation to provide information to the extent doing so would (i) breach any duty to a third party, (ii) violate Applicable Law, or (iii) jeopardize attorney-client privilege.\n\n7.2 Inspection Rights (Optional). Upon reasonable advance notice and during normal business hours, the Investor may reasonably inspect the Company’s books and records that relate to the Investor’s rights under this SAFE, provided that such inspection (a) does not unreasonably interfere with the Company’s operations and (b) is subject to confidentiality restrictions.\n\n7.3 Pro Rata Participation Right (Optional).\n(a) Right. In connection with the Equity Financing in which this SAFE converts, the Company shall offer the Investor the right to purchase additional Equity Financing Securities at the same price and on the same terms as other purchasers in such Equity Financing, in an amount up to the amount necessary for the Investor to maintain its pro rata ownership percentage of the Company’s Capital Stock on a fully-diluted basis immediately prior to the Equity Financing, calculated after giving effect to the conversion of this SAFE.\n(b) Procedure. The Company shall provide written notice of the pro rata opportunity, including the calculation of the investor’s pro rata amount, and the Investor shall have at least five (5) Business Days to elect to participate.\n(c) Allocation. If the Equity Financing is oversubscribed, the Company may reduce allocations on a pro rata basis among participating investors or as required by the lead investor(s), provided the Company applies such reduction in a commercially reasonable manner.\n\n7.4 No Voting Rights. The Investor shall have no voting or consent rights as a holder of this SAFE.\n\n7.5 No Board Rights. This SAFE does not grant the Investor any right to board representation or observer rights unless separately agreed in writing.\n\n7.6 Most Favored Nation (MFN).\n(a) MFN Right. If the Company issues any other SAFE prior to the conversion or termination of this SAFE and such other SAFE contains terms that are more favorable to the holder thereof than the terms of this SAFE (including a higher valuation cap, a greater discount, or additional investor protections directly related to conversion economics), then the Investor may elect to amend this SAFE to incorporate such more favorable terms.\n(b) Election Mechanism. The Investor shall deliver written notice to the Company identifying the more favorable terms and requesting incorporation within thirty (30) days after the Company provides notice (or the Investor otherwise becomes aware) of such issuance.\n(c) Limitations. The MFN right does not apply to terms that are specific to the identity of a holder (e.g., board seat, information rights not offered generally, strategic commercial terms) unless the Company expressly agrees.\n\n7.7 Termination of Optional Rights. The optional rights in this Section 7 (other than MFN if elected) may be modified or waived by written agreement and, where applicable, shall terminate upon conversion or termination of this SAFE."},{"id":"company_representations","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. COMPANY REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES; COVENANTS","content":"8.1 Organization; Good Standing. The Company is duly organized, validly existing, and (to the extent applicable for its entity type) in good standing under the laws of the State of New York, and has the requisite power and authority to own its properties and conduct its business as presently conducted.\n\n8.2 Authorization; Enforceability. The Company has all requisite power and authority to execute and deliver this SAFE and to perform its obligations hereunder. This SAFE has been duly authorized by all necessary corporate or other organizational action on the part of the Company. When executed and delivered by the Company, this SAFE constitutes a valid and binding obligation of the Company enforceable against the Company in accordance with its terms, subject to bankruptcy, insolvency, fraudulent conveyance, reorganization, moratorium, and similar laws affecting creditors’ rights and general principles of equity.\n\n8.3 Valid Issuance. The SAFE Securities, when issued in accordance with this SAFE and the Company’s organizational documents, will be duly authorized and validly issued, fully paid and non-assessable (or, in the case of an LLC or similar entity, issued in accordance with its operating agreement and free of any obligation to make additional capital contributions except as expressly agreed in writing).\n\n8.4 No Conflicts. The execution, delivery, and performance of this SAFE by the Company do not and will not (a) violate the Company’s organizational documents, (b) conflict with or result in a breach of any material agreement to which the Company is a party, or (c) violate Applicable Law, except, in each case, as would not reasonably be expected to have a material adverse effect on the Company’s ability to perform its obligations under this SAFE.\n\n8.5 Capitalization. The Company has provided or made available to the Investor, upon request, a description of its current capitalization and any material outstanding rights to acquire Capital Stock, subject to customary confidentiality and privilege limitations.\n\n8.6 Securities Law Compliance; Martin Act.\n(a) Exempt Offering. The Company intends that the issuance of this SAFE and the issuance of SAFE Securities upon conversion or settlement will be exempt from registration under the Securities Act and applicable state \"blue sky\" laws, including New York law and applicable regulations administered under the Martin Act.\n(b) No General Solicitation (if applicable). If the offering is conducted in reliance on an exemption that prohibits general solicitation, the Company represents that it has not engaged in general solicitation or general advertising in violation of such exemption.\n(c) Filings. The Company shall use commercially reasonable efforts to make any required notice filings (e.g., Form D and state notices) if the Company elects or is required to do so.\n\n8.7 No Broker or Finder. The Company has not taken any action that would give rise to a valid claim by any Person for a brokerage commission, finder’s fee, or similar compensation in connection with the issuance of this SAFE, based on arrangements made by the Company.\n\n8.8 Bad Actor. To the Company’s knowledge, none of the Company, any of its directors, executive officers, or other covered persons is subject to a \"disqualifying event\" as described in Rule 506(d) under Regulation D, except as disclosed in writing to the Investor.\n\n8.9 Compliance with Law. The Company is in compliance with Applicable Law applicable to its business, except where noncompliance would not reasonably be expected to have a material adverse effect on the Company.\n\n8.10 Covenant Regarding Notices of Triggering Events. The Company shall provide the notices contemplated by Sections 3, 4, 5, and 7 in good faith and with reasonable detail, including the anticipated closing date and a summary of how the conversion or payment will be calculated.\n\n8.11 No Advice. The Company acknowledges that it is not providing the Investor with tax, legal, or investment advice. The Company further acknowledges that statements regarding valuation, projections, or future performance, if any, may be forward-looking and subject to risk and uncertainty.\n\n8.12 Data Security and Privacy (Limited Representation). To the extent the Company maintains personal information of the Investor (including name, address, email, tax forms, and payment information), the Company will maintain a data security program that includes reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards consistent with New York’s SHIELD Act requirements to protect such information from unauthorized access, use, modification, or disclosure."},{"id":"investor_representations","type":"standard","order":9,"title":"9. INVESTOR REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES","content":"9.1 Authorization; Capacity. The Investor has full power and authority to execute and deliver this SAFE and to perform its obligations hereunder. If the Investor is an entity, the execution, delivery, and performance of this SAFE have been duly authorized by all necessary action.\n\n9.2 Accredited Investor; Investment Experience. The Investor is an \"accredited investor\" as defined in Rule 501 of Regulation D under the Securities Act, or otherwise qualifies to purchase this SAFE under an available exemption from registration, and has such knowledge and experience in financial and business matters as to be capable of evaluating the merits and risks of the investment.\n\n9.3 Investment Intent; Restricted Securities.\n(a) The Investor is acquiring this SAFE (and will acquire any SAFE Securities issued upon conversion or settlement) for investment for its own account, not as a nominee or agent, and not with a view to, or for resale in connection with, any distribution thereof in violation of the Securities Act.\n(b) The Investor understands that this SAFE and the SAFE Securities have not been registered under the Securities Act or any state securities laws, and must be held indefinitely unless subsequently registered or an exemption from registration is available.\n\n9.4 Access to Information. The Investor has had the opportunity to ask questions of, and receive answers from, the Company regarding the terms and conditions of this SAFE and the business, finances, and operations of the Company, and has obtained such additional information as the Investor deems necessary to verify the accuracy of any information furnished.\n\n9.5 Risk Acknowledgment. The Investor acknowledges and agrees that:\n(a) an investment in the Company is speculative and involves a high degree of risk;\n(b) the Investor may lose the entire Purchase Amount;\n(c) this SAFE is not a debt instrument and provides no maturity date, interest, or guaranteed return;\n(d) the timing and likelihood of an Equity Financing, Liquidity Event, or Dissolution Event are uncertain;\n(e) the valuation cap and discount (if any) may not provide the Investor with a favorable conversion price depending on future financings and capitalization;\n(f) the Company may raise additional financing that could dilute the Investor’s potential ownership.\n\n9.6 No Reliance; Independent Advisors. The Investor is not relying on the Company or any of its representatives for legal, tax, accounting, or investment advice and has consulted, or had the opportunity to consult, the Investor’s own advisors.\n\n9.7 No Broker or Finder. The Investor has not engaged any broker, finder, or agent for which the Company could be responsible for any commission or fee in connection with this SAFE.\n\n9.8 Compliance with Law; No Illegal Purpose. The Investor is purchasing this SAFE in compliance with Applicable Law. The Investor is not purchasing this SAFE with funds derived from unlawful activities and is not using this SAFE for any unlawful purpose.\n\n9.9 Sanctions; Anti-Money Laundering.\n(a) The Investor is not (and is not owned or controlled by any Person that is) the subject of sanctions administered or enforced by the U.S. Department of the Treasury’s Office of Foreign Assets Control or other relevant Governmental Authority.\n(b) The Investor acknowledges that the Company may be required to obtain certain information from the Investor to comply with applicable anti-money laundering and know-your-customer requirements.\n\n9.10 ERISA (If Applicable). If the Investor is an employee benefit plan or is investing plan assets, the Investor represents that the purchase and holding of this SAFE does not violate applicable law, including ERISA or Section 4975 of the Internal Revenue Code.\n\n9.11 Residency. The Investor’s principal residence or place of business is at the address set forth in the signature block, and the Investor will notify the Company promptly of any change.\n\n9.12 Survival. The representations and warranties of the Investor in this Section 9 shall survive the execution and delivery of this SAFE and the conversion or settlement of this SAFE."},{"id":"transfer_and_assignment","type":"negotiable","order":10,"title":"10. TRANSFER; ASSIGNMENT","content":"10.1 General Restriction on Transfer. The Investor may not transfer, sell, assign, pledge, encumber, or otherwise dispose of this SAFE (a \"Transfer\") except as expressly permitted by this Section 10 and in compliance with Applicable Law.\n\n10.2 Permitted Transfers. Notwithstanding Section 10.1, the Investor may Transfer this SAFE without the Company’s prior written consent to:\n(a) an Affiliate of the Investor;\n(b) a trust for estate planning purposes for the benefit of the Investor and/or the Investor’s immediate family members;\n(c) upon the Investor’s death, by will or intestacy to the Investor’s heirs, executors, administrators, or personal representatives; or\n(d) any other transferee approved in writing by the Company (such approval not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned, or delayed).\n\n10.3 Conditions to Transfer. As a condition to any Transfer:\n(a) the transferee must agree in writing to be bound by the terms of this SAFE as the \"Investor\" hereunder;\n(b) the Company may require reasonable evidence that the Transfer complies with Applicable Law, including securities law exemptions and any required legends or transfer restrictions; and\n(c) the Investor shall remain liable for any obligations of the Investor that arose prior to the effective date of the Transfer.\n\n10.4 Securities Law Legends; Stop-Transfer Instructions. The Company may place appropriate legends on any SAFE Securities issued under this SAFE and may issue stop-transfer instructions to its transfer agent (if any) to enforce the restrictions contained herein and under Applicable Law.\n\n10.5 Assignment by the Company. The Company may not assign this SAFE or its obligations hereunder without the prior written consent of the Investor, except that the Company may assign this SAFE in connection with a merger, consolidation, reorganization, or other transaction in which the Company is not the surviving entity, provided that the successor entity expressly assumes the Company’s obligations under this SAFE.\n\n10.6 Effect of Transfer. Any purported Transfer in violation of this Section 10 shall be null and void to the fullest extent permitted by Applicable Law.\n\n10.7 Further Assurances. Each Party agrees to execute and deliver such additional documents as may be reasonably necessary to effectuate any permitted Transfer or assignment consistent with this SAFE."},{"id":"confidentiality_privacy_trade_secrets","type":"optional","order":11,"title":"11. OPTIONAL — CONFIDENTIALITY; PRIVACY; TRADE SECRETS","content":"11.1 Confidential Information. \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed by or on behalf of the Company to the Investor (whether before or after the Effective Date) relating to the Company or its business, technology, customers, suppliers, finances, plans, or operations, including information shared pursuant to Section 7, and including trade secrets under New York common law.\n\n11.2 Confidentiality Obligation. The Investor agrees (a) to keep Confidential Information strictly confidential, (b) not to disclose Confidential Information to any third party except as permitted by Section 11.3, and (c) not to use Confidential Information for any purpose other than evaluating and monitoring the Investor’s investment in the Company.\n\n11.3 Permitted Disclosures. The Investor may disclose Confidential Information:\n(a) to the Investor’s attorneys, accountants, advisors, financing sources, and Affiliates who have a need to know and are bound by confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those set forth herein;\n(b) to the extent required by Applicable Law, regulation, court order, or subpoena, provided that, to the extent legally permitted, the Investor gives the Company prompt written notice and reasonably cooperates (at the Company’s expense) with the Company’s efforts to seek protective treatment; and\n(c) with the Company’s prior written consent.\n\n11.4 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Investor can demonstrate by written records: (a) is or becomes publicly available through no breach of this SAFE, (b) was already known to the Investor without restriction at the time of disclosure, (c) is independently developed by the Investor without use of the Company’s Confidential Information, or (d) is lawfully received from a third party without breach of a duty of confidentiality.\n\n11.5 Data Protection; NY SHIELD Act. To the extent either Party receives, stores, processes, or transmits \"private information\" (as defined under New York General Business Law § 899-bb, as amended, commonly referred to as the SHIELD Act) of the other Party or individuals associated with the other Party in connection with this SAFE, such Party shall maintain reasonable safeguards to protect such information and shall notify the other Party promptly upon discovery of any unauthorized access to or acquisition of such information to the extent required by Applicable Law.\n\n11.6 Defend Trade Secrets Act Notice of Immunity (Whistleblower Notice). Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b), an individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that: (a) is made (i) in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, and (ii) solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (b) is made in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal. Further, an individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding if the individual: (1) files any document containing the trade secret under seal; and (2) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order.\n\n11.7 Equitable Relief. The Investor acknowledges that unauthorized disclosure or use of Confidential Information could cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be an inadequate remedy. Accordingly, the Company shall be entitled to seek injunctive or other equitable relief in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity, without the necessity of posting a bond to the fullest extent permitted by Applicable Law.\n\n11.8 Term. The obligations in this Section 11 begin on the Effective Date and continue until the earlier of (a) the third (3rd) anniversary of termination or conversion of this SAFE or (b) with respect to trade secrets, for so long as the applicable information remains a trade secret under New York common law.\n\n11.9 No Non-Compete. Nothing in this SAFE is intended to create any non-competition obligation. The Parties acknowledge that non-compete provisions are disfavored and strictly scrutinized under New York law and agree that no non-compete restriction is imposed by this SAFE."},{"id":"miscellaneous","type":"standard","order":12,"title":"12. MISCELLANEOUS","content":"12.1 Governing Law. This SAFE and any dispute arising out of or relating to this SAFE or the transactions contemplated hereby shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of New York, without regard to conflict of laws principles that would result in the application of the laws of another jurisdiction.\n\n12.2 Venue; Jurisdiction; Service of Process.\n(a) Exclusive Venue. Subject to Section 12.2(b), the Parties agree that any action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this SAFE shall be brought exclusively in the state courts of New York located in {{venue_county}} County, or, if jurisdiction exists, the federal courts of the United States located in {{venue_county}} County, New York.\n(b) Equitable Relief. Notwithstanding Section 12.2(a), the Company may seek temporary, preliminary, or permanent injunctive relief or other equitable relief in any court of competent jurisdiction to protect trade secrets or Confidential Information.\n(c) Consent to Jurisdiction. Each Party irrevocably submits to the personal jurisdiction of such courts and waives any objection based on inconvenient forum.\n(d) Service. Each Party agrees that service of process may be effected by the methods for notice set forth in Section 12.4 to the extent permitted by Applicable Law, in addition to any other lawful means.\n\n12.3 Waiver of Jury Trial. EACH PARTY HEREBY IRREVOCABLY WAIVES, TO THE FULLEST EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION OR PROCEEDING ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS SAFE.\n\n12.4 Notices.\n(a) Form. All notices or other communications under this SAFE must be in writing and will be deemed given when: (i) delivered personally, (ii) sent by nationally recognized overnight courier (with written confirmation of receipt), (iii) mailed by certified or registered mail, return receipt requested, postage prepaid, or (iv) sent by email with confirmation of transmission (excluding automated out-of-office replies), provided that email notices for legal disputes must also be sent by one of the methods in clauses (i)-(iii).\n(b) Addresses.\n(i) If to the Company: {{party_a_company}}, Attention: {{party_a_name}}, {{party_a_address}}, Email: {{party_a_email}}.\n(ii) If to the Investor: {{party_b_name}}, {{party_b_address}}, Email: {{party_b_email}}.\n(c) Updates. Either Party may change its notice address by notice to the other Party in accordance with this Section 12.4.\n\n12.5 Amendment; Waiver.\n(a) Amendment. This SAFE may be amended, modified, or supplemented only by a written instrument executed by the Company and the Investor.\n(b) Waiver. No waiver of any provision of this SAFE will be effective unless in writing and signed by the Party against whom the waiver is to be enforced. A waiver of any breach will not be a waiver of any other breach.\n\n12.6 Entire Agreement. This SAFE (together with any exhibits, addenda, or side letters expressly incorporated by reference) constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties with respect to the subject matter hereof and supersedes all prior and contemporaneous understandings, agreements, and representations, whether written or oral.\n\n12.7 Severability. If any provision of this SAFE is held to be invalid, illegal, or unenforceable in any respect under Applicable Law, the validity, legality, and enforceability of the remaining provisions shall not be affected. The Parties shall negotiate in good faith a lawful and enforceable substitute provision that most nearly reflects the original intent.\n\n12.8 Counterparts. This SAFE may be executed in any number of counterparts, each of which shall be deemed an original, and all of which together shall be deemed one and the same instrument.\n\n12.9 Electronic Signatures; ESRA; Records.\n(a) Electronic Signatures. This SAFE and any notices, consents, elections, or other documents related hereto may be executed and delivered by electronic signature and electronic means.\n(b) New York ESRA and Federal E-SIGN. The Parties intend that this SAFE satisfies the requirements of the New York Electronic Signatures and Records Act (State Technology Law Article 3) and the federal Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (E-SIGN), and that electronic records and signatures shall have the same legal effect as original paper records and handwritten signatures.\n(c) Record Retention. Each Party agrees to retain a copy of this SAFE and related records evidencing performance hereunder for at least six (6) years, or longer if required by Applicable Law, recognizing that certain New York statutes (including, where applicable, NY Labor Law Article 44 and NYC Admin. Code § 20-927 et seq.) impose record-retention expectations for covered arrangements.\n\n12.10 Assignment; Successors. This SAFE binds and benefits the Parties and their permitted successors and assigns in accordance with Section 10.\n\n12.11 No Partnership; No Agency. Nothing in this SAFE creates any partnership, joint venture, agency, fiduciary relationship (other than any fiduciary duties that may exist under Applicable Law by virtue of corporate office or status), employment, or other relationship between the Parties. Neither Party has authority to bind the other.\n\n12.12 No Publicity. The Investor shall not issue any press release or public announcement regarding this SAFE or the Company without the Company’s prior written consent, except as required by Applicable Law.\n\n12.13 Expenses. Each Party shall bear its own legal, accounting, and other professional fees and expenses incurred in connection with this SAFE and the transactions contemplated hereby, unless otherwise agreed in writing.\n\n12.14 Remedies Cumulative. The rights and remedies provided in this SAFE are cumulative and not exclusive of any rights or remedies provided by Applicable Law.\n\n12.15 Construction; Currency. All monetary amounts are in U.S. dollars unless expressly stated otherwise.\n\n12.16 Securities Law Legends; Transfer Restrictions. The Investor acknowledges that this SAFE and the SAFE Securities are subject to restrictions on transfer under the Securities Act, New York securities laws (including requirements and enforcement authority associated with the Martin Act), and this SAFE. The Company may require an opinion of counsel reasonably satisfactory to the Company prior to any transfer of SAFE Securities, unless the transfer is pursuant to an effective registration statement or a well-established exemption.\n\n12.17 Payment Administration; Timing; Late Payment.\n(a) Administrative Cooperation. The Investor agrees to provide reasonably requested information and documentation necessary for the Company to make payments (including wire instructions and tax forms) and to issue SAFE Securities.\n(b) Payment Timing for Cash Obligations. If the Company is required to pay cash to the Investor under Sections 4 or 5, the Company shall pay such cash at the time specified in those Sections, and in any event, if not paid at closing, within thirty (30) days following the applicable closing or determination date, subject to escrow/holdback arrangements applied generally to holders of Common Stock.\n(c) Statutory Rights Preserved. Nothing in this SAFE is intended to limit any nonwaivable statutory rights regarding payment timing or remedies that may apply under Applicable Law in a properly applicable context.\n\n12.18 Optional — Compliance With NY Labor Law / Freelance Isn’t Free Act (No Services Intended).\n(a) No Services Intended. The Parties reaffirm that this SAFE is not a contract for services and is not intended to be governed by worker-classification statutes.\n(b) Separate Agreement Required for Services. If the Company and Investor (or an Affiliate of Investor) enter into a separate arrangement under which the Investor provides services as an independent contractor, then the Parties intend to comply with applicable worker classification requirements under New York Labor Law and, if applicable, the New York City Freelance Isn’t Free Act and New York Labor Law Article 44, including (to the extent applicable based on the facts and location): a written agreement for covered work of $800 or more, payment within thirty (30) days of completion if not otherwise specified, anti-retaliation protections, and record retention for six (6) years.\n(c) No Retaliation (If Applicable). To the extent any such service arrangement is covered by anti-retaliation provisions of Applicable Law, the Company shall not retaliate against the service provider for exercising protected rights.\n\n12.19 Optional — Non-Solicitation (Narrow; No Non-Compete). If separately initialed or agreed by the Parties in writing, the Investor agrees that for a period of twelve (12) months following the Effective Date, the Investor will not knowingly solicit for employment any employee of the Company with whom the Investor had material direct contact through the Investor’s relationship with the Company; provided that general solicitations not targeted at such employees (including general advertisements) shall not be prohibited. The Parties agree that this provision is intended to be narrowly tailored and does not constitute a non-competition agreement.\n\n12.20 Further Assurances. Each Party shall execute and deliver such additional documents and take such further actions as may be reasonably necessary to carry out the intent and purposes of this SAFE.\n\n12.21 No Third-Party Beneficiaries. Except as expressly provided herein, this SAFE is for the sole benefit of the Parties and their permitted successors and assigns and does not confer any rights on any other Person.\n\n12.22 Time of the Essence. Time is of the essence for the performance of obligations under this SAFE where timing is expressly stated or where the nature of the obligation reasonably implies time sensitivity.\n\n12.23 Survival. Sections that by their nature should survive (including Sections 10, 11 (if included), and this Section 12) shall survive any conversion, termination, or settlement of this SAFE."}]'::jsonb,
