-- Update: Consulting Services Agreement (Texas)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Consulting Services Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between (a) {{party_a_company}}, a {{party_a_entity_type}} with its principal place of business at {{party_a_address}} ("Client"), and (b) {{party_b_company}}, a {{party_b_entity_type}} with its principal place of business at {{party_b_address}} ("Consultant"). Client and Consultant may be referred to herein individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties."',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, Client desires to retain Consultant to provide certain professional consulting services and/or deliverables in accordance with the terms of this Agreement and any applicable statement(s) of work;
WHEREAS, Consultant represents that Consultant has the experience, personnel (if applicable), skill, and resources necessary to perform the Services (defined below) in a timely and professional manner;
WHEREAS, the Parties desire to set forth in writing their mutual understandings regarding the Services, compensation, intellectual property, confidentiality, data protection, and other matters.

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS; DOCUMENT STRUCTURE; ORDER OF PRECEDENCE","content":"1.1 Definitions. Capitalized terms used in this Agreement have the meanings set forth below or elsewhere in this Agreement.\n\n(a) \"Acceptance\" has the meaning set forth in Section 3.4.\n\n(b) \"Affiliate\" means, with respect to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with such Party, where \"control\" means the power to direct management and policies, whether through ownership of voting securities, by contract, or otherwise.\n\n(c) \"Background IP\" means any inventions, software, works of authorship, methodologies, know-how, tools, processes, templates, models, libraries, scripts, utilities, and other intellectual property that (i) was developed, acquired, or owned by Consultant prior to the Effective Date, or (ii) is developed by Consultant outside the scope of the Services without use of Client Confidential Information, and in each case is not Work Product.\n\n(d) \"Client Materials\" means materials, content, data, documents, specifications, designs, trademarks, information, equipment, systems, or other items provided or made available by or on behalf of Client to Consultant in connection with the Services.\n\n(e) \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed or made available (whether in writing, orally, visually, electronically, or by inspection) by or on behalf of a Party (the \"Disclosing Party\") to the other Party (the \"Receiving Party\") that is (i) designated as confidential or proprietary, (ii) by its nature or the circumstances of disclosure reasonably should be understood to be confidential, or (iii) constitutes a trade secret under applicable law, including the Texas Uniform Trade Secrets Act (Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A) (\"TUTSA\") and the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act (18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq.) (\"DTSA\"). Confidential Information includes Client Materials, Work Product (until publicly released by Client), business plans, product plans, customer lists, pricing, financial information, security information, technical data, source code, and Personal Data.\n\n(f) \"Deliverables\" means the tangible and/or intangible outputs, reports, analyses, recommendations, designs, software, documentation, training materials, or other items expressly identified as deliverables in a Statement of Work.\n\n(g) \"Documentation\" means user guides, technical documentation, runbooks, specifications, or other written materials (in any format) that Consultant is required to deliver as part of the Deliverables.\n\n(h) \"Harmful Code\" means any virus, worm, Trojan horse, time bomb, ransomware, malware, or other code intended to (i) disrupt, disable, damage, or impair operations; (ii) permit unauthorized access; or (iii) exfiltrate data.\n\n(i) \"Personal Data\" means information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked (directly or indirectly) with an identified or identifiable individual, including any data regulated as \"personal data\" or \"personal information\" under applicable privacy or data security laws. Personal Data includes, as applicable, \"Sensitive Data\" (if any) as defined under the Texas Data Privacy and Security Act (\"TDPSA\").\n\n(j) \"Processing\" means any operation or set of operations performed on Personal Data, whether or not by automated means, such as collection, recording, organization, structuring, storage, use, disclosure, transmission, deletion, or destruction.\n\n(k) \"Security Incident\" means any actual or reasonably suspected unauthorized access to, acquisition of, disclosure of, or loss of (i) Personal Data, or (ii) Client systems, credentials, or Confidential Information, including events that may trigger notice obligations under Texas Business & Commerce Code Chapter 521 or other applicable law.\n\n(l) \"Services\" means the professional consulting services described in Section 2 and the applicable Statement(s) of Work.\n\n(m) \"Statement of Work\" or \"SOW\" means a written statement of work, work order, or similar document that (i) references this Agreement, (ii) describes the Services and/or Deliverables, and (iii) is executed by authorized representatives of both Parties.\n\n(n) \"Term\" has the meaning set forth in Section 6.1.\n\n(o) \"Work Product\" means all Deliverables and any other work product, inventions (whether patentable or not), discoveries, developments, designs, works of authorship, documentation, data compilations, reports, and other materials created, conceived, authored, reduced to practice, or otherwise developed by Consultant (alone or with others) in the course of performing the Services, excluding Background IP and Third-Party Materials.\n\n(p) \"Third-Party Materials\" means any materials, content, software (including open-source software), data, or other items owned by a third party that are incorporated into or provided with the Work Product.\n\n1.2 Document Structure; Statements of Work. The Parties may enter into one or more SOWs. Each SOW will be subject to the terms of this Agreement unless expressly stated otherwise in that SOW.\n\n1.3 Order of Precedence. If there is a conflict between this Agreement and an SOW, the documents will control in the following order: (a) the SOW, but only with respect to the scope, schedule, Deliverables, and fees for that SOW and only to the extent the SOW expressly states it is overriding a specific section of this Agreement; then (b) this Agreement.\n\n1.4 Interpretation. Headings are for convenience only. The words \"include,\" \"includes,\" and \"including\" are deemed to be followed by \"without limitation.\" Any reference to a \"day\" means a calendar day unless expressly stated otherwise.\n\n1.5 Counterparts; Electronic Records. This Agreement and any SOW may be executed in counterparts and delivered by electronic means. The Parties agree that electronic signatures and records are enforceable under the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (Texas Business & Commerce Code Chapter 322) and the federal E-SIGN Act."},{"id":"engagement","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. ENGAGEMENT AND SERVICES","content":"2.1 Engagement. Client hereby engages Consultant, and Consultant hereby accepts such engagement, to perform the Services in accordance with this Agreement, each applicable SOW, and any written project plan mutually agreed by the Parties.\n\n2.2 Scope of Services. The Services will be as described in {{services_description}} and/or in the applicable SOW(s), including any assumptions, dependencies, and constraints stated therein.\n\n2.3 Standard of Performance. Consultant will perform the Services (a) in a professional and workmanlike manner consistent with generally accepted industry standards for similar services; (b) using appropriately skilled and trained personnel (if any); and (c) in compliance with applicable law.\n\n2.4 No Authority to Bind. Consultant has no authority to bind Client, enter into contracts on Client’s behalf, or make representations or warranties on behalf of Client unless Client expressly authorizes Consultant in a separate writing signed by Client.\n\n2.5 Project Management; Points of Contact. Each Party will designate a point of contact for day-to-day communications: Client: {{client_poc_name}} ({{client_poc_email}}) and Consultant: {{consultant_poc_name}} ({{consultant_poc_email}}), or such other contact as either Party may designate by written notice.\n\n2.6 Client Responsibilities; Timely Cooperation. Client will timely provide access to information, systems (as applicable), personnel, and Client Materials reasonably necessary for Consultant to perform the Services. Consultant is not responsible for delays, increased costs, or performance issues caused by Client’s failure to provide such cooperation or by changes to Client requirements.\n\n2.7 Access to Premises and Systems. If the Services require Consultant to access Client premises and/or systems, Consultant will comply with Client’s reasonable written security and access policies provided in advance, including any acceptable use policy, visitor policy, and safety rules. Consultant will not intentionally introduce Harmful Code into Client systems.\n\n2.8 Subcontractors and Personnel. Consultant may not subcontract performance of material portions of the Services without Client’s prior written consent, not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed. Consultant remains responsible for its subcontractors’ acts and omissions as if they were Consultant’s own. Consultant will ensure that any subcontractors or personnel who may access Client Confidential Information are bound by written confidentiality and assignment obligations at least as protective as this Agreement.\n\n2.9 Changes; Change Orders. Either Party may request changes to scope, assumptions, Deliverables, timeline, or fees. Any change must be documented in a written change order or amended SOW signed by both Parties. Consultant is not obligated to commence changed work until the Parties have agreed in writing on the change.\n\n2.10 Suspension. Client may direct Consultant to suspend Services for up to {{suspension_max_days}} days upon written notice. During a suspension, Consultant will use reasonable efforts to mitigate costs; however, Client remains responsible for fees and non-cancelable commitments incurred consistent with this Agreement and the applicable SOW."},{"id":"deliverables_acceptance","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. DELIVERABLES; MILESTONES; ACCEPTANCE","content":"3.1 Deliverables and Milestones. If an SOW identifies Deliverables and/or milestones, Consultant will use commercially reasonable efforts to deliver the Deliverables and meet milestone dates in accordance with the SOW. Any dates are estimates unless the SOW expressly states they are firm deadlines.\n\n3.2 Delivery Format and Method. Deliverables will be delivered in the format(s) and via the method(s) set forth in the SOW, or if not specified, in a commercially reasonable format selected by Consultant. If Deliverables are delivered via electronic means, Client is responsible for maintaining access credentials and inbox capacity for receipt.\n\n3.3 Client Review and Feedback. Within {{acceptance_review_period_days}} days after delivery of a Deliverable (the \"Review Period\"), Client will either (a) provide written acceptance, or (b) provide a written rejection describing in reasonable detail any material nonconformity with the applicable acceptance criteria.\n\n3.4 Acceptance. Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, a Deliverable will be deemed \"Accepted\" upon the earliest of: (a) Client’s written acceptance; (b) expiration of the Review Period without a timely written rejection; or (c) Client’s use of the Deliverable for production, commercial, or operational purposes (other than testing or evaluation).\n\n3.5 Rejection and Remedy. If Client timely rejects a Deliverable, Consultant will use commercially reasonable efforts to correct the identified nonconformity and redeliver the Deliverable. The Parties will repeat the review process described above. Client’s sole and exclusive remedy for failure to meet acceptance criteria is re-performance or correction as described in this Section 3.5, except to the extent prohibited by law or as otherwise expressly stated in an SOW.\n\n3.6 Dependencies and Assumptions. Consultant’s performance may depend on Client providing timely feedback, access, and accurate information. If Client requests or requires work based on incomplete or inaccurate inputs, the Parties will address resulting rework via a change order.\n\n3.7 Records for Time-and-Materials. If fees are based on hourly or daily rates, Consultant will maintain reasonable records of time spent and will provide summary time reporting with invoices upon request. Client may reasonably request clarification regarding time entries; however, Client may not unreasonably withhold payment of undisputed portions of an invoice.\n\n3.8 Delivery of Work Product Upon Termination. If this Agreement or an SOW is terminated, Consultant will deliver to Client any Work Product completed and paid for as of the termination effective date, subject to Section 8 (Intellectual Property) and Section 9 (Confidentiality) and payment of any undisputed amounts due."},{"id":"fees_payment","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. FEES; INVOICING; EXPENSES; TAXES","content":"4.1 Fees and Pricing Model. In consideration for performance of the Services, Client will pay Consultant the fees described in the applicable SOW or, if not specified, as follows: (a) fixed fees totaling {{payment_amount}} and/or (b) time-and-materials at an hourly rate of {{hourly_rate}}. Any fees not expressly included are excluded.\n\n4.2 Invoicing Schedule. Consultant will invoice as set forth in the SOW. If no schedule is stated, Consultant will invoice monthly in arrears for time-and-materials Services and upon milestone completion for fixed-fee Deliverables. Invoices will be sent to {{invoice_delivery_email}} and/or such other address as Client designates in writing.\n\n4.3 Payment Terms. Client will pay all undisputed invoice amounts within {{payment_terms_days}} days after receipt. Payments will be made via {{payment_method}}. Client will include invoice reference information reasonably requested by Consultant.\n\n4.4 Disputed Amounts. If Client disputes an invoice in good faith, Client will notify Consultant in writing within {{invoice_dispute_days}} days after receipt, describing the basis for the dispute in reasonable detail. The Parties will promptly work to resolve disputes. Client will pay all undisputed portions in accordance with Section 4.3.\n\n4.5 Late Payments; Interest; Collection Costs. Past-due undisputed amounts will accrue interest at the lesser of (a) {{late_fee_rate_percent}}% per month, or (b) the maximum rate permitted by applicable Texas law. Client will reimburse Consultant for reasonable costs of collection of past-due undisputed amounts, including reasonable attorneys’ fees, as permitted by law.\n\n4.6 Expenses. Unless otherwise stated in an SOW, Consultant is responsible for its expenses. If an SOW permits reimbursement, (a) expenses must be pre-approved in writing by Client (email acceptable), (b) expenses must be reasonable, actually incurred, and supported by documentation, and (c) reimbursement is limited to {{expense_cap_amount}} in the aggregate unless Client approves otherwise in writing. Travel time is billable only if expressly stated in an SOW.\n\n4.7 Taxes; Withholding. Consultant is responsible for all taxes arising from amounts paid under this Agreement, including federal income taxes, self-employment taxes, and any other applicable taxes (excluding taxes on Client’s net income). Client will not withhold payroll taxes or pay unemployment insurance on Consultant’s behalf. If a taxing authority requires withholding from payments to Consultant, Client may withhold and remit the required amount and will provide evidence of such remittance.\n\n4.8 Tax Forms. Consultant will provide Client with a completed IRS Form W-9 (or other appropriate form) upon request. Client may issue IRS Form 1099 as required.\n\n4.9 No Setoff. Client may not set off or withhold amounts owed to Consultant except for amounts disputed in good faith in accordance with Section 4.4 or as required by law.\n\n4.10 Rate Changes. Consultant may not increase rates during the Term for an existing SOW unless the SOW expressly allows rate adjustments or the Parties agree in writing.\n\n4.11 Most-Favored Invoicing Practices (Optional). If {{enable_po_requirement}} is true, Client’s obligation to pay is conditioned on Consultant including the applicable purchase order number on each invoice, provided that Client timely provides such purchase order number."},{"id":"consultant_status","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. CONSULTANT STATUS; WORKER CLASSIFICATION; INSURANCE","content":"5.1 Independent Contractor Relationship. Consultant is and will remain an independent contractor. Nothing in this Agreement creates an employer-employee relationship, partnership, joint venture, agency, fiduciary relationship, or other form of legal association between the Parties. Consultant is not authorized to represent itself as an employee or agent of Client.\n\n5.2 Control of Means and Manner. Subject to the requirements of this Agreement and any SOW, Consultant will determine the means, manner, and method of performing the Services, including the selection and supervision of any personnel used by Consultant.\n\n5.3 Texas Labor Code; Proper Classification. The Parties intend and agree that Consultant is properly classified as an independent contractor under applicable law, including the Texas Labor Code and applicable federal law. Consultant is solely responsible for (a) wages and benefits for its personnel (if any); (b) compliance with employment laws applicable to Consultant; (c) workers’ compensation coverage (if any) and unemployment insurance (if applicable); and (d) maintaining any required business registrations and licenses.\n\n5.4 No Benefits. Consultant is not eligible for, and waives any right to, participate in Client’s employee benefit plans, including any health, retirement, vacation, sick leave, or other benefits.\n\n5.5 Other Clients; Non-Exclusivity. Consultant may provide services to other clients, provided that doing so does not (a) cause Consultant to breach this Agreement, (b) create a conflict of interest that materially impairs performance, or (c) require use or disclosure of Client Confidential Information.\n\n5.6 Personnel Screening and Conduct (Optional). If {{require_background_checks}} is true and to the extent permitted by law, Consultant will ensure that personnel with access to Client premises or systems have undergone reasonable background screening consistent with industry practice. Consultant is responsible for the conduct of its personnel.\n\n5.7 Insurance (Optional). If {{require_insurance}} is true, Consultant will maintain during the Term the following coverages with reputable insurers: (a) commercial general liability with limits of not less than {{cgl_limit}} per occurrence; (b) professional liability/errors and omissions with limits of not less than {{e_o_limit}}; and (c) cyber/privacy liability with limits of not less than {{cyber_limit}} (if Consultant processes Personal Data or accesses Client systems). Upon request, Consultant will provide certificates of insurance.\n\n5.8 Safety; Compliance with Site Policies. If Services are performed on Client’s premises, Consultant will comply with Client’s reasonable written safety and security policies provided in advance and applicable to contractors.\n\n5.9 No Immigration Advice; Work Authorization. Consultant represents it is authorized to perform the Services in the United States and will ensure its personnel (if any) are authorized to work in the United States as required by law."},{"id":"term_termination","type":"standard","order":6,"title":"6. TERM AND TERMINATION","content":"6.1 Term. This Agreement begins on the Effective Date and continues until the earlier of (a) {{expiration_date}}, if specified, or (b) completion of the Services under all SOWs (the \"Term\"), unless terminated earlier in accordance with this Section 6.\n\n6.2 Termination for Convenience. Either Party may terminate this Agreement and/or any SOW for convenience upon {{notice_period}} days’ prior written notice to the other Party, unless the applicable SOW states a different notice period.\n\n6.3 Termination for Cause. Either Party may terminate this Agreement and/or any SOW immediately upon written notice if the other Party: (a) materially breaches this Agreement and fails to cure such breach within {{cure_period_days}} days after receipt of written notice describing the breach in reasonable detail; (b) becomes insolvent, makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, files or has filed against it a petition in bankruptcy that is not dismissed within 60 days, or has a receiver appointed; or (c) engages in fraud, willful misconduct, or unlawful conduct in connection with this Agreement.\n\n6.4 Suspension for Non-Payment. If Client fails to pay undisputed amounts when due and such failure continues for {{nonpayment_cure_days}} days after written notice, Consultant may suspend performance until amounts are paid, without liability for resulting delay.\n\n6.5 Effect of Termination. Upon any termination or expiration: (a) Consultant will promptly cease performing the terminated Services; (b) each Party will return or destroy the other Party’s Confidential Information in accordance with Section 9.8; (c) Client will pay Consultant for all Services performed and expenses incurred in accordance with this Agreement through the effective date of termination, plus any non-cancelable commitments approved by Client; and (d) for fixed-fee SOWs, fees will be prorated based on work completed, unless the SOW provides a different mechanism.\n\n6.6 Transition Assistance (Optional). If {{enable_transition_assistance}} is true, upon termination for convenience by Client, Consultant will provide reasonable transition assistance for up to {{transition_hours}} hours at Consultant’s then-current rates, provided Client requests such assistance within 30 days after termination and pays all undisputed amounts due.\n\n6.7 Survival. The following provisions survive termination or expiration: Sections 4 (to the extent payment obligations accrued), 8 (Intellectual Property), 9 (Confidentiality), 10 (Privacy and Data Security), 11 (Representations and Compliance) (to the extent by their nature), 12 (Limitation of Liability), 13 (Indemnification), 15 (Governing Law; Venue), 16 (General Provisions), and any other provisions that by their nature should survive."},{"id":"intellectual_property","type":"negotiable","order":7,"title":"7. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; WORK PRODUCT","content":"7.1 Work Product Definition. \"Work Product\" is defined in Section 1.1(o). For clarity, Work Product includes interim materials created specifically for Client in performing the Services (e.g., drafts, working papers, and prototypes) to the extent they are included in the Deliverables or necessary for Client’s use of the Deliverables.\n\n7.2 Work Made for Hire; Assignment. To the maximum extent permitted by law, Work Product that qualifies as a \"work made for hire\" under U.S. copyright law will be deemed a work made for hire for Client. To the extent any Work Product does not qualify as a work made for hire or ownership does not automatically vest in Client, Consultant hereby irrevocably assigns, transfers, and conveys to Client all right, title, and interest worldwide in and to the Work Product, including all intellectual property rights therein.\n\n7.3 Further Assurances; Power of Attorney. Consultant will execute and deliver, and will cause its personnel to execute and deliver, such further documents and take such further actions as Client may reasonably request to evidence, perfect, maintain, enforce, or defend Client’s rights in the Work Product. If Consultant fails to do so after reasonable request, Consultant hereby appoints Client as Consultant’s attorney-in-fact (coupled with an interest) solely to execute such documents on Consultant’s behalf.\n\n7.4 Background IP; License. Consultant retains all rights in Background IP. To the extent any Background IP is incorporated into or necessary to use the Work Product, Consultant grants to Client a perpetual, irrevocable (except for Client’s material breach of license terms), worldwide, royalty-free, transferable, sublicensable license to use, reproduce, modify, prepare derivative works of, distribute, perform, display, and otherwise exploit such Background IP solely as part of or in connection with Client’s use of the Work Product and Client’s products and services.\n\n7.5 Consultant Tools and General Know-How. Consultant may use generalized skills, experience, and know-how in performing the Services. Nothing in this Agreement prevents Consultant from providing services to others using Consultant’s general knowledge and experience, provided Consultant does not use or disclose Client Confidential Information or infringe Client’s intellectual property rights.\n\n7.6 Client Materials. Client retains all rights in Client Materials. Client grants Consultant a limited, non-exclusive, non-transferable license to use Client Materials solely to perform the Services during the Term.\n\n7.7 Third-Party Materials; Open Source. Consultant will not incorporate Third-Party Materials into Work Product unless: (a) Consultant identifies the Third-Party Materials in writing to Client prior to delivery (or as soon as practicable), (b) Consultant has the legal right to incorporate and license such Third-Party Materials as contemplated, and (c) Client approves in writing where the Third-Party Materials impose material restrictions (including copyleft open-source licenses). Upon request, Consultant will provide a written list of Third-Party Materials included in the Work Product and applicable license terms.\n\n7.8 Moral Rights. To the extent permitted by law, Consultant waives and agrees not to assert any \"moral rights\" or similar rights in the Work Product. Where such rights cannot be waived, Consultant agrees not to enforce such rights against Client or its successors and assigns.\n\n7.9 No Harmful Code. Consultant represents and warrants that, to Consultant’s knowledge after reasonable practices, the Work Product will not contain Harmful Code designed to disrupt, disable, or compromise Client’s systems or data.\n\n7.10 Portfolio Use (Optional). If {{allow_portfolio_use}} is true, Consultant may include non-confidential, non-sensitive descriptions of the Services in Consultant’s marketing materials (excluding Client Confidential Information), provided Consultant obtains Client’s prior written approval for any use of Client’s name, logos, or trademarks.\n\n7.11 Pre-Existing Third-Party Restrictions. Consultant will not grant Client rights in any materials subject to third-party restrictions that would prevent Client from exercising the rights granted in this Agreement, unless Client expressly accepts such restrictions in writing."},{"id":"confidentiality","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS; INJUNCTIVE RELIEF; DTSA NOTICE","content":"8.1 Purpose; Use Limitation. The Receiving Party will use the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information solely to perform its obligations and exercise its rights under this Agreement (the \"Permitted Purpose\"). The Receiving Party will not use the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information for any other purpose, including to compete with the Disclosing Party or to solicit its customers, except as expressly permitted in writing.\n\n8.2 Protection Standard. The Receiving Party will protect the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information using at least the same degree of care it uses to protect its own confidential information of like kind (but no less than reasonable care). The Receiving Party will implement reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards to prevent unauthorized use, access, disclosure, or loss.\n\n8.3 Permitted Disclosures. The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information only to its employees, officers, directors, agents, contractors, and professional advisors who (a) have a need to know for the Permitted Purpose, and (b) are bound by written confidentiality obligations at least as protective as this Agreement. The Receiving Party is responsible for any breach by such persons.\n\n8.4 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by contemporaneous written records: (a) is or becomes publicly available through no breach of this Agreement; (b) was lawfully known to the Receiving Party prior to disclosure by the Disclosing Party; (c) is lawfully received from a third party without breach of any duty of confidentiality; or (d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.\n\n8.5 Trade Secrets; TUTSA and DTSA. The Parties acknowledge that certain Confidential Information may constitute trade secrets under TUTSA and DTSA. The Receiving Party will not acquire trade secrets by improper means and will not use or disclose trade secrets except as permitted by this Agreement. The Receiving Party acknowledges that misappropriation may cause irreparable harm.\n\n8.6 Compelled Disclosure. If the Receiving Party is required by law, regulation, court order, subpoena, or governmental request to disclose Confidential Information, the Receiving Party will (to the extent legally permitted) promptly notify the Disclosing Party in writing and reasonably cooperate (at the Disclosing Party’s expense) with efforts to seek a protective order or other appropriate remedy. The Receiving Party will disclose only the portion legally required and will use reasonable efforts to ensure confidential treatment.\n\n8.7 Non-Disclosure Period; Trade Secrets. The confidentiality and non-use obligations in this Section 8 apply during the Term and for {{confidentiality_years}} years thereafter; provided that, with respect to trade secrets, such obligations continue for so long as the information remains a trade secret under applicable law.\n\n8.8 Return or Destruction. Upon the Disclosing Party’s written request or upon termination/expiration of this Agreement, the Receiving Party will promptly (a) return or destroy all Confidential Information in its possession or control, including copies, extracts, and summaries, and (b) certify in writing upon request that it has complied. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Receiving Party may retain (i) archival copies automatically stored under routine backup procedures, and (ii) copies required to be retained by law or professional obligations, provided such retained information remains subject to this Agreement and is not accessed except as required.\n\n8.9 No License. Except as expressly stated in this Agreement, neither Party grants the other any license or other rights in its Confidential Information by disclosure under this Agreement.\n\n8.10 Injunctive Relief. The Parties agree that a breach of this Section 8 may cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be an insufficient remedy. Accordingly, in the event of actual or threatened breach, the non-breaching Party may seek equitable relief, including temporary restraining orders, preliminary injunctions, and permanent injunctions, in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity, without the necessity of posting bond to the extent permitted by law.\n\n8.11 DTSA Whistleblower Immunity Notice (18 U.S.C. § 1833(b)). Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement:\n(a) An individual will not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that (i) is made in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, and solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (ii) is made in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal.\n(b) An individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding, if the individual (i) files any document containing the trade secret under seal, and (ii) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order.\n\n8.12 Publicity. Neither Party will issue press releases or public statements regarding this Agreement without the other Party’s prior written consent, except as required by law or securities regulations."},{"id":"privacy_security","type":"standard","order":9,"title":"9. PRIVACY; DATA SECURITY; SECURITY INCIDENTS","content":"9.1 Scope. This Section 9 applies to the extent Consultant Processes Personal Data on behalf of Client, accesses Client systems, or otherwise handles information that is subject to privacy or data security obligations.\n\n9.2 Roles. Unless otherwise stated in an SOW or a separate data processing addendum (\"DPA\"), the Parties intend that: (a) Client is the business/controller with respect to Personal Data it provides or makes available; and (b) Consultant is a service provider/processor acting on Client’s instructions for the limited purpose of performing the Services.\n\n9.3 Compliance with Privacy and Security Laws. Consultant will comply with applicable privacy and data security laws in performing the Services, which may include (as applicable) the Texas Data Privacy and Security Act (TDPSA) (effective July 1, 2024, as amended), Texas Business & Commerce Code Chapter 521 (breach notification and identity theft protections), and applicable federal laws. Consultant will not intentionally take any action that would cause Client to violate applicable privacy law.\n\n9.4 Data Minimization; Purpose Limitation. Consultant will (a) Process Personal Data only as necessary to perform the Services and only in accordance with Client’s documented instructions, and (b) not sell Personal Data or Process Personal Data for targeted advertising or profiling in furtherance of decisions that produce legal or similarly significant effects concerning an individual, except as expressly authorized in writing by Client.\n\n9.5 Security Measures. Consultant will implement and maintain a written information security program appropriate to the nature of the Services and the sensitivity of the data and systems accessed. At a minimum, Consultant will implement reasonable safeguards, which may include as appropriate: (a) access controls and least-privilege principles; (b) unique user IDs and strong authentication (and multi-factor authentication where feasible) for system access; (c) encryption in transit and at rest for sensitive information, where appropriate; (d) secure configuration and patch management; (e) vulnerability management; (f) malware protection; (g) secure development practices if software is delivered; and (h) security awareness training for personnel with access to Client data.\n\n9.6 Security Incident Notice. Consultant will notify Client without undue delay, and in any event within {{security_incident_notice_hours}} hours after becoming aware of a Security Incident. Such notice will include, to the extent known and legally permitted: (a) the nature of the Security Incident; (b) the categories and approximate number of affected individuals and records (if applicable); (c) likely consequences; (d) measures taken or proposed to address the incident; and (e) a point of contact for follow-up. Consultant will promptly supplement the notice as additional information becomes available.\n\n9.7 Cooperation and Mitigation. Consultant will reasonably cooperate with Client’s investigation, mitigation, and remediation efforts related to any Security Incident, including by providing relevant logs, reports, and reasonable access to personnel. Consultant will not notify any third party (including affected individuals or regulators) regarding a Security Incident involving Client data without Client’s prior written consent unless required by law, in which case Consultant will provide advance notice to Client to the extent legally permitted.\n\n9.8 Subprocessors. Consultant will not engage subcontractors or other third parties to Process Personal Data (\"Subprocessors\") without ensuring they are bound by written terms that provide a level of protection for Personal Data at least as protective as this Agreement. Upon Client’s request, Consultant will provide a list of Subprocessors materially involved in Processing Personal Data for Client.\n\n9.9 Data Location; Cross-Border Transfers (Optional). If {{restrict_data_location}} is true, Consultant will store and Process Personal Data only in {{permitted_data_locations}} unless Client approves otherwise in writing.\n\n9.10 Data Retention and Deletion. Consultant will retain Personal Data only for as long as necessary to perform the Services or as required by law. Upon Client’s written request or upon termination/expiration of the applicable SOW, Consultant will delete or return Personal Data in its possession or control, except to the extent retention is required by law or is stored in backups not readily accessible, in which case Consultant will isolate and protect such retained data and delete it in accordance with normal backup deletion cycles.\n\n9.11 DPA (Optional). If {{require_dpa}} is true, the Parties will in good faith execute Client’s standard DPA or a mutually agreed DPA, and the DPA will control to the extent of conflict with this Agreement regarding Processing of Personal Data.\n\n9.12 Audit and Assessments (Optional). If {{enable_security_audit}} is true, upon reasonable prior notice and no more than once per year (unless a Security Incident occurs), Client may request (a) a summary of Consultant’s security controls relevant to the Services, (b) copies of available third-party security certifications or reports (e.g., SOC 2) if any, and/or (c) a reasonable security questionnaire. Any on-site audit will be subject to reasonable confidentiality and security restrictions and scheduling.\n\n9.13 Sensitive Data and Regulated Data (Optional). If the Services involve Sensitive Data, protected health information, payment card data, or other regulated data types identified in the SOW ({{regulated_data_description}}), the Parties will agree in writing on additional controls and contractual terms appropriate to such data (e.g., HIPAA BAA, PCI DSS responsibilities)."},{"id":"representations_warranties","type":"standard","order":10,"title":"10. REPRESENTATIONS; WARRANTIES; LEGAL COMPLIANCE","content":"10.1 Mutual Authority. Each Party represents and warrants that: (a) it is duly organized, validly existing, and in good standing (if applicable) under the laws of its jurisdiction of formation; (b) it has the power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement; and (c) this Agreement constitutes a valid and binding obligation enforceable against it in accordance with its terms, subject to applicable bankruptcy and equitable principles.\n\n10.2 Consultant Performance Warranty. Consultant represents and warrants that it will perform the Services in a professional and workmanlike manner consistent with generally accepted industry standards.\n\n10.3 Non-Infringement. Consultant represents and warrants that, to Consultant’s knowledge, the Work Product as delivered and used by Client as permitted under this Agreement will not infringe or misappropriate any U.S. intellectual property right of a third party. This warranty does not apply to claims arising from (a) Client Materials or specifications provided by Client, (b) modifications not made by Consultant, (c) combinations with items not provided by Consultant, or (d) use other than as permitted under this Agreement.\n\n10.4 Compliance with Laws. Consultant will comply with applicable laws and regulations in performing the Services, including laws related to anti-bribery, anti-corruption, and unfair competition. Consultant represents that it is not prohibited from performing the Services due to sanctions or debarment.\n\n10.5 Export Controls. Consultant will not provide or transfer any Work Product, software, or technical data in violation of applicable export control or sanctions laws.\n\n10.6 Client Responsibilities. Client represents and warrants that it has the rights necessary to provide Client Materials to Consultant for use in performing the Services.\n\n10.7 Disclaimer. EXCEPT AS EXPRESSLY SET FORTH IN THIS AGREEMENT, NEITHER PARTY MAKES ANY WARRANTY, WHETHER EXPRESS, IMPLIED, STATUTORY, OR OTHERWISE, AND EACH PARTY EXPRESSLY DISCLAIMS ALL IMPLIED WARRANTIES, INCLUDING ANY IMPLIED WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, TITLE, AND NON-INFRINGEMENT.\n\n10.8 Professional Judgment. Consultant may provide recommendations and advice; however, Client is responsible for its business decisions and for implementing recommendations."},{"id":"limitation_of_liability","type":"negotiable","order":11,"title":"11. LIMITATION OF LIABILITY","content":"11.1 Exclusion of Certain Damages. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, NEITHER PARTY WILL BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER FOR ANY INDIRECT, INCIDENTAL, SPECIAL, CONSEQUENTIAL, EXEMPLARY, OR PUNITIVE DAMAGES, OR FOR ANY LOSS OF PROFITS, REVENUE, BUSINESS OPPORTUNITY, GOODWILL, OR DATA, ARISING OUT OF OR RELATED TO THIS AGREEMENT, EVEN IF ADVISED OF THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH DAMAGES.\n\n11.2 Liability Cap. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, EACH PARTY’S TOTAL AGGREGATE LIABILITY ARISING OUT OF OR RELATED TO THIS AGREEMENT WILL NOT EXCEED THE FEES PAID OR PAYABLE BY CLIENT TO CONSULTANT UNDER THE APPLICABLE SOW GIVING RISE TO THE CLAIM DURING THE {{liability_cap_lookback_months}} MONTHS IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING THE EVENT GIVING RISE TO THE CLAIM.\n\n11.3 Allocation of Risk. The Parties acknowledge that the fees reflect the allocation of risk under this Agreement and that, absent these limitations, the fees would be substantially higher.\n\n11.4 Exceptions. The limitations in this Section 11 do not apply to: (a) a Party’s payment obligations (including fees, expenses, and indemnification payments); (b) a Party’s fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence; (c) a Party’s infringement or misappropriation of the other Party’s intellectual property rights; or (d) breach of Section 8 (Confidentiality) or Section 9 (Privacy; Data Security), to the extent such limitations are not permitted by law. The Parties may optionally agree to a separate cap for data incidents in an SOW ({{data_liability_cap_amount}}).\n\n11.5 Time Limitation. To the extent permitted by law, no action arising out of this Agreement may be brought more than {{claims_limitations_months}} months after the cause of action accrues, except for claims for nonpayment or intentional misconduct.\n\n11.6 Essential Purpose. If any limited remedy is found to have failed of its essential purpose, the limitations of liability in this Agreement will continue to apply to the fullest extent permitted by law."},{"id":"indemnification","type":"negotiable","order":12,"title":"12. INDEMNIFICATION","content":"12.1 Consultant Indemnity. Consultant will defend, indemnify, and hold harmless Client and its Affiliates and their respective officers, directors, employees, and agents from and against any third-party claims, demands, suits, or proceedings (\"Claims\") and all related damages, losses, liabilities, penalties, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) arising out of or related to: (a) Consultant’s negligence, gross negligence, or willful misconduct; (b) a claim that the Work Product (excluding Client Materials and Third-Party Materials approved by Client) infringes or misappropriates a third party’s U.S. intellectual property right; (c) Consultant’s breach of Section 8 (Confidentiality) or Section 9 (Privacy; Data Security); or (d) bodily injury (including death) or tangible property damage to the extent caused by Consultant.\n\n12.2 IP Infringement Remedies. If the Work Product becomes (or in Consultant’s reasonable opinion is likely to become) the subject of an infringement Claim, Consultant may, at its expense and option: (a) procure for Client the right to continue using the Work Product; (b) modify or replace the Work Product so that it becomes non-infringing while materially preserving functionality; or (c) if (a) and (b) are not commercially reasonable, terminate the affected SOW and refund any prepaid fees for the infringing portion of the Work Product that were not earned.\n\n12.3 Client Indemnity. Client will defend, indemnify, and hold harmless Consultant and its Affiliates and their respective officers, directors, employees, and agents from and against any Claims and related losses arising out of or related to: (a) Client Materials or Client specifications, including claims that Client Materials infringe or misappropriate a third party’s rights; (b) Client’s use of the Work Product in violation of this Agreement; or (c) Client’s negligence or willful misconduct.\n\n12.4 Indemnification Procedure. The indemnified Party will: (a) promptly notify the indemnifying Party of any Claim (provided that failure to promptly notify will relieve the indemnifying Party only to the extent it is materially prejudiced); (b) provide reasonable cooperation at the indemnifying Party’s expense; and (c) allow the indemnifying Party to control the defense and settlement of the Claim. The indemnifying Party may not settle any Claim in a manner that imposes liability or obligations on the indemnified Party or admits fault on behalf of the indemnified Party without the indemnified Party’s prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed).\n\n12.5 Exclusive Remedy for IP Claims. This Section 12 states Client’s exclusive remedies and Consultant’s entire liability for third-party intellectual property infringement or misappropriation Claims regarding the Work Product.\n\n12.6 Insurance Offset (Optional). To the extent any loss is covered by insurance maintained by the indemnifying Party, the indemnifying Party remains responsible for deductibles and uninsured portions, subject to the limitations of this Agreement."},{"id":"optional_restrictive_covenants","type":"optional","order":13,"title":"13. OPTIONAL CLAUSE — RESTRICTIVE COVENANTS (NON-COMPETE; NON-SOLICIT; NO-HIRE) (TEXAS)","content":"13.1 Applicability. This Section 13 applies only if {{enable_restrictive_covenants}} is true. The Parties acknowledge that Texas law may enforce certain restrictive covenants if they are ancillary to or part of an otherwise enforceable agreement and contain reasonable limitations as to time, geographic area, and scope of activity restrained, consistent with Texas Business & Commerce Code § 15.50. The Parties further acknowledge that Texas courts may reform overbroad restrictions under Texas Business & Commerce Code § 15.51.\n\n13.2 Consideration; Ancillary Agreement. Consultant acknowledges that (a) Consultant will receive access to Client Confidential Information and trade secrets and/or specialized training, and (b) such access constitutes adequate consideration and forms part of the basis for this Agreement. The Parties intend this Section 13 to be ancillary to and part of an otherwise enforceable agreement.\n\n13.3 Non-Competition (Optional). During the Term and for {{noncompete_term_months}} months thereafter (the \"Restricted Period\"), Consultant will not, within {{noncompete_geography}} (the \"Restricted Area\"), directly or indirectly provide services that are the same as or substantially similar to the Services to any business that competes with Client’s business in {{restricted_business_description}} (the \"Restricted Business\"), where such services would require or inevitably use Client trade secrets or Confidential Information.\n\n13.4 Customer Non-Solicitation (Optional). During the Restricted Period, Consultant will not directly solicit for the purpose of providing competing services any customer or prospective customer of Client (a) with whom Consultant had material contact through the Services, or (b) whose identity or relevant needs Consultant learned through Client Confidential Information, in each case to provide services competitive with the Services.\n\n13.5 Employee/Contractor Non-Solicitation; No-Hire (Optional). During the Term and for {{nohire_term_months}} months thereafter, Consultant will not directly solicit for employment or engagement, or hire, any employee or independent contractor of Client with whom Consultant had material contact during performance of the Services; provided that general solicitations not targeted to such persons (e.g., general advertisements) will not violate this Section.\n\n13.6 Reasonableness; Reformation. Consultant agrees that the restrictions in this Section 13 are reasonable and necessary to protect Client’s legitimate business interests, including protection of Confidential Information and goodwill. If a court finds any restriction unenforceable, the Parties request that the court reform the restriction to the minimum extent necessary to render it enforceable and enforce it as reformed.\n\n13.7 Tolling. If Consultant breaches this Section 13, the Restricted Period will be tolled for the duration of the breach.\n\n13.8 Injunctive Relief. Consultant acknowledges that breach of this Section 13 may cause irreparable harm and that Client may seek injunctive relief in addition to any other remedies.\n\n13.9 Carve-Outs. Nothing in this Section 13 restricts Consultant from (a) owning less than 2% of a publicly traded company, or (b) providing services that do not implicate Client trade secrets or Confidential Information and do not violate any other obligations under this Agreement."},{"id":"dispute_resolution","type":"standard","order":14,"title":"14. DISPUTE RESOLUTION; EQUITABLE RELIEF","content":"14.1 Good-Faith Negotiation. Before initiating litigation (except for requests for temporary restraining orders or other emergency equitable relief), the Parties will attempt in good faith to resolve any dispute arising out of or relating to this Agreement by escalating the dispute to senior management representatives.\n\n14.2 Optional Mediation. If {{require_mediation}} is true, the Parties agree to attempt to resolve the dispute through non-binding mediation in {{venue_county}} County, Texas, using a mutually agreed mediator, before commencing litigation. Each Party will bear its own costs and will share the mediator’s fees equally.\n\n14.3 Equitable Relief. Notwithstanding Sections 14.1 and 14.2, either Party may seek injunctive or other equitable relief in any court of competent jurisdiction to prevent or curtail (a) breach of Section 8 (Confidentiality), (b) misappropriation of trade secrets under TUTSA/DTSA, (c) breach of Section 9 (Privacy; Data Security), or (d) infringement or misappropriation of intellectual property rights.\n\n14.4 Attorneys’ Fees. If {{prevailing_party_fees}} is true, the prevailing Party in any action arising out of this Agreement will be entitled to recover its reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs, to the extent permitted by law."},{"id":"governing_law_venue","type":"standard","order":15,"title":"15. GOVERNING LAW; VENUE; JURISDICTION; JURY TRIAL WAIVER","content":"15.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and all claims arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the Services, and the relationship of the Parties will be governed by the laws of the State of Texas, without regard to Texas choice-of-law rules that would result in the application of another jurisdiction’s laws.\n\n15.2 Exclusive Venue and Jurisdiction. Subject to Section 14.3 (Equitable Relief), the Parties agree that any legal action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement will be brought exclusively in the state courts located in {{venue_county}} County, Texas, or, if federal jurisdiction exists, the United States District Court with jurisdiction over {{venue_county}} County, Texas. Each Party irrevocably submits to the personal jurisdiction of such courts and waives any objection based on inconvenient forum.\n\n15.3 Service of Process. Each Party consents to service of process by (a) certified mail, return receipt requested, (b) nationally recognized overnight courier, or (c) any other method permitted by Texas law, at its notice address in Section 16.2.\n\n15.4 Waiver of Jury Trial. TO THE EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, EACH PARTY KNOWINGLY AND VOLUNTARILY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION OR PROCEEDING ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT.\n\n15.5 Waiver of Exemplary Damages for Contract Claims (Optional). If {{waive_exemplary_damages_contract}} is true, to the extent permitted by law, the Parties waive exemplary/punitive damages for claims arising solely in contract (excluding claims based on fraud or willful misconduct)."},{"id":"general","type":"standard","order":16,"title":"16. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"16.1 Notices. All notices, requests, demands, and other communications under this Agreement must be in writing and will be deemed given when: (a) delivered personally; (b) sent by nationally recognized overnight courier with tracking; (c) mailed by certified or registered mail, return receipt requested, postage prepaid; or (d) emailed with confirmation of transmission (provided that email will not be sufficient for notices of termination or indemnification claims unless the recipient confirms receipt in writing). Notices will be sent to the addresses below (or such other address a Party designates by notice):\n\nIf to Client:\n{{party_a_company}}\nAttn: {{party_a_notice_name}}\n{{party_a_notice_address}}\nEmail: {{party_a_notice_email}}\n\nIf to Consultant:\n{{party_b_company}}\nAttn: {{party_b_notice_name}}\n{{party_b_notice_address}}\nEmail: {{party_b_notice_email}}\n\n16.2 Assignment. Neither Party may assign or transfer this Agreement without the prior written consent of the other Party, except that either Party may assign this Agreement without consent to an Affiliate or successor in connection with a merger, acquisition, corporate reorganization, or sale of substantially all assets, provided the assigning Party gives prompt notice and the assignee assumes all obligations. Any assignment in violation of this Section is void.\n\n16.3 Subcontracting. Except as expressly permitted in Section 2.8, Consultant may not subcontract material obligations without Client’s prior written consent. Any permitted subcontracting does not relieve Consultant of responsibility for performance.\n\n16.4 Force Majeure. Neither Party will be liable for failure or delay in performing its obligations (other than payment obligations) due to events beyond its reasonable control, including acts of God, natural disasters, labor disputes not involving the affected Party’s workforce, war, terrorism, civil unrest, governmental actions, or widespread outages of telecommunications or cloud providers. The affected Party will promptly notify the other Party and use commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate the impact.\n\n16.5 Relationship of the Parties. The Parties are independent contractors. Neither Party will be deemed an agent of the other. Neither Party may make statements, warranties, or commitments on the other Party’s behalf without prior written authorization.\n\n16.6 Entire Agreement; Amendment. This Agreement, together with all SOWs and any exhibits expressly incorporated, constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties regarding its subject matter and supersedes all prior and contemporaneous agreements and understandings. Any amendment must be in a writing signed by both Parties.\n\n16.7 Severability. If any provision of this Agreement is held invalid or unenforceable, the remaining provisions will remain in full force and effect. The invalid provision will be modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it valid and enforceable while best effectuating the Parties’ intent.\n\n16.8 Waiver. No waiver of any breach will be deemed a waiver of any other breach. No waiver is effective unless in writing and signed by the waiving Party.\n\n16.9 Counterparts; Electronic Signatures. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which is deemed an original. Signatures delivered by electronic means (including PDF, click-to-sign, or other electronic signature) are binding and enforceable under Texas Business & Commerce Code Chapter 322 and the federal E-SIGN Act.\n\n16.10 Confidentiality of Agreement (Optional). If {{confidentiality_of_agreement}} is true, the terms of this Agreement are Confidential Information, except that either Party may disclose the existence and general nature of the relationship to its professional advisors, lenders, and potential acquirers under obligations of confidentiality.\n\n16.11 Further Assurances. Each Party will execute and deliver such further documents and take such further actions as may be reasonably necessary to carry out the intent of this Agreement.\n\n16.12 No Third-Party Beneficiaries. Except as expressly stated with respect to indemnified parties, there are no third-party beneficiaries to this Agreement.\n\n16.13 Interpretation; Drafting. The Parties acknowledge that each Party has had the opportunity to consult counsel. This Agreement will not be construed against either Party as the drafter.\n\n16.14 Optional Non-Compete Reference. Any non-compete, non-solicitation, or other restrictive covenant not set forth in Section 13 (if applicable) must be set forth in a separate written agreement or an SOW addendum signed by both Parties. The Parties acknowledge that enforceability in Texas is governed by Texas Business & Commerce Code § 15.50 and related provisions.\n\n16.15 Conflicts with Client Policies (Optional). If {{client_policy_applicable}} is true, Consultant will comply with Client’s written contractor policies provided to Consultant in advance and applicable to on-site access or system access, provided that no such policy will amend this Agreement unless expressly stated in a signed writing.\n\n16.16 Non-Disparagement (Optional). If {{enable_non_disparagement}} is true, during the Term and for {{non_disparagement_term_months}} months thereafter, neither Party will make public statements that it knows are materially false and disparaging about the other Party, its products, or its services; provided that truthful statements required by law or in connection with legal proceedings are permitted."}]'::jsonb,
  signature_block = 'IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Agreement as of {{signature_date}} (or, if later, the date of the last signature).

