-- Update: Freelance Services Agreement (Texas)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Freelance Services Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between {{party_a_company}} ("Hiring Party" or "Client"), with its principal place of business at {{party_a_address}}, and {{party_b_name}} doing business as {{party_b_company}} ("Freelancer" or "Contractor"), with an address at {{party_b_address}}. Hiring Party and Freelancer may be referred to individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties".

The Parties intend that this Agreement constitutes a binding contract. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts and delivered by electronic means. The Parties agree that electronic signatures and records shall be given legal effect to the fullest extent permitted under applicable law, including the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 322) and the federal Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act ("ESIGN").',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, Hiring Party desires to engage Freelancer to perform certain professional services and/or produce certain deliverables in connection with {{project_name}}; 

WHEREAS, Freelancer represents that Freelancer has the experience, skill, and resources to perform such services in a professional and workmanlike manner;

WHEREAS, the Parties desire to set forth their respective rights and obligations, including scope, deliverables, fees, intellectual property, confidentiality, and other terms;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises contained herein and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS; INTERPRETATION","content":"1.1 Defined Terms. Capitalized terms have the meanings set forth below or elsewhere in this Agreement.\n\n1.2 \"Acceptance\" or \"Accepted\" means Hiring Party’s written confirmation (including by email) that the applicable Deliverable conforms in all material respects to the Acceptance Criteria, or deemed acceptance under Section 3.\n\n1.3 \"Acceptance Criteria\" means the objective and/or written criteria for a Deliverable set forth in the Statement of Work or otherwise agreed in writing by the Parties, including specifications, formats, performance requirements, and compatibility requirements.\n\n1.4 \"Agreement\" means this Freelance Services Agreement, together with all exhibits, attachments, schedules, statements of work, change orders, and other written amendments or addenda executed or confirmed in writing by both Parties.\n\n1.5 \"Background IP\" means (a) any inventions, works of authorship, software, tools, templates, libraries, methodologies, designs, frameworks, documentation, data, know-how, trade secrets, or other intellectual property and materials owned or controlled by Freelancer prior to the Effective Date, and (b) materials developed by Freelancer outside the scope of Services without using or relying upon Hiring Party Confidential Information. Background IP includes Freelancer’s general skills, experience, and non-confidential know-how.\n\n1.6 \"Change Order\" means a written modification to the Services, Deliverables, Timeline, or Fees, signed by both Parties or otherwise confirmed in writing by authorized representatives of both Parties (including by email confirmation) in accordance with Section 5.\n\n1.7 \"Client Materials\" means any information, content, branding assets, data, documentation, materials, software, code, credentials, hardware, or other items provided or made available by or on behalf of Hiring Party to Freelancer in connection with the Services.\n\n1.8 \"Confidential Information\" has the meaning set forth in Section 11. Confidential Information includes Trade Secrets.\n\n1.9 \"Deliverables\" means the specific work product, outputs, and other items to be delivered by Freelancer to Hiring Party as part of the Services, as described in {{services_description}}, the Statement of Work (if any), and/or any Change Order.\n\n1.10 \"Disclosing Party\" means the Party disclosing Confidential Information.\n\n1.11 \"Effective Date\" has the meaning stated in the preamble.\n\n1.12 \"Fees\" means all amounts payable by Hiring Party to Freelancer for the Services, including any project fees, hourly fees, retainers, milestone payments, subscription fees (if any), and other charges specified in this Agreement, the Statement of Work, and/or a Change Order.\n\n1.13 \"Hiring Party\" has the meaning stated in the preamble and may also be referred to as \"Client.\" If Hiring Party is acting on behalf of an affiliated entity, business unit, or end customer, the Parties may identify such entity in a Statement of Work.\n\n1.14 \"Intellectual Property Rights\" means all rights arising under patent, copyright, trademark, trade secret, database protection, moral rights (to the extent recognized), and any other intellectual property or proprietary rights recognized in any jurisdiction, whether registered or unregistered.\n\n1.15 \"Invoice\" means a written request for payment delivered by Freelancer to Hiring Party that identifies the billing period (if applicable), Services performed, Deliverables (if applicable), amounts due, and reasonable supporting documentation upon request.\n\n1.16 \"Open Source Software\" means software components subject to license terms that require (as a condition of use, modification, or distribution) that such software or derivative works be disclosed or distributed in source code form, licensed for the purpose of making derivative works, or redistributed at no charge.\n\n1.17 \"Party\" and \"Parties\" have the meanings stated in the preamble.\n\n1.18 \"Personal Data\" means information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked, directly or indirectly, with an identified or identifiable individual, to the extent protected under applicable law. Personal Data may include \"Sensitive Personal Information\" or similar categories under applicable law.\n\n1.19 \"Receiving Party\" means the Party receiving Confidential Information.\n\n1.20 \"Services\" means the professional services to be performed by Freelancer as described in Section 2 and {{services_description}}, as may be modified by a Change Order.\n\n1.21 \"Statement of Work\" or \"SOW\" means a written statement of work, proposal, scope document, or similar document that describes Services, Deliverables, assumptions, timelines, and pricing, identified as {{statement_of_work_title}} (if applicable), and incorporated into this Agreement upon execution or written confirmation by both Parties.\n\n1.22 \"Term\" has the meaning set forth in Section 13.\n\n1.23 \"Third-Party Materials\" means any materials, content, code, data, software, fonts, stock assets, libraries, tools, or other items not owned by either Party that are used or incorporated into any Deliverable.\n\n1.24 \"Trade Secret\" means information that constitutes a trade secret under applicable law, including the Texas Uniform Trade Secrets Act, Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A (\"TUTSA\"), and the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act, 18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq. (\"DTSA\").\n\n1.25 \"Work Product\" means all Deliverables and other work product created, authored, developed, prepared, conceived, reduced to practice, or otherwise produced by Freelancer (alone or jointly with others) in the course of performing the Services, excluding Background IP and excluding Third-Party Materials not owned by Freelancer.\n\n1.26 Interpretation. In this Agreement: (a) \"including\" means \"including without limitation\"; (b) headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation; (c) words in the singular include the plural and vice versa; (d) references to \"days\" mean calendar days unless stated otherwise; and (e) any reference to a statute includes its amendments and successor provisions.\n\n1.27 Order of Precedence. If there is a conflict between the body of this Agreement and any SOW or Change Order, the following order of precedence applies unless expressly stated otherwise in the conflicting document: (a) a Change Order that expressly states it controls; (b) an SOW that expressly states it controls; (c) this Agreement; (d) any other attachments or exhibits."},{"id":"services","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. ENGAGEMENT; SCOPE OF SERVICES","content":"2.1 Engagement. Hiring Party hereby engages Freelancer to perform the Services, and Freelancer accepts such engagement, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement.\n\n2.2 Scope Description; SOW. The Services and Deliverables are described in {{services_description}} and/or the SOW (if any). The Parties acknowledge that a clear written scope is essential. If the Parties use an SOW, the SOW should include (as applicable): (a) Deliverables; (b) Acceptance Criteria; (c) milestones and due dates; (d) assumptions and exclusions; (e) tools/technology; and (f) pricing.\n\n2.3 Standard of Performance. Freelancer shall perform the Services in a professional and workmanlike manner, consistent with generally accepted industry standards for similar services, and in accordance with any applicable specifications expressly set forth in the SOW or agreed in writing.\n\n2.4 Method and Means. Subject to the requirements of this Agreement and the SOW (including deadlines and Acceptance Criteria), Freelancer retains control over the method, details, and means of performing the Services. Hiring Party may provide feedback, business objectives, and reasonable direction regarding desired outcomes.\n\n2.5 Hiring Party Responsibilities. Hiring Party shall: (a) provide timely access to Client Materials, personnel, and information reasonably necessary for Freelancer to perform the Services; (b) respond to Freelancer questions and approval requests within a reasonable time (or within any timelines stated in the SOW); (c) ensure that Client Materials are accurate and lawful for their intended use; and (d) designate a point of contact ({{client_contact_name}}; {{client_contact_email}}) authorized to provide instructions and approvals.\n\n2.6 Cooperation; Dependencies. Freelancer’s ability to meet deadlines and Acceptance Criteria may depend on Hiring Party’s cooperation, approvals, and timely delivery of Client Materials. Any delay by Hiring Party, or changes requested by Hiring Party, may require adjustments to the Timeline and/or Fees through a Change Order.\n\n2.7 Location; Access; Remote Work. Unless otherwise specified in the SOW, the Services may be performed remotely from a location determined by Freelancer. If on-site work is required, the Parties shall agree in writing on location(s), schedule, safety rules, and any access requirements.\n\n2.8 Subcontractors and Assistants. Freelancer shall not subcontract or delegate material portions of the Services to any third party without Hiring Party’s prior written consent, except for routine administrative support. If approved, Freelancer shall remain responsible for the acts and omissions of subcontractors and shall ensure subcontractors are bound by confidentiality and IP assignment obligations at least as protective as those in this Agreement.\n\n2.9 No Authority to Bind. Freelancer shall not have authority to enter into contracts or make commitments on behalf of Hiring Party, represent that Freelancer is an employee or agent of Hiring Party, or use Hiring Party’s name except as expressly authorized in writing.\n\n2.10 Optional: Background Checks / Policies. If required by Hiring Party and legally permissible, Freelancer shall comply with Hiring Party’s reasonable written security and access policies applicable to contractors (provided in advance), including any background check requirements described in the SOW. Hiring Party shall be responsible for any fees charged by third parties for required background checks unless otherwise stated in the SOW."},{"id":"deliverables_acceptance","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. DELIVERABLES; REVIEW AND ACCEPTANCE","content":"3.1 Delivery. Freelancer shall deliver Deliverables in the form and manner specified in the SOW or otherwise agreed in writing (e.g., file formats, repositories, transfer methods).\n\n3.2 Acceptance Period. Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, Hiring Party shall have {{acceptance_period_days}} days after delivery of a Deliverable to review and either Accept the Deliverable or provide a written notice of rejection.\n\n3.3 Rejection; Required Specificity. Any rejection notice must: (a) be in writing; (b) identify with reasonable specificity each material nonconformity with the Acceptance Criteria; and (c) include sufficient information for Freelancer to reproduce and address the issue. A rejection based on subjective preference or requirements not stated in the Acceptance Criteria may constitute a change in scope subject to Section 5.\n\n3.4 Deemed Acceptance. A Deliverable will be deemed Accepted if: (a) Hiring Party does not provide a rejection notice within the Acceptance Period; (b) Hiring Party uses the Deliverable in production or externally (other than for internal testing), unless such use is expressly for evaluation and communicated in writing; or (c) Hiring Party provides written confirmation of acceptance.\n\n3.5 Remedy for Valid Rejection. If Hiring Party timely rejects a Deliverable for material failure to meet the Acceptance Criteria, Freelancer shall use commercially reasonable efforts to correct the identified issues and re-deliver within a reasonable time or within the time stated in the SOW. The Parties acknowledge that correction efforts are limited to the Acceptance Criteria and do not include new scope.\n\n3.6 Partial Acceptance; Independent Modules. If a Deliverable includes distinct components that can reasonably be accepted independently, Hiring Party may accept conforming portions and reject only the nonconforming portions.\n\n3.7 Access and Credentials. If Deliverables require access to Hiring Party systems, accounts, or credentials, Hiring Party shall provide such access in a secure manner. Freelancer shall not be responsible for delays or performance issues caused by lack of access, revoked access, or changes to third-party platforms outside Freelancer’s control.\n\n3.8 Archival Copy. Unless otherwise specified, Freelancer may retain one archival copy of Deliverables solely to comply with recordkeeping obligations, resolve disputes, and/or for portfolio use as permitted under Section 10.12, subject to the confidentiality obligations in Section 11."},{"id":"timeline_milestones","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TIMELINE; MILESTONES; SCHEDULE","content":"4.1 Timeline. The expected schedule, milestones, and delivery dates (the \"Timeline\") are set forth in {{milestone_schedule}} and/or the SOW. The Parties acknowledge that dates may be estimates unless expressly stated as firm deadlines.\n\n4.2 Milestones. If the SOW includes milestones, each milestone may include (as applicable): (a) a description of milestone Deliverables; (b) dependencies (including required Hiring Party inputs); (c) a due date; and (d) a milestone payment.\n\n4.3 Delays Caused by Hiring Party. If Freelancer’s performance is delayed due to Hiring Party’s failure to provide timely feedback, approvals, access, Client Materials, or other dependencies, Freelancer shall not be deemed in breach due to such delay and the Timeline shall be equitably adjusted.\n\n4.4 Delays Caused by Freelancer. If Freelancer anticipates a material delay within Freelancer’s reasonable control, Freelancer shall promptly notify Hiring Party in writing, provide a proposed mitigation plan, and use commercially reasonable efforts to minimize delay.\n\n4.5 Suspension; Restart. Hiring Party may request in writing that Freelancer suspend work. Suspension may require a Change Order to adjust the Timeline and Fees, including remobilization costs, re-planning time, and rescheduling to Freelancer availability.\n\n4.6 Communication Cadence (Optional). Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, the Parties may agree on a cadence for status updates (e.g., weekly email updates or calls). Hiring Party acknowledges that excessive meetings, unscheduled calls, or ad hoc requests may reduce productive time and may be treated as billable time if hourly pricing applies.\n\n4.7 Time is of the Essence (Optional). If the Parties intend that time is of the essence for specific obligations, such intent must be stated in the SOW or a Change Order for the specific deadline(s)."},{"id":"changes","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. CHANGES; CHANGE ORDERS","content":"5.1 No Implied Scope Changes. The Services, Deliverables, Timeline, and Fees may be modified only through a Change Order. Informal requests, discussions, or feedback do not modify scope unless confirmed in writing.\n\n5.2 Change Request Process. Either Party may request changes by submitting a written change request describing the requested modification and the business reason. Within a reasonable time, Freelancer shall respond with an impact assessment describing any changes to: (a) Deliverables and Acceptance Criteria; (b) Timeline; (c) Fees (including additional hours, fixed fees, rush fees, or retainer adjustments); and (d) assumptions and responsibilities.\n\n5.3 Authorization. Freelancer is not obligated to begin work on a change request until a Change Order is executed or confirmed in writing by both Parties.\n\n5.4 Rates for Out-of-Scope Work. Unless otherwise specified in a Change Order, out-of-scope work shall be billed at the hourly rate of {{hourly_rate}} (or, if not specified, at Freelancer’s then-current standard rate communicated in writing), plus approved expenses.\n\n5.5 Emergency Changes. If an urgent issue requires immediate action to avoid material harm (e.g., security incident, production outage), Hiring Party may authorize work via email or messaging platform, and the Parties shall promptly document the change through a Change Order.\n\n5.6 Third-Party Platform Changes. If a third-party platform (e.g., hosting provider, social media platform, app store, SaaS tool) changes its APIs, terms, or functionality in a manner affecting the Deliverables, the Parties acknowledge that associated modifications may constitute a change in scope.\n\n5.7 No Waiver. Hiring Party’s payment for additional work or Freelancer’s performance of additional work does not waive the requirement that changes be documented in writing."},{"id":"payment","type":"standard","order":6,"title":"6. FEES; INVOICING; PAYMENT TERMS; TAXES","content":"6.1 Fee Structure. Hiring Party shall pay Freelancer the Fees described in {{services_description}} and/or the SOW, which may include one or more of the following:\n(a) Fixed Project Fee: {{payment_amount}};\n(b) Hourly Fees: {{hourly_rate}} per hour for time worked;\n(c) Retainer (Optional): {{retainer_amount}} due on or before the Effective Date, to be applied against future invoices as specified in the SOW;\n(d) Milestone Payments (Optional): as specified in {{milestone_schedule}} or the SOW;\n(e) Other fees: as specified in a Change Order.\n\n6.2 Invoice Frequency and Format. Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, Freelancer shall invoice {{invoice_frequency}}. Each Invoice will describe the Services performed and/or Deliverables delivered, and may include reasonable supporting detail (e.g., time entries, milestone reference). For hourly work, Freelancer may provide a summary of hours by task category.\n\n6.3 Payment Due Date. Hiring Party shall pay all undisputed amounts within {{invoice_due_days}} days after receipt of the Invoice (\"Net {{invoice_due_days}}\"). Payment shall be made via {{payment_method}} or another method agreed by the Parties in writing.\n\n6.4 Disputed Amounts. If Hiring Party disputes any portion of an Invoice, Hiring Party shall notify Freelancer in writing within ten (10) days of receipt of the Invoice (or within the payment due date, if sooner), identifying the disputed amount and the basis for the dispute in reasonable detail. The Parties shall work in good faith to resolve disputes promptly. Hiring Party shall timely pay all undisputed portions of the Invoice.\n\n6.5 Late Payments; Interest; Collection Costs. Past-due undisputed amounts shall accrue interest at the lower of: (a) {{late_interest_rate}}% per month, or (b) the maximum lawful rate permitted under Texas law. In addition, Hiring Party shall reimburse Freelancer for reasonable costs of collection of undisputed past-due amounts, including reasonable attorneys’ fees and court costs, to the extent permitted by law.\n\n6.6 Suspension for Nonpayment. If Hiring Party fails to pay undisputed amounts within ten (10) days after written notice of delinquency, Freelancer may suspend work until all past-due undisputed amounts are paid. The Timeline shall be adjusted to account for any suspension, and Freelancer shall not be responsible for delays resulting from such suspension.\n\n6.7 Deposit / Upfront Payment (Optional). If specified in the SOW, Hiring Party shall pay an upfront deposit of {{deposit_amount}} or {{deposit_percentage}}% of the total project fee prior to commencement. Unless otherwise required by law or stated in the SOW, deposits are non-refundable and are intended to reserve Freelancer capacity.\n\n6.8 No Setoff. Hiring Party shall not withhold or set off amounts due to Freelancer except for disputed amounts identified under Section 6.4 in good faith.\n\n6.9 Taxes.\n(a) Freelancer Taxes. Freelancer is solely responsible for all federal taxes, self-employment taxes, and other taxes, duties, or governmental charges arising from compensation paid under this Agreement.\n(b) No Withholding. Hiring Party will not withhold payroll taxes from payments to Freelancer. Freelancer may receive an IRS Form 1099 (or equivalent) as required.\n(c) Sales/Use Taxes. If applicable sales, use, or similar taxes are imposed on the Services or Deliverables, such taxes will be itemized on the Invoice and paid by Hiring Party unless Hiring Party provides a valid exemption certificate.\n\n6.10 Currency. All payments shall be in U.S. dollars unless otherwise agreed in writing.\n\n6.11 Payment Processor Fees (Optional). If Hiring Party requests payment via a credit card or third-party processor that charges transaction fees, the Parties may agree in writing whether such fees will be absorbed by Freelancer or reimbursed by Hiring Party.\n\n6.12 Audit of Time Records (Optional). For hourly Services, Hiring Party may reasonably request clarification regarding time entries within thirty (30) days after the Invoice date. Freelancer will cooperate in good faith, subject to Freelancer’s confidentiality obligations to other clients.\n\n6.13 Most-Favored Customer (Not Applicable). Unless expressly stated in a signed writing, this Agreement does not create any most-favored-customer pricing obligation."},{"id":"revisions","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. REVISIONS; CLIENT FEEDBACK; MEETINGS","content":"7.1 Included Revisions. Unless otherwise specified in the SOW, the Fees include up to {{included_revision_rounds}} rounds of reasonable revisions per Deliverable, provided that: (a) revision requests are consolidated and delivered in writing; (b) revisions are consistent with the Acceptance Criteria and agreed scope; and (c) Hiring Party provides feedback within the timeframes reasonably necessary to maintain the Timeline.\n\n7.2 Out-of-Scope Revisions. Revisions that change project direction, add new features, require substantial rework, or arise from new requirements not included in the scope are out-of-scope and shall be handled via Change Order.\n\n7.3 Review Materials and Consolidated Feedback. Hiring Party shall designate a reviewer or representative to provide consolidated feedback. Freelancer is not responsible for conflicting instructions provided by multiple Hiring Party personnel.\n\n7.4 Meeting Time (Optional). Unless otherwise specified, meetings, calls, and time spent responding to emails and messages related to the Services are billable time for hourly engagements, and are included within fixed-fee pricing only to the extent assumed in the SOW.\n\n7.5 Delays Due to Late Feedback. If Hiring Party does not provide feedback or approvals within the agreed or reasonable time, the Timeline shall be extended and Freelancer may reallocate scheduling based on availability.\n\n7.6 No Guarantee of Subjective Satisfaction. Unless the SOW states otherwise, Freelancer does not guarantee subjective satisfaction or aesthetic preference beyond meeting the Acceptance Criteria."},{"id":"expenses","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. EXPENSES; CLIENT-PROVIDED ACCOUNTS; THIRD-PARTY COSTS","content":"8.1 General Rule. Unless otherwise stated in the SOW or approved in writing in advance, Freelancer shall be responsible for ordinary overhead expenses (e.g., home office, standard software, internet access).\n\n8.2 Pre-Approved Reimbursable Expenses. Hiring Party shall reimburse Freelancer for reasonable, necessary, and pre-approved expenses incurred solely to perform the Services, including travel, lodging, shipping, specialized software, stock assets, or third-party services, up to a cap of {{expense_cap_amount}} unless otherwise approved in writing.\n\n8.3 Expense Documentation. Freelancer shall provide reasonable documentation upon request (e.g., receipts) for reimbursable expenses. Reimbursable expenses may be invoiced as incurred or with the next Invoice, as stated in the SOW.\n\n8.4 Client-Provided Accounts. If work requires third-party accounts (e.g., cloud hosting, analytics, ad platforms, design tool subscriptions), Hiring Party should provide its own accounts and credentials where feasible. If Freelancer uses Freelancer’s accounts at Hiring Party’s request: (a) Hiring Party shall pay all third-party charges; (b) Hiring Party acknowledges third-party terms apply; and (c) access may be revoked upon termination once appropriate transition is completed.\n\n8.5 Third-Party Licenses and Subscriptions. Unless specifically included in the Fees, third-party licenses, subscriptions, and usage fees are not included. Hiring Party is responsible for procuring and maintaining licenses needed for Client Materials or for ongoing use of Deliverables, unless the SOW states otherwise.\n\n8.6 Travel (Optional). If travel is required, the Parties shall agree in advance on: (a) travel dates; (b) per diem or expense policy; (c) booking responsibility; and (d) whether travel time is billable (and at what rate).\n\n8.7 No Markup (Optional). Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, Freelancer will not mark up reimbursable expenses and will invoice such expenses at cost."},{"id":"freelancer_status","type":"negotiable","order":9,"title":"9. INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR STATUS; TEXAS COMPLIANCE","content":"9.1 Independent Contractor. Freelancer is an independent contractor and not an employee, partner, joint venturer, agent, or legal representative of Hiring Party for any purpose. Nothing in this Agreement creates an employment relationship.\n\n9.2 No Benefits. Freelancer is not eligible to participate in any Hiring Party employee benefit plans, including health insurance, retirement plans, paid leave, unemployment insurance, or workers’ compensation coverage, unless required by applicable law and expressly agreed in writing.\n\n9.3 Control of Work. Freelancer retains the right to control and direct the manner and means of performing the Services, subject to the requirements of this Agreement and the SOW (including deliverables, deadlines, and Acceptance Criteria). Hiring Party may specify desired results and business requirements.\n\n9.4 Tools and Equipment. Freelancer shall provide Freelancer’s own tools, equipment, and workspace, except as expressly provided by Hiring Party in writing.\n\n9.5 Business of Freelancer; Other Clients. Freelancer may provide services to other clients, including competitors of Hiring Party, provided Freelancer does not use or disclose Hiring Party Confidential Information and does not create a conflict that materially impairs Freelancer’s ability to perform under this Agreement.\n\n9.6 Taxes and Reporting. Freelancer is responsible for all federal taxes and other governmental charges arising from payments under this Agreement. Hiring Party will not withhold taxes. Hiring Party may issue a Form 1099 as required.\n\n9.7 Texas Worker Classification; Labor Code Considerations. The Parties intend and agree that Freelancer is properly classified as an independent contractor under applicable law, including relevant provisions of the Texas Labor Code and guidance applied by the Texas Workforce Commission and other agencies. Freelancer shall not represent to any third party that Freelancer is an employee of Hiring Party.\n\n9.8 No Authority. Freelancer has no authority to bind Hiring Party, incur obligations on Hiring Party’s behalf, or make representations or warranties on behalf of Hiring Party.\n\n9.9 Insurance (Optional). If specified in the SOW or reasonably requested due to the nature of the Services, Freelancer shall maintain the following insurance during the Term: {{insurance_requirements}}. Upon request, Freelancer shall provide certificates of insurance.\n\n9.10 Safety and Compliance. If Services are performed on Hiring Party premises, Freelancer shall comply with reasonable on-site policies provided in advance, including safety and security procedures, provided such policies do not convert the relationship into employment.\n\n9.11 No Exclusivity. Unless the SOW expressly states otherwise, this Agreement is non-exclusive.\n\n9.12 Independent Business Expenses. Freelancer is responsible for expenses and costs associated with operating Freelancer’s business except as expressly reimbursable under Section 8."},{"id":"intellectual_property","type":"negotiable","order":10,"title":"10. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; OWNERSHIP; LICENSES","content":"10.1 Overview. This Section allocates ownership of Work Product and related IP between the Parties. The Parties intend for Hiring Party to obtain the rights necessary to use the Deliverables as contemplated, while preserving Freelancer’s Background IP.\n\n10.2 Work Made for Hire (If Applicable). To the extent permitted by law and to the extent any Work Product qualifies as a \"work made for hire\" under the U.S. Copyright Act, the Work Product shall be considered a work made for hire and owned by Hiring Party upon creation. To the extent any Work Product is not a work made for hire, the assignment provisions below apply.\n\n10.3 Assignment of Work Product. Subject to Section 10.6 (Freelancer Background IP) and Section 10.8 (Third-Party Materials), upon receipt of full and final payment of all Fees and reimbursable expenses due for the applicable Work Product, Freelancer hereby assigns to Hiring Party all right, title, and interest in and to the Work Product, including all Intellectual Property Rights therein.\n\n10.4 Further Assurances. Freelancer shall execute and deliver further documents and take such further actions reasonably requested by Hiring Party to evidence, perfect, or enforce Hiring Party’s rights in the Work Product, including assignments and declarations, provided Hiring Party reimburses Freelancer for reasonable out-of-pocket costs and pays Freelancer for time spent at Freelancer’s then-current hourly rate if not de minimis.\n\n10.5 Reservation of Rights. Except as expressly granted in this Agreement, each Party reserves all rights in its respective intellectual property.\n\n10.6 Freelancer Background IP; License. Freelancer retains all right, title, and interest in and to Freelancer’s Background IP. To the extent any Background IP is incorporated into, necessary to use, or delivered with the Work Product, Freelancer grants to Hiring Party a perpetual, worldwide, non-exclusive, royalty-free, fully paid, irrevocable (except for material breach uncured after notice), transferable license (with the right to sublicense) to use, reproduce, modify, create derivative works of, publicly perform, publicly display, distribute, and otherwise exploit such Background IP solely as incorporated in or necessary to use the Work Product for Hiring Party’s business purposes.\n\n10.7 Tools and Templates. Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, Freelancer may use general tools, templates, scripts, libraries, and know-how in performing the Services. Freelancer may reuse such general components for other clients, provided that Freelancer does not disclose Hiring Party Confidential Information and does not reuse Hiring Party-specific assets, branding, or proprietary materials.\n\n10.8 Third-Party Materials.\n(a) Identification. Freelancer shall inform Hiring Party in writing if Freelancer proposes to incorporate material Third-Party Materials into any Deliverable.\n(b) Licenses. Third-Party Materials are subject to their own license terms. Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, Hiring Party is responsible for obtaining and complying with licenses for Third-Party Materials required for ongoing use.\n(c) Open Source. Freelancer will not knowingly include Open Source Software in a manner that would require the Work Product (or Hiring Party proprietary software) to be disclosed or licensed in source code form, unless Hiring Party provides prior written consent after being informed of the relevant license obligations.\n\n10.9 Client Materials. Hiring Party owns and retains all right, title, and interest in and to Client Materials. Hiring Party grants Freelancer a limited, non-exclusive, revocable license to use Client Materials solely to perform the Services during the Term.\n\n10.10 Moral Rights; Waiver. To the extent permitted by applicable law, Freelancer waives and agrees not to assert any moral rights, droit moral, or similar rights in the Work Product, and agrees that Hiring Party may use, modify, and exploit the Work Product without attribution. Where waiver is not permitted, Freelancer agrees not to assert such rights to the maximum extent permitted.\n\n10.11 Credit (Optional). Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, Hiring Party has no obligation to provide attribution or credit to Freelancer.\n\n10.12 Portfolio Use (Optional). Unless {{portfolio_allowed}} is set to \"no\" in the SOW or a written notice by Hiring Party, Freelancer may display non-confidential portions of the Work Product in Freelancer’s portfolio or marketing materials after public release by Hiring Party, provided that: (a) Freelancer does not disclose Hiring Party Confidential Information; (b) Freelancer complies with Hiring Party’s written brand guidelines; and (c) Hiring Party may request removal of specific portfolio items for reasonable cause.\n\n10.13 Pre-Existing Deliverables and Licenses. If the Deliverables include items that are customarily licensed rather than assigned (e.g., fonts, stock images, plugins), the Parties agree such items are not Work Product and are instead governed by the applicable third-party or Freelancer license terms disclosed to Hiring Party.\n\n10.14 No Implied License to Hiring Party Marks. Except as needed to perform Services, nothing grants Freelancer rights to use Hiring Party trademarks, logos, or brand assets.\n\n10.15 IP Infringement Risk Allocation. The indemnities and limitations of liability in Sections 15 and 16 apply to IP-related claims. Hiring Party acknowledges that requested similarity to third-party works or use of Client Materials may increase infringement risk."},{"id":"confidentiality","type":"standard","order":11,"title":"11. CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS (TUTSA/DTSA); RETURN OF INFORMATION","content":"11.1 Definition of Confidential Information. \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed by or on behalf of a Party (the Disclosing Party) to the other Party (the Receiving Party), in any form, that (a) is designated as confidential or proprietary, (b) reasonably should be understood to be confidential given the nature of the information or the circumstances of disclosure, or (c) constitutes a Trade Secret. Confidential Information includes, without limitation: business plans; financial information; customer and prospect lists; pricing; product roadmaps; marketing strategies; non-public technical information; source code; software architectures; security information; inventions; processes; designs; specifications; and the terms of this Agreement (optional, unless disclosure is required for legal, accounting, or financing purposes).\n\n11.2 Trade Secrets. The Parties acknowledge that certain Confidential Information may constitute Trade Secrets protected under TUTSA (Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A) and/or DTSA and other applicable law. Receiving Party agrees to protect Trade Secrets with at least reasonable measures and in no event less than the measures Receiving Party uses to protect its own trade secrets of like importance.\n\n11.3 Confidentiality Obligations. The Receiving Party shall:\n(a) use Confidential Information solely for purposes of performing or receiving Services under this Agreement;\n(b) not disclose Confidential Information to any third party except as permitted by Section 11.4;\n(c) protect Confidential Information using reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards designed to prevent unauthorized use, access, or disclosure; and\n(d) promptly notify Disclosing Party upon becoming aware of any unauthorized access to or disclosure of Confidential Information.\n\n11.4 Permitted Disclosures. The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information only to its employees, contractors, agents, and professional advisors who have a need to know for purposes of this Agreement and who are bound by written obligations of confidentiality at least as protective as those set forth herein. Receiving Party shall be responsible for any breach of this Section by such persons.\n\n11.5 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by competent evidence: (a) is or becomes public through no breach of this Agreement; (b) was lawfully known by the Receiving Party without restriction prior to disclosure by Disclosing Party; (c) is lawfully received from a third party without breach of any obligation owed to Disclosing Party; or (d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to Disclosing Party Confidential Information.\n\n11.6 Compelled Disclosure. If the Receiving Party is required by law, regulation, subpoena, or court order to disclose Confidential Information, the Receiving Party shall (to the extent legally permitted) provide Disclosing Party prompt written notice and reasonably cooperate (at Disclosing Party’s expense) to seek a protective order or other appropriate remedy. If disclosure is required, Receiving Party shall disclose only the minimum amount legally required and shall use reasonable efforts to ensure confidential treatment.\n\n11.7 Return or Destruction. Upon the earlier of: (a) Disclosing Party’s written request, or (b) termination or expiration of this Agreement, Receiving Party shall promptly return or destroy (at Disclosing Party’s election) Disclosing Party Confidential Information in Receiving Party’s possession or control, including copies, notes, and summaries. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Receiving Party may retain copies to the extent required by law, regulation, or bona fide internal recordkeeping and backup policies, provided such retained information remains subject to this Agreement.\n\n11.8 No License. Except as expressly stated in this Agreement, no license or other rights to Confidential Information are granted by implication, estoppel, or otherwise.\n\n11.9 Equitable Relief. The Receiving Party acknowledges that unauthorized use or disclosure of Confidential Information, including Trade Secrets, may cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be an inadequate remedy. Accordingly, the Disclosing Party may seek injunctive or other equitable relief, in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity, without the necessity of posting bond to the extent permitted by law.\n\n11.10 Defend Trade Secrets Act Whistleblower Immunity Notice (18 U.S.C. § 1833(b)).\n(a) Immunity. An individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that is made: (i) in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (ii) in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal.\n(b) Anti-Retaliation. An individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding, if the individual: (i) files any document containing the trade secret under seal; and (ii) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order.\n\n11.11 Duration. The obligations in this Section begin on the Effective Date and continue during the Term and for {{confidentiality_period}} years after termination or expiration; provided that with respect to Trade Secrets, the obligations continue for so long as the information remains a trade secret under applicable law.\n\n11.12 Publicity; No Press Release. Neither Party shall issue press releases or public announcements regarding this Agreement or the relationship without the other Party’s prior written consent, except as required by law."},{"id":"privacy_data_security","type":"optional","order":12,"title":"12. DATA PRIVACY; DATA SECURITY; BREACH NOTIFICATION (TEXAS)","content":"12.1 Scope. This Section applies to the extent Freelancer creates, accesses, receives, stores, transmits, processes, or otherwise handles Personal Data, or otherwise handles data regulated by applicable privacy or security laws, in connection with the Services.\n\n12.2 Roles; Instructions. Hiring Party is the owner or controller of Client Materials and any Personal Data therein, and Freelancer acts as a service provider/processor to Hiring Party when processing Personal Data solely on Hiring Party’s documented instructions. Hiring Party shall provide instructions sufficient for Freelancer to perform the Services lawfully.\n\n12.3 Data Minimization. Freelancer shall use and access Personal Data only to the extent reasonably necessary to perform the Services and shall not sell Personal Data or use Personal Data for Freelancer’s own marketing or unrelated purposes.\n\n12.4 Security Measures. Freelancer shall implement and maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards appropriate to the nature of the information and the Services, which may include (as appropriate): least-privilege access; multi-factor authentication where available; encryption in transit; device security; secure credential storage; and secure disposal.\n\n12.5 Credentials and Access.\n(a) Hiring Party shall provide credentials using a secure method.\n(b) Freelancer shall not share credentials except with approved subcontractors bound by written confidentiality obligations.\n(c) Freelancer shall promptly revoke access for any subcontractor removed from the project.\n\n12.6 Security Incident Notification. Freelancer shall notify Hiring Party without undue delay after becoming aware of a confirmed unauthorized access to or acquisition of Personal Data or Hiring Party Confidential Information (a \"Security Incident\"). Such notice shall include, to the extent reasonably known: (a) a description of the incident; (b) categories of data potentially affected; (c) remediation steps taken or planned; and (d) recommended steps for Hiring Party.\n\n12.7 Texas Breach Notification Considerations. The Parties acknowledge that Texas law may impose obligations related to notification of certain data security breaches and identity theft matters, including under Texas Business & Commerce Code Chapter 521 (\"Identity Theft Enforcement and Protection Act\"). Hiring Party is responsible for determining whether legal notice to individuals or regulators is required, and for delivering any legally required notices, unless the SOW expressly assigns notice responsibilities to Freelancer.\n\n12.8 Cross-Border Transfers. If Personal Data is transferred or accessed across national borders, the Parties shall comply with applicable transfer restrictions. If additional contractual terms are required (e.g., a data processing addendum), the Parties agree to negotiate in good faith.\n\n12.9 Regulated Data. Hiring Party shall notify Freelancer in writing before providing any data subject to specialized regulations (e.g., HIPAA/medical information, GLBA financial information, COPPA children’s data, PCI-DSS payment card data, or export-controlled data). Unless expressly agreed in a signed SOW or addendum, Freelancer does not agree to act as a HIPAA \"business associate\" or to process regulated data requiring special compliance.\n\n12.10 Data Retention and Deletion. Upon termination or completion of the Services, Freelancer shall, at Hiring Party’s written request, return or delete Personal Data in Freelancer’s possession or control, subject to Section 11.7 (permitted retention) and reasonable backup retention policies.\n\n12.11 Subprocessors (Optional). If Freelancer uses subprocessors to process Personal Data, Freelancer shall remain responsible for such subprocessors and shall ensure they are bound by obligations materially similar to this Section.\n\n12.12 Privacy Policy Alignment (Optional). If Hiring Party provides a privacy policy, security policy, or vendor requirements, Freelancer will reasonably cooperate to align with such policies to the extent consistent with Freelancer’s obligations to other clients and the agreed scope and Fees."},{"id":"term","type":"standard","order":13,"title":"13. TERM; TERMINATION; CANCELLATION; EFFECT OF TERMINATION","content":"13.1 Term. This Agreement begins on the Effective Date and continues until the earlier of: (a) completion and Acceptance of the Services and Deliverables, (b) {{expiration_date}} (if specified), or (c) termination pursuant to this Section (the \"Term\").\n\n13.2 Termination for Convenience. Either Party may terminate this Agreement for convenience upon {{notice_period}} days’ written notice to the other Party.\n\n13.3 Termination for Cause. Either Party may terminate this Agreement immediately upon written notice if the other Party: (a) materially breaches this Agreement and fails to cure such breach within seven (7) days after written notice describing the breach; (b) becomes insolvent, makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, or has a receiver appointed; or (c) engages in fraud, willful misconduct, or illegal conduct in connection with this Agreement.\n\n13.4 Suspension as Alternative. In lieu of termination, Hiring Party may request a temporary pause as described in Section 4.5. The Parties acknowledge that a pause may require a Change Order addressing scheduling impacts.\n\n13.5 Effect of Termination.\n(a) Cessation of Work. Upon termination, Freelancer shall stop performing Services as of the termination effective date, except for reasonable wind-down activities.\n(b) Delivery of Work in Progress. Upon request and subject to payment of undisputed amounts due, Freelancer shall provide Hiring Party with Deliverables completed as of the termination effective date and any work-in-progress in a reasonably deliverable format.\n(c) Payment. Hiring Party shall pay Freelancer for: (i) all Services performed through the termination effective date; (ii) all approved reimbursable expenses incurred; and (iii) any non-cancellable commitments or third-party costs incurred at Hiring Party’s request.\n\n13.6 Early Termination / Kill Fee (Optional). If specified in the SOW, Hiring Party shall pay an early termination fee of {{early_termination_fee}} to compensate for reserved capacity and project ramp-up.\n\n13.7 Refunds. Except as expressly stated in the SOW, all Fees paid are non-refundable. If a deposit or retainer is refundable, the conditions for refund must be stated in the SOW.\n\n13.8 Transition Assistance (Optional). If Hiring Party requests reasonable transition assistance after termination (e.g., handoff meetings, documentation, repository transfer), such assistance shall be billed at {{hourly_rate}} unless otherwise agreed.\n\n13.9 Survival. Sections that by their nature should survive termination shall survive, including Sections 6 (payment obligations), 10 (IP), 11 (confidentiality), 12 (privacy, to the extent applicable), 15 (limitation of liability), 16 (indemnification), 18 (governing law/venue), and 20 (general provisions)."},{"id":"warranties","type":"standard","order":14,"title":"14. WARRANTIES; DISCLAIMERS","content":"14.1 Mutual Authority. Each Party represents and warrants that: (a) it has full power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement; and (b) the person executing this Agreement on its behalf has authority to bind that Party.\n\n14.2 Freelancer Warranties. Freelancer represents and warrants that:\n(a) Professional Services. Freelancer will perform the Services in a professional and workmanlike manner consistent with generally accepted industry standards.\n(b) Non-Infringement. To Freelancer’s knowledge, the Work Product (excluding Client Materials and Third-Party Materials) does not infringe any U.S. copyright, trademark, patent, or other Intellectual Property Rights of any third party.\n(c) Right to Grant. Freelancer has the right to grant the licenses and assignments described in Section 10.\n(d) No Malicious Code. Freelancer will not knowingly include in Deliverables any malicious code designed to disrupt, damage, or provide unauthorized access to systems (e.g., viruses, worms, time bombs).\n\n14.3 Hiring Party Warranties. Hiring Party represents and warrants that:\n(a) Client Materials. Hiring Party has the right to provide Client Materials to Freelancer and to permit their use for the Services.\n(b) Instructions and Content. Hiring Party is responsible for the accuracy and legality of Client Materials and for ensuring that Hiring Party’s instructions do not violate applicable law.\n\n14.4 Disclaimer. EXCEPT AS EXPRESSLY PROVIDED IN THIS AGREEMENT, AND TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, THE SERVICES, DELIVERABLES, AND WORK PRODUCT ARE PROVIDED \"AS IS\" AND \"AS AVAILABLE,\" AND FREELANCER DISCLAIMS ALL OTHER WARRANTIES, WHETHER EXPRESS, IMPLIED, STATUTORY, OR OTHERWISE, INCLUDING IMPLIED WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, TITLE, AND NON-INFRINGEMENT.\n\n14.5 No Guarantee of Outcomes. Freelancer does not warrant or guarantee business outcomes, marketing performance, revenue, ranking results, regulatory approval, or other results dependent on third parties, market conditions, or Hiring Party’s implementation choices.\n\n14.6 Third-Party Services. Freelancer is not responsible for downtime, interruptions, or changes in functionality caused by third-party providers or platforms not controlled by Freelancer.\n\n14.7 Warranty Claims Procedure. Hiring Party shall notify Freelancer promptly of any claimed breach of warranty during the Term or within a reasonable time after discovery. Freelancer’s sole obligation, and Hiring Party’s exclusive remedy, for breach of Section 14.2(a) shall be re-performance of nonconforming Services, unless prohibited by law or otherwise stated in the SOW."},{"id":"liability","type":"negotiable","order":15,"title":"15. LIMITATION OF LIABILITY","content":"15.1 Exclusion of Certain Damages. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, IN NO EVENT SHALL EITHER PARTY BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER FOR ANY INDIRECT, INCIDENTAL, SPECIAL, CONSEQUENTIAL, EXEMPLARY, OR PUNITIVE DAMAGES, OR FOR ANY LOSS OF PROFITS, LOSS OF REVENUE, LOSS OF BUSINESS, LOSS OF GOODWILL, LOSS OF DATA (EXCEPT TO THE EXTENT SUCH LOSS OF DATA CONSTITUTES DIRECT DAMAGES), OR COST OF COVER, ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT, WHETHER IN CONTRACT, TORT (INCLUDING NEGLIGENCE), STRICT LIABILITY, OR OTHERWISE, EVEN IF ADVISED OF THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH DAMAGES.\n\n15.2 Liability Cap. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, EACH PARTY’S TOTAL AGGREGATE LIABILITY ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT SHALL NOT EXCEED THE TOTAL FEES PAID OR PAYABLE BY HIRING PARTY TO FREELANCER UNDER THIS AGREEMENT IN THE {{liability_cap_period}} MONTHS PRECEDING THE EVENT GIVING RISE TO THE CLAIM, OR {{liability_cap_amount}}, WHICHEVER IS GREATER, EXCEPT AS SET FORTH IN SECTION 15.3.\n\n15.3 Exceptions. The limitations in Sections 15.1 and 15.2 do not apply to: (a) a Party’s gross negligence, fraud, or willful misconduct; (b) a Party’s breach of Section 11 (Confidentiality) involving Trade Secrets or intentional unauthorized disclosure; (c) a Party’s indemnification obligations under Section 16 (to the extent expressly stated in Section 16); or (d) liabilities that cannot be limited under applicable law.\n\n15.4 Allocation of Risk. The Parties acknowledge that the Fees reflect the allocation of risk and the limitations of liability set forth in this Agreement, and that absent these limitations the Fees would be higher.\n\n15.5 Essential Purpose. If any remedy under this Agreement is found to have failed of its essential purpose, the limitations of liability shall still apply to the fullest extent permitted by law.\n\n15.6 Insurance. The Parties acknowledge that insurance may be used to mitigate risk. Any insurance maintained by either Party does not increase the other Party’s liability cap."},{"id":"indemnification","type":"negotiable","order":16,"title":"16. INDEMNIFICATION","content":"16.1 Freelancer Indemnity (IP Infringement). Freelancer shall defend, indemnify, and hold harmless Hiring Party and its officers, directors, employees, and agents from and against any third-party claim, demand, suit, or proceeding (a \"Claim\") alleging that the Work Product (excluding Client Materials and excluding Third-Party Materials) infringes such third party’s U.S. Intellectual Property Rights, and shall pay resulting damages finally awarded by a court or agreed in a settlement approved by Freelancer.\n\n16.2 Exclusions. Freelancer shall have no obligation under Section 16.1 to the extent a Claim arises from: (a) Client Materials; (b) Third-Party Materials or Open Source Software approved by Hiring Party; (c) modifications to the Work Product not made by or authorized in writing by Freelancer; (d) use of the Work Product in combination with items not provided by Freelancer where the Claim would not have occurred but for such combination; or (e) Hiring Party’s instructions requiring Freelancer to copy, imitate, or match third-party content or designs.\n\n16.3 Infringement Mitigation. If a Claim under Section 16.1 is made or, in Freelancer’s reasonable opinion, likely to be made, Freelancer may, at Freelancer’s option: (a) procure the right for Hiring Party to continue using the affected Work Product; (b) modify or replace the affected portion to be non-infringing while substantially preserving functionality; or (c) if (a) and (b) are not commercially reasonable, terminate the affected portion of the Services and refund the portion of Fees actually paid for the infringing portion of the Work Product that cannot reasonably be used.\n\n16.4 Hiring Party Indemnity (Client Materials). Hiring Party shall defend, indemnify, and hold harmless Freelancer and its officers, directors, employees, and agents from and against any Claim arising from or relating to: (a) Client Materials (including any allegation that Client Materials infringe a third party’s rights); (b) Hiring Party’s products or services (except to the extent caused by Freelancer’s breach); or (c) Hiring Party’s use of Deliverables in violation of this Agreement or applicable law.\n\n16.5 Indemnification Procedure. The Party seeking indemnification (the \"Indemnified Party\") shall: (a) promptly notify the other Party (the \"Indemnifying Party\") in writing of the Claim (provided that failure to give prompt notice only relieves the Indemnifying Party of obligations to the extent materially prejudiced); (b) provide reasonable cooperation at the Indemnifying Party’s expense; and (c) allow the Indemnifying Party to control the defense and settlement of the Claim.\n\n16.6 Settlement Restrictions. The Indemnifying Party shall not settle any Claim in a manner that admits liability on behalf of the Indemnified Party, imposes non-monetary obligations on the Indemnified Party, or fails to include a full release of the Indemnified Party, unless the Indemnified Party provides prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld).\n\n16.7 Counsel. The Indemnified Party may participate in the defense with counsel of its own choosing at its own expense, except where a conflict of interest requires separate counsel, in which case the Indemnifying Party shall pay reasonable fees for such counsel.\n\n16.8 Limitations. Indemnification obligations are subject to the limitations of liability in Section 15, except that the liability cap shall not apply to amounts owed to third parties under Section 16.1 and 16.4 if and to the extent such limitation is prohibited by law or expressly carved out in Section 15.3."},{"id":"restrictive_covenants_optional","type":"optional","order":17,"title":"17. OPTIONAL RESTRICTIVE COVENANTS; NON-SOLICITATION; NON-COMPETE (TEXAS)","content":"17.1 Purpose; Reasonableness. The Parties acknowledge that during the engagement Freelancer may receive access to Hiring Party Confidential Information, including customer relationships and Trade Secrets. Any restrictive covenant in this Section is intended to be reasonable and no broader than necessary to protect Hiring Party’s legitimate business interests, consistent with Texas Business and Commerce Code § 15.50.\n\n17.2 Non-Solicitation of Hiring Party Employees/Contractors (Optional). During the Term and for {{non_solicit_term_months}} months thereafter, Freelancer shall not, directly or indirectly, solicit for employment or engagement any employee or independent contractor of Hiring Party with whom Freelancer had material contact through the Services; provided that general solicitations not specifically targeted at Hiring Party personnel (e.g., general job postings) are permitted.\n\n17.3 Non-Solicitation of Clients/Customers (Optional). If specified in the SOW, during the Term and for {{non_solicit_term_months}} months thereafter, Freelancer shall not knowingly solicit for competing services any customer or active prospective customer of Hiring Party with whom Freelancer had material contact through performance of the Services, where such solicitation would require use or disclosure of Hiring Party Confidential Information.\n\n17.4 Non-Competition (Optional; Must Be Reasonable). If and only if expressly enabled in the SOW, and to the extent permitted by Texas Business and Commerce Code § 15.50 and related law, Freelancer agrees that during the Term and for {{non_compete_term_months}} months thereafter, within {{non_compete_geography}}, Freelancer will not provide services that are the same as or substantially similar to the Services to a business that competes with Hiring Party in {{non_compete_scope_of_business}}, where such restriction is ancillary to an otherwise enforceable agreement (including the confidentiality and IP obligations herein) and is necessary to protect Hiring Party’s goodwill and Confidential Information.\n\n17.5 Reformation / Blue-Pencil. If any restriction in this Section is found by a court of competent jurisdiction to be unenforceable as written, the Parties intend that the court reform the restriction to the extent necessary to make it enforceable (including under Texas Business and Commerce Code § 15.51), and enforce the restriction as reformed.\n\n17.6 Injunctive Relief. Freelancer agrees that a breach or threatened breach of this Section may cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be inadequate, and Hiring Party may seek injunctive relief in addition to other remedies.\n\n17.7 Non-Disparagement (Optional). If enabled in the SOW, during the Term and for {{non_disparagement_term_months}} months thereafter, each Party agrees not to make false statements of fact about the other Party, its products, services, or personnel.\n\n17.8 Optional Waiver. Unless expressly enabled in the SOW, the Parties agree that Sections 17.2 through 17.7 do not apply."},{"id":"governing_law_venue","type":"standard","order":18,"title":"18. GOVERNING LAW; VENUE; JURISDICTION","content":"18.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and any dispute arising out of or relating to this Agreement (including tort and statutory claims) shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Texas, without regard to conflict of laws principles that would apply the law of another jurisdiction.\n\n18.2 Exclusive Venue and Jurisdiction. Subject to Section 18.4 (Optional Dispute Resolution), the Parties agree that any legal action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement shall be brought exclusively in: (a) the state courts located in {{venue_county}} County, Texas; and (b) if federal jurisdiction exists, the United States District Court for {{federal_district}}. Each Party irrevocably submits to the personal jurisdiction of such courts and waives any objection based on inconvenient forum.\n\n18.3 Service of Process. Each Party consents to service of process in any manner authorized by applicable law, including by certified mail to the notice address in Section 19, in addition to any other permitted method.\n\n18.4 Optional Dispute Resolution. If the Parties enable the optional dispute resolution clause in Section {{dispute_resolution_section_number}}, the venue and forum selection terms of that clause will apply to the extent stated therein.\n\n18.5 Waiver of Jury Trial (Optional). If enabled in the SOW, EACH PARTY HEREBY KNOWINGLY, VOLUNTARILY, AND INTENTIONALLY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY in any action arising out of or relating to this Agreement, to the maximum extent permitted by Texas and federal law."},{"id":"notices","type":"standard","order":19,"title":"19. NOTICES","content":"19.1 Notice Addresses. Notices under this Agreement must be in writing and delivered to the Parties at the addresses below (or at any updated address provided by notice in accordance with this Section):\n(a) If to Hiring Party: {{party_a_company}}, Attn: {{party_a_name}}, {{party_a_address}}, Email: {{party_a_email}}.\n(b) If to Freelancer: {{party_b_company}}, Attn: {{party_b_name}}, {{party_b_address}}, Email: {{party_b_email}}.\n\n19.2 Permitted Methods. Notices shall be delivered by one of the following methods: (a) personal delivery; (b) nationally recognized overnight courier; (c) certified mail, return receipt requested; or (d) email (for notices that may be given by email under this Agreement).\n\n19.3 Deemed Receipt. Notices are deemed received: (a) upon delivery if personally delivered; (b) one (1) business day after deposit with an overnight courier; (c) three (3) business days after mailing by certified mail; or (d) for email, when sent (provided the sender does not receive an automated bounce-back or other notice of delivery failure). Notwithstanding the foregoing, notices of dispute, termination, indemnification claims, and legal process should be provided by at least one method in (a)-(c), in addition to email.\n\n19.4 Change of Address. Either Party may change its notice address by providing notice to the other Party in accordance with this Section.\n\n19.5 Routine Communications. Day-to-day project communications (e.g., feedback, approvals, scheduling) may be conducted via email, project management tools, or other agreed channels, and will be treated as written communications for purposes of this Agreement."},{"id":"general","type":"standard","order":20,"title":"20. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"20.1 Entire Agreement. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties regarding its subject matter and supersedes all prior and contemporaneous agreements, proposals, negotiations, and communications, whether oral or written.\n\n20.2 Amendments. Any amendment or modification to this Agreement must be in writing and signed by both Parties, provided that a Change Order confirmed in writing by authorized representatives satisfies this requirement for scope, timeline, and fee changes.\n\n20.3 Assignment. Neither Party may assign this Agreement or any rights or obligations hereunder without the prior written consent of the other Party, except that either Party may assign this Agreement without consent in connection with a merger, reorganization, or sale of substantially all assets, provided that the assignee agrees in writing to be bound by this Agreement. Any prohibited assignment is void.\n\n20.4 Subcontracting. Except as permitted under Section 2.8, Freelancer may not subcontract material Services without Hiring Party’s prior written consent.\n\n20.5 Severability. If any provision of this Agreement is held invalid or unenforceable, that provision shall be enforced to the maximum extent permitted, and the remaining provisions shall remain in full force and effect.\n\n20.6 Waiver. No waiver of any provision of this Agreement shall be effective unless in writing and signed by the Party against whom the waiver is asserted. A waiver of any breach shall not be a waiver of any subsequent breach.\n\n20.7 Force Majeure. Neither Party shall be liable for any failure or delay in performance (except payment obligations) due to causes beyond its reasonable control, including acts of God, natural disasters, war, terrorism, labor disputes, internet or hosting provider failures, governmental actions, or power outages. The affected Party shall use commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate and resume performance.\n\n20.8 Relationship of the Parties. The Parties are independent contractors. Nothing in this Agreement creates a partnership, joint venture, fiduciary relationship, or agency relationship.\n\n20.9 Compliance with Laws. Each Party shall comply with applicable laws, rules, and regulations in connection with its performance under this Agreement. Without limiting the foregoing, neither Party shall violate applicable anti-corruption laws, sanctions, or export control laws.\n\n20.10 No Third-Party Beneficiaries. Except as expressly stated in Section 16 (indemnified parties), this Agreement is for the benefit of the Parties and their permitted successors and assigns, and does not create rights in any third party.\n\n20.11 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which is deemed an original, and all of which together constitute one instrument.\n\n20.12 Electronic Signatures; Electronic Records. The Parties agree that signatures and records may be executed, delivered, and stored electronically, and that such electronic signatures and records shall have the same legal effect as originals, to the fullest extent permitted under the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 322) and ESIGN.\n\n20.13 Attorneys’ Fees (Optional). If enabled in the SOW, the prevailing Party in any action to enforce this Agreement shall be entitled to recover its reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs.\n\n20.14 Remedies Cumulative. Except as expressly stated otherwise, the rights and remedies of the Parties are cumulative and in addition to any rights and remedies available at law or in equity.\n\n20.15 Construction. This Agreement shall be construed as if jointly drafted by the Parties, and no presumption shall apply against the drafting Party.\n\n20.16 Authority to Sign. Each individual signing this Agreement represents and warrants that they are authorized to execute this Agreement on behalf of the applicable Party.\n\n20.17 Optional Dispute Resolution (Mediation/Arbitration). If the Parties enable Section {{dispute_resolution_section_number}}, that clause is incorporated by reference and shall apply.\n\n20.18 Optional Dispute Resolution Clause Text (Enabled Only If Selected).\n(a) Good Faith Negotiation. The Parties shall first attempt in good faith to resolve any dispute through informal negotiations between authorized representatives.\n(b) Mediation. If the dispute is not resolved within fifteen (15) days after written notice of dispute, either Party may request non-binding mediation to be held in {{mediation_city}}, Texas, through {{mediation_provider}}.\n(c) Arbitration (Optional). If enabled in the SOW, any dispute not resolved by mediation shall be finally resolved by binding arbitration conducted in {{arbitration_city}}, Texas, administered by {{arbitration_provider}} under its applicable rules. Judgment on the award may be entered in any court of competent jurisdiction. Nothing prevents either Party from seeking temporary injunctive relief in court to prevent irreparable harm, including to protect Confidential Information or Trade Secrets.\n(d) Fees. The arbitrator may award fees and costs to the prevailing Party as permitted by law and the arbitration rules.\n\n20.19 Survival. Provisions that by their nature are intended to survive will survive termination or expiration, including confidentiality, IP ownership and licenses, payment obligations accrued, limitations of liability, indemnification, and governing law/venue.\n\n20.20 Optional Exhibits. The Parties may attach and incorporate by reference: (a) Exhibit A (Statement of Work); (b) Exhibit B (Change Order Form); (c) Exhibit C (Security Requirements); and/or (d) Exhibit D (Non-Compete/Non-Solicit Election)."}]'::jsonb,
  signature_block = 'IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Agreement as of {{signature_date}}.

HIRING PARTY:
