-- Update: Independent Contractor Agreement (Texas)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Independent Contractor Agreement (the "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between {{party_a_company}}, a {{party_a_entity_type}} organized under the laws of {{party_a_state_of_formation}}, with a principal place of business at {{party_a_address}} ("Client"), and {{party_b_company}}, a {{party_b_entity_type}} organized under the laws of {{party_b_state_of_formation}}, with a principal place of business at {{party_b_address}} ("Contractor"). Client and Contractor may be referred to individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties".

This Agreement may incorporate one or more statements of work, exhibits, purchase orders, or similar documents that describe the Services (each, a "Statement of Work" or "SOW"). If there is a conflict between the main body of this Agreement and an SOW, the following order of precedence applies unless the SOW expressly states otherwise: (1) an amendment signed by both Parties, (2) the SOW, (3) this Agreement, and (4) any other document.',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, Client desires to retain Contractor to perform certain services for Client, as further described in this Agreement and any applicable SOW(s);

WHEREAS, Contractor represents that Contractor has the expertise, resources, and ability to perform such services as an independent contractor and is customarily engaged in an independently established trade, occupation, profession, or business of the same nature as the Services;

WHEREAS, the Parties desire to set forth their respective rights and obligations regarding performance of the Services, payment, ownership of work product, confidentiality, data protection, and other terms;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"services","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. SERVICES","content":"1.1 Services. Contractor shall perform the services described in {{services_description}} or the applicable SOW (the \"Services\") in a professional and workmanlike manner, consistent with generally accepted industry standards and with the degree of care and skill ordinarily exercised by qualified contractors performing similar services.\n\n1.2 Deliverables; Schedule; Dependencies. Any deliverables, milestones, deadlines, service levels, performance metrics, and acceptance criteria (collectively, \"Deliverables\") shall be as specified in {{services_description}} or an applicable SOW. Contractor shall promptly notify Client in writing if Contractor becomes aware of any event or circumstance that may materially affect the schedule, quality, or completion of the Services.\n\n1.3 Project Management; Points of Contact. Each Party will designate a primary point of contact for day-to-day communications (Client: {{client_rep_name}} / {{client_rep_email}}; Contractor: {{contractor_rep_name}} / {{contractor_rep_email}}). Either Party may change its point of contact by notice. Contractor shall provide periodic status updates at the cadence specified in the SOW or, if not specified, upon Client’s reasonable request.\n\n1.4 Place and Manner of Performance; Cooperation. Contractor will determine the method, details, and means of performing the Services; provided that Contractor shall (a) reasonably cooperate with Client’s operational, safety, acceptable-use, security, and onsite policies when accessing Client facilities, systems, networks, devices, personnel, or data; (b) comply with any facility sign-in requirements, confidentiality badges, and safety rules; and (c) not unreasonably interfere with Client’s business operations.\n\n1.5 Access to Client Systems. To the extent the Services require access to Client Systems, Contractor shall (a) use only credentials authorized by Client; (b) keep credentials confidential and not share them; (c) use multi-factor authentication if provided or required by Client; (d) promptly report any suspected compromise; and (e) access only those systems and data reasonably necessary to perform the Services.\n\n1.6 Client Responsibilities. Client shall provide timely access to Client Materials (as defined in Section 5), business requirements, and reasonably necessary information to enable Contractor to perform the Services. Client is responsible for decisions regarding business objectives, approvals, and acceptance of Deliverables.\n\n1.7 Changes; Change Orders. Client may request changes to the scope, specifications, or priorities of the Services. Any material change affecting scope, timeline, Deliverables, or compensation must be documented in a written change order or SOW amendment signed by both Parties. Contractor is not required to commence work on a material change until the change order is fully executed.\n\n1.8 Acceptance. Unless otherwise stated in an SOW, Client shall have {{deliverables_acceptance_days}} business days after delivery of a Deliverable to review and either (a) accept it in writing, or (b) reject it in writing with reasonably specific reasons for nonconformance with the agreed acceptance criteria. If Client does not provide a rejection notice within the acceptance period, the Deliverable will be deemed accepted. If rejected, Contractor shall use commercially reasonable efforts to correct the nonconformities and resubmit the Deliverable for acceptance.\n\n1.9 Subcontractors and Personnel. Contractor shall not subcontract or delegate any material portion of the Services without Client’s prior written consent (which may be conditioned on reasonable requirements). Contractor shall remain responsible for the acts and omissions of all subcontractors and personnel, and shall ensure that any permitted subcontractors are bound by written obligations at least as protective of Client as this Agreement, including confidentiality, IP assignment (as applicable), and data protection obligations.\n\n1.10 Compliance with Policies. If Contractor or its personnel perform Services at Client’s premises or with Client-provided access, Contractor shall ensure compliance with Client’s written policies that Client provides or makes available, including security, confidentiality, safety, harassment prevention, and acceptable use policies, to the extent such policies are reasonably applicable and do not convert Contractor into an employee.\n\n1.11 Non-Exclusivity; Conflicts. Unless the SOW provides otherwise, Contractor may provide services to third parties during the Term; provided that such services do not materially interfere with Contractor’s performance hereunder, do not create a conflict of interest, and do not involve disclosure or misuse of Client Confidential Information.\n\n1.12 No Authority. Contractor has no authority to bind Client, incur obligations on Client’s behalf, or make representations as an agent of Client unless expressly authorized in a writing signed by an authorized representative of Client."},{"id":"compensation","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. COMPENSATION; INVOICING; EXPENSES","content":"2.1 Fees and Rate Structure. As full consideration for the Services, Client shall pay Contractor the fees described in {{services_description}} or the applicable SOW, which may include (a) a fixed fee of {{payment_amount}}, (b) an hourly rate of {{hourly_rate}}, (c) milestone-based payments, or (d) another structure expressly agreed in writing.\n\n2.2 No Additional Fees Without Approval. Except as expressly stated in an SOW, Contractor shall not charge additional fees for administrative tasks, internal meetings, routine communications, rework caused by Contractor, or tasks reasonably necessary to complete the Services in accordance with this Agreement.\n\n2.3 Invoicing Requirements. Contractor shall submit invoices in accordance with the SOW. Unless otherwise stated, each invoice must include, as applicable: (a) the dates of Services, (b) a description of Services performed and Deliverables delivered, (c) hours worked and applicable rates, (d) approved expenses with receipts, (e) the applicable SOW reference or project name {{project_name}}, and (f) any other information reasonably requested by Client to validate the charges.\n\n2.4 Payment Terms; Undisputed Amounts. Unless otherwise stated in the SOW, Client shall pay all undisputed, properly invoiced amounts within {{payment_terms_days}} days after receipt of the invoice. Client may withhold payment of any disputed portion of an invoice, provided Client gives Contractor written notice of the dispute (with reasonable detail) within {{invoice_dispute_days}} days after receipt of the invoice. The Parties shall work in good faith to resolve invoice disputes promptly.\n\n2.5 Late Payments. Subject to Section 2.4 and applicable law, undisputed amounts not paid when due may accrue interest at the lesser of (a) {{late_fee_percent}}% per month or (b) the maximum rate permitted by applicable law, calculated from the due date until paid. Contractor’s sole remedy for late payment is interest as provided herein and, if nonpayment persists after written notice and a reasonable opportunity to cure, suspension or termination as provided in Section 4.\n\n2.6 Expenses. Unless expressly authorized in advance in writing by Client, Contractor is responsible for all costs and expenses incurred in performing the Services, including tools, equipment, supplies, staffing, insurance, and ordinary overhead. If Client authorizes reimbursable expenses, Contractor shall comply with {{expense_reimbursement_policy}} and provide reasonable documentation (e.g., itemized receipts). Client will not reimburse for alcohol, entertainment, or first-class travel unless expressly approved.\n\n2.7 Taxes; Reporting; Forms. Contractor is solely responsible for all federal, state, and local taxes, assessments, and other governmental charges arising from payments made under this Agreement, including self-employment taxes, and for filing all required returns. Client will not withhold or pay payroll taxes on Contractor’s behalf. Upon request, Contractor shall provide a properly completed IRS Form W-9 (or applicable substitute form), and Client may issue IRS Form 1099 or other tax reporting forms as required by law.\n\n2.8 No Employee Benefits. Contractor acknowledges and agrees that Contractor (and Contractor’s personnel) is not eligible for any Client-provided benefits, including health insurance, retirement benefits, disability benefits, paid leave, or other employee benefits.\n\n2.9 Purchase Orders; Administrative Requirements. If Client requires a purchase order number for payment processing, Client will provide it upon request. Contractor agrees that Client’s internal administrative requirements (e.g., vendor onboarding, invoice submission portals) may apply, provided they do not materially change the Parties’ substantive obligations.\n\n2.10 Records; Audit (Limited). Contractor shall maintain accurate books and records reasonably sufficient to substantiate time-and-materials charges and approved reimbursable expenses for at least {{records_retention_years}} years after the applicable invoice date. Upon reasonable notice and during normal business hours, Client may audit such records solely to verify amounts invoiced under this Agreement, not more than once per calendar year, and subject to reasonable confidentiality protections.\n\n2.11 No Setoff by Contractor. Contractor may not set off any amounts allegedly owed by Client against Contractor’s performance obligations. Client may set off amounts finally determined to be owed by Contractor to Client (or otherwise agreed by the Parties) against amounts payable, to the extent permitted by law.\n\n2.12 Currency; Payment Method. Unless otherwise stated in an SOW, all fees are stated and payable in U.S. dollars. Payment shall be made by ACH, check, wire transfer, or another method agreed by the Parties."},{"id":"independent_contractor_status","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR STATUS; TEXAS LABOR CODE / WORKER CLASSIFICATION","content":"3.1 Independent Contractor Relationship. Contractor is an independent contractor and not an employee, partner, joint venturer, agent, or representative of Client. Contractor is responsible for the manner and means of performing the Services, subject to the requirements of this Agreement and any SOW regarding results, deadlines, and Deliverables.\n\n3.2 No Employment Relationship; No Authority. Nothing in this Agreement creates an employment relationship, and Contractor shall not hold itself out as Client’s employee or agent. Contractor has no authority to enter into contracts or incur obligations on Client’s behalf.\n\n3.3 Contractor’s Business; Customarily Engaged. Contractor represents that it is customarily engaged in an independently established business of the same nature as the Services, maintains its own business operations, and offers services to multiple clients (or has the right to do so).\n\n3.4 Tools, Equipment, and Workspace. Unless expressly stated in an SOW, Contractor will provide, at its own expense, the tools, equipment, software, internet access, and workspace necessary to perform the Services. If Client provides equipment or accounts, such provision is for convenience and security and does not change Contractor’s status.\n\n3.5 Control Factors; Discretion. The Parties intend that the relationship reflect independent contractor status under applicable law, including common-law tests applied by the Texas Workforce Commission and the Texas Labor Code as relevant. Consistent with that intent: (a) Contractor controls scheduling and staffing (subject to deadlines and availability commitments), (b) Contractor may hire assistants at Contractor’s expense (subject to Section 1.9), (c) Contractor bears the risk of profit or loss, (d) Contractor may perform similar services for others (subject to conflicts and confidentiality), and (e) Contractor is not required to work exclusively for Client.\n\n3.6 Contractor Personnel; Hiring and Supervision. Contractor is solely responsible for recruiting, hiring, compensating, supervising, disciplining, and terminating its personnel. Contractor shall ensure that its personnel are appropriately qualified and trained and comply with applicable laws and the terms of this Agreement.\n\n3.7 Insurance and Workplace Injuries. Contractor is responsible for workplace safety for its personnel and for maintaining appropriate insurance, including those described in Section 9 if applicable. Unless required by law or expressly stated in an SOW, Client does not provide workers’ compensation insurance for Contractor or Contractor’s personnel.\n\n3.8 Compliance With Law; Licenses and Permits. Contractor shall obtain and maintain any business registrations, licenses, permits, and approvals required to perform the Services and shall comply with all applicable federal, state, and local laws, regulations, and ordinances.\n\n3.9 Unemployment; Workers’ Compensation; Benefits. Contractor acknowledges that Contractor is not entitled to unemployment benefits from Client and is not covered by Client’s workers’ compensation or unemployment insurance programs unless required by applicable law and expressly agreed in writing.\n\n3.10 Misclassification Cooperation; Indemnity. If any governmental authority, taxing authority, or court asserts that Contractor or Contractor’s personnel should be classified as employees of Client, Contractor shall reasonably cooperate with Client in responding. To the extent permitted by law, Contractor shall indemnify and hold harmless Client from and against any taxes, penalties, interest, assessments, claims, and liabilities arising out of Contractor’s breach of this Section 3 or Contractor’s failure to pay amounts for which Contractor is responsible; provided that this Section does not apply to amounts arising solely from Client’s independent actions unrelated to Contractor’s performance.\n\n3.11 Background Checks (Optional). If the Services require access to sensitive Client facilities, systems, or data, Client may require reasonable background checks consistent with applicable law. Contractor shall obtain any required consents from its personnel and shall ensure that background checks are conducted in compliance with applicable law.\n\n3.12 No Partnership; No Fiduciary Duty. The Parties agree that this Agreement does not create a partnership, joint venture, or fiduciary relationship between the Parties."},{"id":"term_termination","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TERM; TERMINATION; SUSPENSION; EFFECTS","content":"4.1 Term. This Agreement begins on the Effective Date and continues until {{expiration_date}}, unless earlier terminated in accordance with this Section 4 (the \"Term\"). If no expiration date is specified, the Term continues until completion of the Services or termination under this Agreement.\n\n4.2 Renewal (Optional). If the Parties wish to extend the Term, they may do so by written amendment or by executing an additional SOW that expressly extends or renews this Agreement.\n\n4.3 Termination for Convenience. Either Party may terminate this Agreement (and/or any SOW) for convenience upon {{notice_period}} days’ prior written notice to the other Party. If Client terminates for convenience, Client will pay Contractor for Services actually performed and accepted (or, if acceptance is not applicable, properly performed) through the effective termination date, plus any authorized, non-cancelable commitments reasonably incurred prior to termination that are supported by documentation and were necessary to perform the Services.\n\n4.4 Termination for Cause. Either Party may terminate this Agreement immediately upon written notice if the other Party: (a) materially breaches this Agreement and fails to cure such breach within {{cure_period_days}} days after receipt of written notice describing the breach; (b) becomes insolvent, makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, files or has filed against it any bankruptcy or similar proceeding that is not dismissed within 60 days, or ceases to operate in the ordinary course; or (c) engages in fraud, willful misconduct, or unlawful conduct that materially affects the terminating Party.\n\n4.5 Suspension (Optional). Client may suspend Contractor’s access to Client Systems and/or temporarily suspend performance of the Services (in whole or in part) if Client reasonably believes that (a) Contractor’s continued access poses a security risk, (b) Contractor has materially breached confidentiality, data protection, or security obligations, (c) there is suspected fraud or misuse, or (d) suspension is necessary to comply with law or a governmental request. Client shall use reasonable efforts to provide notice and to lift the suspension promptly after the issue is resolved. During a suspension not caused by Contractor’s breach, the Parties will in good faith adjust timelines, and Contractor may be entitled to equitable schedule relief; fees, if any, shall be as set forth in the SOW.\n\n4.6 Effect of Termination or Expiration. Upon termination or expiration: (a) Contractor shall promptly cease using Client Confidential Information and Client Systems; (b) Contractor shall deliver to Client all completed or in-progress Work Product and Deliverables for which Client has paid (or is obligated to pay), and all Client Materials and Client property in Contractor’s possession or control; (c) Contractor shall promptly return or destroy Client Confidential Information as required by Section 6.9; and (d) each Party shall pay any amounts accrued and undisputed prior to the effective date of termination.\n\n4.7 Transition Assistance (Optional). At Client’s request, Contractor shall provide reasonable transition assistance for up to {{transition_assistance_days}} days following termination or expiration to help Client transition the Services or Work Product to Client or a replacement provider, at the rates set forth in the SOW or, if not specified, at Contractor’s then-current standard rates, provided Client approves such rates in writing.\n\n4.8 No Waiver. Termination or suspension of this Agreement does not limit either Party’s rights or remedies, including the right to seek injunctive or equitable relief.\n\n4.9 Survival. The rights and obligations that by their nature should survive will survive termination or expiration, including Sections 2 (to the extent of unpaid obligations), 5 (Intellectual Property), 6 (Confidentiality; Trade Secrets; Data Protection), 7 (Representations and Warranties), 8 (Indemnification; Limitation of Liability), 10 (Non-Compete/Non-Solicitation, if applicable), and 11-12 (Governing Law; Venue; General Provisions/Definitions)."},{"id":"intellectual_property","type":"negotiable","order":5,"title":"5. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; WORK PRODUCT","content":"5.1 Definitions.\n(a) \"Work Product\" means all Deliverables and all inventions, discoveries, developments, designs, works of authorship, documentation, reports, know-how, data compilations, improvements, mask works, and other materials, whether tangible or intangible, created, conceived, reduced to practice, authored, or developed by Contractor (alone or jointly) in connection with the Services.\n(b) \"Client Materials\" means all information, materials, software, specifications, data, content, and other items provided by or on behalf of Client to Contractor.\n(c) \"Background Technology\" means any technology, software, tools, templates, processes, inventions, materials, or know-how that (i) Contractor owned or developed prior to the Effective Date, or (ii) Contractor develops independently of the Services without use of Client Confidential Information.\n(d) \"Third-Party Materials\" means any software, libraries, data, content, or other materials owned by a third party and incorporated into, required to use, or delivered with the Work Product.\n(e) \"Open Source Software\" means software subject to a license that is approved by the Open Source Initiative or that imposes conditions on distribution, source code disclosure, or derivative works.\n\n5.2 Work Made for Hire; Assignment. To the fullest extent permitted by law, the Parties intend that the Work Product be deemed a \"work made for hire\" for Client. To the extent any Work Product (or any portion thereof) is not a work made for hire or ownership does not automatically vest in Client, Contractor hereby irrevocably assigns, transfers, and conveys to Client all right, title, and interest in and to the Work Product, including all intellectual property rights (including copyright, patent rights, trade secret rights, mask work rights, and all other proprietary rights), worldwide.\n\n5.3 Pre-Existing Materials; Background Technology License. Contractor retains all rights in Background Technology. If Contractor incorporates or uses any Background Technology in the Work Product, Contractor hereby grants to Client a perpetual, irrevocable (except for Client’s material breach of license restrictions, if any, expressly stated in an SOW), worldwide, nonexclusive, royalty-free, fully paid, transferable, sublicensable license to use, reproduce, modify, create derivative works of, display, perform, distribute, and otherwise exploit such Background Technology solely as incorporated in or necessary to use the Work Product for Client’s internal business purposes and any purposes expressly described in the SOW.\n\n5.4 Third-Party Materials; Approvals; Pass-Through Terms. Contractor shall not incorporate Third-Party Materials into Work Product without Client’s prior written approval, except for standard commercially available components identified in the SOW. Contractor shall identify all Third-Party Materials and applicable license terms (including any pass-through terms) and shall ensure that Client’s use of the Work Product as contemplated will not require Client to (a) disclose source code, (b) license its proprietary software or data, or (c) pay additional royalties or fees, unless Client expressly agrees in writing.\n\n5.5 Open Source Compliance. If the Work Product includes any Open Source Software, Contractor shall (a) disclose such Open Source Software to Client in writing prior to delivery, including license text and version; (b) ensure compliance with all applicable Open Source Software license obligations; and (c) not include any Open Source Software that would require disclosure of Client proprietary source code or impose copyleft obligations on Client’s proprietary materials, unless Client expressly approves in writing.\n\n5.6 Contractor Personnel Assignments. Contractor shall ensure that all of Contractor’s personnel who contribute to Work Product are bound by written agreements that (a) assign to Contractor (or directly to Client if required) all rights in such contributions, and (b) contain confidentiality obligations at least as protective as this Agreement, so that Contractor can grant and assign rights as required herein.\n\n5.7 Further Assurances; Power of Attorney. Contractor shall execute and deliver, and shall cause its personnel to execute and deliver, any documents and take any actions reasonably requested by Client to perfect, maintain, enforce, or evidence Client’s rights in the Work Product (including patent and copyright filings). If Contractor fails to execute such documents within a reasonable time after request, Contractor hereby appoints Client as Contractor’s agent and attorney-in-fact (coupled with an interest) to execute such documents on Contractor’s behalf solely for the purpose of perfecting Client’s rights in the Work Product.\n\n5.8 Moral Rights Waiver. To the maximum extent permitted by applicable law, Contractor waives and agrees not to assert any \"moral rights\" (including rights of attribution or integrity) in the Work Product. If such waiver is not enforceable, Contractor agrees not to exercise such rights in a manner that interferes with Client’s full enjoyment of the Work Product.\n\n5.9 Reservation of Rights; No Implied Licenses. Except as expressly stated in this Agreement, neither Party grants the other any rights, licenses, or interests by implication, estoppel, or otherwise.\n\n5.10 Portfolio/Attribution (Optional). Unless Client objects in writing, Contractor may include in Contractor’s portfolio a general description of the Services and non-confidential screenshots or excerpts of the Work Product that have been made public by Client, provided that Contractor does not disclose Client Confidential Information and complies with Client’s branding guidelines if provided. Contractor shall not issue press releases or public announcements regarding the relationship without Client’s prior written consent."},{"id":"confidentiality","type":"standard","order":6,"title":"6. CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS (TUTSA/DTSA); DATA PROTECTION (TEXAS)","content":"6.1 Definitions.\n(a) \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed or made available by or on behalf of Client to Contractor (or that Contractor otherwise receives or accesses in connection with the Services), whether in oral, visual, electronic, or written form, that (i) is designated as confidential or proprietary, or (ii) should reasonably be understood to be confidential given the nature of the information or the circumstances of disclosure. Confidential Information includes Client Materials, Client Systems information, business plans, pricing, customer lists, vendor information, product roadmaps, designs, source code, non-public security information, and Personal Data.\n(b) \"Trade Secret\" means information that qualifies as a trade secret under the Texas Uniform Trade Secrets Act, Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A (\"TUTSA\"), and/or the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act, 18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq. (\"DTSA\").\n(c) \"Personal Data\" means information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked (directly or indirectly) with an identified or identifiable individual, including any information that constitutes \"personal identifying information\" under applicable Texas law.\n(d) \"Security Incident\" means any actual or reasonably suspected unauthorized access to, acquisition of, use of, disclosure of, or compromise of Confidential Information or Personal Data, including any event that triggers notice obligations under applicable law.\n\n6.2 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that Contractor can demonstrate by contemporaneous written records: (a) is or becomes generally available to the public through no wrongful act or omission of Contractor; (b) was lawfully known by Contractor prior to disclosure by Client without restriction; (c) is lawfully received by Contractor from a third party without breach of any duty of confidentiality; or (d) is independently developed by Contractor without use of or reference to Client Confidential Information.\n\n6.3 Use and Non-Disclosure Obligations. Contractor shall: (a) use Confidential Information solely to perform the Services and for no other purpose; (b) protect Confidential Information using at least the same degree of care Contractor uses to protect its own confidential information of similar importance, and in no event less than reasonable care; (c) not disclose Confidential Information to any third party except as expressly permitted by this Agreement; and (d) limit access to Confidential Information to Contractor’s personnel and permitted subcontractors who have a need to know for purposes of performing the Services and who are bound by written confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those in this Agreement.\n\n6.4 Protection of Trade Secrets (TUTSA/DTSA). Contractor acknowledges that Client’s Trade Secrets derive independent economic value from not being generally known and are the subject of reasonable measures to maintain secrecy. Contractor shall not, directly or indirectly, misappropriate (as defined under TUTSA) any Trade Secret and shall take reasonable measures to maintain the secrecy of any Trade Secrets accessed in connection with the Services.\n\n6.5 No Improper Acquisition; No Reverse Engineering. Contractor shall not (a) access or attempt to access Client Systems beyond authorized permissions; (b) probe, scan, or test the vulnerability of Client Systems except as expressly authorized in writing; or (c) reverse engineer, decompile, or disassemble any non-public Client software or technology except to the extent expressly permitted by applicable law that cannot be waived and then only after providing advance written notice to Client.\n\n6.6 Permitted Disclosures. Contractor may disclose Confidential Information only to the extent required: (a) to Contractor’s attorneys, accountants, and professional advisors who are bound by confidentiality obligations; (b) pursuant to a valid order or subpoena issued by a court or governmental authority; or (c) as otherwise expressly authorized in writing by Client.\n\n6.7 Compelled Disclosure Procedures. If Contractor is required by law, regulation, subpoena, or court order to disclose any Confidential Information, Contractor shall (to the extent legally permitted): (a) provide Client prompt written notice of the requirement so Client may seek a protective order or other remedy; (b) reasonably cooperate with Client (at Client’s expense) in seeking to limit disclosure; and (c) disclose only the portion of Confidential Information legally required to be disclosed.\n\n6.8 Data Protection; Applicable Laws; Processing Instructions.\n(a) Compliance. Contractor shall comply with all applicable privacy, data security, and breach notification laws in connection with the Services, including, as applicable, the Texas Identity Theft Enforcement and Protection Act (Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 521), the Texas Data Privacy and Security Act (as and when applicable), and any other applicable federal or state privacy and data security laws.\n(b) Role. To the extent Contractor processes Personal Data on Client’s behalf, Contractor will process such Personal Data solely as instructed by Client and solely to perform the Services.\n(c) Data Minimization. Contractor shall access, collect, use, store, and transmit Personal Data only to the extent necessary to perform the Services.\n(d) Cross-Border Transfers. Contractor shall not transfer Personal Data outside the United States without Client’s prior written consent, except as expressly contemplated in an SOW.\n\n6.9 Information Security Program. Contractor shall implement and maintain a written information security program with administrative, physical, and technical safeguards appropriate to the nature of the Confidential Information and Personal Data. Such safeguards shall include, as appropriate: (a) access controls and least-privilege access; (b) encryption of Personal Data in transit and at rest where commercially reasonable; (c) timely security patching and vulnerability management; (d) malware protection; (e) secure development practices if software is developed; (f) logging and monitoring proportionate to risk; and (g) secure disposal of Confidential Information.\n\n6.10 Security Incidents; Notice and Cooperation.\n(a) Notice. Contractor shall notify Client in writing of any Security Incident without undue delay and in no event later than {{data_breach_notice_hours}} hours after Contractor becomes aware of it.\n(b) Content. Such notice shall include, to the extent known at the time: (i) the nature of the Security Incident, (ii) the categories of data involved, (iii) the approximate number of affected records (if known), (iv) mitigation steps taken or planned, and (v) a point of contact for further information.\n(c) Cooperation. Contractor shall promptly take reasonable steps to contain, investigate, and remediate the Security Incident and shall reasonably cooperate with Client in connection with Client’s legal, regulatory, and contractual obligations (including breach notifications), at Contractor’s expense to the extent the Security Incident was caused by Contractor’s breach of this Agreement or Contractor’s failure to maintain required safeguards.\n(d) No Public Statements. Contractor shall not make any public statement, press release, or notification to affected individuals or regulators relating to a Security Incident involving Client data without Client’s prior written consent, except to the extent required by law.\n\n6.11 Return, Destruction, and Deletion.\n(a) Upon Client’s request or upon termination/expiration, Contractor shall promptly return to Client or destroy all Confidential Information in Contractor’s possession or control, including all copies, extracts, and summaries.\n(b) If destruction is requested, Contractor shall certify destruction in writing upon request.\n(c) Notwithstanding the foregoing, Contractor may retain archival copies of Confidential Information solely to the extent required by law or bona fide backup systems, provided that such retained information remains subject to this Agreement and is not accessed except as required by law.\n\n6.12 Duration. Contractor’s obligations with respect to Confidential Information shall continue during the Term and for {{confidentiality_term_years}} years thereafter; provided that obligations with respect to Trade Secrets shall continue for so long as the information remains a Trade Secret under applicable law.\n\n6.13 Injunctive Relief. Contractor acknowledges that any breach of this Section 6 may cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be an inadequate remedy. Client is entitled to seek temporary, preliminary, and permanent injunctive relief and other equitable remedies, without posting a bond to the extent permitted by law, in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity.\n\n6.14 DTSA Whistleblower Immunity Notice (Required). Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b), Contractor is hereby notified that an individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that (a) is made (i) in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (ii) in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal. Further, an individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding, if the individual (x) files any document containing the trade secret under seal and (y) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order."},{"id":"representations_warranties","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES","content":"7.1 Mutual Authority; Enforceability. Each Party represents and warrants that: (a) it is duly organized (if applicable), validly existing, and in good standing under the laws of its jurisdiction of formation; (b) it has full power and authority to enter into this Agreement and to perform its obligations; and (c) this Agreement is a legal, valid, and binding obligation enforceable against it in accordance with its terms.\n\n7.2 Contractor Performance Warranty. Contractor represents and warrants that: (a) the Services will be performed in a professional and workmanlike manner consistent with generally accepted industry standards; (b) Contractor will devote sufficient resources and qualified personnel to perform the Services; and (c) Contractor will use commercially reasonable efforts to meet agreed timelines.\n\n7.3 Compliance With Laws. Contractor represents and warrants that it will perform the Services in compliance with all applicable federal, state, and local laws and regulations, including those relating to privacy, data security, and intellectual property.\n\n7.4 Non-Infringement; Rights in Work Product. Contractor represents and warrants that: (a) Contractor has and will maintain the full right, power, and authority to grant the rights and assignments set forth in Section 5; (b) the Work Product (excluding Client Materials) will not infringe, misappropriate, or otherwise violate any third party’s intellectual property or proprietary rights; and (c) Contractor will not knowingly incorporate any Third-Party Materials in a manner that would restrict Client’s intended use of the Work Product without Client’s prior written approval.\n\n7.5 No Malicious Code. Contractor represents and warrants that Contractor will not introduce into Client Systems or deliver to Client any viruses, worms, time bombs, Trojan horses, ransomware, back doors, or other malicious or harmful code or functionality intended to (a) disrupt, disable, harm, or impair operations, or (b) permit unauthorized access to systems or data.\n\n7.6 No Conflicts. Contractor represents and warrants that entering into and performing under this Agreement does not and will not violate any agreement to which Contractor is a party or by which Contractor is bound, and Contractor has no conflict of interest that would materially impair performance.\n\n7.7 Sanctions; Export Controls (Optional). Contractor represents and warrants that it is not subject to U.S. sanctions that would prohibit performance and will comply with applicable export control and sanctions laws to the extent applicable to the Services.\n\n7.8 Disclaimer. EXCEPT AS EXPRESSLY PROVIDED IN THIS AGREEMENT, NEITHER PARTY MAKES ANY OTHER WARRANTIES, EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, INCLUDING ANY IMPLIED WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, TITLE, OR NON-INFRINGEMENT."},{"id":"indemnification","type":"negotiable","order":8,"title":"8. INDEMNIFICATION; LIMITATION OF LIABILITY","content":"8.1 Indemnification by Contractor. Contractor shall defend, indemnify, and hold harmless Client and its affiliates, and each of their respective officers, directors, employees, and agents (collectively, \"Client Indemnitees\") from and against any third-party claims, demands, suits, proceedings, damages, losses, liabilities, penalties, fines, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) to the extent arising out of or related to: (a) Contractor’s negligence, gross negligence, or willful misconduct; (b) Contractor’s breach of this Agreement (including Sections 5 and 6); (c) allegations that the Work Product (excluding Client Materials) infringes, misappropriates, or otherwise violates any third party intellectual property or proprietary right; (d) a Security Incident caused by Contractor’s failure to comply with Section 6; or (e) Contractor’s violation of applicable law in performance of the Services.\n\n8.2 Indemnification by Client. Client shall defend, indemnify, and hold harmless Contractor and its officers, directors, employees, and agents (collectively, \"Contractor Indemnitees\") from and against any third-party claims, damages, losses, liabilities, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) to the extent arising out of allegations that Client Materials provided by Client infringe or misappropriate any third party intellectual property rights, provided that Contractor used such Client Materials only as authorized.\n\n8.3 Indemnification Procedure.\n(a) Notice. The indemnified Party shall promptly notify the indemnifying Party in writing of any claim for which indemnity is sought; provided that failure to provide prompt notice will not relieve the indemnifying Party of its obligations except to the extent materially prejudiced.\n(b) Control. The indemnifying Party shall have the right to control the defense and settlement of the claim with counsel reasonably acceptable to the indemnified Party. The indemnified Party may participate with its own counsel at its own expense.\n(c) Settlement. The indemnifying Party shall not settle any claim in a manner that admits fault on behalf of the indemnified Party, imposes non-monetary obligations on the indemnified Party, or fails to provide a full release of the indemnified Party, without the indemnified Party’s prior written consent (not to be unreasonably withheld).\n\n8.4 IP Infringement Remedies. If the Work Product is, or in Contractor’s reasonable opinion is likely to be, the subject of an infringement claim, Contractor shall, at its expense and as Client’s exclusive remedy for such claim (except where otherwise required by law or for Contractor’s willful misconduct): (a) procure for Client the right to continue using the affected Work Product; (b) modify or replace the affected Work Product so that it becomes non-infringing while maintaining materially equivalent functionality; or (c) if (a) and (b) are not commercially reasonable, refund to Client the fees paid for the affected Work Product that is the subject of the claim, on a pro rata basis reflecting the portion not usable as intended, and upon refund Client will cease use of the affected Work Product.\n\n8.5 Limitation of Liability.\n(a) EXCLUSION OF CERTAIN DAMAGES. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, NEITHER PARTY SHALL BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER FOR ANY INDIRECT, INCIDENTAL, SPECIAL, CONSEQUENTIAL, EXEMPLARY, OR PUNITIVE DAMAGES, OR FOR LOSS OF PROFITS, LOSS OF REVENUE, LOSS OF DATA (EXCEPT TO THE EXTENT ARISING FROM A SECURITY INCIDENT), OR BUSINESS INTERRUPTION, ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT, WHETHER IN CONTRACT, TORT, OR ANY OTHER THEORY, EVEN IF ADVISED OF THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH DAMAGES.\n(b) CAP ON LIABILITY. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY LAW, EACH PARTY’S TOTAL AGGREGATE LIABILITY ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT SHALL NOT EXCEED {{liability_cap_amount}} (OR, IF STATED IN THE SOW, {{liability_cap_multiplier}} TIMES THE TOTAL FEES PAID OR PAYABLE UNDER THE APPLICABLE SOW, WHICHEVER IS GREATER).\n(c) EXCEPTIONS. THE LIMITATIONS IN THIS SECTION 8.5 SHALL NOT APPLY TO: (i) A PARTY’S INDEMNIFICATION OBLIGATIONS UNDER SECTION 8.1 OR 8.2 (AS APPLICABLE); (ii) A PARTY’S BREACH OF SECTION 6 (CONFIDENTIALITY; DATA PROTECTION), INCLUDING SECURITY INCIDENTS CAUSED BY THAT PARTY; (iii) A PARTY’S INFRINGEMENT OR MISAPPROPRIATION OF THE OTHER PARTY’S INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; OR (iv) A PARTY’S FRAUD, GROSS NEGLIGENCE, OR WILLFUL MISCONDUCT, OR LIABILITY THAT CANNOT BE LIMITED UNDER APPLICABLE LAW.\n\n8.6 Duty to Mitigate. Each Party shall use commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate damages arising from or related to any breach of this Agreement.\n\n8.7 Exclusive Remedies. Except as expressly stated in this Agreement (including injunctive relief for confidentiality and IP), the remedies in this Agreement are cumulative and not exclusive of any remedies provided by law."},{"id":"insurance","type":"optional","order":9,"title":"9. INSURANCE (OPTIONAL)","content":"9.1 Coverage. If required by an SOW or if Contractor will perform Services onsite at Client facilities or access sensitive systems/data, Contractor shall procure and maintain during the Term, at Contractor’s expense, insurance coverage with reputable carriers licensed to do business in Texas (or otherwise acceptable to Client), which may include: (a) commercial general liability insurance with limits of not less than {{general_liability_limit}} per occurrence; (b) professional liability (errors and omissions) insurance with limits of not less than {{professional_liability_limit}}; (c) cyber/privacy liability insurance with limits of not less than {{cyber_liability_limit}}; and (d) workers’ compensation insurance as required by applicable law.\n\n9.2 Certificates; Additional Insured. Upon request, Contractor shall provide certificates of insurance evidencing coverage. To the extent commercially available, Contractor shall name Client as an additional insured on the commercial general liability policy for claims arising out of Contractor’s performance.\n\n9.3 No Limitation. Contractor’s insurance obligations do not limit Contractor’s liability under this Agreement."},{"id":"non_compete","type":"optional","order":10,"title":"10. RESTRICTIVE COVENANTS (TEXAS) (OPTIONAL)","content":"10.1 Texas Law; Intent. The Parties acknowledge that restrictive covenants in Texas are governed by Texas Business and Commerce Code § 15.50 and related provisions, and may be enforceable if they are ancillary to or part of an otherwise enforceable agreement and are reasonable as to time, geographic area, and scope of activity. The Parties agree that Contractor’s access to Client Confidential Information, Trade Secrets, customer relationships, and/or specialized training may constitute sufficient consideration supporting the restrictive covenants in this Section 10.\n\n10.2 Non-Competition (Optional; If Selected in an SOW or Addendum). During the Term and for {{non_compete_term_months}} months thereafter (the \"Restricted Period\"), Contractor shall not, within {{non_compete_geography}} (the \"Restricted Area\"), directly or indirectly perform services that are the same as or substantially similar to the Services for a business that is in the business of {{restricted_business_activities}} and that competes with Client, if such services would necessarily require or involve the use or disclosure of Client Trade Secrets or Confidential Information. This covenant is intended to be narrowly tailored to protect Client’s legitimate business interests.\n\n10.3 Non-Solicitation of Customers/Prospects (Optional). During the Restricted Period, Contractor shall not directly or indirectly solicit or induce any customer, client, or active prospect of Client with whom Contractor had material contact or about whom Contractor received Confidential Information during the Term (the \"Restricted Customers\") for the purpose of providing products or services that are competitive with the Services or Client’s business as described in the SOW.\n\n10.4 Non-Solicitation/No-Hire of Employees (Optional). During the Restricted Period, Contractor shall not directly or indirectly solicit for employment or hire any employee of Client with whom Contractor worked or interacted in connection with the Services; provided that general solicitations not targeted to Client employees (such as general job postings) will not violate this Section.\n\n10.5 Reasonableness; Reformation. Contractor acknowledges that the restrictions in this Section 10 are reasonable and necessary to protect Client’s legitimate business interests. If a court determines that any restriction is overbroad, the Parties intend that the court reform (\"blue-pencil\") the restriction to the extent necessary to make it enforceable under Texas law and then enforce it as reformed (including under Texas Business and Commerce Code § 15.51).\n\n10.6 Separate Consideration; Severability. If required to support enforceability, the Parties agree that the restrictive covenants are supported by adequate consideration, including access to Confidential Information and Trade Secrets. Each covenant in this Section 10 is severable and independently enforceable.\n\n10.7 Remedies. In addition to any other remedies, Client may seek injunctive relief to enforce this Section 10 without the necessity of proving actual damages, in accordance with applicable law."},{"id":"governing_law","type":"standard","order":11,"title":"11. GOVERNING LAW; VENUE; JURISDICTION","content":"11.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and any dispute arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the Services, or the relationship of the Parties shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Texas, without regard to conflict of laws rules.\n\n11.2 Exclusive Venue; Courts. Subject to Section 11.4 (Optional Dispute Resolution) if included, the Parties agree that any legal action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement shall be brought exclusively in the state courts located in {{venue_county}} County, Texas, or the federal courts of the United States located in the {{federal_district}} District of Texas, and each Party irrevocably submits to the personal jurisdiction of such courts.\n\n11.3 Waiver of Forum Non Conveniens. Each Party waives any objection to venue in such courts, including any claim that such forum is inconvenient or improper.\n\n11.4 Optional Pre-Suit Mediation. Before filing suit (other than for temporary restraining orders, preliminary injunctions, or other emergency equitable relief), either Party may request that the Parties attempt to resolve the dispute through non-binding mediation in {{venue_county}} County, Texas. The Parties shall share mediator fees equally and bear their own attorneys’ fees.\n\n11.5 Service of Process. Each Party agrees that service of process may be effected in accordance with Texas law and, where permitted, by certified mail or reputable overnight courier to the notice address in Section 12.8."},{"id":"general_provisions","type":"standard","order":12,"title":"12. DEFINITIONS; GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"12.1 Additional Definitions.\n(a) \"Affiliate\" means, with respect to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with such Party.\n(b) \"Client Systems\" means Client’s networks, systems, software, applications, devices, accounts, and environments, including third-party systems to which Client provides access.\n(c) \"Documentation\" means user guides, technical documentation, specifications, and other materials describing installation, configuration, operation, or use of the Deliverables.\n(d) \"Including\" means including without limitation.\n(e) \"Writing\" or \"Written\" includes email and electronic records that satisfy applicable signature and record requirements.\n\n12.2 Notices.\n(a) Method. All notices under this Agreement must be in writing and will be deemed given when: (i) delivered personally, (ii) sent by a nationally recognized overnight courier with tracking, (iii) mailed by certified mail (return receipt requested), postage prepaid, or (iv) sent by email with confirmation of transmission (excluding auto-replies) to the email addresses below.\n(b) Notice Addresses. Notices shall be sent to the following (or to such other address/email a Party designates by notice):\nClient: {{party_a_company}}, Attn: {{party_a_name}}, {{party_a_address}}, Email: {{party_a_email}}\nContractor: {{party_b_company}}, Attn: {{party_b_name}}, {{party_b_address}}, Email: {{party_b_email}}\n\n12.3 Assignment. Contractor may not assign, delegate, or transfer this Agreement or any rights or obligations hereunder without Client’s prior written consent. Any attempted assignment in violation of this Section is void. Client may assign this Agreement (a) to an Affiliate, or (b) in connection with a merger, reorganization, acquisition, or sale of all or substantially all of its assets, upon written notice to Contractor.\n\n12.4 Subcontracting. Any subcontracting is subject to Section 1.9. No permitted subcontracting relieves Contractor of responsibility for performance.\n\n12.5 Publicity; Use of Names. Neither Party may use the other Party’s name, trademarks, or logos in marketing, publicity, or press releases without the other Party’s prior written consent, except as required by law.\n\n12.6 Non-Disparagement (Optional). During the Term and for one (1) year thereafter, neither Party will make public statements that disparage the other Party, its products, or its services; provided that this Section does not restrict truthful statements required by law or made in legal proceedings.\n\n12.7 Compliance; Ethics (Optional). Contractor shall not offer, promise, authorize, or provide any improper payment or benefit to any person in connection with the Services. Contractor shall comply with applicable anti-corruption laws and maintain accurate records.\n\n12.8 Confidentiality of Agreement (Optional). The Parties may treat the pricing and statements of work terms of this Agreement as Confidential Information. Either Party may disclose the Agreement to its professional advisors and as required by law.\n\n12.9 Injunctive Relief; Cumulative Remedies. The Parties agree that a breach of Sections 5, 6, or 10 may cause irreparable harm and that equitable relief may be appropriate in addition to any other remedies.\n\n12.10 Severability. If any provision of this Agreement is held invalid, illegal, or unenforceable, the remaining provisions remain in full force and effect, and the invalid provision will be enforced to the maximum extent permitted so as to effect the intent of the Parties.\n\n12.11 Waiver. No waiver of any breach of any provision of this Agreement constitutes a waiver of any prior, concurrent, or subsequent breach. Any waiver must be in writing and signed by the Party granting the waiver.\n\n12.12 Independent Development. Nothing in this Agreement prohibits Contractor from developing, for itself or others, materials that are similar to the Work Product, provided Contractor does not use or disclose Client Confidential Information or Client Trade Secrets and does not violate Section 10 if applicable.\n\n12.13 Entire Agreement; Amendments. This Agreement (together with all SOWs and exhibits) constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties regarding its subject matter and supersedes all prior or contemporaneous agreements and understandings. Any amendment must be in writing and signed by both Parties.\n\n12.14 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which will be deemed an original, and all of which together constitute one instrument.\n\n12.15 Electronic Signatures; Electronic Records. The Parties agree that this Agreement and related documents may be executed and delivered by electronic means and that such signatures and records are enforceable under the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 322) and the federal Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (E-SIGN).\n\n12.16 Force Majeure. Neither Party will be liable for any delay or failure to perform (except payment obligations) due to causes beyond its reasonable control, including natural disasters, acts of government, labor disputes, internet outages not caused by the affected Party, terrorism, or war. The affected Party shall promptly notify the other and use commercially reasonable efforts to resume performance.\n\n12.17 Attorneys’ Fees (Optional). In any action arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the prevailing Party may recover its reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs, to the extent permitted by law.\n\n12.18 Waiver of Jury Trial (Optional). TO THE EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, EACH PARTY KNOWINGLY, VOLUNTARILY, AND INTENTIONALLY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY LEGAL PROCEEDING ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT.\n\n12.19 Headings; Interpretation. Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation. This Agreement will be construed as jointly drafted by the Parties and no presumption shall apply against either Party as drafter."}]'::jsonb,
  signature_block = 'IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Agreement as of {{signature_date}}.

