-- Update: Mutual Non-Disclosure Agreement (Texas)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Mutual Non-Disclosure Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between (i) {{party_a_company}}, with a mailing address of {{party_a_address}} ("Party A" and, where applicable, "{{party_a_name}}"), and (ii) {{party_b_company}}, with a mailing address of {{party_b_address}} ("Party B" and, where applicable, "{{party_b_name}}"). Party A and Party B may be referred to individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties".

This Agreement is intended to facilitate the exchange of certain Confidential Information (as defined below) between the Parties in order to evaluate, discuss, and/or pursue a potential business relationship. The Parties acknowledge that this Agreement is a mutual non-disclosure agreement and, unless expressly stated otherwise, does not obligate either Party to proceed with any transaction, relationship, or other arrangement.',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, the Parties wish to explore, evaluate, and/or pursue a potential business relationship concerning {{purpose}} (the "Purpose");

WHEREAS, in connection with the Purpose, each Party (as a Disclosing Party) may disclose to the other Party (as a Receiving Party) certain confidential, proprietary, and/or trade secret information, including information relating to each Party’s business, customers, suppliers, technology, personnel, and operations;

WHEREAS, the Parties desire to establish the terms and conditions under which such information will be protected and used, in accordance with applicable law, including without limitation the Texas Uniform Trade Secrets Act (Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A) ("TUTSA"), the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act (18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq.) ("DTSA"), the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 322), and applicable Texas privacy and data security laws;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS","content":"1.1 \"Affiliate\" means, with respect to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly Controls, is Controlled by, or is under common Control with that Party. \"Control\" means the power, directly or indirectly, to direct or cause the direction of the management or policies of an entity, whether through ownership of voting securities, by contract, or otherwise.\n\n1.2 \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed by or on behalf of a Party (the \"Disclosing Party\") to the other Party (the \"Receiving Party\"), whether disclosed before or after the Effective Date, and whether disclosed in writing, orally, visually, electronically, by inspection, by demonstration, by access to systems or facilities, or in any other form, that (a) is designated as confidential or proprietary, (b) is disclosed under circumstances that reasonably indicate it is confidential, or (c) reasonably should be understood to be confidential given the nature of the information or the circumstances of disclosure.\n\n1.3 Confidential Information includes, without limitation, information relating to: (a) business plans, strategies, budgets, forecasts, and financial information; (b) pricing, margins, costs, bids, and proposals; (c) products and services, roadmaps, features, specifications, designs, drawings, schematics, prototypes, and performance information; (d) research and development, inventions, discoveries, methods, processes, techniques, know-how, trade secrets, and proprietary tools; (e) software, firmware, source code, object code, architecture, APIs, models, datasets, documentation, and development pipelines; (f) security measures, vulnerabilities, incident response information, audit reports, and risk assessments; (g) customer, prospect, and supplier lists, identities, contact information, purchasing histories, requirements, contract terms, and account details; (h) marketing and sales plans, analytics, conversion data, and market research; (i) personnel information, including compensation data, performance metrics, and organizational structure; (j) any notes, analyses, compilations, summaries, forecasts, studies, or other materials prepared by or for the Receiving Party that contain, reflect, or are derived from Confidential Information (\"Derived Materials\"); and (k) the existence and terms of this Agreement and the fact and status of the Parties’ discussions and evaluations, to the extent such information is not public (\"Discussion Confidentiality\").\n\n1.4 \"Trade Secret\" means information that qualifies as a trade secret under TUTSA (Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A) and/or under DTSA, and includes all forms and types of financial, business, scientific, technical, economic, or engineering information, whether tangible or intangible, if (a) the owner thereof has taken reasonable measures to keep such information secret, and (b) the information derives independent economic value, actual or potential, from not being generally known to, and not being readily ascertainable through proper means by, another person who can obtain economic value from its disclosure or use. Trade Secrets are included within Confidential Information.\n\n1.5 \"Personal Data\" means information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked (directly or indirectly) with an identified or identifiable individual, to the extent regulated by applicable U.S. privacy and data security laws, including where applicable the Texas Data Privacy and Security Act (\"TDPSA\") and Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 521. Personal Data includes, where applicable, \"Sensitive Data\" as defined under TDPSA.\n\n1.6 \"Sensitive Data\" (where applicable) includes categories such as government-issued identifiers, financial account information with access credentials, precise geolocation, racial or ethnic origin, religious beliefs, mental or physical health diagnosis, sexuality, citizenship or immigration status, genetic or biometric data processed for uniquely identifying an individual, and Personal Data of a known child, in each case to the extent such category is regulated under applicable law.\n\n1.7 \"Representatives\" means, with respect to a Party, that Party and its Affiliates’ directors, officers, employees, agents, contractors, consultants, temporary workers, and professional advisors (including attorneys, accountants, bankers, and insurers) who (a) have a bona fide need to know the Confidential Information for the Purpose, and (b) are bound by written or professional confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those contained in this Agreement. Representatives do not include any person who is a direct competitor of the Disclosing Party, unless the Disclosing Party provides prior written consent.\n\n1.8 \"Evaluation Material\" means (a) Confidential Information; (b) Derived Materials; and (c) all media, copies, excerpts, and embodiments of the foregoing, regardless of format.\n\n1.9 \"Permitted Purpose\" means the Purpose stated in the Recitals and any activities reasonably necessary to evaluate, structure, negotiate, and/or implement the contemplated opportunity, strictly subject to the limitations in this Agreement.\n\n1.10 \"Disclosing Party\" means a Party that discloses Confidential Information (including through its Representatives) to the other Party.\n\n1.11 \"Receiving Party\" means a Party that receives Confidential Information (including through its Representatives) from the other Party.\n\n1.12 \"Access\" means any ability to view, receive, retrieve, listen to, inspect, download, copy, reproduce, transmit, or otherwise obtain information, including through systems credentials, physical access to facilities, or remote access.\n\n1.13 \"Law\" means any applicable federal, state (including Texas), or local law, statute, ordinance, regulation, rule, order, subpoena, civil investigative demand, or other binding legal process.\n\n1.14 \"Security Incident\" means any actual or reasonably suspected unauthorized access to, acquisition of, disclosure of, or use of Confidential Information (including Personal Data), or any material loss of availability or integrity of Confidential Information, including incidents involving malware, ransomware, or inadvertent disclosure.\n\n1.15 \"Written\" or \"in writing\" means written communications, including electronic records and signatures, that satisfy the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 322) and the federal Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (\"ESIGN\").\n\n1.16 \"Including\" means including without limitation.\n\n1.17 \"Person\" includes an individual, corporation, partnership, limited liability company, association, trust, governmental entity, or other legal or commercial entity.\n\n1.18 \"Competing Product/Service\" (if used in this Agreement) means any product, service, or offering that is reasonably substitutable for, or is intended to compete with, the Disclosing Party’s product(s) or service(s) that are the subject of the Purpose, as reasonably understood based on information disclosed under this Agreement."},{"id":"confidentiality_obligations","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. CONFIDENTIALITY OBLIGATIONS","content":"2.1 Permitted Purpose; Limited Use. The Receiving Party shall use the Confidential Information solely for the Permitted Purpose. Without limiting the foregoing, the Receiving Party shall not use Confidential Information to (a) compete with the Disclosing Party; (b) create, improve, or reverse engineer products or services that are competitive with the Disclosing Party; (c) solicit the Disclosing Party’s customers, suppliers, or personnel (except as expressly permitted under an optional clause, if included and elected); or (d) file, prosecute, or support any patent or other intellectual property application based on the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.\n\n2.2 Need-to-Know Disclosure; Responsibility for Representatives. The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information only to its Representatives who have a bona fide need to know such Confidential Information for the Permitted Purpose. The Receiving Party shall be responsible for any breach of this Agreement by its Representatives, and shall ensure that its Representatives comply with the terms of this Agreement as if they were the Receiving Party.\n\n2.3 Standard of Care. The Receiving Party shall protect Confidential Information using at least the same degree of care it uses to protect its own confidential information of similar nature, but in no event less than reasonable care.\n\n2.4 Safeguards and Information Security. The Receiving Party shall implement and maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards designed to (a) prevent unauthorized Access to Confidential Information, (b) protect against reasonably anticipated threats or hazards to the security or integrity of Confidential Information, and (c) prevent unauthorized disclosure or use. Such safeguards shall be appropriate to the nature of the Confidential Information and the manner of Access.\n\n2.5 No Unapproved Copying or Distribution. The Receiving Party shall not copy, reproduce, or distribute Confidential Information except to the extent reasonably necessary for the Permitted Purpose. All copies and reproductions shall remain subject to this Agreement, and (to the extent reasonably practicable) shall include the Disclosing Party’s confidentiality legends or other identifying markings.\n\n2.6 No Reverse Engineering; No Decompilation. Unless expressly permitted in a separate signed agreement, the Receiving Party shall not, and shall not permit any third party to, (a) reverse engineer, disassemble, decompile, decode, or otherwise attempt to derive source code, underlying ideas, algorithms, structure, or organization from any Confidential Information, prototype, software, or other tangible embodiment provided by the Disclosing Party; or (b) analyze any samples or components for the purpose of replicating or competing with the Disclosing Party.\n\n2.7 No Circumvention of Security. The Receiving Party shall not attempt to bypass, disable, or circumvent any access controls, rate limits, authentication mechanisms, encryption, watermarking, or other security measures used by the Disclosing Party in connection with the Confidential Information.\n\n2.8 Discussion Confidentiality; No Publicity. Except as required by Law, neither Party shall issue any press release or public statement regarding the Purpose, the discussions between the Parties, or this Agreement, without the other Party’s prior written consent.\n\n2.9 Compelled Disclosure. If the Receiving Party (or any of its Representatives) is required by Law to disclose any Confidential Information, the Receiving Party shall, to the extent legally permitted: (a) promptly notify the Disclosing Party in writing of the requirement (including the identity of the requesting authority and the scope of requested disclosure); (b) reasonably cooperate with the Disclosing Party, at the Disclosing Party’s expense, in seeking a protective order or other appropriate remedy; and (c) disclose only that portion of Confidential Information that the Receiving Party is legally required to disclose, using commercially reasonable efforts to obtain confidential treatment for any Confidential Information so disclosed.\n\n2.10 Notice of Misuse or Security Incident. The Receiving Party shall promptly notify the Disclosing Party in writing if it becomes aware of (a) any unauthorized use or disclosure of Confidential Information, (b) any Security Incident involving Confidential Information, or (c) any other breach or suspected breach of this Agreement. Unless prohibited by Law or law enforcement, such notice shall be provided without unreasonable delay and, where feasible, within {{security_incident_notice_hours}} hours after discovery.\n\n2.11 Mitigation; Cooperation. Following any event described in Section 2.10, the Receiving Party shall (a) take reasonable steps to contain, mitigate, and remediate the event; (b) cooperate with the Disclosing Party’s reasonable requests for information regarding the event; and (c) provide reasonable assistance (at the Disclosing Party’s expense) in connection with notifications, investigations, or filings required by Law, to the extent related to the Receiving Party’s acts or omissions.\n\n2.12 No Requirement to Mark. Confidential Information does not need to be marked or identified as confidential to be protected under this Agreement if it otherwise meets the definition of Confidential Information.\n\n2.13 Reservation of Rights. All Confidential Information remains the property of the Disclosing Party (or its licensors, as applicable). Except for the limited rights expressly granted in this Agreement to use Confidential Information for the Permitted Purpose, no license or other rights (by implication, estoppel, or otherwise) are granted under any patent, copyright, trademark, trade secret, or other intellectual property right.\n\n2.14 Trade Secret Preservation. The Receiving Party acknowledges and agrees that the Disclosing Party intends for Confidential Information that constitutes Trade Secrets to be maintained as such. The Receiving Party will use reasonable measures to preserve the secrecy and confidentiality of Trade Secrets consistent with TUTSA and DTSA."},{"id":"exclusions","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. EXCLUSIONS FROM CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION","content":"3.1 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by contemporaneous written records or other competent evidence:\n\n(a) is or becomes generally available to the public through no breach of this Agreement by the Receiving Party or its Representatives;\n\n(b) was lawfully in the Receiving Party’s possession, without restriction on use or disclosure, prior to disclosure by the Disclosing Party;\n\n(c) is lawfully received by the Receiving Party from a third party without breach of any obligation of confidentiality owed to the Disclosing Party;\n\n(d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information, as evidenced by contemporaneous written records; or\n\n(e) is approved for release or disclosure by the Disclosing Party in a written instrument signed by an authorized representative of the Disclosing Party.\n\n3.2 Combination of Information. The exclusions in Section 3.1 apply only to the extent the information itself meets the exclusion. Information will not be deemed excluded merely because it is included within more general public information or because individual components are public, if the combination, compilation, or assembly is not publicly known.\n\n3.3 No Implied Authorization by Disclosure. Disclosure of Confidential Information under this Agreement does not constitute a waiver of any applicable privilege, immunity, or protection (including attorney-client privilege, work product, or trade secret protection), and does not by itself make the information public or non-confidential."},{"id":"term_and_duration","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TERM AND DURATION","content":"4.1 Term. This Agreement begins on the Effective Date and continues until the earlier of: (a) {{expiration_date}} (if provided), or (b) termination by either Party upon {{notice_period}} days’ prior written notice to the other Party (the \"Term\").\n\n4.2 Survival of Obligations. Except as set forth in Section 4.3, the Receiving Party’s obligations under this Agreement with respect to Confidential Information disclosed during the Term shall survive termination or expiration of this Agreement for a period of {{confidentiality_period}} years from the date of disclosure of the applicable Confidential Information.\n\n4.3 Trade Secrets. Notwithstanding Section 4.2, with respect to any Confidential Information that constitutes a Trade Secret, the Receiving Party’s confidentiality and non-use obligations shall continue for so long as such information remains a Trade Secret under applicable law (including TUTSA and DTSA).\n\n4.4 Effect of Termination; Ongoing Restrictions. Termination or expiration of this Agreement does not (a) relieve either Party of obligations accrued prior to termination or expiration; (b) eliminate any obligation to return or destroy Evaluation Material as provided in Section 5; or (c) limit any right or remedy available to the Disclosing Party.\n\n4.5 No Obligation to Proceed. Either Party may discontinue discussions regarding the Purpose at any time. Except as expressly set forth in a definitive written agreement executed by both Parties, neither Party shall have any obligation to enter into any transaction or relationship with the other Party."},{"id":"return_of_information","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. RETURN OR DESTRUCTION OF INFORMATION","content":"5.1 Return or Destruction Upon Request. Upon the Disclosing Party’s written request, the Receiving Party shall, within {{return_destroy_days}} days, (a) return to the Disclosing Party all Evaluation Material in the Receiving Party’s possession or control, or (b) destroy such Evaluation Material, at the Disclosing Party’s election. The Disclosing Party may make such request at any time, including upon termination or expiration of this Agreement.\n\n5.2 Scope of Return/Destruction. The obligation in Section 5.1 includes all copies, reproductions, excerpts, and embodiments of Evaluation Material, including those contained in emails, messaging platforms, ticketing systems, source control repositories, shared drives, and other storage locations, to the extent reasonably accessible and within the Receiving Party’s control.\n\n5.3 Certification. Upon written request, an authorized representative of the Receiving Party shall certify in writing that the Receiving Party has complied with Section 5.1, describing the general categories of materials returned or destroyed and the date(s) of such return or destruction.\n\n5.4 Archival Copies; Legal Hold. Notwithstanding Section 5.1, the Receiving Party may retain limited copies of Evaluation Material solely to the extent (a) required by applicable Law, regulation, court order, or bona fide legal hold, or (b) automatically retained in routine system backups in accordance with the Receiving Party’s standard retention practices, provided that: (i) any retained Evaluation Material remains subject to this Agreement; (ii) such retained Evaluation Material is not accessed or used for any purpose other than compliance with Law or legal hold; and (iii) the Receiving Party uses commercially reasonable efforts to delete such retained Evaluation Material when it is no longer required to be retained.\n\n5.5 No Duty to Delete System Logs. The Parties acknowledge that certain system logs, metadata, and security or compliance records may be retained as part of ordinary-course operations. Such retained information remains subject to confidentiality obligations to the extent it contains Confidential Information.\n\n5.6 Return Does Not Limit Remedies. The return or destruction of Evaluation Material does not limit the Disclosing Party’s right to seek remedies for any breach of this Agreement."},{"id":"remedies","type":"negotiable","order":6,"title":"6. REMEDIES","content":"6.1 Injunctive and Equitable Relief. Each Party acknowledges that unauthorized use or disclosure of Confidential Information may cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be inadequate or difficult to ascertain. Accordingly, in the event of any actual or threatened breach of this Agreement, the Disclosing Party shall be entitled to seek temporary, preliminary, and permanent injunctive relief and other equitable relief from any court of competent jurisdiction, without the necessity of proving actual damages. To the extent permitted by Law, the Parties agree to waive any requirement for the Disclosing Party to post a bond or other security; if such waiver is not enforceable, bond shall be set in the minimum amount required by Law.\n\n6.2 Monetary Damages; Accounting. In addition to equitable relief, the Disclosing Party shall be entitled to pursue all damages available at law or in equity, including without limitation actual damages, unjust enrichment, and (where available) exemplary damages and attorneys’ fees under TUTSA and/or DTSA.\n\n6.3 Attorneys’ Fees and Costs. In any action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the prevailing party shall be entitled to recover its reasonable attorneys’ fees and court costs, in addition to any other relief to which it may be entitled, to the extent permitted by Law.\n\n6.4 Cumulative Rights. All rights and remedies are cumulative and not exclusive of any rights or remedies that may be available under Law, including TUTSA and DTSA.\n\n6.5 Defend Trade Secrets Act Whistleblower Immunity Notice. Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b): (a) An individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that (i) is made in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (ii) is made in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal. (b) An individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding, if the individual (i) files any document containing the trade secret under seal, and (ii) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order.\n\n6.6 DTSA Notice Distribution (Acknowledgement). To the extent a Party provides Confidential Information to its employees or individual contractors under this Agreement, that Party is responsible for providing the notice in Section 6.5 (or substantially similar notice) to such individuals in any contract or policy governing trade secret or confidential information, as applicable, in order to preserve rights under DTSA."},{"id":"governing_law","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. GOVERNING LAW AND VENUE","content":"7.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and any dispute, claim, or controversy arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the Confidential Information, or the Purpose (whether in contract, tort, statute, or otherwise) shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Texas, without regard to its conflict of laws rules.\n\n7.2 Exclusive Venue and Jurisdiction. Subject to Section 7.3, the Parties irrevocably submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of the state courts located in {{venue_county}} County, Texas, and the United States federal courts whose district includes {{venue_county}} County, Texas, for any action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement, and the Parties waive any objection to venue in such courts, including any claim of inconvenient forum.\n\n7.3 Equitable Relief Carve-Out. Notwithstanding Section 7.2, a Party may seek temporary, preliminary, or emergency injunctive relief in any court of competent jurisdiction to prevent imminent or ongoing misuse or disclosure of Confidential Information; provided that any subsequent merits proceeding shall be brought in the courts specified in Section 7.2 to the maximum extent permitted by Law.\n\n7.4 Service of Process. Each Party consents to service of process in any action by personal service, nationally recognized overnight courier, or any other method permitted by Texas law or the applicable court rules."},{"id":"general_provisions","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"8.1 Notices. All notices or other communications required or permitted under this Agreement shall be in writing and shall be deemed given: (a) when delivered personally; (b) one (1) business day after being sent by a nationally recognized overnight courier; (c) three (3) business days after being mailed by certified or registered mail, return receipt requested, postage prepaid; or (d) when sent by email with confirmation of transmission (such as a sent confirmation, read receipt, or other confirmation mechanism reasonably indicating successful delivery). Notices shall be sent to the addresses and emails listed in the signature block (or to such other address or email as a Party may designate by notice).\n\n8.2 No License; Ownership. All Confidential Information disclosed by a Disclosing Party is and shall remain the Disclosing Party’s property (or the property of its licensors). Except for the limited right to use Confidential Information for the Permitted Purpose during the Term, nothing in this Agreement grants the Receiving Party any license or other right under any intellectual property right, whether by implication, estoppel, or otherwise.\n\n8.3 No Representation or Warranty. ALL CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION IS PROVIDED \"AS IS.\" THE DISCLOSING PARTY MAKES NO REPRESENTATION OR WARRANTY, EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, REGARDING THE ACCURACY, COMPLETENESS, NON-INFRINGEMENT, MERCHANTABILITY, OR FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE OF ANY CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION, OR THAT ANY ERRORS CAN OR WILL BE CORRECTED. Neither Party shall be liable to the other for decisions made based on Confidential Information, except to the extent liability arises from a Party’s breach of this Agreement or other applicable Law.\n\n8.4 Independent Contractors; No Employment Relationship. The Parties are independent contractors. Nothing in this Agreement creates a partnership, joint venture, fiduciary relationship, agency, or employment relationship between the Parties. Each Party is solely responsible for (a) the direction and control of its personnel, (b) wages, benefits, and insurance, and (c) compliance with all applicable worker classification, wage and hour, and labor and employment laws (including, as applicable, provisions of the Texas Labor Code) with respect to its own employees and contractors.\n\n8.5 No Obligation to Disclose. Neither Party is required to disclose any particular Confidential Information, and each Party reserves the right, in its sole discretion, to determine what information (if any) it will disclose in connection with the Purpose.\n\n8.6 No Restriction on Residual Knowledge (Optional—If Elected). Unless the Parties initial or otherwise expressly designate this Section 8.6 as applicable in writing, the Parties do not agree to any \"residuals\" rights. If elected, the Receiving Party may use information retained in the unaided memory of its Representatives who had access to Confidential Information, provided that such use does not involve (a) intentional memorization of Trade Secrets, (b) use of any written or recorded materials, or (c) violation of Section 2 (including non-disclosure and non-reverse-engineering obligations). For clarity, residual knowledge does not include source code, customer lists, pricing, or other information that would reasonably be considered highly sensitive.\n\n8.7 No Third-Party Beneficiaries. This Agreement is for the sole benefit of the Parties and their permitted successors and assigns, and nothing herein, express or implied, is intended to or shall confer upon any other Person any legal or equitable right, benefit, or remedy.\n\n8.8 Assignment. Neither Party may assign, delegate, or transfer this Agreement (by operation of law or otherwise) without the prior written consent of the other Party; provided that either Party may assign this Agreement without consent to an Affiliate or to a successor in interest in connection with a merger, consolidation, reorganization, or sale of all or substantially all of its business or assets, so long as the assignee agrees in writing to be bound by this Agreement. Any prohibited assignment is void.\n\n8.9 Severability; Reformation. If any provision of this Agreement is held invalid, illegal, or unenforceable in any respect, (a) the provision shall be enforced to the maximum extent permitted by Law, and if necessary shall be reformed to the minimum extent necessary to make it enforceable while preserving the Parties’ intent, and (b) the remaining provisions shall remain in full force and effect.\n\n8.10 Waiver. No waiver of any breach of any provision of this Agreement shall constitute a waiver of any prior, concurrent, or subsequent breach of the same or any other provisions. No waiver shall be effective unless in writing and signed by the Party against whom the waiver is sought to be enforced.\n\n8.11 Entire Agreement; Amendments. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties regarding its subject matter and supersedes all prior and contemporaneous agreements, proposals, negotiations, representations, and understandings, whether written or oral, relating to such subject matter. Any amendment or modification must be in writing and signed by both Parties.\n\n8.12 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which is deemed an original and all of which together constitute one instrument.\n\n8.13 Electronic Signatures and Records. This Agreement and any notices, approvals, or consents may be executed and delivered electronically and shall be valid and enforceable under the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 322) and ESIGN. The Parties agree that electronic records of signatures and delivery may be used as evidence.\n\n8.14 Headings; Interpretation. Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation. In the event of ambiguity, no presumption or burden of proof will arise favoring or disfavoring either Party by virtue of authorship.\n\n8.15 Further Assurances. Each Party shall execute and deliver such further documents and take such further actions as may be reasonably necessary to carry out the intent of this Agreement.\n\n8.16 Waiver of Jury Trial (Optional—If Enforceable). TO THE EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, EACH PARTY KNOWINGLY AND VOLUNTARILY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION OR PROCEEDING ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT."},{"id":"privacy_data_security","type":"standard","order":9,"title":"9. PRIVACY; DATA PROTECTION; SECURITY","content":"9.1 Applicability. This Section 9 applies to the extent Confidential Information includes Personal Data or other information subject to privacy, data protection, or data security requirements.\n\n9.2 Compliance with Privacy and Security Laws. Each Party shall comply with applicable privacy and data security Laws in connection with its receipt, use, storage, processing, and disclosure of Personal Data under this Agreement, including, to the extent applicable: (a) the Texas Data Privacy and Security Act (TDPSA); and (b) Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 521 (including requirements related to safeguarding sensitive personal information and breach notification).\n\n9.3 Minimum Necessary; Purpose Limitation. The Receiving Party shall limit its collection, access, use, retention, and disclosure of Personal Data to what is reasonably necessary for the Permitted Purpose and shall not retain Personal Data longer than necessary for the Permitted Purpose, except as required by Law.\n\n9.4 Security Program. The Receiving Party shall maintain an information security program with reasonable safeguards appropriate to the nature of the Personal Data and the risks presented, which may include as appropriate: access controls, least-privilege permissions, multi-factor authentication for remote access, encryption in transit, encryption at rest for sensitive datasets, vulnerability management, logging and monitoring, and workforce security awareness.\n\n9.5 Security Incidents Involving Personal Data. Without limiting Section 2.10, if a Security Incident involves Personal Data, the Receiving Party shall (a) promptly provide the Disclosing Party the information reasonably necessary for the Disclosing Party to assess legal obligations; (b) reasonably cooperate with the Disclosing Party’s investigation and remediation; and (c) not make any legally required notifications to individuals, regulators, or consumer reporting agencies regarding the Disclosing Party’s Personal Data without the Disclosing Party’s prior written approval, unless required by Law (in which case the Receiving Party shall provide advance notice to the extent legally permitted).\n\n9.6 Cross-Border Transfers. If the Receiving Party transfers Personal Data across national borders, it shall do so in compliance with applicable Laws and shall implement appropriate safeguards for such transfer.\n\n9.7 De-Identification and Aggregation. If the Receiving Party creates de-identified or aggregated data derived from Personal Data included in Confidential Information, such de-identified or aggregated data remains Confidential Information unless and until the Disclosing Party expressly agrees in writing otherwise. The Receiving Party shall not attempt to re-identify de-identified data.\n\n9.8 Regulated Data (Optional). If Confidential Information includes regulated data subject to specific sectoral Laws (e.g., HIPAA, GLBA, FERPA, COPPA, ITAR, EAR, or PCI DSS), the Parties shall not exchange such regulated data unless and until they enter into an appropriate written addendum (e.g., a business associate agreement) defining permitted uses, safeguards, and responsibilities.\n\n9.9 Data Subject Requests. If the Receiving Party receives a request from an individual (or authorized agent) to access, delete, correct, or otherwise exercise rights regarding Personal Data that is part of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information, the Receiving Party shall (a) promptly notify the Disclosing Party to the extent legally permitted, and (b) not respond to the request except as instructed by the Disclosing Party or as required by Law.\n\n9.10 No Sale; No Sharing for Targeted Advertising. The Receiving Party shall not sell Personal Data or share Personal Data for targeted advertising or cross-context behavioral advertising (as such terms may be defined under applicable Law) when such Personal Data is received as Confidential Information under this Agreement."},{"id":"compliance","type":"optional","order":10,"title":"10. COMPLIANCE WITH LAWS; EXPORT CONTROLS (OPTIONAL)","content":"10.1 General Compliance. Each Party shall comply with all applicable Laws relating to its performance under this Agreement, including laws relating to anti-corruption, anti-bribery, and fair competition.\n\n10.2 Export Controls and Sanctions. The Receiving Party acknowledges that Confidential Information, including certain software, technical data, and technology, may be subject to U.S. export control laws and regulations (including the Export Administration Regulations) and U.S. economic sanctions laws. The Receiving Party agrees that it will not export, re-export, transfer, or disclose (including deemed export) any such Confidential Information in violation of applicable export control or sanctions laws.\n\n10.3 Government Requests. If the Receiving Party receives any inquiry, request, subpoena, or demand from a governmental authority relating to the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information (including requests for interviews or testimony), the Receiving Party shall (to the extent legally permitted) promptly notify the Disclosing Party and reasonably cooperate with the Disclosing Party.\n\n10.4 No Improper Acquisition. The Receiving Party represents that it will not use, and will not request that the Disclosing Party disclose, any information that the Receiving Party knows (or reasonably should know) was obtained by improper means or in violation of any duty owed to a third party.\n\n10.5 Conflicts with Other Obligations. Each Party represents that entering into and performing this Agreement does not violate any obligation it owes to any third party. If a Party becomes aware of a conflict between this Agreement and any other agreement or legal obligation that could affect the confidentiality, use, or disclosure of Confidential Information, that Party shall promptly notify the other Party."},{"id":"non_solicitation","type":"optional","order":11,"title":"11. NON-SOLICITATION (OPTIONAL)","content":"11.1 Optional Nature. This Section 11 applies only if the Parties expressly elect it in writing (including by checking an applicable box in an order form, statement of work, or addendum referencing this Agreement). If not elected, this Section 11 shall be of no force or effect.\n\n11.2 Non-Solicitation of Personnel. During the Term and for {{non_solicitation_period_months}} months thereafter, neither Party shall, directly or indirectly, solicit for employment or engagement, or knowingly induce to leave employment or engagement, any employee or individual contractor of the other Party with whom the soliciting Party had material contact or who became known to the soliciting Party through Confidential Information in connection with the Purpose.\n\n11.3 Non-Solicitation of Customers/Prospects (Optional Subsection). If elected by the Parties in writing, during the Term and for {{non_solicitation_period_months}} months thereafter, neither Party shall knowingly solicit, for the purpose of providing a Competing Product/Service, any customer or actively pursued prospective customer of the other Party that (a) was specifically identified as part of Confidential Information and (b) with whom the soliciting Party had material contact through the Purpose.\n\n11.4 Permitted Activities; Carve-Outs. Section 11 does not prohibit: (a) general solicitations not targeted at the other Party’s personnel (such as advertisements, job fairs, or use of recruiters not specifically directed to the other Party’s personnel); (b) hiring any person who responds to a general solicitation; or (c) solicitations or relationships that existed independently of the Purpose and can be substantiated by contemporaneous records.\n\n11.5 Reasonableness; Enforcement. The Parties acknowledge that the restrictions in this Section 11 are intended to be reasonable and no broader than necessary to protect legitimate business interests. If any restriction is found overly broad, a court may modify it to the extent necessary to make it enforceable to the maximum extent permitted by applicable Texas law."},{"id":"non_compete","type":"optional","order":12,"title":"12. NON-COMPETITION / NON-CIRCUMVENTION (TEXAS) (OPTIONAL)","content":"12.1 Optional Nature; Texas Law Requirements. This Section 12 applies only if the Parties expressly elect it in writing. The Parties acknowledge that Texas Business and Commerce Code § 15.50 governs the enforceability of covenants not to compete. The Parties intend that any restrictive covenant in this Section 12 be (a) ancillary to or part of an otherwise enforceable agreement, including the confidentiality and trade secret protections in this Agreement, and (b) limited to reasonable restrictions as to time, geographic area, and scope of activity.\n\n12.2 Consideration; Legitimate Business Interests. The Parties acknowledge and agree that (a) the disclosure of Confidential Information and Trade Secrets, and (b) the mutual promises and obligations contained in this Agreement, constitute valuable consideration supporting this Section 12, and that this Section 12 is designed to protect legitimate business interests, including Trade Secrets, confidential business information, goodwill, and customer relationships.\n\n12.3 Restricted Activities. During the Term and for {{non_compete_period_months}} months thereafter, the Receiving Party shall not use the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information to engage in the following restricted activities within {{restricted_territory}}: {{restricted_activities}}.\n\n12.4 Non-Circumvention (Alternative to Non-Compete). If the Parties elect non-circumvention instead of (or in addition to) Section 12.3, then during the Term and for {{non_compete_period_months}} months thereafter, neither Party shall knowingly use the other Party’s Confidential Information to circumvent the other Party in connection with the Purpose, including by bypassing the other Party to directly contract with a specifically identified third party contact or business opportunity introduced through the Purpose, where such circumvention would deprive the other Party of a reasonably expected opportunity directly related to the Purpose.\n\n12.5 Exceptions. This Section 12 does not restrict a Party from (a) engaging in business activities that were conducted in the ordinary course prior to the Effective Date and can be substantiated by contemporaneous records, (b) engaging in activities unrelated to the Purpose that do not use or rely on the other Party’s Confidential Information, or (c) competing based solely on the Party’s general skills and knowledge and publicly available information, provided that no Confidential Information or Trade Secrets are used or disclosed.\n\n12.6 Reformation; Court Modification. If any provision of this Section 12 is determined to be invalid or unenforceable as written, the Parties intend that such provision be reformed or modified by a court to the minimum extent necessary to make it enforceable under Texas law and enforced as reformed, consistent with Texas Business and Commerce Code § 15.51.\n\n12.7 No Requirement to Enter Definitive Agreement. For clarity, election of this Section 12 does not obligate either Party to enter into any definitive agreement relating to the Purpose."}]'::jsonb,
