-- Update: One-Way Non-Disclosure Agreement (Texas)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This One-Way Non-Disclosure Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date") by and between (i) {{party_a_company}}, with a mailing address of {{party_a_address}} (the "Disclosing Party" and, as applicable, "{{party_a_name}}"), and (ii) {{party_b_company}}, with a mailing address of {{party_b_address}} (the "Receiving Party" and, as applicable, "{{party_b_name}}"; Disclosing Party and Receiving Party are each a "Party" and together the "Parties").

Each Party represents and warrants that: (a) it is duly organized, validly existing, and in good standing under the laws of its jurisdiction of formation (if an entity), (b) it has full power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement, and (c) the person signing this Agreement on its behalf has been duly authorized to bind that Party.

The Parties acknowledge and agree that this Agreement is intended to be enforceable under the laws of the State of Texas and applicable federal law, including the Texas Uniform Trade Secrets Act (Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A) and the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act of 2016 (18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq.).',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, the Disclosing Party possesses certain confidential, proprietary, and/or trade secret information and materials, including without limitation business, financial, technical, operational, and strategic information, that the Disclosing Party desires to disclose to the Receiving Party in connection with {{purpose}} (the "Purpose");

WHEREAS, the Receiving Party desires to receive and evaluate such information solely for the Purpose and acknowledges that the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information (as defined below) is valuable and that unauthorized use or disclosure could cause irreparable harm;

WHEREAS, the Parties desire to set forth their understanding regarding the handling, protection, and permitted use of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information, including information disclosed in tangible and intangible forms, whether disclosed before or after the Effective Date;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises contained in this Agreement and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS","content":"1.1 \"Affiliate\" means, with respect to a Party, any entity that directly or indirectly controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with that Party, where \"control\" means the power to direct management or policies through ownership of voting securities, by contract, or otherwise.\n\n1.2 \"Business Day\" means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday, or day on which banks are authorized or required to close in the State of Texas.\n\n1.3 \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed or made available by or on behalf of the Disclosing Party to the Receiving Party (including to any of its Representatives), whether before or after the Effective Date, and whether disclosed in writing, orally, visually, electronically, digitally, by inspection of facilities or equipment, by demonstration, by providing access to systems or data rooms, or in any other form or medium, that: (a) is marked or identified as confidential or proprietary at the time of disclosure; (b) is disclosed under circumstances that reasonably indicate it is confidential; or (c) reasonably should be understood to be confidential given the nature of the information or the circumstances of disclosure.\n\n1.4 Confidential Information includes, without limitation (whether or not marked as confidential): (a) trade secrets; (b) inventions (whether patentable or not), discoveries, ideas, works of authorship, know-how, methods, processes, formulas, techniques, protocols, algorithms, models, architectures, designs, drawings, specifications, source code, object code, firmware, and software documentation; (c) business and strategic plans; budgets; financial statements; pricing; cost and margin information; forecasts; metrics; KPIs; product roadmaps; market analyses; and expansion plans; (d) customer, vendor, partner, supplier, and contractor information, including lists, identities, contact information, purchasing history, contract terms, and deal pipelines; (e) marketing, branding, and go-to-market strategies; (f) internal policies, security measures, operational information, and training materials; (g) information regarding employees, contractors, compensation structures, recruiting, and organizational charts; (h) non-public information received from third parties that the Disclosing Party is obligated to keep confidential; and (i) the fact that discussions or negotiations are taking place regarding the Purpose, the status of such discussions, and the terms and substance of any communications between the Parties relating to the Purpose.\n\n1.5 \"Derived Information\" means all notes, summaries, analyses, compilations, studies, reports, extracts, adaptations, translations, interpretations, and other materials (whether in written, electronic, or other form) that are created by or for the Receiving Party and that contain, reflect, are based on, or otherwise incorporate any Confidential Information.\n\n1.6 \"Documentation\" means any documents, records, correspondence, presentations, memoranda, files, images, audio or video recordings, data sets, reports, and other materials (including copies) in any form.\n\n1.7 \"Law\" means any applicable federal, state, or local law, statute, ordinance, rule, regulation, code, order, judgment, decree, or other legal requirement of any governmental authority.\n\n1.8 \"Personal Data\" means any information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked (directly or indirectly) to an identified or identifiable natural person, including without limitation names, addresses, email addresses, phone numbers, government-issued identifiers, account credentials, financial account numbers, biometric identifiers, and any other information subject to privacy, data protection, or breach notification Laws.\n\n1.9 \"Permitted Purpose\" means the Purpose described in the Recitals and any more specific written description agreed by the Parties from time to time.\n\n1.10 \"Receiving Party\" includes its Affiliates only to the extent (and solely if) such Affiliates are expressly permitted under Section 2.4 and are bound in writing to confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those in this Agreement.\n\n1.11 \"Representatives\" means the Receiving Party’s and its permitted Affiliates’ directors, officers, employees, agents, professional advisors (including attorneys and accountants), contractors, consultants, and financial sources (including prospective investors and lenders) who have a legitimate need to know the Confidential Information for the Permitted Purpose, provided that such persons are bound by written obligations of confidentiality and restricted use that are at least as protective as those set forth in this Agreement.\n\n1.12 \"Security Incident\" means any actual or reasonably suspected unauthorized access to, acquisition of, disclosure of, loss of, or inability to account for Confidential Information (including Personal Data), or any compromise of the Receiving Party’s systems that could reasonably be expected to impact the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of Confidential Information.\n\n1.13 \"Trade Secret\" means information that constitutes a trade secret under the Texas Uniform Trade Secrets Act (Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A) and/or the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act (18 U.S.C. § 1839), including information that derives independent economic value from not being generally known and is subject to reasonable measures to maintain its secrecy.\n\n1.14 \"Written\" or \"in writing\" includes writing in paper form and electronic records, including emails and other electronic communications, to the extent recognized under the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (Texas Business & Commerce Code Chapter 322) and the federal Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (15 U.S.C. § 7001 et seq.)."},{"id":"confidentiality_obligations","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. CONFIDENTIALITY OBLIGATIONS","content":"2.1 Limited Use.\n(a) The Receiving Party shall use the Confidential Information solely for the Permitted Purpose and for no other purpose, including without limitation to compete with the Disclosing Party, to obtain an unfair competitive advantage, to circumvent the Disclosing Party, or to create or improve products or services for any use outside the Permitted Purpose.\n(b) The Receiving Party shall not use the Confidential Information in any manner that violates Law, infringes intellectual property rights, misappropriates trade secrets, or violates contractual or fiduciary duties owed to the Disclosing Party.\n\n2.2 Non-Disclosure.\n(a) The Receiving Party shall not disclose, publish, disseminate, transmit, or otherwise make available any Confidential Information to any person or entity except as expressly permitted under this Agreement.\n(b) The Receiving Party shall not disclose Confidential Information to any Representative unless such Representative: (i) has a need to know for the Permitted Purpose; (ii) is informed of the confidential nature of the Confidential Information; and (iii) is bound by written confidentiality and restricted-use obligations at least as protective as this Agreement.\n(c) The Receiving Party shall be responsible and liable for any breach of this Agreement by its Representatives as if such breach were committed by the Receiving Party.\n\n2.3 Standard of Care; Protection of Trade Secrets.\n(a) The Receiving Party shall protect the Confidential Information using at least the same degree of care it uses to protect its own confidential information of similar sensitivity and importance, but in no event less than a commercially reasonable standard of care.\n(b) Without limiting the foregoing, the Receiving Party acknowledges that Trade Secrets require reasonable measures to maintain secrecy and agrees to apply heightened precautions reasonably appropriate to the nature of the information (e.g., least-privilege access, encryption in transit and at rest where appropriate, access logging, and secure storage).\n\n2.4 Permitted Disclosures to Affiliates (Optional).\n(a) The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information to its Affiliates only if necessary for the Permitted Purpose and only if such Affiliates are bound by written obligations at least as protective as this Agreement.\n(b) Upon the Disclosing Party’s written request, the Receiving Party shall identify the Affiliates (and categories of Representatives) to whom Confidential Information has been disclosed.\n\n2.5 Security Measures.\n(a) The Receiving Party shall implement and maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards designed to protect Confidential Information against unauthorized access, disclosure, alteration, or destruction.\n(b) Such safeguards shall, as appropriate to the nature of the Confidential Information and the Receiving Party’s environment, include: (i) access controls and authentication; (ii) role-based permissions; (iii) encryption or secure transmission methods for sensitive data; (iv) secure disposal of physical materials; (v) malware protection and patch management; and (vi) reasonable personnel screening and training for those with access.\n(c) The Receiving Party shall not remove any confidentiality legends or proprietary notices from materials provided by the Disclosing Party.\n\n2.6 Handling, Copying, and Minimization.\n(a) The Receiving Party shall limit copying and reproduction of Confidential Information to the minimum necessary for the Permitted Purpose.\n(b) Any copies or reproductions of Confidential Information remain the Disclosing Party’s property and are subject to this Agreement.\n(c) Derived Information is deemed Confidential Information for purposes of this Agreement.\n\n2.7 No Reverse Engineering; No Decompilation.\n(a) The Receiving Party shall not, and shall not permit any person to, reverse engineer, disassemble, decompile, decode, or otherwise attempt to derive the composition, source code, underlying ideas, structure, or trade secrets from any Confidential Information, prototypes, samples, software, devices, or other materials provided by the Disclosing Party, except to the extent such restriction is prohibited by Law.\n(b) If any Law permits limited reverse engineering notwithstanding this restriction, the Receiving Party shall provide the Disclosing Party with prior written notice (to the extent legally permitted) and shall limit any such activity strictly to what is legally required.\n\n2.8 No Publicity; No Announcement.\nThe Receiving Party shall not issue press releases or make public statements regarding the Permitted Purpose or the relationship contemplated hereby, nor use the Disclosing Party’s name, trademarks, or logos, without the Disclosing Party’s prior written consent, except as required by Law.\n\n2.9 Compelled Disclosure.\n(a) If the Receiving Party (or any Representative) is required by Law, regulation, subpoena, court order, civil investigative demand, or other legal process to disclose any Confidential Information, the Receiving Party shall, to the extent legally permitted: (i) promptly notify the Disclosing Party in writing; (ii) reasonably cooperate with the Disclosing Party (at the Disclosing Party’s expense) in seeking a protective order or other appropriate remedy; and (iii) disclose only the portion of Confidential Information that is legally required to be disclosed.\n(b) The Receiving Party shall use commercially reasonable efforts to ensure that any Confidential Information disclosed pursuant to this Section 2.9 is treated confidentially by the receiving authority.\n\n2.10 Security Incident Notification.\n(a) The Receiving Party shall notify the Disclosing Party without undue delay (and in any event within {{security_incident_notice_hours}} hours) after becoming aware of a Security Incident that involves or reasonably may involve the Confidential Information.\n(b) The Receiving Party shall provide information reasonably requested by the Disclosing Party regarding the nature and scope of the Security Incident, the types of information implicated, the steps taken or planned to investigate and mitigate the incident, and any communications with law enforcement or regulators.\n(c) The Receiving Party shall cooperate in good faith with the Disclosing Party’s reasonable requests to mitigate harm and prevent recurrence.\n(d) The Receiving Party shall not make any legally required breach notifications to affected individuals or regulators that reference the Disclosing Party without first consulting the Disclosing Party, unless prohibited by Law. The Parties acknowledge that certain notifications may be required under applicable Texas and federal breach notification laws, including, where applicable, the Texas Identity Theft Enforcement and Protection Act (Texas Business & Commerce Code Chapter 521).\n\n2.11 Export Controls and Sanctions.\nThe Receiving Party shall not export, re-export, transfer, or disclose any Confidential Information in violation of U.S. export control or economic sanctions Laws. The Disclosing Party makes no representation that any Confidential Information is suitable for use in any jurisdiction.\n\n2.12 No Obligation to Disclose; No Reliance.\n(a) The Disclosing Party has no obligation to disclose any particular information or to continue discussions regarding the Permitted Purpose.\n(b) The Receiving Party acknowledges that Confidential Information may be incomplete or contain errors and agrees that, to the maximum extent permitted by Law, the Disclosing Party disclaims liability for the accuracy or completeness of Confidential Information, provided that nothing in this Section 2.12 limits liability for fraud.\n\n2.13 Preservation of Privilege.\nAny Confidential Information that is subject to attorney-client privilege, work product protection, or any other privilege or immunity shall remain privileged. Disclosure under this Agreement is not intended to waive, and shall not waive, any privilege or immunity. The Receiving Party shall promptly notify the Disclosing Party if it becomes aware of any unauthorized disclosure of privileged materials."},{"id":"exclusions","type":"standard","order":3,"title":"3. EXCLUSIONS FROM CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION","content":"3.1 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Receiving Party can demonstrate by competent written evidence:\n(a) is or becomes publicly available through no breach of this Agreement by the Receiving Party or its Representatives;\n(b) was lawfully known by the Receiving Party, without restriction on use or disclosure, prior to disclosure by or on behalf of the Disclosing Party;\n(c) is lawfully received by the Receiving Party from a third party who, to the Receiving Party’s knowledge after reasonable inquiry, had the legal right to disclose such information without restriction;\n(d) is independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of or reference to any Confidential Information and without breach of any obligation owed to the Disclosing Party; or\n(e) is approved for release in writing by an authorized representative of the Disclosing Party.\n\n3.2 Combination and Degree of Similarity. Information shall not be deemed to fall within any exclusion above merely because it is embraced by more general information in the public domain or in the Receiving Party’s possession. A combination of features shall be considered Confidential Information even if individual elements are publicly available, if the combination itself is not publicly known and provides value.\n\n3.3 No Implied Rights from Exclusions. Any information that meets an exclusion under Section 3.1 shall be excluded solely to the extent it meets that exclusion. No exclusion grants the Receiving Party any license or other rights in any intellectual property of the Disclosing Party.\n\n3.4 Burden of Proof. The Receiving Party bears the burden of establishing that an exclusion applies. The Parties agree that general assertions or conclusory statements are insufficient; appropriate contemporaneous records may be required to establish independent development or prior knowledge.\n\n3.5 Compelled Disclosure Not an Exclusion. Disclosure pursuant to Section 2.9 (Compelled Disclosure) does not render the disclosed information non-confidential and does not create any exclusion under this Section 3."},{"id":"term_and_duration","type":"standard","order":4,"title":"4. TERM AND DURATION","content":"4.1 Term. This Agreement begins on the Effective Date and continues until the earlier of: (a) {{expiration_date}}, or (b) termination by either Party upon {{notice_period}} days’ prior written notice to the other Party (the \"Term\").\n\n4.2 Effect of Termination. Termination or expiration of this Agreement does not relieve the Receiving Party of its obligations with respect to Confidential Information disclosed prior to termination or expiration, including without limitation the obligations in Sections 2 (Confidentiality Obligations), 5 (Return or Destruction), 6 (Remedies), 7 (Governing Law; Venue), and 8 (General Provisions) to the extent applicable.\n\n4.3 Survival Period for Non-Trade Secret Confidential Information. Except as provided in Section 4.4, the Receiving Party’s obligations to protect Confidential Information shall continue for {{confidentiality_period}} years from the date of disclosure of the applicable Confidential Information.\n\n4.4 Trade Secrets. With respect to any Trade Secret, the Receiving Party’s obligations shall continue for so long as such information remains a Trade Secret under applicable Law, including the Texas Uniform Trade Secrets Act (Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A) and the Defend Trade Secrets Act.\n\n4.5 Equitable Tolling. If the Receiving Party breaches this Agreement, any applicable time period for protection of Confidential Information shall be equitably tolled for the period of breach and any period during which the Disclosing Party is deprived of the benefits of this Agreement.\n\n4.6 Continuing Duty to Protect. The Parties acknowledge that Confidential Information may be disclosed on an ongoing basis. Each disclosure is subject to this Agreement regardless of whether made before or after the Effective Date.\n\n4.7 Optional Short-Term Evaluation. If the Parties agree in writing, the Parties may define a limited evaluation period for the Permitted Purpose; however, such evaluation period shall not limit the Receiving Party’s confidentiality obligations as set forth in this Agreement."},{"id":"return_of_information","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. RETURN OR DESTRUCTION OF INFORMATION","content":"5.1 Return/Destruction Upon Request. Upon the Disclosing Party’s written request at any time, or upon termination or expiration of this Agreement (whichever occurs first), the Receiving Party shall, within {{return_or_destroy_days}} days:\n(a) return to the Disclosing Party all Confidential Information in tangible form (including without limitation documents, media, samples, prototypes, and equipment) in the Receiving Party’s possession or control; or\n(b) destroy all such Confidential Information, at the Disclosing Party’s election; and\n(c) permanently delete Confidential Information from systems to the extent reasonably practicable, including from shared drives, collaboration tools, and portable media, subject to Section 5.3.\n\n5.2 Certification. Upon the Disclosing Party’s request, the Receiving Party shall provide a written certification signed by an authorized officer stating that it has complied with Section 5.1, describing in reasonable detail the steps taken, and identifying any categories of Confidential Information retained pursuant to Section 5.3.\n\n5.3 Permitted Retention.\n(a) The Receiving Party may retain Confidential Information solely to the extent required by Law or bona fide automated backup, archival, or disaster recovery systems maintained in accordance with the Receiving Party’s standard retention policies, provided that: (i) such retained Confidential Information remains subject to this Agreement; (ii) access is limited to personnel with a legal or compliance need to know; and (iii) such retained Confidential Information is not accessed for any other purpose.\n(b) If a litigation hold or regulatory retention obligation applies, the Receiving Party may retain the minimum necessary Confidential Information until the hold is lifted, and shall continue to protect it under this Agreement.\n\n5.4 Destruction of Derived Information. The Receiving Party shall also return or destroy all Derived Information, except to the extent retention is permitted under Section 5.3.\n\n5.5 No Lien. The Receiving Party shall not assert any lien or other right to withhold return of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.\n\n5.6 Continued Protection. Return, destruction, or deletion does not relieve the Receiving Party of its obligations with respect to any Confidential Information that is retained pursuant to Section 5.3 or that cannot be practically deleted from backups, archives, or logging systems, which shall remain protected under this Agreement."},{"id":"remedies","type":"negotiable","order":6,"title":"6. REMEDIES","content":"6.1 Injunctive Relief; Specific Performance. The Receiving Party acknowledges and agrees that any unauthorized use or disclosure of Confidential Information, including Trade Secrets, may cause irreparable harm to the Disclosing Party for which monetary damages may be an inadequate remedy. Accordingly, the Disclosing Party shall be entitled to seek equitable relief, including temporary restraining orders, temporary injunctions, permanent injunctions, and specific performance, in addition to any other rights and remedies available at law or in equity.\n\n6.2 Bond. To the fullest extent permitted by applicable Law and court rules, the Receiving Party waives any requirement for the Disclosing Party to post bond or other security in connection with any request for injunctive or equitable relief. If a court nevertheless requires a bond, the Parties agree the bond shall be in the minimum amount required by such court.\n\n6.3 Attorneys’ Fees and Costs. To the extent permitted by applicable Law, the prevailing Party in any action or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement (including enforcement and defense) shall be entitled to recover its reasonable attorneys’ fees and court costs from the non-prevailing Party.\n\n6.4 Cumulative Remedies. The rights and remedies provided in this Agreement are cumulative and in addition to any rights and remedies available under the Texas Uniform Trade Secrets Act (Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A), the Defend Trade Secrets Act (18 U.S.C. § 1836), and any other applicable Law.\n\n6.5 Defend Trade Secrets Act Whistleblower Immunity Notice. Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b):\n(a) Immunity. An individual shall not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that: (i) is made in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (ii) is made in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal.\n(b) Use in Anti-Retaliation Lawsuit. An individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding, if the individual: (i) files any document containing the trade secret under seal; and (ii) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order.\n(c) Notice Purpose. The Parties acknowledge that providing this notice is intended to comply with the notice requirements of 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b) and is not intended to encourage or authorize wrongful disclosure of Confidential Information beyond what the statute protects.\n\n6.6 Optional Indemnification (If Agreed). If {{include_indemnification}} is \"Yes\", then the Receiving Party shall indemnify and hold harmless the Disclosing Party from and against losses, damages, liabilities, penalties, fines, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) arising out of or relating to the Receiving Party’s breach of this Agreement or breach by its Representatives."},{"id":"governing_law","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. GOVERNING LAW; VENUE","content":"7.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and any dispute arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the Confidential Information, or the Permitted Purpose shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Texas, without giving effect to any conflict of laws principles that would result in the application of the laws of another jurisdiction.\n\n7.2 Exclusive Venue; Jurisdiction.\n(a) Except as provided in Section 7.3, the Parties agree that any action, suit, or proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement shall be brought exclusively in the state courts located in {{venue_county}} County, Texas, or, if subject matter jurisdiction exists, the United States District Court serving {{venue_county}} County, Texas.\n(b) Each Party irrevocably submits to the personal jurisdiction of such courts and waives any objection to venue or forum, including any claim of inconvenient forum.\n\n7.3 Equitable Relief. The Disclosing Party may seek temporary, preliminary, or permanent injunctive relief and other equitable remedies in the courts identified in Section 7.2. If exigent circumstances require immediate relief and a court outside the venue described in Section 7.2 issues temporary emergency relief, the Parties agree that the merits of the dispute shall be litigated exclusively in the courts identified in Section 7.2 to the fullest extent permitted by Law.\n\n7.4 Service of Process. Each Party consents to service of process in any manner permitted by Texas law and applicable rules of civil procedure, including by certified mail or other authorized means, at the addresses set forth in this Agreement (as updated by notice).\n\n7.5 Waiver of Jury Trial (Optional). If {{include_jury_waiver}} is \"Yes\", then EACH PARTY HEREBY KNOWINGLY, VOLUNTARILY, AND INTENTIONALLY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION OR PROCEEDING ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT."},{"id":"general_provisions","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"8.1 Notices.\n(a) Form. All notices, requests, demands, and other communications required or permitted under this Agreement must be in writing.\n(b) Delivery Methods. Notices shall be deemed given: (i) when delivered personally; (ii) one (1) Business Day after being sent by a nationally recognized overnight courier with tracking; (iii) three (3) Business Days after being mailed by certified or registered mail, return receipt requested, postage prepaid; or (iv) when sent by email with confirmation of transmission (not including an automated out-of-office reply), provided that a copy is also sent by one of the methods in clauses (i)–(iii) if the recipient requests it.\n(c) Notice Addresses. Notices shall be sent to the addresses and emails in the signature block (or to such other address as a Party may designate by notice).\n\n8.2 Ownership; No License.\n(a) All Confidential Information is and shall remain the property of the Disclosing Party and/or its licensors.\n(b) No license, assignment, or other transfer of any intellectual property rights is granted or implied by this Agreement, by disclosure of Confidential Information, or by any discussions between the Parties, except the limited right to use the Confidential Information solely for the Permitted Purpose as expressly provided herein.\n(c) Any goodwill arising from use of the Disclosing Party’s trademarks or logos (if any is authorized in writing) inures exclusively to the Disclosing Party.\n\n8.3 Feedback (Optional).\nIf the Receiving Party provides suggestions, comments, or feedback regarding the Disclosing Party’s products, services, or technology (\"Feedback\"), the Disclosing Party may use such Feedback without restriction or obligation, provided that the Disclosing Party does not knowingly use Feedback that constitutes the Receiving Party’s confidential information.\n\n8.4 No Partnership; No Agency. Nothing in this Agreement creates any partnership, joint venture, fiduciary relationship, employment relationship, or agency between the Parties. Neither Party has authority to bind the other Party.\n\n8.5 Worker Classification; No Employment Benefits. The Receiving Party acknowledges that its personnel and Representatives who receive Confidential Information do so solely in their capacity as personnel/contractors of the Receiving Party and not as employees of the Disclosing Party. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed to create an employment relationship between the Disclosing Party and any employee or independent contractor of the Receiving Party. The Receiving Party is solely responsible for compliance with applicable worker classification, wage, tax withholding, and labor obligations under the Texas Labor Code and other applicable Laws with respect to its personnel.\n\n8.6 Compliance with Laws. Each Party shall comply with all applicable Laws relating to its performance under this Agreement. Without limiting the foregoing, the Receiving Party shall not use Confidential Information in a manner that violates applicable anti-corruption, anti-money laundering, or competition Laws.\n\n8.7 No Waiver. No waiver of any provision of this Agreement shall be effective unless in writing and signed by the waiving Party. A waiver of any breach shall not be a waiver of any other breach or of any subsequent breach.\n\n8.8 Severability; Reformation. If any provision of this Agreement is held invalid, illegal, or unenforceable by a court of competent jurisdiction, the remaining provisions shall remain in full force and effect. The Parties intend that any invalid or unenforceable provision be reformed and enforced to the maximum extent permitted by Law to effect the Parties’ intent.\n\n8.9 Assignment. Neither Party may assign or transfer this Agreement, by operation of law or otherwise, without the prior written consent of the other Party, except that either Party may assign this Agreement without consent to a successor in connection with a merger, reorganization, or sale of substantially all of its assets, provided that such successor agrees in writing to be bound by this Agreement.\n\n8.10 Entire Agreement; Amendment. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties regarding the subject matter hereof and supersedes all prior and contemporaneous agreements, understandings, and communications, whether written or oral, relating to such subject matter. Any amendment or modification must be in writing and signed by both Parties.\n\n8.11 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which is deemed an original, and all of which together constitute one instrument.\n\n8.12 Electronic Signatures; Electronic Records. This Agreement may be executed and delivered by electronic signature and maintained as an electronic record. The Parties agree that electronic signatures and electronic records are intended to be binding and enforceable under the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (Texas Business & Commerce Code Chapter 322) and the federal ESIGN Act.\n\n8.13 Interpretation. Headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation. The words \"including\" and \"include\" mean \"including without limitation.\" Any ambiguities shall not be construed against either Party by reason of that Party having drafted or prepared the document.\n\n8.14 No Third-Party Beneficiaries. Except as expressly provided in Section 2.2(c) and Section 6.5 for statutory notice purposes, nothing in this Agreement is intended to confer any rights or remedies on any person other than the Parties.\n\n8.15 Further Assurances. Each Party shall execute and deliver such additional documents and take such further actions as may be reasonably necessary to carry out the intent of this Agreement.\n\n8.16 Optional Audit/Assurance (If Agreed). If {{include_audit_right}} is \"Yes\", then upon reasonable prior notice and during normal business hours, the Disclosing Party may request reasonable information from the Receiving Party regarding the Receiving Party’s compliance with this Agreement (including confirmation of return/destruction and high-level description of safeguards), provided that such request shall not require disclosure of the Receiving Party’s own confidential information or compromise security.\n\n8.17 Optional No-Solicitation/Non-Compete Addendum. If {{restrictive_covenants_enabled}} is \"Yes\", the Parties agree that Section 9 (Optional Restrictive Covenants) applies and is incorporated into this Agreement."},{"id":"optional_restrictive_covenants","type":"negotiable","order":9,"title":"9. OPTIONAL RESTRICTIVE COVENANTS (IF ENABLED)","content":"9.1 Applicability. This Section 9 applies only if {{restrictive_covenants_enabled}} is \"Yes\". The Parties acknowledge that these covenants are intended to be ancillary to and in furtherance of an otherwise enforceable agreement and to protect legitimate business interests, including the Disclosing Party’s goodwill, customer relationships, and Trade Secrets, consistent with Texas Business & Commerce Code § 15.50.\n\n9.2 Non-Solicitation of Customers/Business (Optional).\n(a) During the Restricted Period (defined below), the Receiving Party shall not, directly or indirectly, solicit for the purpose of providing competing products or services any customer or active prospective customer of the Disclosing Party that the Receiving Party learned of through the Confidential Information or with whom the Receiving Party had material contact in connection with the Permitted Purpose.\n(b) \"Restricted Period\" for purposes of this Section 9.2 means {{non_solicit_period}} months following the later of (i) termination/expiration of this Agreement or (ii) the last disclosure of Confidential Information.\n\n9.3 Non-Solicitation of Employees/Contractors (Optional).\nDuring the Restricted Period, the Receiving Party shall not directly solicit for employment or engagement any employee or independent contractor of the Disclosing Party with whom the Receiving Party had contact or about whom the Receiving Party received Confidential Information in connection with the Permitted Purpose; provided that general solicitations not targeted at such persons (e.g., generalized job postings) shall not be prohibited.\n\n9.4 Limited Non-Competition (Optional; Use with Caution).\n(a) During {{non_compete_period}} months after termination/expiration of this Agreement, the Receiving Party shall not, within {{non_compete_territory}}, engage in the following activities that are competitive with the Disclosing Party’s business as described in {{restricted_business_description}} (the \"Restricted Business\"): owning, managing, operating, controlling, or participating in the ownership, management, operation, or control of any business substantially similar to or competitive with the Restricted Business.\n(b) Carve-Outs. Passive ownership of not more than two percent (2%) of the outstanding securities of a publicly traded company shall not be a violation of this Section 9.4.\n\n9.5 Reasonableness; Reformation (Texas). The Parties agree that the time, geographic area, and scope of activity restrictions in this Section 9 are intended to be reasonable and no greater than necessary to protect the Disclosing Party’s legitimate business interests. If any restriction is found overly broad or unenforceable, a court shall reform the restriction to the extent necessary for it to be enforceable to the maximum extent permitted under Texas Business & Commerce Code § 15.51 and related Texas law, and enforce it as reformed.\n\n9.6 Independent Obligations. The obligations in Section 9 are in addition to, and do not limit, the Receiving Party’s obligations under Sections 2 and 5 and the Disclosing Party’s rights and remedies under Section 6.\n\n9.7 No Restriction on Lawful Whistleblowing. Nothing in this Section 9 prohibits disclosures protected by Section 6.5 (Defend Trade Secrets Act Whistleblower Immunity Notice) or any other applicable whistleblower protections under Law."}]'::jsonb,
  signature_block = 'IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Agreement as of {{signature_date}}.

