-- Update: Simple Agreement for Future Equity - SAFE (Texas)
UPDATE contract_templates SET
  preamble = 'This Simple Agreement for Future Equity (this "SAFE") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between {{party_a_company}}, a Texas {{entity_type}} (the "Company"), and {{party_b_name}} (the "Investor"). The Company and the Investor may be referred to herein individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties."',
  recitals = 'WHEREAS, the Company is engaged in the business of developing and commercializing products and/or services and desires to raise capital to fund operations, growth, and other corporate purposes;

WHEREAS, the Investor desires to provide financing to the Company in the amount of the Purchase Amount (defined below) on the terms set forth herein, including the right to receive equity securities of the Company upon the occurrence of specified events;

WHEREAS, the Company and the Investor intend that this SAFE constitutes a binding agreement establishing contractual rights to receive equity securities in the future, and not a present issuance of equity securities (other than the contractual right created hereby), and that the conversion and/or settlement of this SAFE will occur only as expressly provided herein;

WHEREAS, the Parties desire to set forth their mutual understandings and agreements with respect to the foregoing;

NOW, THEREFORE, for good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:',
  clauses = '[{"id":"definitions","type":"standard","order":1,"title":"1. DEFINITIONS","content":"1.1 Defined Terms. For purposes of this SAFE, the following terms have the meanings set forth below. Any capitalized term used but not defined in a particular provision will have the meaning assigned to it in this Section 1.\n\n1.2 \"Affiliate\" means, with respect to any Person, any other Person that directly or indirectly Controls, is Controlled by, or is under common Control with such Person.\n\n1.3 \"Board\" means the Company’s board of directors (or, if the Company is not a corporation, the comparable governing body or manager/member with authority to approve issuances of securities).\n\n1.4 \"Business Day\" means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday, or day on which banks in {{venue_county}} County, Texas are authorized or required to close.\n\n1.5 \"Capital Stock\" means the shares, units, membership interests, or other equity interests of the Company, including Common Stock and Preferred Stock, and any other class or series of equity securities issued by the Company.\n\n1.6 \"Change of Control\" means the occurrence of any of the following events, whether in a single transaction or a series of related transactions: (a) a merger, consolidation, reorganization, or similar transaction after which the holders of the Company’s voting securities immediately prior to such transaction do not hold a majority of the voting power of the surviving or acquiring entity (or its ultimate parent); (b) any Person or group (within the meaning of Section 13(d)(3) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended) becomes the beneficial owner, directly or indirectly, of more than fifty percent (50%) of the Company’s voting power; or (c) the sale, lease, transfer, exclusive license, or other disposition of all or substantially all of the Company’s assets (other than in connection with an Equity Financing) to any Person that is not an Affiliate of the Company.\n\n1.7 \"Common Stock\" means the Company’s common stock or other junior equity securities that are generally entitled to vote and participate in profits and residual value after payment of debts and preferences.\n\n1.8 \"Company Capitalization\" means, as of immediately prior to the applicable event (e.g., an Equity Financing or Liquidity Event), the fully-diluted capitalization of the Company, including: (a) all issued and outstanding shares of Capital Stock (on an as-converted to Common Stock basis, if applicable); (b) all shares of Capital Stock reserved for issuance under any stock option or other equity incentive plan of the Company (whether or not granted); (c) all shares of Capital Stock reserved for issuance pursuant to any warrants, convertible notes, SAFEs, or other convertible or exercisable securities of the Company (on an as-converted or as-exercised basis, as applicable), including this SAFE and any other SAFEs (whether or not then convertible); and (d) any other securities or rights to acquire Capital Stock that the Board determines in good faith should be included consistent with customary venture financing practice; provided that the Board’s determination will be conclusive absent manifest error.\n\n1.9 \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed or made available by or on behalf of the Company to the Investor (whether before or after the Effective Date) that is designated as confidential or that reasonably should be understood to be confidential given the nature of the information and the circumstances of disclosure, including non-public business, financial, technical, product, engineering, customer, supplier, pricing, marketing, strategy, and personnel information. Confidential Information includes Trade Secrets (defined below) and the terms of this SAFE (except to the extent disclosure is permitted pursuant to Section 11 (if included) or Section 12).\n\n1.10 \"Control\" (including \"Controlled by\" and \"under common Control with\") means possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management and policies of a Person, whether through ownership of voting securities, by contract, or otherwise.\n\n1.11 \"Discount Rate\" means {{discount_rate}}%, expressed as a percentage discount to the price per share paid by investors in an Equity Financing when determining the conversion price of this SAFE.\n\n1.12 \"Dissolution Event\" means (a) the voluntary termination of operations and commencement of winding up of the Company, (b) a general assignment for the benefit of creditors, (c) the filing by the Company of a voluntary petition in bankruptcy or similar proceeding, (d) the entry of an order for relief against the Company in involuntary bankruptcy that is not dismissed within sixty (60) days, or (e) any other liquidation, dissolution, or winding up of the Company (other than a Liquidity Event).\n\n1.13 \"Equity Financing\" means a bona fide transaction or series of related transactions in which the Company issues and sells shares of its Preferred Stock (or other equity securities that are substantially similar) to investors for the primary purpose of raising capital, and the Company receives aggregate gross cash proceeds of not less than {{qualifying_round_threshold}} (excluding (i) proceeds from the conversion or settlement of this SAFE and other SAFEs or convertible instruments, and (ii) proceeds from incurrence of debt). Equity Financing excludes issuances: (a) pursuant to employee, advisor, or director equity incentive plans approved by the Board; (b) upon conversion or exercise of outstanding convertible securities or warrants; (c) as consideration in connection with acquisitions, strategic transactions, joint ventures, equipment leases, bank financings, or other transactions not principally for the purpose of raising equity capital; and (d) in connection with a Liquidity Event.\n\n1.14 \"ESIGN\" means the Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (15 U.S.C. § 7001 et seq.).\n\n1.15 \"Governmental Authority\" means any federal, state, local, or foreign governmental or quasi-governmental authority, court, agency, department, commission, board, instrumentality, or political subdivision.\n\n1.16 \"Initial Public Offering\" or \"IPO\" means the closing of the Company’s first firm-commitment underwritten initial public offering of its Common Stock pursuant to an effective registration statement under the Securities Act.\n\n1.17 \"Investor\" has the meaning set forth in the Preamble and includes any permitted transferee or assignee of this SAFE in accordance with Section 10.\n\n1.18 \"Liquidity Event\" means (a) a Change of Control, or (b) an IPO.\n\n1.19 \"Major Investor\" means, for purposes of any optional Pro Rata Rights (if included), any investor or holder of SAFE/convertible securities who, together with its Affiliates, purchases at least {{major_investor_threshold}} of the Company’s securities in the Equity Financing (or such other threshold as the lead investors in the Equity Financing may reasonably require).\n\n1.20 \"Maturity\". This SAFE has no maturity date. No interest accrues on the Purchase Amount.\n\n1.21 \"Person\" means any individual, corporation, limited liability company, partnership, trust, association, joint venture, Governmental Authority, or other entity.\n\n1.22 \"Preferred Stock\" means the Company’s preferred stock or other senior equity securities that may have liquidation preferences, conversion rights, and other rights, privileges, and preferences over Common Stock.\n\n1.23 \"Purchase Amount\" means {{investment_amount}}.\n\n1.24 \"SAFE\" means this simple agreement for future equity, including all exhibits, schedules, riders, and written amendments executed in accordance with this SAFE.\n\n1.25 \"SAFE Preferred Stock\" means the shares of a series of Preferred Stock issued to the Investor upon conversion of this SAFE in an Equity Financing pursuant to Section 3, with the rights, preferences, and privileges described in Section 3.6.\n\n1.26 \"Safe Securities\" means any and all securities issued or issuable to the Investor pursuant to this SAFE, including SAFE Preferred Stock or Common Stock issued upon conversion or settlement, and any securities issued in connection with a stock split, stock dividend, combination, reclassification, recapitalization, or similar event with respect to such securities.\n\n1.27 \"Securities Act\" means the U.S. Securities Act of 1933, as amended, and the rules and regulations promulgated thereunder.\n\n1.28 \"State Securities Laws\" means applicable state “blue sky” laws, including the Texas Securities Act (Texas Revised Civil Statutes, Article 581-1 et seq.), and the rules and regulations of the Texas State Securities Board, as amended.\n\n1.29 \"Subsidiary\" means any entity of which the Company owns, directly or indirectly, more than fifty percent (50%) of the voting power or equity interests.\n\n1.30 \"Texas UETA\" means the Texas Uniform Electronic Transactions Act, Texas Business and Commerce Code Chapter 322.\n\n1.31 \"Texas UTSA\" means the Texas Uniform Trade Secrets Act, Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code Chapter 134A.\n\n1.32 \"Trade Secrets\" means information that constitutes a trade secret under applicable law, including the Texas UTSA and the federal Defend Trade Secrets Act (18 U.S.C. § 1836 et seq.) (\"DTSA\"), including information that derives independent economic value, actual or potential, from not being generally known or readily ascertainable and that is subject to reasonable measures to keep it secret.\n\n1.33 \"Transfer\" means any sale, assignment, pledge, hypothecation, encumbrance, transfer by operation of law, or other disposition, whether voluntary or involuntary.\n\n1.34 \"Valuation Cap\" means {{valuation_cap}}.\n\n1.35 Construction. (a) The words “include,” “includes,” and “including” are deemed to be followed by “without limitation.” (b) The headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation. (c) Unless the context requires otherwise, “or” is inclusive. (d) References to any statute include amendments and successor provisions.\n\n1.36 Acknowledgement of Texas Law; Equity Interest Characterization. The Parties intend that this SAFE is a contract right to receive future equity and is not a loan, debt instrument, or deposit account. The Investor acknowledges that the Company is not guaranteeing any return and that the Investor assumes the risks described in Section 9."},{"id":"investment","type":"standard","order":2,"title":"2. PURCHASE AMOUNT; ISSUANCE; CLOSING MECHANICS","content":"2.1 Purchase and Sale. Subject to the terms and conditions of this SAFE, the Investor agrees to pay the Purchase Amount to the Company, and in consideration of such payment, the Company hereby issues to the Investor this SAFE, representing the contractual right to receive Safe Securities upon the occurrence of certain events described herein.\n\n2.2 Payment Mechanics. (a) The Investor will pay the Purchase Amount on or before {{funding_deadline}} (the \"Funding Deadline\") by wire transfer, ACH, check, or other immediately available funds to the account designated by the Company in writing (including by email) (the \"Company Payment Instructions\"). (b) The Company may accept payment in multiple installments only if expressly approved by the Company in writing; absent such written approval, the Company may treat partial payment as no payment.\n\n2.3 No Interest; No Maturity. The Purchase Amount does not bear interest, and there is no maturity or repayment obligation except as expressly set forth in Sections 4 and 5 (as applicable).\n\n2.4 Use of Proceeds. The Company will use the Purchase Amount for general working capital and other lawful corporate purposes, as determined by the Company in its discretion, subject to any limitations imposed by applicable law or any written side letter between the Parties (if any).\n\n2.5 Capitalized Terms; Integration with Other SAFEs. This SAFE may be issued as part of a series of SAFEs with identical or different terms. The Company may issue additional SAFEs, convertible notes, or other securities from time to time, subject to applicable law and any contractual restrictions.\n\n2.6 No Rights as Stockholder. Prior to the issuance of Safe Securities to the Investor in accordance with this SAFE, the Investor is not entitled to any rights as a holder of Capital Stock of the Company, including voting rights, dividends, or inspection rights, except as expressly stated in Section 7 (Investor Rights) or required by applicable law.\n\n2.7 Book-Entry; Legends. The SAFE and any Safe Securities will be issued in book-entry form unless otherwise determined by the Company. The Company may place legends on any certificates or book-entry notations reflecting restrictions on transfer under the Securities Act, State Securities Laws, and this SAFE.\n\n2.8 Conditions to Company’s Obligations. The Company’s obligation to issue this SAFE is conditioned upon (a) receipt of the Purchase Amount, (b) the accuracy in all material respects of the Investor’s representations and warranties in Section 9 as of the Effective Date (or the date of funding, if different), and (c) compliance by the Investor with any reasonable “know your customer” (KYC), anti-money laundering, or sanctions compliance requests described in Section 9.12.\n\n2.9 Company Discretion to Reject Funds. To the extent permitted by law, the Company may reject the Investor’s payment if the Company reasonably determines that acceptance would violate applicable law, including securities laws, sanctions, or anti-money laundering requirements, and the Company will promptly return the funds received (without interest) to the Investor at the Investor’s written direction."},{"id":"conversion","type":"negotiable","order":3,"title":"3. CONVERSION UPON EQUITY FINANCING","content":"3.1 Automatic Conversion. If an Equity Financing occurs prior to the termination of this SAFE under Section 5 (Dissolution Event) or settlement under Section 4 (Liquidity Event), then upon the closing of such Equity Financing, the Purchase Amount will automatically convert into shares of SAFE Preferred Stock.\n\n3.2 Conversion Price. The conversion price per share (the \"SAFE Price\") will be the lower of:\n\n3.2.1 Discount Price. The price per share paid by the investors purchasing the Company’s Preferred Stock in the Equity Financing (the \"Financing Price\"), multiplied by (1 - Discount Rate); and\n\n3.2.2 Cap Price. The price per share equal to (A) the Valuation Cap divided by (B) the Company Capitalization.\n\n3.3 Number of Shares Issued. The number of shares of SAFE Preferred Stock issuable to the Investor in the Equity Financing will equal the Purchase Amount divided by the SAFE Price, rounded down to the nearest whole share unless the Company’s charter documents and customary practice in the Equity Financing permit fractional shares or cash-in-lieu.\n\n3.4 Treatment of Post-Money and Pre-Money Structures. The Parties acknowledge that venture financings may be structured on a pre-money or post-money basis and may include option pool increases, warrants, and other customary terms. The Board will determine, in good faith and consistent with customary venture financing practice, the Company Capitalization to be used in the Cap Price calculation, including whether and to what extent unallocated option pool increases that are a condition to the Equity Financing are included.\n\n3.5 Mechanics; Documentation. (a) At the closing of the Equity Financing, the Investor will execute and deliver customary financing documents (including a stock purchase agreement, investors’ rights agreement, right of first refusal and co-sale agreement, and voting agreement, if applicable) on substantially the same terms as required of other purchasers of Preferred Stock in the Equity Financing, subject to reasonable exceptions for the Investor’s status as a SAFE holder converting into Preferred Stock. (b) The Company will deliver to the Investor evidence of issuance of the SAFE Preferred Stock (e.g., a cap table update and/or book-entry statement) and will use commercially reasonable efforts to deliver copies of executed financing documents to the Investor (subject to confidentiality obligations and redactions customary in the market).\n\n3.6 Rights of SAFE Preferred Stock. The SAFE Preferred Stock issued upon conversion will be a series of the Preferred Stock issued in the Equity Financing (or will have rights, preferences, and privileges substantially equivalent to the Preferred Stock issued in the Equity Financing), except that the conversion may be subject to limitations necessary to preserve exemptions under applicable securities laws. If the Equity Financing involves multiple closings, the conversion occurs at the first closing at which the Equity Financing minimum is met, unless the Company reasonably determines otherwise.\n\n3.7 Reorganizations; Substitutions. In the event of a recapitalization, stock split, reverse stock split, stock dividend, reclassification, or similar change affecting the Company’s Capital Stock prior to conversion, the Valuation Cap, Company Capitalization, and SAFE Price will be equitably adjusted to prevent dilution or enlargement of the Investor’s rights, as determined by the Board in good faith.\n\n3.8 No Separate Consideration; No Cash Settlements. Except as expressly provided in Section 4 (Liquidity Event) or Section 5 (Dissolution Event), the Investor will not be entitled to any cash payment in respect of this SAFE, and the Investor’s remedy is limited to receiving Safe Securities as provided herein.\n\n3.9 Taxes; Withholding. The Company may withhold from any amounts payable (if any) or take other actions as required by law with respect to taxes; provided, however, this SAFE is intended to convert into equity and not to generate wage withholding obligations. The Investor is solely responsible for its own tax consequences arising from this SAFE and any Safe Securities.\n\n3.10 Company Notice of Equity Financing. The Company will provide the Investor notice of an Equity Financing within a commercially reasonable time prior to closing (which may be less than five (5) days if required by the timeline of the financing), including a description of the anticipated terms relevant to conversion (Financing Price, security type, and expected closing date) and instructions for execution of closing documents.\n\n3.11 Optional Side Letter. The Parties may enter into a side letter regarding information rights, pro rata rights, board observation, or other matters. Any such side letter must be in writing and executed by both Parties to be binding.\n\n3.12 Acknowledgement of Dilution. The Investor acknowledges that the Company may issue additional securities, establish or increase option pools, or otherwise take actions that may dilute the Investor’s potential ownership percentage following conversion, and the Investor accepts such risk subject only to express rights granted in this SAFE or any written side letter."},{"id":"liquidity_event","type":"negotiable","order":4,"title":"4. LIQUIDITY EVENT","content":"4.1 Liquidity Event Prior to Conversion. If a Liquidity Event occurs before the conversion of this SAFE pursuant to Section 3, then the Investor will be entitled, at the Investor’s election, to receive either (a) a cash payment or (b) equity securities, as described in this Section 4.\n\n4.2 Investor Election; Default Treatment. (a) The Company will provide notice of a Liquidity Event to the Investor promptly after the Liquidity Event becomes reasonably probable and in any event sufficiently prior to closing to permit the Investor to make an election. (b) The Investor must deliver written notice of its election within {{liquidity_election_days}} days after receipt of the Company’s notice (the \"Election Period\"). (c) If the Investor does not make a timely election, the Investor will be deemed to have elected the equity conversion option described in Section 4.4, unless the Liquidity Event is an IPO, in which case the Company may require automatic conversion as a condition to the IPO.\n\n4.3 Cash-Out Option. If the Investor elects the cash-out option, the Company will pay the Investor an amount equal to the Purchase Amount (the \"Liquidity Cash Amount\") at the closing of the Liquidity Event. The Liquidity Cash Amount is not increased for interest, dividends, or any other amount.\n\n4.4 Equity Conversion Option. If the Investor elects (or is deemed to elect) the equity conversion option, then the Purchase Amount will convert immediately prior to the closing of the Liquidity Event into a number of shares of Common Stock equal to the Purchase Amount divided by the Liquidity Price.\n\n4.5 Liquidity Price. For purposes of Section 4.4, \"Liquidity Price\" means the price per share equal to (a) the Valuation Cap divided by (b) the Company Capitalization, each as determined immediately prior to the closing of the Liquidity Event.\n\n4.6 Treatment in Change of Control; Consideration. In a Change of Control, the Company may require that the securities issued upon conversion under Section 4.4 be (a) the same form and class of securities received by holders of Common Stock in the Change of Control or (b) cash, if all holders of Common Stock are cashed out and no equity consideration is issued. If the consideration payable to holders of Common Stock includes non-cash consideration (e.g., stock of the acquirer), the value of such consideration will be based on the transaction documents as determined in good faith by the Board.\n\n4.7 IPO Mechanics. In the case of an IPO, the Company may require that this SAFE automatically convert into Common Stock immediately prior to the IPO at the Liquidity Price as a condition to the IPO, and the Investor will execute customary documents reasonably requested to effect such conversion and to comply with underwriter requirements (including lock-up agreements of customary duration, not to exceed {{ipo_lockup_days}} days, and customary representations).\n\n4.8 Subordination and Priority. Any payment to the Investor under Section 4.3 is subordinate to payment of the Company’s debts and liabilities to creditors and will be made only if and to the extent permitted by applicable law and the transaction documents.\n\n4.9 No Fiduciary Duty. The Investor acknowledges that the Company and its officers, directors, and equityholders may have interests in a Liquidity Event that differ from those of the Investor. This SAFE does not create any fiduciary or similar duty on the part of the Company to the Investor; provided that nothing herein limits duties imposed by applicable law.\n\n4.10 Waiver of Appraisal Rights. To the maximum extent permitted by applicable law, the Investor waives any appraisal, dissenters’, or similar rights in connection with a Liquidity Event with respect to this SAFE (not any equity securities the Investor may hold separate from this SAFE).\n\n4.11 Disclosure of Terms. The Investor acknowledges that the Company may be required to disclose the existence and terms of this SAFE in connection with financings, due diligence, audits, or regulatory filings, and the Investor consents to such disclosure as reasonably necessary."},{"id":"dissolution_event","type":"standard","order":5,"title":"5. DISSOLUTION EVENT","content":"5.1 Dissolution Prior to Conversion. If a Dissolution Event occurs prior to conversion of this SAFE pursuant to Section 3 and prior to settlement pursuant to Section 4, the Company will pay the Investor, at the time of and in preference to any distribution to holders of Common Stock, an amount equal to the Purchase Amount (the \"Dissolution Amount\"), subject to the limitations in this Section 5.\n\n5.2 Priority and Limitations. (a) The Dissolution Amount is payable only after payment (or provision for payment) of the Company’s debts and liabilities to creditors, including secured and unsecured creditors, as required by applicable law. (b) The Dissolution Amount is also subject and subordinate to any liquidation preferences or other senior rights of any series of Preferred Stock outstanding at the time of the Dissolution Event.\n\n5.3 Insufficient Assets; Pro Rata. If the assets available for distribution are insufficient to pay the Dissolution Amount in full to all SAFE holders (and holders of other instruments with substantially similar rights), the Company will distribute available assets to such holders pro rata in proportion to the respective amounts payable to them.\n\n5.4 No Further Rights. Upon payment of the Dissolution Amount (or the pro rata portion thereof), this SAFE will terminate and be of no further force or effect, and the Investor will have no further rights under this SAFE.\n\n5.5 Notice. The Company will provide the Investor notice of a Dissolution Event as soon as reasonably practicable after the Company determines that a Dissolution Event will occur or has occurred, together with instructions for receiving payment and any documentation reasonably required."},{"id":"valuation_cap_discount","type":"negotiable","order":6,"title":"6. VALUATION CAP AND DISCOUNT; ADJUSTMENTS","content":"6.1 Valuation Cap. The Valuation Cap is intended to reward early investment risk by providing a maximum valuation at which the SAFE may convert. The Valuation Cap applies only as expressly set forth in Sections 3 and 4.\n\n6.2 Discount Rate. The Discount Rate is intended to provide a discount to the Financing Price in an Equity Financing and applies only as expressly set forth in Section 3.\n\n6.3 Better of Cap or Discount. In an Equity Financing, the Investor receives the benefit of whichever results in a lower SAFE Price: the Cap Price or the Discount Price.\n\n6.4 Adjustments for Stock Splits and Similar Events. In the event of any stock split, reverse stock split, stock dividend, combination, reclassification, recapitalization, or similar change affecting the Company’s Capital Stock, the Valuation Cap and/or Discount Rate (as applicable) will be equitably adjusted by the Board in good faith to preserve the economic intent of this SAFE.\n\n6.5 Optional Most-Favored-Nation Clarification. If the MFN provision in Section 7.6 is triggered, and the alternative SAFE includes a different economic structure (e.g., post-money SAFE, different capitalization definition, or different conversion mechanics), the Parties will cooperate in good faith to amend this SAFE to reflect substantially equivalent economic terms to the Investor, consistent with the original intent of this SAFE.\n\n6.6 No Implied Rights. Nothing in this SAFE obligates the Company to consummate any Equity Financing or Liquidity Event, nor restricts the Company’s ability to issue any securities, incur indebtedness, or modify its capital structure, subject to any express rights granted herein."},{"id":"investor_rights","type":"standard","order":7,"title":"7. INVESTOR RIGHTS (INFORMATION; OPTIONAL PRO RATA; MFN)","content":"7.1 General. The Investor Rights in this Section 7 apply only prior to conversion or termination of this SAFE, unless otherwise stated.\n\n7.2 Information Rights (Baseline). Until the earlier of (a) conversion or termination of this SAFE or (b) the Company becoming subject to public reporting requirements under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, upon the Investor’s reasonable written request and subject to Section 7.5, the Company will provide:\n\n7.2.1 Annual Financial Statements. Within one hundred twenty (120) days after the end of each fiscal year, (i) a balance sheet and statements of income and cash flows for such fiscal year and (ii) a brief narrative update regarding the Company’s business, in each case prepared in accordance with the Company’s customary practices (which may be unaudited).\n\n7.2.2 Quarterly Updates (Optional). If {{include_quarterly_updates}} is \"yes\", within forty-five (45) days after the end of each fiscal quarter, unaudited quarterly financial statements or management reports of comparable scope to the Company’s internal reporting.\n\n7.2.3 Event Notices. Notice of (a) an Equity Financing, (b) a Liquidity Event, or (c) a Dissolution Event, in each case within a commercially reasonable time before closing when practicable.\n\n7.3 Optional — Pro Rata Rights. If {{include_pro_rata_rights}} is \"yes\", then upon a Qualified Equity Financing (i.e., an Equity Financing) in which this SAFE converts, the Investor will have the right to purchase, at the same price and on the same terms as the new money investors, a portion of the securities sold in such financing sufficient to enable the Investor to maintain its percentage ownership of the Company’s Capital Stock (calculated on a fully-diluted basis immediately prior to such financing, assuming conversion of this SAFE), up to a maximum purchase amount of {{pro_rata_max_purchase_amount}} (the \"Pro Rata Right\").\n\n7.3.1 Exercise Procedure. The Company will provide written notice describing the terms of the financing and the Investor’s maximum allocation. The Investor must exercise the Pro Rata Right by written notice within {{pro_rata_election_days}} days after receipt of notice.\n\n7.3.2 Allocation; Oversubscription. If demand exceeds the available allocation, the Company may allocate participation among holders entitled to pro rata rights in a manner determined by the Company and/or lead investors in good faith and consistent with customary practice.\n\n7.3.3 Exceptions. The Pro Rata Right does not apply to (a) issuances under employee or advisor equity plans, (b) shares issued in connection with acquisitions or strategic transactions, (c) shares issued upon conversion or exercise of outstanding convertible securities, or (d) any financing in which the Investor is in material breach of this SAFE.\n\n7.3.4 Termination of Pro Rata Right. The Pro Rata Right will terminate upon the earliest to occur of (a) an IPO, (b) a Change of Control, or (c) conversion of this SAFE.\n\n7.4 No Voting Rights; No Control. The Investor acknowledges and agrees that, prior to conversion, the Investor has no voting rights, consent rights, approval rights, or management rights with respect to the Company by virtue of this SAFE.\n\n7.5 Confidential Treatment of Information. The Company may require that the Investor execute a reasonable nondisclosure agreement as a condition to providing information, or may condition disclosure on the confidentiality obligations in Section 11 (if included). The Company may also withhold (a) competitively sensitive information, (b) information subject to attorney-client privilege, or (c) information the disclosure of which the Company reasonably believes could violate applicable law or contractual obligations.\n\n7.6 Most-Favored Nation (MFN). If the Company issues any other SAFE or substantially similar instrument after the Effective Date with terms that are, in the aggregate, more favorable to the investor than the terms of this SAFE (excluding differences solely related to purchase amount or investor identity), then upon the Investor’s written request delivered within {{mfn_request_days}} days after the Company provides notice (or after the Investor becomes aware through reasonable diligence), the Company will amend this SAFE to match such more favorable terms.\n\n7.6.1 Scope; Limitations. The MFN right applies only to economic and conversion terms and does not obligate the Company to grant governance or control rights to the Investor.\n\n7.6.2 Notice of New SAFE Issuances. Upon the Investor’s written request, the Company will provide notice of material terms of later SAFE issuances; provided that the Company may redact investor-identifying information.\n\n7.7 No Broker; No Finder. The Investor represents it has not engaged any broker or finder in connection with this SAFE that would obligate the Company to pay compensation, and the Investor will indemnify the Company for any claims arising from a breach of this Section 7.7."},{"id":"company_representations","type":"standard","order":8,"title":"8. COMPANY REPRESENTATIONS, WARRANTIES, AND COVENANTS","content":"8.1 Organization; Good Standing. The Company is duly organized, validly existing, and in good standing under the laws of the State of Texas. The Company has the requisite power and authority to own its properties and to conduct its business as presently conducted.\n\n8.2 Authorization. The Company has taken all necessary corporate or organizational action to authorize the execution, delivery, and performance of this SAFE. This SAFE constitutes a valid and binding obligation of the Company enforceable against the Company in accordance with its terms, subject to bankruptcy, insolvency, fraudulent transfer, reorganization, moratorium, and similar laws of general applicability affecting creditors’ rights and to general principles of equity.\n\n8.3 No Conflict. The execution, delivery, and performance of this SAFE and the consummation of the transactions contemplated hereby do not (a) violate the Company’s certificate of formation/incorporation, bylaws/company agreement, or similar organizational documents, (b) conflict with any material agreement to which the Company is a party, or (c) violate any applicable law or governmental order, except in the case of clause (b) or (c), as would not reasonably be expected to have a material adverse effect on the Company.\n\n8.4 Valid Issuance. The Safe Securities, when issued pursuant to the terms of this SAFE and in accordance with applicable law and the Company’s organizational documents, will be duly authorized and validly issued, fully paid and non-assessable (or, in the case of an LLC or other entity, issued in accordance with the applicable organizational documents and fully paid to the extent applicable).\n\n8.5 Capitalization. Upon the Investor’s reasonable request and subject to confidentiality, the Company will provide a capitalization summary reflecting outstanding equity interests and material convertible or exercisable securities as of a date reasonably close to the request.\n\n8.6 Compliance with Laws (General). The Company is in compliance in all material respects with applicable laws and regulations, including applicable anti-corruption laws, sanctions laws, and applicable employment laws.\n\n8.7 Employment and Worker Classification (Texas Labor Code). The Company represents that, in all material respects, it has classified its workers in accordance with applicable law (including the Texas Labor Code and applicable federal law), and has maintained policies and practices reasonably designed to comply with wage and hour, payroll tax, and worker classification requirements.\n\n8.8 Intellectual Property. To the Company’s knowledge, the Company owns or has sufficient rights to use the intellectual property used in its business as currently conducted, except as would not reasonably be expected to have a material adverse effect. The Company does not make any representation regarding non-infringement beyond the foregoing knowledge qualifier.\n\n8.9 No Registration. Assuming the accuracy of the Investor’s representations in Section 9, the Company believes the issuance of this SAFE is exempt from the registration requirements of the Securities Act and applicable State Securities Laws.\n\n8.10 No Public Solicitation (Optional). If {{offering_type}} is \"506(b)\", the Company covenants that it has not engaged in general solicitation or general advertising in connection with this offering in a manner that would jeopardize an exemption under Regulation D.\n\n8.11 Data Security (Reasonable Measures). The Company maintains commercially reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards designed to protect Company systems and non-public information, taking into account the size and nature of the Company’s business. The Company makes no representation that its safeguards are infallible.\n\n8.12 Disclosure. No representation or warranty is made by the Company as to future performance, future valuation, or the likelihood of any Equity Financing, Liquidity Event, or conversion of this SAFE."},{"id":"investor_representations","type":"standard","order":9,"title":"9. INVESTOR REPRESENTATIONS, WARRANTIES, AND ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS","content":"9.1 Authorization. The Investor has full power and authority to execute and deliver this SAFE and to perform its obligations hereunder. If the Investor is an entity, the execution and delivery of this SAFE have been duly authorized by all necessary action.\n\n9.2 Accredited Investor; Sophistication. The Investor is an “accredited investor” within the meaning of Rule 501 of Regulation D under the Securities Act, or otherwise meets the requirements for an applicable exemption from registration, and the Investor has such knowledge and experience in financial and business matters that the Investor is capable of evaluating the merits and risks of the investment in this SAFE.\n\n9.3 Investment Intent; Restricted Securities. The Investor is acquiring this SAFE, and will acquire any Safe Securities issued upon conversion, for the Investor’s own account for investment purposes only and not with a view to, or for resale in connection with, any distribution in violation of the Securities Act or State Securities Laws. The Investor understands that the SAFE and any Safe Securities have not been registered under the Securities Act or State Securities Laws and must be held indefinitely unless subsequently registered or an exemption from registration is available.\n\n9.4 Ability to Bear Risk. The Investor understands that investment in the SAFE is highly speculative and involves a high degree of risk, including the risk of losing the entire Purchase Amount. The Investor has the financial ability to bear such risk and does not require liquidity in the investment.\n\n9.5 No Reliance. The Investor acknowledges that neither the Company nor any of its officers, directors, employees, agents, or representatives has made any representation or warranty to the Investor regarding the future value of the Company, the likelihood of an Equity Financing or Liquidity Event, or the amount or timing of any conversion. The Investor is not relying on the Company for legal, tax, accounting, or investment advice.\n\n9.6 Access to Information. The Investor has had the opportunity to ask questions and receive answers from the Company regarding the Company and the terms of this SAFE, and to obtain additional information to the extent the Company possesses such information or can acquire it without unreasonable effort or expense.\n\n9.7 No Registration Rights. The Investor acknowledges that this SAFE does not provide the Investor with registration rights with respect to any Safe Securities.\n\n9.8 Legends and Stop Transfer. The Investor agrees that the Company may place restrictive legends or notations on the SAFE and any Safe Securities and may impose stop-transfer instructions with the Company’s transfer agent or in the Company’s records.\n\n9.9 No Voting; No Control. The Investor acknowledges that it has no right to participate in management or control of the Company by virtue of this SAFE and has no voting rights prior to conversion.\n\n9.10 Compliance with Laws. The Investor is acquiring this SAFE in compliance with applicable laws. The Investor is not relying on the Company to comply with any of the Investor’s legal or regulatory obligations.\n\n9.11 Source of Funds. The Investor represents that the Purchase Amount is not derived from unlawful activities and is not being provided to the Company for any illegal purpose.\n\n9.12 Sanctions; AML; OFAC. The Investor represents that (a) neither the Investor nor, if applicable, any beneficial owner of the Investor is the target of sanctions administered or enforced by the U.S. Department of the Treasury’s Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) or other Governmental Authority, (b) the Investor is not located, organized, or resident in a country or territory that is the target of comprehensive sanctions, and (c) the Investor will not use any proceeds or rights under this SAFE in a manner that would cause the Company to violate applicable sanctions or anti-money laundering laws.\n\n9.13 Finder’s Fees. The Investor has not taken any action that would give rise to any claim by any Person for brokerage commissions, placement agent fees, finder’s fees, or similar compensation from the Company in connection with the transactions contemplated by this SAFE.\n\n9.14 Acknowledgement of Company Discretion and Risk of Dilution. The Investor acknowledges that the Company may issue additional securities, grant options, and enter into financing transactions that may dilute the Investor’s potential ownership upon conversion. The Investor further acknowledges that the Board will make certain determinations under this SAFE (including Company Capitalization), and that such determinations will be made in good faith.\n\n9.15 No Guaranteed Conversion. The Investor acknowledges that the SAFE may never convert into equity if no Equity Financing or Liquidity Event occurs, and the Investor may receive no return on investment.\n\n9.16 Status of Investor. The Investor acknowledges that it is acting for its own account and not as an employee, agent, independent contractor, or representative of the Company. Nothing in this SAFE creates an employment relationship, independent contractor relationship, partnership, joint venture, or agency relationship between the Parties."},{"id":"transfer_and_assignment","type":"negotiable","order":10,"title":"10. TRANSFER; ASSIGNMENT","content":"10.1 General Restriction on Transfer. The Investor may not Transfer this SAFE, in whole or in part, without the prior written consent of the Company; provided, however, that the Investor may Transfer this SAFE without the Company’s consent to a Permitted Transferee (as defined in Section 10.2) so long as the conditions in Section 10.3 are satisfied.\n\n10.2 Permitted Transferees. \"Permitted Transferee\" means (a) an Affiliate of the Investor, (b) any member of the Investor’s immediate family or any trust, limited partnership, or other entity for the primary benefit of the Investor or the Investor’s immediate family, (c) if the Investor is an entity, any successor entity in a merger or reorganization or any transferee of all or substantially all of the Investor’s assets, or (d) any other transferee approved by the Company in writing.\n\n10.3 Conditions to Transfer. Any Transfer permitted under Section 10.1 is conditioned upon: (a) the transferee executing a written joinder or assumption agreement in a form reasonably acceptable to the Company agreeing to be bound by the terms of this SAFE; (b) the Investor and transferee providing any information reasonably requested by the Company to confirm compliance with applicable securities laws; (c) the Transfer being effected in compliance with the Securities Act and applicable State Securities Laws; and (d) if requested by the Company, the Investor delivering an opinion of counsel reasonably satisfactory to the Company that the Transfer is exempt from registration.\n\n10.4 Company Assignment. The Company may assign this SAFE without the Investor’s consent to (a) any successor entity in connection with a merger, consolidation, reorganization, or Change of Control, or (b) any Affiliate, provided that such assignee assumes the Company’s obligations hereunder. Any other assignment by the Company requires the Investor’s written consent, not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed.\n\n10.5 Binding Effect. This SAFE will be binding upon and inure to the benefit of the Parties and their respective successors and permitted assigns.\n\n10.6 No Fractionalization; Partial Transfers. The Company may, in its reasonable discretion, prohibit partial Transfers that would result in administrative burden (e.g., splitting the SAFE among multiple transferees) unless such partial Transfers are to Permitted Transferees and do not materially increase the Company’s administrative costs.\n\n10.7 Further Assurances. The Parties agree to execute and deliver such further documents and take such further actions as may be reasonably necessary to carry out the intent of this Section 10."},{"id":"confidentiality_data","type":"optional","order":11,"title":"11. OPTIONAL — CONFIDENTIALITY; TRADE SECRETS; DATA PRIVACY; EQUITABLE RELIEF","content":"11.1 Applicability. If {{include_confidentiality}} is \"yes\", then this Section 11 applies and is binding on the Investor from the Effective Date. If {{include_confidentiality}} is not \"yes\", this Section 11 does not apply except for Section 11.7 (DTSA Notice), which applies regardless.\n\n11.2 Confidentiality Obligations. The Investor will (a) hold all Confidential Information in strict confidence, (b) not disclose Confidential Information to any third party except as permitted under Section 11.3, and (c) not use Confidential Information for any purpose other than evaluating, monitoring, or enforcing the Investor’s rights under this SAFE.\n\n11.3 Permitted Disclosures. The Investor may disclose Confidential Information only to the Investor’s Representatives who have a need to know for the permitted purpose and who are bound by confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those herein. \"Representatives\" means the Investor’s Affiliates and their respective directors, officers, employees, agents, attorneys, accountants, and financial advisors.\n\n11.4 Compelled Disclosure. If the Investor is required by law, regulation, or legal process to disclose Confidential Information, the Investor will, to the extent legally permitted, (a) promptly notify the Company to allow the Company to seek a protective order or other remedy, and (b) disclose only that portion of Confidential Information that the Investor is legally required to disclose.\n\n11.5 Exclusions. Confidential Information does not include information that the Investor can demonstrate by contemporaneous written records: (a) is or becomes generally available to the public through no breach by the Investor, (b) was known by the Investor prior to disclosure by the Company without breach of any obligation, (c) is received from a third party without breach of any obligation, or (d) is independently developed by the Investor without use of or reference to Confidential Information.\n\n11.6 Remedies; Texas UTSA. The Investor acknowledges that unauthorized use or disclosure of Confidential Information or Trade Secrets could cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be an inadequate remedy. Accordingly, in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity, the Company will be entitled to seek injunctive or other equitable relief to prevent or curtail any actual or threatened breach of this Section 11, including relief under the Texas UTSA and DTSA, without the necessity of posting a bond except as required by law.\n\n11.7 DTSA Whistleblower Notice (Required). Pursuant to the Defend Trade Secrets Act (18 U.S.C. § 1833(b)), the Investor is hereby notified that an individual will not be held criminally or civilly liable under any federal or state trade secret law for the disclosure of a trade secret that: (a) is made (i) in confidence to a federal, state, or local government official, either directly or indirectly, or to an attorney, and (ii) solely for the purpose of reporting or investigating a suspected violation of law; or (b) is made in a complaint or other document filed in a lawsuit or other proceeding, if such filing is made under seal. Further, an individual who files a lawsuit for retaliation by an employer for reporting a suspected violation of law may disclose the trade secret to the individual’s attorney and use the trade secret information in the court proceeding, if the individual (x) files any document containing the trade secret under seal and (y) does not disclose the trade secret, except pursuant to court order.\n\n11.8 Data Privacy; Personal Data. To the extent the Investor receives Personal Data (defined below) from the Company, the Investor will use such Personal Data only for the permitted purpose and will implement reasonable safeguards to protect it. \"Personal Data\" means information that identifies, relates to, describes, is reasonably capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked, directly or indirectly, with a particular individual.\n\n11.9 Texas Privacy and Data Security. The Investor acknowledges that Texas and federal law may impose obligations relating to safeguarding and notification regarding certain categories of personal information (including, as applicable, Texas Business & Commerce Code Chapter 521 regarding identity theft and data breach notification). The Investor will promptly notify the Company if the Investor becomes aware of unauthorized access to Company Personal Data in the Investor’s possession that triggers legal notification obligations.\n\n11.10 Return or Destruction. Upon the Company’s written request, the Investor will promptly return or destroy (at the Company’s option) all Confidential Information in the Investor’s possession or control, except that the Investor may retain one archival copy maintained by legal counsel solely for compliance and recordkeeping purposes, subject to ongoing confidentiality obligations.\n\n11.11 Non-Solicitation (Optional). If {{include_non_solicit}} is \"yes\", then for a period of {{non_solicit_months}} months from the Effective Date, the Investor will not, directly or indirectly, solicit for employment any employee of the Company with whom the Investor had material contact through the investment relationship; provided that general solicitations not targeted at such employees (e.g., general advertisements) will not be a breach.\n\n11.12 Non-Competition (Optional; Texas BCC § 15.50). If {{include_non_compete}} is \"yes\", the Parties agree that (a) this Section 11.12 is ancillary to and part of an otherwise enforceable agreement, including the Company’s disclosure of Confidential Information and Trade Secrets to the Investor and/or the Investor’s Representatives; and (b) the restrictions are reasonable and necessary to protect the Company’s goodwill and legitimate business interests. Accordingly, for {{non_compete_months}} months from the Effective Date, the Investor will not use the Company’s Trade Secrets or Confidential Information to develop or commercialize {{restricted_business_description}} within {{restricted_territory}}. This Section 11.12 does not restrict the Investor from making passive investments of less than {{passive_investment_percent}}% in a publicly traded company.\n\n11.13 Reformation (Texas BCC § 15.51). If any restriction in Section 11.11 or 11.12 is found by a court of competent jurisdiction to be overly broad, unreasonable, or unenforceable, the court is requested to reform such restriction to the extent necessary to make it enforceable to the maximum extent permitted by Texas law, and as reformed, it will be enforced.\n\n11.14 Survival. The Investor’s obligations under this Section 11 will survive any termination, conversion, or assignment of this SAFE for the period specified in {{confidentiality_years}} years after the later of (a) the date of last disclosure of Confidential Information or (b) the date the Investor ceases to hold this SAFE; provided that obligations relating to Trade Secrets will survive as long as such information remains a trade secret under applicable law."},{"id":"miscellaneous","type":"standard","order":12,"title":"12. MISCELLANEOUS","content":"12.1 Governing Law. This SAFE and any dispute arising out of or relating to this SAFE, the transactions contemplated hereby, or the relationship of the Parties will be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Texas, without giving effect to any choice-of-law or conflict-of-laws rule that would cause the application of laws of any jurisdiction other than Texas.\n\n12.2 Exclusive Venue; Jurisdiction; Service. (a) Exclusive Venue. Subject to Section 12.14 (Optional Arbitration), the Parties agree that any action, suit, or proceeding arising out of or relating to this SAFE will be brought exclusively in the state courts of Texas located in {{venue_county}} County, Texas, or, if jurisdiction exists, the United States District Court for the federal judicial district encompassing {{venue_county}} County, Texas. (b) Personal Jurisdiction. Each Party irrevocably submits to the personal jurisdiction of such courts and waives any objection based on inconvenient forum. (c) Service. Each Party consents to service of process by any method authorized by Texas law, including service by certified mail to the notice addresses set forth in Section 12.6.\n\n12.3 Waiver of Jury Trial. TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, EACH PARTY WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY LEGAL PROCEEDING ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS SAFE OR THE TRANSACTIONS CONTEMPLATED HEREBY.\n\n12.4 Specific Performance. The Parties agree that money damages may be inadequate for certain breaches of this SAFE and that the non-breaching Party will be entitled to seek equitable relief (including specific performance and injunctive relief) in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity.\n\n12.5 Notices.\n\n12.5.1 Form of Notice. All notices, requests, consents, claims, demands, waivers, and other communications under this SAFE (each, a \"Notice\") must be in writing.\n\n12.5.2 Methods. Notices will be deemed given (a) when delivered by hand (with written confirmation of receipt); (b) when received by the addressee if sent by a nationally recognized overnight courier (with written confirmation of receipt); (c) on the date sent by email (with confirmation of transmission) if sent during normal business hours on a Business Day, otherwise on the next Business Day; or (d) on the third Business Day after mailing by certified mail, return receipt requested, postage prepaid.\n\n12.5.3 Addresses. Notices must be sent to the Parties at the addresses below (or to such other address as a Party may designate by Notice):\n\nIf to Company:\n{{party_a_company}}\nAttn: {{party_a_name}}, {{party_a_title}}\n{{party_a_address}}\nEmail: {{party_a_email}}\n\nIf to Investor:\n{{party_b_name}}\n{{party_b_address}}\nEmail: {{party_b_email}}\n\n12.6 Amendments; Waivers. No amendment, modification, or waiver of any provision of this SAFE will be effective unless in writing and signed by the Company and the Investor. No waiver of any breach will be deemed to be a waiver of any subsequent breach.\n\n12.7 Assignment; Successors. Section 10 governs assignment and transfer. Subject to Section 10, this SAFE will be binding upon and inure to the benefit of the Parties and their respective successors and permitted assigns.\n\n12.8 Entire Agreement. This SAFE (together with any exhibits, schedules, or written side letters expressly referenced herein and executed by both Parties) constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties with respect to the subject matter hereof and supersedes all prior and contemporaneous understandings and agreements, whether written or oral.\n\n12.9 Severability. If any term or provision of this SAFE is held invalid, illegal, or unenforceable in any jurisdiction, such invalidity, illegality, or unenforceability will not affect any other term or provision of this SAFE or invalidate or render unenforceable such term or provision in any other jurisdiction. The Parties intend that any invalid provision be modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it enforceable while preserving intent.\n\n12.10 Counterparts. This SAFE may be executed in any number of counterparts, each of which will be deemed an original, and all of which together will constitute one and the same instrument.\n\n12.11 Electronic Signatures; Electronic Records. The Parties agree that this SAFE and any signatures hereon may be executed and delivered by electronic means and will be legally valid, binding, and enforceable. The Parties intend that the Texas UETA, ESIGN, and applicable law governing electronic signatures and records apply to this SAFE.\n\n12.12 Expenses. Except as otherwise agreed in writing, each Party will bear its own fees and expenses (including attorneys’ fees) incurred in connection with this SAFE and the transactions contemplated hereby.\n\n12.13 No Partnership; No Agency. Nothing in this SAFE creates any partnership, joint venture, agency, fiduciary, or employment relationship between the Parties. Neither Party has authority to bind the other.\n\n12.14 OPTIONAL — Arbitration. If {{include_arbitration}} is \"yes\", then any dispute, claim, or controversy arising out of or relating to this SAFE will be resolved by binding arbitration administered by {{arbitration_provider}} in {{venue_county}} County, Texas, under the then-current rules of the provider, and judgment on the award may be entered in any court of competent jurisdiction. Notwithstanding the foregoing, either Party may seek temporary or preliminary injunctive relief in the courts specified in Section 12.2 to prevent irreparable harm.\n\n12.15 Securities Law Compliance. The Parties intend and agree that the issuance of this SAFE is exempt from registration under the Securities Act and applicable State Securities Laws. The Investor agrees to provide such additional information and execute such additional documents as the Company reasonably requests to support reliance on such exemptions, including (as applicable) accredited investor questionnaires, investor representations, and Form D or state notice filings.\n\n12.16 Time of the Essence. Time is of the essence with respect to each Party’s obligations under this SAFE.\n\n12.17 Survival. Sections that by their nature should survive (including Sections 9, 10, 11 (if included), and 12) will survive conversion, termination, or assignment of this SAFE.\n\n12.18 Interpretation Against Drafter. The Parties acknowledge that each Party has had the opportunity to consult counsel regarding this SAFE. Accordingly, no rule of construction will be applied against any Party based on authorship or drafting.\n\n12.19 Authority to Sign. Each individual executing this SAFE on behalf of an entity represents and warrants that such individual has the authority to bind such entity.\n\n12.20 No Third-Party Beneficiaries. Except as expressly provided herein, this SAFE is for the sole benefit of the Parties and their permitted successors and assigns and does not confer any rights or remedies upon any other Person."}]'::jsonb,
